<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS QB ANXIOUS TO MAKE POSITIVE STATEMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everyone else has spent the past two weeks
quizzing USC quarterback Carson Palmer about his poor performance
against Penn State, so wide receiver Kareem Kelly figured he might
as well get his turn, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he was a little excited and anxious, and forcing a
lot of passes,'' Kelly said following the pair's conversation.
</P>
<P>
   That's a little more forthcoming than Palmer has usually been
when assessing himself. Words like ``excited'' and ``anxious'' are
rarely heard from the laid-back sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity for Carson and me to get our timing
down,'' said Kelly, who caught just two passes against Penn State.
``He wasn't too effective in the Penn State game.''
</P>
<P>
   Because his emotions produced such an unexpectedly weak opening
effort, all eyes will be on Palmer tonight as the 11th-ranked
Trojans play Colorado at 5 at the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Can Palmer bounce back? It's a question USC (1-0) will be forced
to answer early and often, because the Buffaloes (0-1) allowed
Colorado State to run for just 65 yards, while giving up 327 yards
passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel ready,'' Palmer said. ``A lot more comfortable. But
we'll know on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer is eager for a big game, if for no other reason so he can
avoid another 14 days of speculation over why he had a rare off day
passing, after completing just 10 of 20 passes for 87 yards against
the Nittany Lions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets old,'' he said. ``Yup, I'm tired of it.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett believes Palmer, who played for the first
time since breaking his collarbone last September, suffered
first-game jitters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Carson will have that kind of game too many
times,'' Hackett said. ``I'm not saying that he won't have another
one, but I think the development with his receivers will continue
to improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of things that happened in that game,
lots of different things, like playing with new people. That's
going to be the case for a while. Let's face it, we are playing
some freshmen and sophomores all over the place.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the focus on Palmer, few have considered that Kelly was
nearly shut out of the offense, as the Trojans were content to milk
the clock and run the ball against Penn State. He hasn't exactly
had an easy couple of weeks himself, but Kelly, who is expected to
have a breakout season, is being patient _ for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to me how many catches I have, as long as we
can pull out victories,'' Kelly said. ``Last year, I had nine
catches for 175 yards in a game and we still lost.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hackett seems determined this week to make Kelly as
prominent as Palmer, especially after watching game tapes of
Colorado State shredding the Buffaloes' secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to run the ball, but on the other hand, if they
are not going to give us a chance to run the ball, we are going to
rely on Kelly and whatever he can get done,'' Hackett said. ``I
come back to Colorado State. The year before, Colorado State runs
the ball down Colorado's throat. This year, they are poor running
the ball. Colorado just nails them.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, for one, is ready for more passing opportunities but
realizes USC probably won't beat Colorado unless tailback Sultan
McCullough (128 yards against Penn State) is a major part of the
offense again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we have a chance to pass more, but hopefully we'll run
the ball much better than Colorado State,'' Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Colorado lost to Colorado State last week 28-24, the
still-respected Buffaloes are a critical team on the Trojans'
schedule. The fact Penn State flopped against Toledo took some
luster off USC's victory, and this will be a chance to address any
lingering skepticism over how much improvement has really been made
since last season.
</P>
<P>
   More important, if USC wins tonight, the rest of the schedule is
not terribly difficult. Of the next eight games, five are at the
Coliseum, and as of today, USC should be favored in all of them.
</P>
<P>
   It's one reason why USC players continue to make brazen
statements about the season, even if they have played just one
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be very aggressive and hopefully go
undefeated,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that road trips will be fewer than normal, Hackett took
time out this week to lecture the Trojans about the importance of
playing well at the Coliseum, where USC is 10-3 in Hackett's
previous two years.
</P>
<P>
   But USC has also blown two 21-point leads at home in those two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win back East (against Penn State) is good, but what really
matters is how you play in the Coliseum,'' Hackett said. ``This is
our house and we need to make sure everyone understands that. We're
focused and ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: A crowd of 65,000 is expected. . . . Former Montclair
Prep football and basketball star Anwawn Jones will start at
defensiveend for Colorado. . . . Four Navy F-18 jets will fly by
before the game in a ``missing man'' formation as a tribute to
former USC swimmer Lt. Mathew Moneymaker, who died in a plane crash
last year upon takeoff from the aircraft carrier USS John F.
Kennedy.
</P>
</TEXT>
