<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPBELL HOPES 18 TACKLES NOT NEEDED AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Travis Campbell figured he had five, maybe six
tackles against Air Force. He figured wrong. He had 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Cal State Northridge safety said he was just doing his job.
But 18 tackles in a game is not in a defensive back's job
description.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the game, we went to dinner and people were asking me
how many I had and I thought it was five or six,'' Campbell said.
``I was just going up and making plays. I don't think it's a big
deal. I'm supposed to tackle.''
</P>
<P>
   CSUN will count on Campbell to have another solid performance in
tonight's game against Southwest Texas State in San Marcos, Texas.
The Matadors (0-1) hope to bounce back from a 55-6 loss to Air
Force.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a Westlake High product, had nine solo and nine
unassisted tackles _ a couple which saved touchdowns _ a pass
deflection and forced fumble.
</P>
<P>
   Those are statistics linebackers commonly register.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played a really fine football game,'' defensive-backs coach
Junior Thurman said. ``He made a lot of nice plays, read his keys
really well and not too many times was he caught out of position,
which is a plus. Basically, he played our defense the way it was
designed, most of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, a sophomore, said he never had more than a few tackles
in a game in high school. He had more tackles against Air Force
than he had all last year, when he played in four games and
recorded six tackles in limited action. He was also hampered by a
bulging disc in his back.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell, who will make his second start today, wasn't
thrilled when he was taken out for a few plays against Air Force.
When he found out he was rested solely to give other defensive
backs experience, he was satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he was going to find a way to play this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was playing this year. I didn't care where _ I would've
played anywhere,'' he said. ``I just wanted to play anywhere _ wide
receiver, anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sit on the sidelines coming in as a freshman, you learn a
lot of humility. I went from people throwing away from me in high
school to sitting on the sidelines. I was like, `Wait. I can play.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In order to secure playing time, Campbell said he gave up plenty
of extracurricular activities in the summer. Campbell said all he
did was work two jobs and work out in the gym.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell got his wish with plenty of work. The Matadors defense
was on the field for 94 plays and Campbell was in on 82 of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was taking its toll and so was the altitude,'' Campbell
said. ``I couldn't get my mouthpiece in sometimes because I had
cotton mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he received all the glory with 18 tackles, but it
was only because the rest of the defensive backs did their jobs,
too. And if there's a statistic he's talking about, it's not all
the tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dropped an interception and I've never dropped a . . .
interception in my life,'' Campbell said. ``I'll never forget it. I
dropped an interception against Air Force. I told my coaches I'll
never drop one again. That keeps me up at night. But I'm my own
worst critic.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurman had plenty of praise for Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much improved from spring football,'' Thurman said. ``He
dedicated himself in the offseason program and it's really paying
off. I look for him to lead the secondary, even though it's his
second year, he's relatively new and it's his first year
starting.''
</P>
<P>
   Had Campbell gone to any of the Pac-10 schools that recruited
him, he'd probably be sitting on the sidelines again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to play and got to get some experience,'' Campbell said.
``I was waiting all spring and all summer for that game to see if I
could play against a Division I team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't mad coming to Northridge. I was testing myself to see
if I could play a Division I school. I proved to myself that I
could compete. (Air Force) will be one of the top five rushing
teams in the country and to have 18 tackles was great. I got to
prove to myself I could play at that level.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell doesn't play at all like his nickname _ ``Pretty Boy''
_ would suggest. Defensive lineman Jason Nicastro gave him the
nickname because Campbell let his hair grow out over the summer and
now has curly locks.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw him, I was like, `Hey dude. You been
surfing?' '' Thurman said. ``I don't care how he looks, I just care
how he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   And 18 tackles looks just fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
