<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7331 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-LOYALTY-AZR &LR;      09-09 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOYALTY-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-LOYALTY-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    STUDENT BATTLING OATH OF LOYALTY(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By EDYTHE JENSEN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Mesa, ARIZ.) - Fabricio Rodriguez, Mesa Community College's
student vice president, isn't getting paid because he refused to
sign a loyalty oath that would have made him a felon for being a
Communist.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Civil Liberties Union is demanding that the Maricopa
County Community College District scrap the oath and give Rodriguez
more than $800 in back pay due him as an elected student officer.
Meanwhile, he faces eviction from his apartment and is surviving on
donated canned goods and borrowed textbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Oaths like the one he is being required to sign were declared
unconstitutional by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1966. Justices ruled
in favor of a Tucson teacher who challenged them years before the
26-year-old Rodriguez was born.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's loyalty oaths date to the 1961 state ``Communist
Control Act.'' Although oaths tied to the law were declared
unconstitutional, the Cold War-era statute was never repealed.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU has no objections to generic loyalty oaths that require
government employees to abide by state and federal laws. The group
challenges those that make personal or political beliefs a
condition of employment.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez refused to sign the oath, used by every college in the
Maricopa County Community College District, when he took office in
early August.
</P>
<P>
   ACLU Director Eleanor Eisenberg said the civil-rights agency is
likely to seek legislation next year to remove ``Communist
control'' from Arizona lawbooks.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Kushibab, lawyer for the community college district, would
not say whether the district plans to eliminate its anti-Communist
loyalty oath. ``I am researching the issue and will advise my
client next week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MCC has offered to rewrite the oath to eliminate the reference
to the Communist Party for Rodriguez only, Kushibab said. But the
student officer said he won't sign it unless the oaths for all
college district employees are changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it unconstitutional to condition the ability to be
paid on this oath,'' Eisenberg said Friday, ``but signing it would
be a felony if you are a member or become a member of the Communist
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State University requires student workers and employees
to sign loyalty oaths, but they are worded differently and omit
mention of political beliefs or party membership. The ASU oath is
constitutional, Eisenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, a sophomore honor student, volunteers as director for
a Mesa literacy and mentoring program for children.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Kearny miner, Rodriguez said he joined the
Communist Party after working as a miner in Arizona, Nevada and
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw in the mines and the treatment of workers firmed my
political beliefs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel compelled to do more than agitate,'' he added,
citing his work as a literacy volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has been unable to buy his college textbooks and
faces eviction from his Gilbert apartment Oct. 1 without the
minimum-wage salary that comes with the student office.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Elfbrandt, a Tucson teacher, challenged a nearly
identical school loyalty oath in the early 1960s. She worked
without pay for five years until the Supreme Court overturned local
decisions and ruled in her favor. Students who elected Rodriguez
last spring knew about his political beliefs, he said, because he
published them in campaign literature.
</P>
<P>
   A few faculty members are helping him by lending him textbooks
and encouraging his fight, he said. Fellow literacy volunteers are
giving him canned goods. ``But I'm really strapped, and they know
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Milner, spokeswoman for MCC, said she knows of no previous
objections to the college loyalty oath, ``but we have no intention
of depriving this student of his paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Milner said she was under the impression that the oath's wording
was mandated by state law for all public employees. She added that
she was not aware of the 1966 Supreme Court decision.
</P>
<P>
   Milner also said she did not know that ASU used a different
oath.
</P>
<P>
   The ACLU has been getting loyalty oath complaints for years, but
individuals have always stopped short of legal challenges ``because
it's an economic hardship, and most of them have families to
support,'' Eisenberg said. ``It takes a tremendous amount of
courage to do what Fabricio is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Eisenberg said the ACLU would have taken the case no matter what
Rodriguez's beliefs because the loyalty oath allows tax-funded
institutions to withhold employee paychecks based on their personal
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at edythe.jensen(a)arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or (602) 444-7939.
</P>
