<HEADLINE>
NL HANDS VALDES SIX-GAME SUSPENSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The long, difficult and disappointing season for
Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes took another bad turn Friday
when he was suspended for six games for a beanball incident Aug. 27
at Chicago's Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes appealed the punishment handed down Friday by Frank
Robinson, baseball's vice president of on-field operations. A
hearing date was not set, which enables Valdes to make his
scheduled start Monday in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked and surprised,'' Valdes said. ``It's the first
time it happened to me in 10 years of baseball. As soon as I found
out what's going on, I said, 'We have to appeal this thing.' I
thought it was no big issue. Now, you can't throw inside, or if you
hit a batter you get suspended for six games? Man. C'mon.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs righty Kerry Wood was suspended three games for throwing
behind Alex Cora's head in the top of the fifth inning following
Bruce Aven's second homer of the game. Wood began serving his
suspension immediately. Both players were also fined $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the bottom of the inning, Valdes' first pitch was high and
inside to Mark Grace. Home plate umpire Mark Wegner warned both
benches. Valdes then hit Grace with a 3-1 pitch and was ejected
from the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't understand it,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``(Wood's pitch) was so violent, flagrant. Kerry Wood should
have been thrown right there, and that didn't happen. Ismael, it
wasn't a knockdown, it was up and in. I don't know where Frank's
coming from on this one.''
</P>
<P>
   As points of reference, Tampa Bay's Dave Eiland, Tony Fiore and
Cory Lidle were each suspended three games for throwing at Boston
batters after a warning was issued. Boston's Pedro Martinez was
suspended five games for throwing at Cleveland's Roberto Alomar
early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Valdes, Robinson said the reason for the six
games were for throwing at Grace, then for hitting him after a
warning was issued, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make a pitch inside and hit a batter, and I
get suspended for six games?'' said Valdes, who's 0-3 with a 6.08
ERA with the Dodgers. ``I'm surprised, I'm angry. I don't think I
deserve this many games.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Once Triple-A Albuquerque finishes the
playoffs, right-hander Eric Gagne and lefty Jeff Williams are
expected to be recalled. . . . Todd Hundley was the starting
catcher for the Dodgers, returning a day earlier than the club
announced from his mother's funeral in Chicago. . . . Center
fielder Devon White said he's only available to pinch-hit because
of his strained left quadriceps. White said he's about 75 percent
and he wasn't ready to run in the outfield. . . . Chicago-based
attorney Mike Abernathy filed motions to quash the subpoenas of the
18 Dodgers, and the since-traded Alan Mills, asked to testify in
the criminal case of Charles Carlin, charged with disorderly
conduct stemming from the May 16 fight at Wrigley Field. Abernathy
said the hearings about the subpoienas would be Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
