<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS ADD DEPTH WITH DUO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings opened training camp
for the 2000-2001 season Friday morning with two two-hour practice
sessions and two new defensemen.
</P>
<P>
   Lubomir Visnovsky and Andreas Lilja are not expected to have the
impact of Garry Galley, who was lost to free agency, and Sean
O'Donnell, who was taken by Minnesota in the expansion draft. But
just months after being selected in the June amateur draft, both
have a chance to make the club and add depth to a suspect blue
line.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' biggest offseason acquisition was free-agent
defenseman Mathieu Schneider. He will play the second unit and team
with Rob Blake on power-play situations. But Visnovsky, a
Slovakian, and Lilja, a Swede, are symbols of the Kings' philosophy
to build through the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure they can contribute right away, but I think
they are candidates,'' said second-year coach Andy Murray, who
played Visnovsky and Lilja together in the afternoon workout.
``It's a process and evaluation right now. We believe the potential
is there. I think they are good players, but are they good enough
to play at the NHL level? That's what we need to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Also part of Murray's evaluation process on defense: Phillipe
Boucher, who missed all but one game last year after foot surgery,
and Jaroslav Modry, a part-time player in 1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
   Visnovsky, 24, and Lilja, 25, are not kids. Both are older than
Aki Berg, who has played parts of four seasons with the Kings even
though he turned just 23 at the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   But Berg was erratic last season, playing well at times but
getting scratched for the first two games of the playoffs against
Detroit. Like Jere Karalahti, the Finnish native who stepped right
in last year as a rookie, Visnovsky and Lilja have considerable
international experience. The Kings are hopeful for an easy
transition to the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Lilja, molded in the same defense-first style as countryman
Mattias Norstrom, played for Malmo last season in the Swedish Elite
League. Like Berg, Lilja has size (6-foot-3, 220) and impressed the
Kings' top European scout Vaclav Nedomansky at the the World Hockey
Championships. He was taken with the 54th overall pick.
</P>
<P>
   Visnovsky is a quick-skating, pesky sort who had 21 goals and 45
points in 54 games for Bratislava of the Slovak League. He was
selected in the fourth round, 118th overall.
</P>
<P>
   Galley and O'Donnell represented the Kings' second defensive
unit behind Blake and Norstrom and both saw playing time on the
power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings tried to keep O'Donnell by offering draft picks before
the expansion draft, but Minnesota turned them down.
</P>
<P>
   Galley, 37, made $1.8 million last season and had one of the
best years of his career. He wanted similar money, but the Kings
were worried about his age. Galley has not caught on with another
team.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Kings general manager Dave Taylor spoke to holdout
center Jozef Stumpel by phone Friday and the two will talk again
today. The club is anxious to get him into camp for conditioning
reasons, as he's missed 43 games the past two years due to groin
and knee injuries. Stumpel, who is represented by Phoenix-based
Benji Robbins, remains at home in Slovakia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
