<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7353 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     09-09 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO RECORDS, ANOTHER LOSS FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Certainly, other teams can do it, but few are better
than spoiling potentially special moments than the Los Angeles
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Gary Sheffield set a Los Angeles record with his
41st homer and Dave Hansen hit his sixth pinch-hit homer to tie a
major-league single-season mark. But on the grander scale, those
homers meant little as the Dodgers lost to Colorado 8-5 Friday at
Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, the Dodgers were a season-high nine games above
.500, but four straight losses have put them within a half-game of
falling into fourth place in the National League West. They'll be
there with a loss to the Rockies today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a group effort,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric
Karros said. ``Although things may get magnified at this time of
year, from the top down to the bottom, I don't think anybody can be
satisfied with what's gone on. I'm sure everybody could do a better
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't one person or one part of the team or whatever. You
can pick parts of this season, and it's offense, pitching. You can
go with individuals. Nobody's excluded.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even Dodgers right-hander Kevin Brown is immune to this
funk.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who's making $15 million for this and the next five
seasons, fell to 12-6 after allowing five runs on nine hits in six
innings. Though Brown's 2.72 ERA is second in the National League,
he's in jeopardy of not even winning 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who missed 11 games with a viral infection, homered
for the first time since Aug. 19. His blast leading off the fourth
inning moved him past Mike Piazza and atop the Los Angeles home run
list. Mike Piazza hit 40 homers in 1997. Sheffield is two home runs
shy of tying Duke Snider's club mark of 43.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth inning, Hansen's leadoff pinch-hit homer was his
sixth this season, tying him with Brooklyn's Johnny Frederick
(1932) for most in one season. However, it only pulled the Dodgers
within 8-5.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough, real tough,'' Hansen said. ``We expect a lot out
of ourselves. It's not like we're not trying, it's just not
happening. It's hard to handle. You have stay professional. You
have to stay positive. We're the Dodgers, a professional
organization, and it demands it. And we will.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
