<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN; ORTIZ BACK ON TRACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ With wide-open arms the Anaheim Angels warmly
greeted the Baltimore Orioles on Friday night at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The sub-.500, down-and-out, wait'll '01, where'd-you-go-Boog
Powell Baltimore Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time in more than a month the Angels faced
someone other than a contender, a welcome breath of fresh air, and
they . . . well, they didn't exactly bury the Birds, but they won
2-1 before a crowd of 30,480.
</P>
<P>
   Benji Gil's sixth-inning homer snapped a 1-1 tie and Ramon
Ortiz, Mike Holtz and Troy Percival combined on a three-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Angels' third win in a row since their season-high
six-game losing streak _ the first time in two months, since July
6-9, they've won three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   It was a timely win, too. Seattle and Oakland lost Friday night,
and so did Cleveland and Boston, thus the Angels gained valuable
ground in the American League West and the A.L. wild-card races.
</P>
<P>
   There's still some climbing to do _ the Angels are five games
out in the A.L. West, 5 back in the wild card _ but as manager Mike
Scioscia noted afterward, ``We still have our eye on the prize.''
</P>
<P>
   The postseason became that much more of a possibility thanks to
the remarkable turnabout by Ortiz, the Pedro Martinez lookalike
and, at times, pitch-alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was impressive,'' Scioscia of Ortiz, who hurled 7 innings,
which were seven more than he lasted in his previous start Sunday
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had good command of all my pitches, I didn't feel any
(pennant-race) pressure, I just treated like a normal game,'' Ortiz
said through translator Bobby Ramos, an Angels coach.
</P>
<P>
   OrtI`tXPS
</P>
</TEXT>
