<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-CUBA-CASTRO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASTRO GETS SYMPATHETIC AUDIENCE AT NEW YORK CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING for all needing)  (ART ADV:  Photos NYT42, -43, -44, and -51  are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD WONG and CHRIS HEDGES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ President Fidel Castro of Cuba denounced the American
economic embargo on his country on Friday night and presented a
bleak vision of the world's future before thousands of cheering and
flag-waving supporters gathered in Riverside Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall be entering the 21st century, and that will happen in
extremely hard conditions for the world,'' the Cuban leader said in
a hoarse voice to about 2,400 listeners. ``The world is undergoing
a catastrophic situation. Don't believe the experts who feign
optimism and ignore the cruel realities of the developing world.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro called the United States' economic sanctions against Cuba
a ``criminal embargo'' and ``a violation of human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban leader arrived shortly after 9 p.m., an hour later
than scheduled. Dressed in his signature olive military uniform, he
strode confidently to the lectern, surrounded by guards in dark
suits. Cheers and screams rose to the dark heights of the church,
and hundreds of arms fervently waved Cuban flags.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers called the event ``an evening of solidarity with
the Cuban people.'' Friday night, those political sympathies were
worn on sleeves, collars and T-shirts, as pins of the Cuban flag
and of Che Guevara, the guerrilla leader who became a symbol of the
communist revolution, abounded.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those who attended, including Rep. Jose E. Serrano,
D.-N.Y., and Rep. Maxine Waters, D-Calif., denounced U.S. policies
toward Cuba. The United States imposed the economic embargo shortly
after Castro took power in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people view Cuba very differently from its
government,'' Serrano told a group of reporters in Spanish. He said
he and those present only wanted Cuba to be ``treated equally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If Cuba discovered oil tomorrow, my country would be its
greatest ally,'' he said. ``If Cuba had, and I don't want it to
have, military arms that could create terror in the world, we would
be allies.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro was invited to Riverside Church by the New York Welcoming
Committee for the Cuban Delegation for the Millennium. People
wanting to attend were asked to fax requests to the group, which
chose about 2,400 spectators. Friday night, about 2,100 of them sat
in the main chamber, while 300 sat in a side room watching the
event on television.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, made up of various grassroots groups, asked
Riverside if they could use the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are against the embargo, and that is why we are holding
this reception,'' said Aleeka Wade, a spokeswoman for the group.
``We hope to show tonight how many people there are who oppose the
embargo.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Bernard Wilson, the executive minister at Riverside,
said before the event that the church was pleased to play host for
the visit. ``Riverside has always been on the cutting edge of what
is happening in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Castro was in New York this week to attend the United Nations
summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech at the United Nations, he criticized the power
that industrialized countries have over the developing world,
saying wealthy nations have ``only served to make us poorer, more
exploited and more dependent.''
</P>
<P>
   He called for a reform of the United Nations, to transform it
``into a true representative body of all the interests of all the
peoples on earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, as she was waiting for Castro to arrive at the
church, Ellen P. Bernstein reflected on the Cuban leader's role in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. people need to hear that he is not a devil, not the
devil he is said to be,'' she said. ``They need to hear he has
important ideas for the same goals we all aspire to: world peace
and security and the proper treatment of the power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
