in Russia are struggling to shed outdated equipment and oversized
workforces. They cannot hope to compete on the global market
because their products are of poor quality. But the Oktava company
has used Soviet-era expertise to become a thriving producer of
microphones. Since it began exporting in 1994, its revenue has more
than doubled and U.S. and British rock musicians prize the
microphones, praising their quality even if they are ugly. By
