<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7390 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-DORMS-BELONGINGS-REVI     09-09 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DORMS-BELONGINGS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAVA LAMP GOES HERE, NEAR THE FRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Del., Md., Ohio, Fla., Mich.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Josephina Finamore, an 18-year-old sophomore from Wilmington,
Del., thinks she has done a good job of making her small dormitory
room at the University of Maryland in College Park feel like home.
When the family's metallic gold Plymouth Voyager was unpacked two
weeks ago, she and her parents unloaded, among other things: a
computer, two suitcases of clothes, a box of sweaters, a plastic
storage bin full of running clothes and a trash bag full of shoes.
She also brought items for the kitchen and bathroom, a CD player,
photo albums, framed pictures and a light brown teddy bear that
sits atop her blue, pink, yellow and green plaid sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Finamore and her roommates share, with others in a suite of
rooms, several televisions, a microwave, a toaster, a large
refrigerator for food and a smaller one reserved for beer. Then
there's the Mardi Gras beads, the book of drinking games and the
cup full of condoms.
</P>
<P>
   The days when students would show up at the end of summer with a
trunk, a suitcase or two and a tennis racquet are long gone, say
college administrators. Today, students have become hermit crabs
and simply take everything with them when they move into dorms. The
ideal seems to be as much stuff as it is possible to cram into
their rooms.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, college housing administrators say it has become
an increasing challenge to accommodate the computers, bean bag
chairs, stereo systems and futons that students are trying to pack
into dorm rooms that were often built to hold two suitcases and a
trunk. Meanwhile, from Pearson Hall at the University of Miami to
the Oxford House at the University of Michigan, parents say they
will need time to recover from helping their children move in.
</P>
<P>
   According to surveys by the Association of College and
University Housing Officers International, based in Columbus, Ohio,
students are bringing more than ever to campus. In many cases, they
are trying to pack a U-Haul's worth of effects into half of a
12-by-15 room.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, administrators say, students began bringing
electric typewriters to school. Later in the decade, small
television sets and stereo systems began to appear. These days, as
consumer electronics are increasingly seen by students as academic
and social necessities, everything from CD players, bubble jet
printers and computers to portable DVDs, large-screen televisions
and electronic keyboards are finding their way into dorms.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the introduction of computers into classrooms and
Ethernet network connections in dorm rooms have made personal
computers (and 24-hour access to e-mail and AOL Instant Messenger)
the norm in college dorms, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Michael DeMayo, a sophomore at the University of Miami, brought
so much stuff this year that he uses a loft bed, which allows him
to sleep up high and store lots of stuff under his bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a lot of people who have made their dorm rooms into
mini-nightclubs,'' he said. ``They brought Christmas lights to put
around their windows, strobe lights, black lights, disco balls,
lava lamps.'' One person, he said, brought at 20-gallon fish tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the other stuff, it's sometimes hard to remember to
bring notebooks for class,'' acknowledged one of Finamore's
roommates, Emily Dammeyer, who brought an equally impressive
collection of items to school with her.
</P>
<P>
   Allan J. Levy, an assistant housing director at the University
of Michigan in Ann Arbor, which has not built a new dorm since
1968, says the fact that students are loading more into their rooms
has caused a ``storage nightmare'' and that the vogue for
electronics has created a significantly increased risk of fire.
Moving in or out, which might have taken half an hour 25 years ago,
can now take hours, he said. So great has the increase in baggage
volume been over the years that the university has been forced to
raise the number of days it allots for student moving to five. It
was two in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, said Levy, who attended the university from
1970 to 1974, while technology may have created this problem, it
seems to be solving it. ``I guess the saving grace is that certain
parts of electronics are getting smaller rather than larger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
