<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7391 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-BANNED-APPAREL-REVIEW     09-09 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANNED-APPAREL-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MINISKIRT AS A NATIONAL SECURITY THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have been under siege for quite some time. This summer in
Swaziland, they were identified as a reason for the spread of AIDS
and banned from schools. In the past, they have been eliminated
from government offices by the likes of former Prime Minister
Victor Chernomyrdin of Russia, who saw them as signs of Western
influence, and purged by Idi Amin in Uganda. In 1967, the legendary
designer Edith Head, who felt they lacked elegance, banned them
from the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   They are miniskirts, and they are dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so dangerous that Congo's president, Laurent Kabila,
made it his first act to get rid of miniskirts when he overthrew
the dictatorship of Mobutu Sese Seko in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Why do politicians turn their attention away from the oppressed
and focus instead on the underdressed? And how does a brief bit of
fabric cause so much consternation?
</P>
<P>
   The scapegoating of the miniskirt serves as a reminder that when
fashion rules, actual rulers get nervous. The idea that the right
uniform can convey a world view or allegiance has always inspired
social snobs, awards show consultants and armies. But the notion
that the enemy can be identified by his clothes is an especially
comforting one in the realm of politics, since it's a lot easier to
get people to change their clothes than to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   In the political world, costumes get taken quite literally, as
if life were a Victorian melodrama in which villains wear black and
heroes wear white, with no attempts at disguise. And everyday
clothing poses an even greater danger than theatrical or military
costume. Political leaders see fashion as a second language that
can be spoken by just about anyone. So they try to crack its codes,
monitor its messages and cultivate its secrets for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   On the opposite end of the political spectrum from the mini, the
most widely persecuted piece of cloth these days is the Islamic
head scarf. For some, covered hair can be as scandalous as naked
legs. Last year, the Turkish Parliament shocked many Westerners by
ejecting a legislator for wearing a traditional hijab to her
swearing-in ceremony. To outsiders, the scarf seemed like a bid for
religious freedom. But to the fiercely secular Turks, the scarf
spoke to a history of oppression, and wearing it to work in
Parliament would probably be like showing up in the U.S. Senate in
Confederate flag earrings.
</P>
<P>
   Regimes that scapegoat clothing give new meaning to the concept
of the fashion victim. In 1994, 20 Muslim girls were expelled from
schools in France for wearing head scarves.
</P>
<P>
   In Afghanistan this July, a visiting group of Pakistani soccer
players had their heads shaved in public as punishment for wearing
shorts instead of long pants.
</P>
<P>
   In Swaziland, it was not only the skirts but the schoolgirls in
them who were blamed for behaving seductively around their
teachers. The Swaziland government had first attempted to get rid
of miniskirts in 1969, but had trouble enforcing the law. Now, AIDS
has been used to justify the directive. So it is that a tiny
African nation can blame a tiny skirt for an international health
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Since fashion itself can seem unscientific, those who would
create or reform fashions often deploy science. Even Oscar Wilde,
often thought of as a whimsical dresser, argued that fashion ought
to be grounded in serious, objective principles. ``The right laws
of dress,'' Wilde wrote in support of Victorian dress reform, ``are
dictated . . . by science and not by fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the reformers who recently persuaded the Iranian
government that girls should be permitted to wear pastels in
addition to dark colors had to give reasons relating to the girls'
physical and mental health. They cited, for example, the threat of
osteoporosis from Vitamin D deficiencies caused by
sunlight-blocking black chadors.
</P>
<P>
   And in France, hygiene is given as the reason for an intriguing
swimming-pool dress code: men must wear skin-tight Speedos rather
than baggy swimming trunks to swim in most public pools. While this
may seem like a Continental fashion preference, like bathing
topless, or possibly the result of some chic French bureaucrat's
disdain for American-style boxers, it is explained as an issue of
cleanliness. The logic goes: longer bathing suits can pass for
shorts, may be worn in potentially unclean public areas and so
could be trailing dirt or germs.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone shocked by the arbitrary, dictatorial bans of skirts that
are too short or bathing suits that are too long must consider the
alternative _ legislating the leg. What if knees were subjected to
a democratic vote? This summer, the Bermuda Parliament voted itself
the right to come to work in Bermuda shorts. Luckily the shorts are
a symbol of national pride and so avoided getting vetoed in the
backlash against casual Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent poll, the number of U.S. companies that
allow casual dress, which had risen steadily to 97 percent in 1998,
declined this year for the first time since 1992, to 87 percent.
Anyone made too lazy by casual dress codes can now look forward to
``Dress Up Thursdays,'' a plot to sell men's suits.
</P>
<P>
   Even in America, where dressing outrageously seems a natural
right, there are those who believe you are what you wear _ notably
Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, known both for writing that
provocative dressing may lead to sexual harassment (Meritor Savings
Bank v. Vinson) and for adding four stripes of gold braid to the
arms of his robe for a more magisterial look.
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential campaign, the politics of fashion have
gotten ugly. First, Vice President Al Gore's critics accused him of
getting a fashion makeover. The vice president had a problem. It
looked as if Gov. George W. Bush would easily outdress him. Even
Bush's clothes have presidential lineage: not only does W. look
great in custom-made suits, he uses the same tailor who dressed
Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if Gore slipped up and wore a single earth tone,
commentators would say he wasn't his own man, which is a shame
because earth tones are some of the vice president's best colors.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Democratic convention, the fashion crisis was
averted. In the opening-night video, world leaders kept extolling
President Clinton, while Clinton kept wearing a tuxedo, radiating
elegance and national prosperity. Then Gore showed up, dressed in
red, white and blue. Dressing like a flag has always been a key to
winning national elections. And saying you're your own man while
wrapped in the colors of the flag _ it doesn't get much better than
that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
