<HEADER>
A7394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      09-09 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Sept. 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK-EURO (Vejle, Denmark) _ With its fat cows and flaky
pastries, its neat streets and nice queen, this pampered little
land seems as foreign to angst as any country could be. But
appearances deceive, for Denmark has an acute case of the identity
crisis now afflicting several European states. The disquiet has
been brought on by a referendum on Sept. 28, when Danes will be
asked whether they wish to preserve the krone or follow 12 other
states of the 15-member European Union in abandoning their money
for a shared currency, the euro. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REFUGEES (Cartagena, Colombia) _ An estimated 2 million
Colombians have been uprooted in recent years. That is more than
were sent fleeing by the war in Kosovo last year. In fact, of all
the countries of the world suffering from the miseries of war, only
Sudan and Angola have more displaced people. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-KOSHER-CONTROVERSY (Jerusalem) _ Rabbi Shlomo Shmulevitz
is director of the commandments related to the Land of Israel for
the Jerusalem rabbinate. This is not a good time to ask him how he
is doing. ``Oy vey,'' he said. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-JUSTICE (Chengde, China) _ Their voices cracking with
outrage, the parents chronicled four years of fear and frustration
as they battle to keep their four sons from being executed for the
alleged robbery and killing of two taxi drivers six years ago. It
is a tale that illustrates the pitfalls of China's criminal justice
system and highlights the sometimes capricious imposition of the
death sentence. These particular defendants have so far escaped
execution only because their families _ all farmers and workers _
were willing to bear official persecution and severe financial
strains to mount repeated legal appeals. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINE-KIDNAP (Bangkok, Thailand) _ More than four months
after 21 people were seized in their beach clothes from a remote
diving resort, the last four Westerners were freed Saturday from
the jungle by Muslim rebel kidnappers. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   NICARAGUA-LAND (Nagarote, Nicaragua) _ More than a decade after
the elections that removed the Sandinistas from power, thousands of
Nicaraguans _ as well as about 900 American citizens _ are
grappling with the legacy of the Sandinista Revolution: confiscated
land, homes and businesses that were distributed to peasants and
party loyalists. While few people expected to get back all they
owned, even skeptics decried what they described as convoluted,
lengthy administrative and legal processes that too often result in
paltry settlements paid in low-value government bonds. By David
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ (Caracas, Venezuela) _ With his control of the
Venezuelan government assured in a landslide election five weeks
ago, President Hugo Chavez is now moving to replace independent
civic and labor groups with equivalents under the control of the
``revolutionary'' movement he leads. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-TERRORISM (Pretoria, South Africa) _ South Africa's
minister of justice, incensed by the assassination this week of a
judge who has presided over an important terrorism trial in Cape
Town, has said he will ban the organization suspected in the
slaying if the group continues what authorities say is a two-year
campaign of bombings and terror. By Henri E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-FAMILIES (Undated) _ When Vice President Al Gore
incorporated ``working families'' into his rhetoric last month and
``hard-working middle-class families'' this month as pivotal
campaign phrases, he pointed a finger at a central fact of American
life: most of the nation's 72 million families feel they cannot
make ends meet. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   PHILLY-SCHOOLS (Philadelphia) _ This city's deeply troubled
public schools reopened in a state of uncertainty as the teachers
union authorized a strike in the face of a powerful new
bargaining-table coalition of state and city political leaders
determined to overhaul the system. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PA-SWING-STATE (Scranton, Pa.) _ Pennsylvania is one of the
handful of states where the presidential race of 2000 will be
decided. It casts 23 electoral votes, more than any other closely
contested state. So when public and private polls suggested the
start of a slide toward Al Gore, George W. Bush stormed in to try
to halt the slide, and the vice president arrived to try to keep
the momentum going. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ADS-STRATEGY (Washington) _ A fundamental predicament is
facing the Bush organization as it heads into an intense eight
weeks of advertising. Campaign officials have concluded that they
have no choice but to run advertisements attacking Al Gore. But how
do they go negative without making the commercials appear too
harsh? It is more of a challenge for George W. Bush than for Gore
because the Texas governor had vowed to run a campaign on a
positive note. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   MINN-SENATE-RACE (St. Paul, Minn.) _ When the Democratic Party
looked for congressional seats it could pick up in the November
elections, the one held by Sen. Rod Grams of Minnesota was high on
the list. But the Democrats have been unable to unify around any of
their four major candidates. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   ALA-SELMA-ELECTION (Selma, Ala.) _ After 35 years, Mayor Joseph
T. Smitherman's high-wire act above the city's churning racial
politics had begun to settle into routine. Every four years, he
would hold barbecues in black neighborhoods, boasting about the
number of black department heads he had appointed, while reminding
white voters that he would be ``the last white mayor of Selma,''
hinting that the racial deluge was around the corner. But this
year, Smitherman has found himself in the fight of his life, forced
for the first time into a runoff election _ on Tuesday _ against a
black candidate, and the hints have become a bit less subtle. By
David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Arizona GOP race rife with dirty
tricks; Prayers are answered if only symbolically; The same old
song with a different beat; Nasty divorce battle finds home in
politics; A Nader supporter voices second thoughts. By B. Drummond
Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ Cushioned by a burgeoning surplus,
Congress is poised to approve large increases in spending by
federal agencies, pushing the national budget to record levels. By
Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   FTC-VIOLENCE-REPORT (Washington) _ The Federal Trade Commission
plans to release a report on Monday that harshly criticizes the
film, recording and video game industries for marketing violent,
adult-rated entertainment to young people, said several officials
familiar with the report. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Shelton, Conn.) _ Cheney MIA on W. vote. By Maureen
Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ Meeting a bad idea partway. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 1 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12 noon.
</P>
