<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One Debate Down. Three to Go. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The debate is over. Let the debates begin.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the week, the Bush and Gore campaigns sparred over
where and how _ or even whether _ the presidential debates would
occur this year. The bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates,
which has been running the forums since 1988, had issued
invitations to Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore to
three debates on college campuses in October.
</P>
<P>
   But last Sunday, Bush issued a debate plan of his own that
included only one 90-minute commission debate and added 60-minute
showdowns on ``Meet the Press'' and ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, however, with Democrats accusing Bush of wanting to
duck the wider television audiences commanded by the commission
debates _ and Republicans increasingly worried that voters might be
seeing it that way, too _ Bush withdrew his plan. This week, aides
to both candidates are to meet in Washington with the commission to
negotiate a final deal that guarantees a series of forums.
</P>
<P>
   All the talk about talking was the dominant story of the first
week of campaigning after Labor Day, traditionally the kickoff of
the final leg of the election. It easily overshadowed the
governor's announcement of the details of his prescription drug
proposal on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's $198 billion overhaul of Medicare would encourage the
elderly to pick subsidized private insurance plans that had
prescription drug coverage. Gore, who previously unveiled his own
$253 billion plan, said Bush's subsidies were not sufficient for
older people.
</P>
<P>
   With Gore still in the throes of a post-convention surge, Bush's
advisers unveiled a retooled strategy and message, focused on a new
theme: ``Real plans for real people.'' The idea is to get Bush
mixing more with ``real people'' at town hall meetings and in
workplace chats.
</P>
<P>
   If It Moves, Impale It &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is struggling with all sorts of technological
challenges _ from designing a national missile defense that works
to perfecting new aircraft like the F-22. But its most embarrassing
technological failure these days is popping up right outside its
front door.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a heavy steel security barricade misfired, striking
a car carrying Germany's defense minister, Rudolf Scharping,
moments before a full-dress honors ceremony on the Pentagon's
steps.
</P>
<P>
   The freak accident wrecked the car, slightly injured Scharping,
the German defense attache and a U.S. security guard, and left
Defense Secretary William Cohen, who rushed to Scharping's aid,
fuming.
</P>
<P>
   Only it was no freak accident.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the same barricade sprang up beneath the car of
Japan's defense minister, Fukushiro Nukaga, injuring him and five
others. In 1995, another gate struck a car carrying then-Defense
Secretary William Perry.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently the system, built in the early 1990s to keep
terrorists out, has a sentry's worst nightmare built in. It has
difficulty distinguishing between friend and foe.
</P>
<P>
   What made last week's accident even more infuriating was that
the Pentagon believed it had fixed the problem by replacing manual
switches with electronic controls meant to keep the barricades open
long enough for motorcades to pass through. (The redesigned
barricade struck a car carrying Chinese military officers last
January, but officials blamed tailgating and insisted the system
worked.)
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon vowed to conduct a new investigation into what is
being called ``Gategate.'' Asked if human error, not technology,
was to blame, the Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth H. Bacon, said
simply, ``I don't think we fully understand yet.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gigantic Gathering Of World Leaders
</P>
<P>
   United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan called it ``a
remarkable convergence of views.'' When about 150 government
leaders representing a large majority of the world's nations ended
their first no-frills working summit on Friday night, there was not
much disagreement over the lopsided effects of the global economy.
That was the easy part. Now, what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders made lofty pledges in a declaration. That and three
days of speeches won't solve the problem, but behind the scenes,
there was an innovation. Leaders broke into groups that mixed rich
and poor, North and South, East and West, to thrash out ideas. The
White House said there was even a moment when President Clinton and
Fidel Castro exchanged a handshake and innocuous chitchat.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong of Singapore, who led one
millennial roundtable, called it the organization's first
``interactive dialogue among leaders'' and suggested that the
United Nations not wait a thousand years to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone's Tough Week
</P>
<P>
   Even as it confronted lawsuits, congressional hearings and
public anger over its defective tires, Bridgestone/Firestone got
one piece of good news. The Japanese-owned tire maker reached a
settlement with the United Steelworkers of America, avoiding a
strike by 8,000 workers. Eager to avert a strike during its current
crisis, Bridgestone gave most workers raises of at least 15 percent
over three years.
</P>
<P>
   Still the crisis built, as hearings on Capitol Hill led to a
release of documents indicating that the tire company and perhaps
Ford knew about a pattern of tire failures long before a recall was
announced in August, and statistics from a widely used federal
database showed that fatal crashes involving Ford Explorers were
almost three times as likely to be tire-related as fatal crashes
involving other sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, Firestone and federal safety regulators said they had not
recognized such a pattern in the statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Glacial School Improvement
</P>
<P>
   A study showed that if American eighth-graders continued to
improve their basic math skills at the pace they have since 1973,
it would take 125 years for them to catch up with their peers in
Singapore _ assuming those students don't raise their own scores.
The study, by the National Assessment of Educational Progress (the
standardized tests known as the nation's report card), showed that
while scores on a new test emphasizing problem-solving and geometry
have risen steadily throughout the 1990s, performance on a test
stressing arithmetic has improved only slightly, and reading scores
have been practically flat since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   An Upset in Lebanon  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lebanon's government, handpicked by Syria's new leader, Bashar  &QL; 
Assad, took a trouncing as a former prime minister, the billionaire
builder Rafik Hariri, swept to an overwhelming victory in
parliamentary elections. It was a bitter blow for President Emile
Lahoud, whom Assad, son of Syria's late ruler, Hafez Assad, put in
power in 1988 during his apprenticeship.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
