   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-FAMILIES (Undated) _ When Vice President Al Gore
incorporated ``working families'' into his rhetoric last month and
``hard-working middle-class families'' this month as pivotal
campaign phrases, he pointed a finger at a central fact of American
life: most of the nation's 72 million families feel they cannot
make ends meet. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 1 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   DENMARK-EURO (Vejle, Denmark) _ With its fat cows and flaky
pastries, its neat streets and nice queen, this pampered little
land seems as foreign to angst as any country could be. But
appearances deceive, for Denmark has an acute case of the identity
crisis now afflicting several European states. The disquiet has
been brought on by a referendum on Sept. 28, when Danes will be
asked whether they wish to preserve the krone or follow 12 other
states of the 15-member European Union in abandoning their money
for a shared currency, the euro. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   PA-SWING-STATE (Scranton, Pa.) _ Pennsylvania is one of the
handful of states where the presidential race of 2000 will be
decided. It casts 23 electoral votes, more than any other closely
contested state. So when public and private polls suggested the
start of a slide toward Al Gore, George W. Bush stormed in to try
to halt the slide, and the vice president arrived to try to keep
the momentum going. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-REFUGEES (Cartagena, Colombia) _ An estimated 2 million
Colombians have been uprooted in recent years. That is more than
were sent fleeing by the war in Kosovo last year. In fact, of all
the countries of the world suffering from the miseries of war, only
Sudan and Angola have more displaced people. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   (Scheduled to move by 2 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
