<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 11:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7408 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MINN-SENATE-NYT &LR;      09-09 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINN-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINNESOTA DEMOCRATS' DIVISIONS COULD KEEP THEM FROM REGAINING
SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, Minn. _ When the Democratic Party looked for
congressional seats it could pick up in the November elections, the
one held by Sen. Rod Grams of Minnesota was high on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Grams, a conservative Republican in a state with a large liberal
bent, has made few legislative splashes in his one term in the
Senate, and his approval rating has been notably low.
</P>
<P>
   Grams also hit several personal speed bumps that took the steam
out of his family-values message. He was divorced, then apparently
became involved in a relationship with a senior aide that led to
the resignation or dismissal of several other staff members. And
last year, sheriff's deputies found marijuana in a truck that
Grams' 21-year-old son was driving.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had been all but counting that Grams, who won the 1994
election with 49 percent of the vote, would make it easy for them
to recapture the Senate seat. But now things look less certain.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have been unable to unify around any of their four
major candidates: an heir to a department store fortune; a trial
lawyer who led the state's lawsuit against the tobacco industry; a
state senator who owns a bar in northern Minnesota; and a
businesswoman who ran a Minneapolis housing agency.
</P>
<P>
   And, faced with a primary on Tuesday, unusually late in the
political season, the candidates have been forced to spend campaign
resources battling one another instead of Grams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grams is ripe for the taking, but so far nobody has really
jumped out as somebody who has a really good chance of taking
him,'' said Chris Gilbert, a political science professor at
Gustavus Aldophus College in St. Peter. ``Even if somebody emerges
with a comfortable victory in the primary, there just isn't much
time left.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four major candidates for Senate are millionaires,
and the primary for Minnesota's Democratic Farmer-Labor Party, as
the Democratic Party is known here, has emerged as the most
expensive in state history.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Dayton, a former state auditor, is heir to the Dayton
Hudson department store fortune and has spent $4.6 million, most of
it his own money. Mike Ciresi, a trial lawyer who orchestrated the
state's $6.6 billion settlement from tobacco companies, has spent
about $3.4 million, financing more than half of it himself. And
Rebecca Yanisch, a construction company executive who also led the
Minneapolis Community Development Agency in the 1990s, a housing
agency, has spent about $1.5 million, a third of it from her own
pocket and some of the rest from Emily's List, which raises money
for Democratic women who support abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   The only candidate who has raised so little money that he could
afford only one last-minute television advertisement is the
candidate who has the party's official endorsement, state Sen.
Jerry Janezich, who owns Tom and Jerry's Lounge in Minnesota's Iron
Range. He has spent about $300,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the endorsed candidate and the only one who's been in
legislative office before,'' said a spokesman for Janezich, Troy
Matson. ``We're going to try and get the message out that he is the
only candidate who is like average Minnesotans.''
</P>
<P>
   Janezich's difficulty in raising money is partly due to his
humble style, political experts say. But it is also a sign of the
weakness of the Democratic Farmer-Labor Party. Its endorsement has
helped Janezich get labor support, but has otherwise made little
difference in fund-raising or the polls. Perhaps the most publicity
Janezich has received came when Jay Leno made him the subject of a
crude joke after he crawled under a table to thank union
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many years, Minnesota prided itself on having a strong
party system, on raising to the highest levels people who came up
through the party with distinguished careers in public service,''
said Steven Schier, chairman of the political science department at
Carleton College in Northfield. ``This is money buys ads, produces
votes. That's what's going on in the nation and it's coming to
Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton, who is well-known here, in part from previous
unsuccessful bids for governor and senator, has pulled ahead in
recent polls. But those polls, taken before last-minute campaign
blitzes by all four candidates, also indicate that a quarter of
voters are undecided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm assuming nothing,'' said Dayton, whose campaign has
included setting up a ``help line'' to assist people in resolving
problems with their health maintenance organizations, and taking
busloads of older people to Canada so they can buy cheaper
prescriptions.
</P>
<P>
   All four candidates, who agree more often than not, talk about
helping the elderly and farmers, and making health care more
affordable. Dayton favors immediate universal health insurance,
while Ciresi and Yanisch want to proceed more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Ciresi, second in the polls, favors normalized trade relations
with China. Janezich, third in recent polls, has a record of
supporting labor, the environment and other liberal causes.
Yanisch, who talks about her early life as a struggling single
mother and her brother's suicide stemming from depression over farm
crop failures, has positioned herself as the most moderate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there are any big issues in Minnesota,'' Schier
said. ``Minnesota is a hotbed of rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins the primary will have no trouble distinguishing
himself or herself from Grams, whose causes include a conservative
plan to privatize Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Grams, whose biggest legislative accomplishment has been the
$500-per-child tax credit, is still not in great political shape.
He has spent all but $1 million of the $5.6 million he has raised,
and a recent poll had his favorable rating dropping 9 points since
June, to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As for charisma, Schier said: ``Our politics are dominated by
two showboats,'' Sen. Paul Wellstone, a Democrat, and Gov. Jesse
Ventura, an independent. ``This guy isn't even a canoe.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Grams, Kurt Zellers, said the senator was aware
that political commentators had predicted his vulnerability, but
``he says it's awfully hard to feel vulnerable when you're out
there campaigning and people come up and say, `Thanks, Rod.'''
</P>
<P>
   And these days, no one in Minnesota thinks a Grams defeat is a
foregone conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think whoever the Democrat is, is still going to have a very
tough time beating Rod Grams,'' said Blois Olson, a former
Democratic consultant who now edits a Web site on Minnesota
politics. ``Rod Grams, whatever he's done or said, has run and
positioned himself among senior and rural voters as this American
champion for tax cuts, health care benefits and apple pie. And I
think people are beginning to think that he's being picked on or
targeted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
