<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 11:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7410 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-DENMARK-EURO-415(2TAK     09-09 1447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENMARK-EURO-415(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDENTITY CRISIS FOR DANES AS EURO VOTE NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VEJLE, Denmark _ ``For Krone and Fatherland'' scream the giant
posters at the annual congress of the nationalist Danish People's
Party, exhorting Danes to defend their currency and their very
nationhood.
</P>
<P>
   Denmark at risk? With its fat cows and flaky pastries, its neat
streets and nice queen, this pampered little land seems as foreign
to angst as any country could be. But appearances deceive, for
Denmark has an acute case of the identity crisis now afflicting
several European states.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate threat to Denmark, as perceived by Pia
Kjaersgaard, the successful leader of the People's Party, is a
referendum on Sept. 28 when Danes will be asked whether they wish
to preserve the krone or follow 12 other states of the 15-member
European Union in abandoning their money for a shared currency, the
euro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essential issue is the preservation of our sovereignty,''
said Kjaersgaard, who founded her party in 1995 and has seen its
support grow to more than 10 percent of the electorate. ``The euro
will erode our national authority and identity at a time when
Denmark is already becoming more and more multiethnic and
globalized.''
</P>
<P>
   To lump the euro with the arrival of foreigners and the effects
of global competition and conjure a three-pronged menace may seem
bizarre. But not necessarily in today's Europe, where concern about
the dilution of nationhood through European integration and
mounting immigration is widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Kjaersgaard's message has struck a chord. Opinion
polls suggest a virtual dead heat, with 48 percent of Danes for the
euro, 46 percent against and 6 percent undecided. ``I still hope we
will get the euro,'' said Marianne Jelved, the economics minister.
``But I cannot say I am confident, because the risk is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only to Denmark. This is a country of just 5.3 million
inhabitants, ``a mere tail to the German bulldog,'' in the words of
Ole Krarup, a law professor. But it has a special capacity for
clarifying the continent's mood because it is the only country that
votes regularly on how far Europe should integrate. A ``No'' vote
could snowball.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, it would further undermine the euro, whose
value against the dollar has plunged 25 percent in a year; delay
any possibility of Britain and Sweden joining the common currency,
and turn Kjaersgaard into a sort of Nordic version of Austria's
Joerg Haider, with an invigorated anti-European and anti-immigrant
message.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It might also expose the seemingly undemocratic nature of the
mainly German and French drive to create a federation resembling a
United States of Europe. Germans, for one, have never voted on such
an idea, or on the euro itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that rejection of the euro would give
Kjaersgaard an added hubris,'' said Jorn Thulstrup, a pollster and
political analyst. ``She'd be wheeled out across the continent to
say more European Union equals more control of small countries by
big ones and more open borders to allow the immigrant hordes in.''
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, identity politics are resurgent. Nationalist,
anti-immigrant parties thrive in Belgium and Austria. In Athens,
Greek identity is said by the Orthodox Church to be under threat
from a government plan to remove mention of religious affiliation
from identification cards.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, Guenter Verheugen, one of the country's top
officials at the European Union's headquarters in Brussels,
denounces the way the euro was introduced ``over the heads of the
people'' and demands a referendum on expansion of the the union
because of German fears of an influx of Poles and Czechs.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, the immigrants washing up from Albania and elsewhere
on the country's southern shores feed the patriotic salvos of
Silvio Berlusconi, whose New Right politics are once again on the
rise.
</P>
<P>
   As for Denmark, its Hamlet syndrome _ a recurrent hesitancy over
whether something is rotten in the state of Europe _ has reached a
new pitch, fed by fears that Peter Skaarup, a People's Party member
of Parliament, summed up as ``the growing anxiety that we won't be
masters in our own house anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   This Danish house has shrunk a lot over the centuries; it is
more of a bungalow today. Territory was lost in various wars
against Sweden and Germany, turning a regional power into a
powerless realm. Like other Europeans steeped in tradition and past
glories, yet aware of the demands of modernity, the Danes are
sensitive about what they have left.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've taken refuge in a sort of small-is-best,
if-you-can't-join-them-beat-them mentality,'' explained Jakob
Busti, the transport minister and a leading member of the governing
Social Democratic Party, which is campaigning for the euro.
</P>
<P>
   After 28 years in the European Union, Denmark is rich. It has a
low unemployment rate of 5 percent, sends 66 percent of its exports
to the other states of the union, has no security concerns and
would be less vulnerable to currency fluctuations and financial
speculators inside Euroland than out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does not take too many Salomon Brothers to empty the Danish
National Bank,'' noted Thulstrup, the political analyst. But nor,
it seems, does it take too many Danes to generate a broad
resistance to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the Danes rejected the Maastricht Treaty on European
Union, only to accept it a year later with slight modifications.
Now, there is a possibility that Denmark will reject the euro _ and
by extension Europe's political integration _ as an alliance of the
far right and far left backs the ``No'' campaign.
</P>
<P>
   On the right of this coalition sits Kjaersgaard, 53,
blonde-haired, blue-eyed, immaculate in a pale-lilac suit, diamond
bracelet glittering on one wrist, dripping disapproval and distaste
for what she sees as the dismantling of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we want to lose control of our lives with more and more
decisions made by the European Central Bank in Frankfurt or in
Brussels?'' she asked. ``Do we want this multiculturalism, this
multiethnicity, about which the country was never consulted? I say
we don't want either.''
</P>
<P>
   On the anti-euro alliance's left wing sit the likes of Krarup,
the law professor at the University of Copenhagen, a rumpled and
thoughtful socialist, distressed by what he sees as the erosion of
democracy in the ``crazy push'' for a European superstate.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Danes, Krarup was alarmed by the European Union's
imposition of sanctions on another small country _ Austria _ in
response to the inclusion of Haider's rightist Freedom Party in
government. Because the sanctions were widely seen as an
infringement of democracy and sovereignty, their imposition has
bolstered Danish opponents of the euro. (Other European states may
actually lift the sanctions before the Danish vote, after a report
on Friday by a panel of experts that said the sanctions are
counterproductive.)
</P>
<P>
   But ought a man of the left to share a platform with
Kjaersgaard? It is very awkward, Krarup confided. But then, this is
a time of collapsing certainties, of ``exponential change,'' so
such odd shifts of political ground could occur.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Denmark's newspapers suggest a time of transition.
They carry reports of immigrant crime and schools disrupted by
``second-generation immigrants'' _ the children of the Turks,
Pakistanis and others who came to work here in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In political circles, the immigrants causing such trouble are
now politely referred to as Ny Danskere _ New Danes. But the term
is problematic. Are the light-skinned then ``Old Danes?'' What
distinguishes the two? ``People often say `New Danes' because they
don't want to say `Not Danes,''' joked Buksti, the transport
minister.
</P>
<P>
   Joking aside, Denmark, like other European states, has gotten
itself in a tangle over immigration, and because both foreigners
and the euro are seen by many to subtract from Denmark, both are in
the snarl.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, in the charitable spirit of its traditional
Social Democratic outlook, Denmark welcomed foreigners; it handed
them a lot of welfare. The number of immigrants _ with papers or
awaiting them _ has risen steadily to 7.1 percent of the
population, from 6.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been a kind of giant, philanthropic buffet table,
inviting immigrants to come and help themselves,'' said Lene
Espersen, a conservative politician who backs the euro but fears
that ``the nightmare of a takeover'' is playing into the hands of
the anti-euro campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Lusin Canacki, 33, a social worker in the port of Arhus,
dark-eyed, olive-skinned, a Danish-speaking Turk, is alarmed by the
way the country has changed. She has been in Denmark since she was
6, has two children who are Danish citizens and is applying for
citizenship herself. But the country she would make hers is
becoming hostile, she feels.
</P>
<P>
   Today, she believes, Denmark is divided into ``us'' and
``them.'' ``We are told to get an education, learn the language,
learn Danish habits,'' she said. ``But when we do, we are still one
of `them.'''
</P>
<P>
   Canacki continued: ``People I know come up to me and say, `It's
not people like you, Lusin, that are a problem, it's all the
others.' But politicians and newspapers don't say `Except Lusin.'
We're all lumped together.''
</P>
<P>
   So strong has the Danish reaction against immigration been that
the government of Prime Minister Poul Nyrup Rasmussen recently
enacted legislation that may make Denmark less attractive to
foreigners. Among the laws was one barring any immigrants under age
25 from bringing a foreign spouse to Denmark.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was presented as an attempt to foster
integration _ by hindering arranged marriages between young Turkish
men or women in Denmark and people in Turkey, where the government
says about 90 percent of Danish Turks find their partner.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures made some welfare dependent on learning Danish
and put new pressure on immigrants to place young children in
kindergartens that charge fees. ``Our priority was to prevent the
spread of immigrant ghettos, the source of these immigrant gangs,''
said Pernille Blach Hansen, a Social Demorat.
</P>
<P>
   But that was not how Suhail Ibrahim, a 37-year-old Dane born in
Lebanon, saw the laws. After more than a decade as a Social
Democrat _ he arrived in Denmark from Beirut in 1986 _ Ibrahim quit
the party this year, saying that it was ``on the way to becoming a
racist party.''
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim, a Palestinian refugee, got his first passport from
Denmark, in 1994. But he said he no longer feels Danish, despite
having a Danish wife and two Danish children. ``Danes talk of
integration and then devise new forms of pressure,'' he argued.
</P>
<P>
   So, in June, Ibrahim founded Denmark's first immigrant party, to
wage a battle for the rights of foreigners. Canacki sees the idea
as a disaster, ``the beginning of war, and more and more
separation.''
</P>
<P>
   The two immigrants do not agree about the euro either. Ibrahim
opposes it as a first step toward possibly severe pan-European
legislation on immigration. Canacki favors the euro, because ``we
foreigners cannot afford a little Denmark, closing to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Danish government agrees with Canacki; it wants the euro
badly. The Economics Ministry has rushed out a publication showing
that Queen Margarethe, much beloved, will appear on one side of
Danish euro coins (the coins are to have differing national
symbols; all euro notes will be the same). ``The sight of the queen
on the coin,'' said Jelved, the economics minister, ``helps calm
fears about loss of identity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7416 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-KOSHER-CONTROV     09-09 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-KOSHER-CONTROVERSY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ISRAEL, SUDDENLY CUCUMBERS ARE NOT KOSHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Rabbi Shlomo Shmulevitz is director of the
commandments related to the Land of Israel for the Jerusalem
rabbinate.
</P>
<P>
   This was not a good week to ask him how he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oy vey,'' he said in Yiddish, then continued in Hebrew-spliced
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so tired with all this shmita business. Shmita, shmita,
shmita. Headlines about shmita! Talk radio about shmita! Who would
have ever imagined?''
</P>
<P>
   Who, indeed? Even in Israel, shmita, pronounced shmee-TA, is an
arcane subject. According to the Torah, shmita is the sabbatical
year when the land of Israel is supposed to lie fallow. It occurs
every seven years, and a new shmita is scheduled to begin at the
end of September on Rosh Hashana, the Jewish New Year.
</P>
<P>
   For a century, the start of shmita was not a matter of general
concern. A longstanding social agreement allowed Israeli farmers to
continue working their land provided that they nominally ``sell''
it to a non-Jew and get a deed of sale from the chief rabbinate.
The rabbinate, in fact, arranged the transaction. The average
cucumber consumer never knew the difference; everything was kosher.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, the cucumber cart was overturned by strictly
Orthodox rabbis who did not think the Torah bypass, originally
justified by the survival needs of the Zionist pioneers, could be
justified any longer.
</P>
<P>
   A leading Hasidic sage ruled that this year the deed of sale
would be invalid. This led the state-financed Jerusalem religious
council to announce that Israeli fruits and vegetables would not be
considered kosher during the shmita year, and that establishments _
grocery stores, restaurants, hotels _ selling them would risk
losing their vital kosher certificates.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, shmita exploded into a national controversy.
Incredibly, it managed to touch a panoply of raw nerves: the
religious-secular conflict, the Israeli-Arab conflict (the non-Jew
who ``buys'' the land of Israel is usually Palestinian), the
conflict between the new high-tech economy and the old agricultural
economy and the conflict between authorities within the Orthodox
world.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, one of Israel's two chief rabbis, Eliyahu
Bakshi-Doron, nearly resigned after he was threatened with being
``ostracized'' by part of the strictly Orthodox world for his
lenient position upholding the validity of the deed of sale. ``I
fear becoming a social outcast,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Ehud Barak intervened on his way to New York last
week, President Moshe Katsav summoned religious leaders to his
residence, a special rabbinical conference on shmita was hastily
assembled and a compromise was reached. The compromise included a
promise by Bakshi-Doron that next year he personally would eat only
fruits and vegetables grown outside the Land of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   That would include produce cultivated in the Golan Heights,
which, despite the right wing's protests to the contrary during the
short-lived Israeli-Syrian peace talks, technically doesn't belong
to the Land of Israel, according to Jewish law. It also includes
produce cultivated inside the Land of Israel that is grown in pots
of Golan Heights soil or on elevated platforms that do not
technically touch Israeli soil.
</P>
<P>
   The modern Orthodox, who are religious Zionists, have always
accepted the compromises on shmita, as put forth in a 24-page
booklet issued by their community's highest authorities _ the
country''s chief rabbis. It is a kind of, ``Everything you always
wanted to know about shmita but were afraid to ask,'' and contains
coping tips, such as computerizing sprinklers for home gardens.
</P>
<P>
   But the strictly Orthodox community is not Zionist and doesn't
recognize the authority of the state's rabbis, obeying instead the
rulings of their own sages. And for many years, those sages have
looked askance at the symbolic sale of the land during the shmita
year. Its economy diversified, Israel no longer depended on
agriculture to survive and, in the rabbis' opinion, the Torah's
commandments should only be skirted if survival was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the rabbis believed that the deed of sale was a sham;
Israel was not really sanctioning the wholesale transfer of its
agricultural lands to the Palestinians whose names were on the
documents.
</P>
<P>
   So religious farmers began letting their fields go fallow, and
strictly Orthodox communities shopped only at their own very kosher
establishments.
</P>
<P>
   Strict shmita observance, like not watching television, became
one of the things that separated the strictly Orthodox from the
modern.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Rabbi Yosef Shalom Elyashiv, a leading authority in
the strictly Orthodox world, changed his recommendation of strict
compliance with the shmita laws to an order.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what makes this shmita any different, Shmulevitz said: ``I
have no idea, and I would never ask. I am not on the great rabbi's
level.'' He added that he assumed it was a logical progression.
</P>
<P>
   Shmulevitz also said that the sage was misunderstood by the
secular public; he had proposed a moderate position, by allowing
produce planted before the shmita year started to be harvested and
sold during the sabbatical and by sanctioning the use of elevated
platforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mea Shearim,'' Shmulevitz said, referring to a strictly
Orthodox neighborhood in Jerusalem, ``they are calling him a
Zionist! And in Tel Aviv, they are calling him a religious
extremist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem religious council translated his order into a
practice that would affect secular farmers and consumers and, in
the eyes of many Israelis, impose the views of a very few on the
majority.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At a farming collective northeast of Ashkelon, Binyamin Elbaz,
52, a vegetable grower, stood in his hothouse and expressed his
suspicions. ``The only explanation is that the strictly Orthodox
are going to make a pile of money off the food they import from
Jordan,'' he said. An Orthodox import cartel is indeed what many
farmers suspect lies behind the move _ a suggestion which
Shmulevitz described as absurd. ``I look like I'm getting rich off
cauliflowers?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Elbaz said, he did what he usually does and
authorized rabbinical officials to ``sell'' the land from which he
harvests 30 tons of cucumbers and 150 tons of peppers a year. He
said he has no idea ``what individual Arab supposedly owns my
land.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a crock,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise reached by the rabbinical assembly is murky. The
chief rabbi backed down from an initial threat to dismiss some
Jerusalem rabbis and to impose on the Jerusalem rabbinate his
ruling that the deeds of sale should be respected in their
territory. He also agreed that local rabbinates could adopt
stricter positions than his, but they apparently accepted that they
would not be allowed to force shopkeepers to abide by their
stringency.
</P>
<P>
   The growers' associations say that if need be, they will market
their goods directly to the consumers, avoiding the markets that
depend on the rabbis for certificates.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers are confused. ``I've got to place my next order for
seeds,'' Elbaz said, ``and I don''t know what's going to develop
between now and the New Year. What do I tell my workers? Go back to
Thailand, the fields will be fallow this year?''
</P>
<P>
   The whole affair exacerbated the already growing tensions
between secular and religious here. Usually, it is the religious
who are urging Israel to leave alone the status quo that governs
the synagogue-state relationship.
</P>
<P>
   But, in proposing that shmita regulations be tightened, strictly
Orthodox rabbis were tampering with the status quo that they
usually guard so zealously. And that could backfire at a time when
Barak is proposing a ``civic revolution'' to curb the powers of the
religious parties. It could make the secular more avidly secular
and affect several ideas now on the table: the city of Herzliya is
preparing to open a new mall with Saturday hours, and the
transportation minister, Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, is proposing that El
Al fly on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a cultural war is left,'' read a headline in the
liberal-left Haaretz newspaper earlier this week, atop a column
asserting that secular Israelis should now feel empowered to
challenge the terms ``dictated by the ultra-Orthodox in the best
tradition of the Wild West.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
