u p BC-ALA-SELMA-ELECTION-NY     09-09 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-SELMA-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELMA'S MAYOR FACES HIS MOST SERIOUS CHALLENGE IN DECADES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SELMA, Ala. _ After 35 years, Mayor Joseph T. Smitherman's
high-wire act above the city's churning racial politics had begun
to settle into routine. Every four years, he would hold barbecues
in black neighborhoods, boasting about the number of black
department heads he had appointed, while reminding white voters
that he would be ``the last white mayor of Selma,'' hinting that
the racial deluge was around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   But this year, Smitherman has found himself in the fight of his
life, forced for the first time into a runoff election _ on Tuesday
_ against a black candidate, and the hints have become a bit less
subtle.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in the city that became the bloodstained symbol of the
fight for voting rights, the former segregationist is promoting
himself as the candidate of diversity, preventing city government
from being engulfed by blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everywhere that you've gone all black, the towns have gone
down,'' he said between cigarettes in his office, citing several
examples of black-run towns that have gone bankrupt. ``You need
white inclusion, you need diversity in the city government. Let's
face it, the whites have the money, the white business people. They
tend to pull back when it goes all black. So that's what I'm trying
to get across to the blacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfiltered and raw, appealing even to black fear of a ruined
economy, this is hardly the velvety approach of the typical New
South white politician. But racial politics in Selma has always
been a few degrees more blunt than average. Many of the city's
white business leaders _ the ones supposedly heading for the door _
shake their heads at Smitherman's argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Smitherman can call up Armageddon as well as any Southern
preacher, and that's what he's doing,'' said Richard P. Morthland,
chairman and chief executive of Peoples Bank and Trust Co., the
city's largest locally owned bank. ``I don't know of any business
that would leave town just because we have a black mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the mayor's arguments have proved remarkably
effective over the years. Though he was mayor on that bloody Sunday
in March 1965 when sheriff's deputies and state troopers attacked
hundreds of people marching across the Edmund Pettus Bridge for
voting rights, he argued persuasively that he and his police had
nothing to do with the beatings. He has made a career out of
renouncing his former support for segregation, making sure he
spread city services evenly in black and white neighborhoods. Now
70 years old, he has been re-elected nine times since 1964, despite
repeated efforts to unseat him by black candidates in a city of
21,000 that is now 65 percent black.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, James Perkins Jr., a former computer consultant,
came as close as anyone ever has to defeating him. Perkins won 43
percent of the vote, just 276 votes behind Smitherman at 46
percent. A second black candidate, City Councilman Yusuf
Abdus-Salaam, won 10 percent of the vote, forcing the two leading
candidates into a runoff on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Salaam, who leads the city's Muslim community, has accused
Perkins of ``religious bigotry'' and appears to be siding with the
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Perkins, 47, who has run against Smitherman twice before,
contends this effort will turn out differently. While black voters
are increasingly put off by the mayor's condescension, he said,
white voters are also disenchanted by Smitherman's performance.
Last year, the city's former police chief and former city clerk,
along with Smitherman's nephew, pleaded guilty to embezzling more
than $700,000 from the city through fraudulent billings. The mayor
said he knew nothing about the theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his job to know what's going on,'' Perkins said. ``And at
the same time, he's allowing a huge disparity in the quality of
life between black and white neighborhoods, and now he's trying to
divide the city by saying industry will leave if I'm elected. This
is obviously a mayor who's panicking.''
</P>
<P>
   Many residents say the mayor has not done enough to improve the
city's economy, which has suffered like much of the rural South
from a continuing drain of manufacturing jobs. (The county's
unemployment rate in July was 10.7 percent, compared with Alabama's
rate of 4.4 percent.) Racial tensions continued to bubble in Selma
long after the marches ended, particularly in 1990 when the city's
first black schools superintendent was dismissed and protests
closed the city schools.
</P>
<P>
   Although black officials now dominate the City Council and the
County Commission, there has long been an outspoken faction of
blacks, led by state Sen. Hank Sanders and his wife, Rose Sanders,
that has worked to remove Smitherman. The group has plastered the
city with posters saying ``Joe's Gotta Go,'' although the Sanderses
say they are not working directly for Perkins.
</P>
<P>
   But while Perkins and his supporters point to a few criticisms
of Smitherman's administration, their main argument against him is
that he has never really left his segregationist core. They liken
him to the late Gov. George C. Wallace as one who changed his
language to suit the times but could never escape his past.
</P>
<P>
   As often as he has heard it, this argument still infuriates the
mayor. Rummaging furiously through his office, he pulls out a
campaign flier showing that nine of 13 department heads are black,
and digs through drawers to unearth tributes he has received over
the years from black leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know I'm not the devil they say I am, but Selma's their
mecca,'' Smitherman said. ``They want Selma because this is where
it all happened, where people got the right to vote. What really
bothers them is that this place of all places has a white mayor,
but I still keep getting elected, don't I?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
