<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7442 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-ACTIVIST-PRIESTS-2TAK     09-09 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACTIVIST-PRIESTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEEN LOST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 NEARING RETIREMENT, PRIESTS ACTIVE IN 1960s FEAR THEIR LEGACY HAS By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Msgr. Thomas Leonard remembers the moment in 1962
when, inspired and enthusiastic, he was first allowed to turn from
the altar to face the congregation as he celebrated Mass at a
retreat at Manhattan College. It was the era of Vatican II, when
the Roman Catholic Church loosened strictures of magisterial
authority, while outside church walls, a turbulent world was
remaking itself day by day.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he was allowed to look out at his parishioners, the
priest thought he saw a new church taking shape. He would no longer
be heading a spiritual army bound for salvation, but become part of
a congregation striving for holiness. In churches from the Bronx to
Buenos Aires, communion rails and other borders were vanishing, and
young priests were interpreting the Gospels as a call to social
action. They fought for integration and school decentralization,
built housing for the poor, and spoke out on everything from
nuclear disarmament to the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   But today, as the priests who first embraced Vatican II prepare
for retirement, they fear replacement with a generation that does
not seem to share their values. The older generation moves with
self-doubt and a measure of disillusionment. While the evidence of
their activism still stands _ in working class apartments that dot
city neighborhoods, in youth centers and in revitalized urban
neighborhoods _ their social values no longer resonate as strongly
among many younger, more conservative priests. As the aging priests
turn to pass the torch to the next generation, many of the men who
are taking up the light seem like strangers to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, of our generation, there's a real sadness,'' said the
Rev. Peter Gavigan, pastor of Our Lady of Victory Roman Catholic
Church in the South Bronx, who was ordained in 1965. ``We're a
vanishing breed, and we're saying, `Wow.' We thought it would be a
golden age by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Msgr. John J. Powis of Brooklyn finds the change painful.
``There's even a feeling they're just waiting for us to go,'' said
Powis, whose life as a priest has included community organizing for
everything from subsidized housing to streetlights in Brownsville
and Bushwick. The dismay is not limited to New York, and does not
arise only from the return to traditionalism embraced by incoming
priests alone. Rather, older priests see their bedrock beliefs
doubted by the Vatican itself. While Pope John Paul II has spoken
out loudly and often in support of human rights, he has also
steadily held the line on innovations begun by the Second Vatican
Council, and selected cardinals from among his most conservative
priests.
</P>
<P>
   The uneasiness of the Vatican II-era priests grew in recent
weeks as the beatification of Pope Pius IX, who confined Jews to
Rome's ghetto and abducted a Jewish child to be raised as a
Catholic, advanced in step with that of John XXIII, father of the
Second Vatican Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council, which met from 1962 to 1965, ushered in a raft of
changes aimed at making the Catholic Church more accessible to the
faithful and more attuned to secular life. Its 16 documents gave
lay people a role in running parishes, replaced the Latin used at
Mass for local languages, and gave priests a voice in church
matters. Vatican II identified the promotion of human rights an
integral part of the church's mission, and reversed the church's
age-old insistence that Jews were responsible for the death of
Jesus. It said Catholicism did not represent the only path to
salvation _ a groundbreaking statement that the Vatican has begun
to reconsider in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1987 book, ``Dreaming About the Church'' (Sheed &AMP; Ward),
the Rev. Walbert Buehlmann, the former secretary-general of
Capuchin Missions in Rome, wrote that the Second Vatican Council
once seemed ``to trace out a whole new future for the church.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why hasn't the promise been kept?'' Buehlmann asked. ``Can we
ignore the current mood of disenchantment and resignation, or can
we come to terms with it?''
</P>
<P>
   In a confidential letter written in March, the archbishop of
Milwaukee, Rembert G. Weakland, prepared his 400 priests for the
conservative successor he expected after he retires. ``It seems
that we are now coming to a period of more uniformity, less
creativity, and less space for personal preferences,'' said the
archbishop, whose letter was obtained and published by the National
Catholic Reporter, a lay weekly.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop suggested that the retrenchment answered the
yearnings of Catholics today. ``The younger generation needs more
structures, clarity and guidance,'' he wrote. ``For those who put
their heart and total energy into the implementation of Vatican
Council II, this new period might seem sterile and empty. I hope
and pray not.''
</P>
<P>
   According to periodic nationwide surveys of thousands of priests
by Dr. Dean R. Hoge, a professor at Catholic University in
Washington, and the National Opinion Research Center in Chicago,
since the 1980s priests have grown increasingly conservative on
theological questions like celibacy in the priesthood and the
ordination of women. Hoge's research shows that the youngest and
oldest priests share similar views, while the generation of Vatican
II stands isolated between them.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 article, Hoge predicted a professionalized priesthood
that would be ``smaller in numbers, more conservative in
ecclesiology, more pressured by leadership responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Katarina Schuth, a sociologist at St. Paul Seminary
School of Divinity in Minnesota who surveyed faculty and students
at 42 seminaries last year, found important differences between
today's seminarians and those of earlier years. Nearly half the
schools' 2,300 students had converted from another religion or
returned to Catholicism after leaving their faith. English was a
second language for one in four.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   These factors contribute to the conservatism of many young
priests, Schuth said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, only about 10 percent of seminarians are
extremely conservative, but their influence far outweighs their
numbers, largely because they tend to have the support of bishops.
Schuth quoted one longtime priest who had told her, ``Only in these
past few years is the word of first-year theologian taken to be
more credible than mine.''
</P>
<P>
   In their gloomiest moments, aging priests and nuns see Vatican
II not so much as the dawn of a more open, inclusive church, but as
an anomalous thunderbolt of progressivism sandwiched between a past
and future that recoil from change and unfettered debate.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Msgr. Harry J. Byrne, as chancellor of the New
York archdiocese and chairman of its Social Justice Task Force,
issued guidelines calling on priests to work for social change.
``Constructive activity in the secular community,'' the task force
said, ``is not an `extra' for priests in parishes, but an essential
part of their ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, priests trained in political activism toil largely behind
the scenes, counting themselves lucky for any support from their
bishops. Others work with immigrants or the poor, not so much
challenging systems as giving out sandwiches and finding other ways
to help people individually. As they discuss their disappointments
over the years, most express fear of appearing bitter or defiant in
print.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne, now retired, lives in an Upper East Side Manhattan
high-rise for working class New Yorkers that was built with federal
and local housing funds in the 1960s. Each Tuesday night, he dines
with a group of other retired priests, who share no illusions that
their values still hold sway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newer priests don't want to work in the inner cities,''
Byrne said. ``They like nice clean white cuffs, pressed
surplices.'' He and his friends also worry about the small number
of young men who are joining the priesthood. In his day, dozens
completed seminary each spring. Now, annual ordinations for the New
York archdiocese can be counted on the fingers of one hand. (It is
the second largest archdiocese in the country, with 2.4 million
Catholics.)
</P>
<P>
   Because their numbers are so few, Msgr. Vincent Fullam, rector
of the Seminary of the Immaculate Conception in Huntington, N.Y.,
considers men who choose the priesthood these days ``heroic, or the
next thing to it.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of aging priests, like Msgr. Philip J. Murnion, wonder
what went wrong. In 1968, he wrote a daring report calling on the
New York archdiocese to open its financial books and to give
priests and lay Catholics a greater say in decision-making. Signed
by more than 500 priests, the report likened discontent in the
church to a revolution. But he now thinks his generation may have
moved too far, too fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our desire to extend the meaning of the sacred, did we end
up with a situation in which nothing is sacred?'' asked Murnion,
who heads the National Pastoral Life Center in New York. Today, he
said, redemption is what happens to food stamps, and Madonna is a
rock star.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
