<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7444 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-COX-DEBATES-0910-1stl     09-09 1494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-DEBATES-0910-1st </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 lede &HT;    VOTERS MAY PUNISH BUSH FOR DEBATE STANCE, HISTORY SUGGESTS
 &HT;    1030&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories
for release Sunday, Sept. 10.
 &HT;    Eds: Note new 13th graf reflecting Bush camp decision to meet
with Gore debate team this week.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By rejecting the traditional presidential debates,
George W. Bush is making the same strategic error that doomed his
father's 1992 campaign, experts say: talking too much about his
opponent, and not enough about the voters.
</P>
<P>
   In the final months of a presidential campaign, ``the message
from voters is, 'I want to hear about me. I don't want to hear
about (the candidates) any more,' `` said Celinda Lake, a noted
Democratic pollster.
</P>
<P>
   No event of the entire sprawling presidential campaign draws the
attention of voters like the face-to-face encounters sponsored by
the bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates.
</P>
<P>
   Three times as many voters watch these nationally televised
debates as the party conventions. In 1992, the viewership
approached 100 million people. And about 35 percent of the voters
make their candidate choice based on the debates, according to exit
polls from the 1992 and 1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate who skips the debates, or who tries to negotiate
substitute formats that lengthen the distance between candidate and
voter, is likely to pay a stiff political price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debates are essentially the final job interview for
presidential candidates,'' said Diana Carlin, a University of
Kansas communications professor who serves on the debate
commission's advisory panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only time you have the candidates in the same place,
the only time you can really compare them side by side,'' added
Carlin. ``And if all they do are shows like 'Meet the Press' and
'Larry King Live,' a lot of people are going to say, 'Wait a minute
_ this was totally candidate-controlled, and there was no chance
for the public to have input.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Carlin's conclusion is based on a dozen years of research for
the debate commission created in 1987 by a coalition of Democratic
and Republican luminaries.
</P>
<P>
   Lake's assessment is cast in starker political terms: ``There's
no way someone is up to the job of president if he won't even
debate an opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not try to avoid debates altogether. But he proposed a
substitute plan that not only eliminated two of the three 90-minute
debates proposed by the commission, but also favored friendlier
formats with a smaller viewing audience.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor also omitted the format preferred the most by
voters: the town hall meeting, in which voters themselves, rather
than a moderator or panel of journalists, do the bulk of the
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Bush compounded his problem by promoting his plan in a way that
even his own campaign officials now acknowledge was a mistake.
Recalling Gore's vow to debate him ``any time, any place,'' Bush
argued that Gore's credibility was in tatters. He even taunted the
vice president in a TV interview: ``Let's get it on, Mr. Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a ludicrous argument,'' an unidentified Bush adviser
acknowledged to the New York Times on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   These problems in the Bush camp finally led to a breakthrough of
sorts: An offer to meet with the Bush handlers sometime this week
in a bid to strike a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gore has long been regarded in political circles as a
gifted debater with a quick command of facts and a taste for the
jugular.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush, despite his success in Republican primary debates
against the likes of Sen. John McCain of Arizona, has yet to bury
the doubts about his intellect that were triggered by his woeful
handling of a TV reporter's pop quiz on the names of world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has given the people the feeling that he's afraid to meet
Gore,'' said Larry Sabato, a political science professor at the
University of Virginia. ``Bush doesn't want to be followed by a guy
in a chicken costume, which will happen soon if this isn't
resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   Hecklers dressed in chicken costumes and holding signs that read
``Chicken George'' started showing up at the rallies of President
Bush in 1992 in an effort to prod him into debates with Clinton,
the Democratic challenger, and Ross Perot, who ran as an
independent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Texas governor's father and namesake, eventually
agreed to meet Clinton and Perot in three debates. One of them
sheds light on his son's political problems this year.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bush had built his general election strategy upon
questions about Clinton's patriotism and already tarnished
character, a tactic that had some success against the 1988
Democratic nominee, Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   But at the second presidential debate of 1992, a town hall
meeting in Richmond, Va., audience member Kimberly Usry challenged
Bush to stop ``trashing'' his opponent's character and start
discussing ``the genuine complexity'' of the issues, especially the
economic recession that had cost her a job in marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded with a defense of his attacks on Clinton's
character, insisting, ``it's fair to put it in focus.'' But when it
came time for Clinton to respond, the challenger agreed with Usry
and took credit for insisting on the town hall format that allowed
her to raise issues directly with the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In Carlin's post-1992 election research, David Wilhelm, who had
managed the 1992 Clinton campaign, observed: ``Bush kept trying to
make the campaign about Clinton, and the American people wanted the
campaign to be about them _ their problems, their hopes, their
dreams, their economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since accepting the Democratic presidential
nomination, Gore has taken up where Clinton left off.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's populist appeals to ``working families'' have filled the
policy void left by Bush's emphasis on his own character as a
political antidote to the personal disgraces of Clinton and, by
extension, Gore, his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush seems to have gotten the message well before his father
did in losing to Clinton in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   After the worst three weeks of his candidacy, the governor is
retooling his campaign to include more intimate gatherings with
voters, talking more about issues and less about Gore's faults.
</P>
<P>
   The hasty restyling apparently includes a new willingness to
negotiate a compromise over the debate stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush was vowing to be in Washington, D.C., on Tuesday to
debate Gore in a prime-time edition of ``Meet the Press,'' even
though NBC officials said the show would not be broadcast without
both candidates.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   How far Bush will go toward a compromise is far from clear, even
though nearly everything in presidential debates is negotiable,
even under the plan already suggested by the commission: formats,
statement and rebuttal times, camera angles, set designs, lighting.
</P>
<P>
   Such negotiations are as old as the Lincoln-Douglas debates
about slavery before the Civil War. ``They had their own debate on
the debates,'' said Carlin, ``only it was by couriers on horseback
instead of on TV and in the newspapers.''
</P>
<P>
   Carlin said it was politically astute for Bush to stake out a
debate position rather than simply accepting the commission's
recommendations outright. ``Every candidate wants a comfort
level,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she argued that the approach most favored by voters _ three
90-minute debates of varying formats, each devoted to four of the
top 12 issues, with longer response times _ gives candidates a
greater opportunity to find that comfort level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having just one debate raises the stakes, and it gives you no
opportunity to recover from a gaffe or to clarify something,'' she
said. ``Candidates are going to gain more if they're giving the
public something they want.''
</P>
<P>
   But too often, Carlin added, candidates are poorly served by
their more strategic-minded campaign handlers, who often
underestimate the candidate's abilities and inadvertently negotiate
away their comfort zones.
</P>
<P>
   She cited a 1996 town hall debate in San Diego. Dole strategists
worried about Clinton moving close to the audience, the way he did
in 1992 in Richmond. To prevent wandering, they demanded that the
area in front of the podiums be marked with tape.
</P>
<P>
   When Dole arrived to inspect the stage, he asked about the tape
in the shape of a baseball coaching box in front of the podium.
Informed that the candidates could not move beyond the tape, Dole
demanded, ``You mean I can't move around?'' He heatedly pointed out
that his political career began with town hall meetings in Russell,
Kansas. But his negotiators had, quite literally, boxed him in.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   www.debates.org
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's email address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
