<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7475 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CHENEY0910-COX     09-09 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Record clear: Cheney votes were conservative as foes portray
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Four hundred eight of 417 House members voted for a
proposal in March 1988 to allow federal employees to donate
vacation days to colleagues who faced a medical or family
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Armey, Tom DeLay, Newt Gingrich, Trent Lott and Dennis
Hastert were among the 165 Republicans who voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, then Wyoming's lone representative in the House,
was one of nine Republicans who voted no. That vote came during
Cheney's last full year in the House of Representatives. He would
become Secretary of Defense early in George Bush's administration
the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential nominee George W. Bush picked Cheney as
his running mate in July. Since then, his voting record has been
picked over in a haphazard fashion _ a vote here and there to
illustrate whatever point someone has wanted to make about the man.
</P>
<P>
   An examination of Cheney's full voting record in 1988 brings
into even sharper focus where he stood in the House throughout his
10-plus years in Congress _ among its most conservative members.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on allowing federal workers to donate unused vacation
days to a colleague was one of dozens in which he voted against
even the overwhelming majority of fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of 29 members, all but one Republican, to oppose
compiling hate-crime statistics for crimes committed on the basis
of race, religion, ethnicity or homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   In a vote that has already drawn a lot of attention, Cheney was
one of four Republicans to oppose banning handguns which lack a
sufficient amount of metal to be picked up by metal detectors in
airports and other settings
</P>
<P>
   He was among 51 members who voted against the banning of lawn
darts, which killed or seriously injured several children in the
late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He frequently sided with President Reagan, although he broke
with the administration at times, including a vote in which he was
one of 18 members to oppose financial aid for drought-stricken
farmers. He received a 100 percent rating from the American
Conservative Union in 1988. The Americans for Democratic Action
gave him a zero.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely is almost a Libertarian in the sense that he
doesn't want the federal government to be involved in almost
everything but national security and foreign policy,'' said James
Thurber, a political scientist at American University. ``Just
because someone gets hit in the head with a lawn dart, or several
people, he doesn't want the federal government dealing with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Thurber, who studies Congress, described Cheney as an
``ideologue,'' but one whose demeanor with his colleagues was
always pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   Another political scientist, who once served as an intern in
Cheney's congressional office, rejected the characterization of
Cheney as an ideologue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that Dick Cheney is an extremist ideologue is
absurd,'' said William Connelly of Washington and Lee University in
Lexington, Va. But, ``there is no question he is a small-government
conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   The 100th Congress that finished its work in 1988 drew
widespread praise as the most productive in years.
</P>
<P>
   It capped costs for Medicare recipients who were struck by
catastrophic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   It toughened welfare requirements and provided the first
significant federal money for AIDS programs and expanded assistance
for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   It banned plastic handguns and reversed a Supreme Court ruling
that weakened civil-rights laws to protect women, racial and
religious minorities and the disabled from discriminatory
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   It forced employers to provide 60 days' notice before closing
plants and strengthened enforcement of the federal fair-housing
law.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney opposed all these measures, except the last two, which he
did not vote on, among the 98 recorded votes he missed in 1998
(more than a fifth of votes taken in the House), according to vote
tallies maintained by Congressional Quarterly.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 12 years, Congress enacted the 13 major
appropriations bills to pay for government operations. And it
accomplished that task on time, avoiding the catch-all bills that
conservatives complain are often larded with pet projects and
wasteful spending. Cheney voted for only five of those bills.
</P>
<P>
   Juleanna Glover Weiss, a spokeswoman for Cheney at the
Bush-Cheney campaign headquarters in Austin, Tex., said that Cheney
routinely opposed spending bills in his time in Congress, an era of
deficit spending.
</P>
<P>
   The drought-relief bill was ``too expensive,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Cheney's votes ``were cast in opposition to or protest
to the heavy-handed tactics of Democratic leaders at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Weiss cited the practice of bringing up bills for
consideration on the House floor ``under suspension of the rules.''
This procedure allows bills to bypass the legislative routine,
including being subject to amendment, and limits debate on the
House floor to a total of 40 minutes. It is most often used for
noncontroversial bills.
</P>
<P>
   She said Cheney's vote against donating vacation days could be
explained by his opposition to the suspension procedure. ``An issue
that important should not be considered with limited debate and no
opportunity for amendment,'' Weiss said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gary Ackerman (D-N.Y.), the sponsor of the legislation,
recalled it differently: ``It was completely noncontroversial. We
thought that was a great humanitarian compassionate gesture and
really didn't cost the government anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, Cheney often voted for legislation that was
handled in similar fashion. Indeed, in 1988, Cheney voted 80 times
for legislation that was brought up under suspension of the rules.
Weiss said that in those cases, the legislation was either routine
_ naming of a building, for example _ or so vitally important that
it needed to be moved along quickly.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
