<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Election is too early to call
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ Will Rogers said he wasn't a member of any
organized political party _ he was a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   After this past week, you could say the same about being a
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush couldn't seem to say anything right,
with the possible exception of his characterization of a New York
Times reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, who went into the conventions looking
like a sacrificial lamb and came out a hooking bull, continued to
stay even or slightly ahead of Bush in the national polls.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Republicans have stopped thinking of Gore in the
past tense, which, as if they need reminding, is ``Gored.''
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, same as most everybody else, I would have bet money
on Bush as the next president. I don't know exactly where he went
wrong, but it was somewhere on the road leading out of
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   His choice of Dick Cheney as a vice presidential running mate
didn't help. The man comes across as reserved to the point of
seeming arrogant, which is hard to imagine _ an arrogant
Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Good ol' Joe Lieberman, the orthodox Jew who Gore tapped as his
vp sidekick, has managed to do what was even more difficult to
imagine _ cast the Democratic Party in a godly light.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to Joe you can't help but think of Job.
</P>
<P>
   That must come as quite a shock for those righteous
right-wingers who equate the G.O.P. with G-O-D.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, something to always keep in mind: Not all Republicans
are of the same mind.
</P>
<P>
   There are two distinct varieties, prayerbook Republicans and
pocketbook Republicans, each easily identified.
</P>
<P>
   Prayerbook Republicans are fierce moralists, hard-core
pro-lifers, the party of the ``Thou Shall Nots.''
</P>
<P>
   Pocketbook Republicans are of the free market persuasion, devout
believers that the answer to peace and prosperity for everybody is
having more money in their pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Think of them as the ``Thou Shall Not Make Rules'' party. The
best way to make a lot of money, they say, is ot to have a lot of
rules.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, for example, is as good a pocketbook
Republican as you'll find.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning for the GOP nomination for president in 1996 and
being pressed on social issues, he put it this way: ``I'm running
for president, not preacher.''
</P>
<P>
   Well said. Never mind that he lost.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said as much, though with a prayerful nod to the
brethren. Asked by Barbara Walters whether he considered it a sin
to be gay, he said he was not going to define sin, that he was a
sinner himself.
</P>
<P>
   Well said. And keep in mind that he won _ leastwise, the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   There remains a great divide between prayerbook Republicans and
pocketbook Republicans. But overall, it's a conservative message,
which is what holds them together, especially when the only
alternative is the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with almost two months before election day, best that
you hold all bets on who will be our next president.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is a senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address
is jmurray(at)txucom.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
TX, 75915; website, http://www.coxnews.com/newsservice
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
