u e BC-REVIEW-ELMORE0910-COX     09-09 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ELMORE0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: Embargoed for Sunday.
 &HT;    Leonard cranks out a winner _ again _ with `Pagan Babies'
 &HT;    By Ron Rollins
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ In an Elmore Leonard novel, there is only one
truism: Everybody's up to something.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, everybody includes Terry Dunn, a con man whose
latest gig has folks thinking he's a Roman Catholic priest _ which
lets him get away with a lot.
</P>
<P>
   It also includes Debbie Dewey, who did time for nailing her
conniving ex with the front bumper of her Buick. Because he
survived, she wants to get back the money he scammed from her,
which is what made her mad in the first place. Debbie wants Terry's
help and figures out he isn't a priest just in time to take him to
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Randy is the ex, and he's trying to turn the restaurant he
bought with Debbie's stolen cash into Detroit's hottest nightspot.
He makes it so hot, in fact, that the mob shows up and tells him
not only will he start running their cal girls from his bar, but
he owes them eight large a week for the privilege.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Mutt, the addlebrained ex-con to whom Randy
turns to settle a few scores. The Mutt welcomes the chance to start
a brand new career as a hitman. After all, this is Detroit, and
there'll always be work for one _ right?
</P>
<P>
   Right. As usual with Leonard, the characters and schemes and
money all crisscross and double back on themselves at a pace that
seems both breakneck and subtly unhurried. In short, he tells
stories like nobody else working and tells them in a way no other
writer can touch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pagan Babies'' starts in Rwanda, of all places, where Dunn is
putting on the Father act for people who've survived that nation's
machete-swinging, genocidal civil war, and need somebody to confess
to. Dunn steps outside the normal channels of penance when a cold
killer goes a bit too far with his good graces, and skips to
Detroit until the air clears.
</P>
<P>
   While he's there, he bumps into Debbie. She bumps back, and
before you know it, they're up to their collars in mob deals,
threats and back stabbing that keep us guessing right up to the
very last page.
</P>
<P>
   After 37 books, Leonard is darn good at this stuff _ and so
beloved by critics and crime readers that the reviews of his work
seemed hackneyed for all the praise. A gazillion reviewers have
noted his knack for jaded, lone-wolf antiheros who manage one
last-minute act of heroism. A billion more have spoken in hushed
tones about the dead-on, perfect pitch of Leonard's dialogue, and
scads of lesser writers (OK, they're all lesser) have tried to ape
his style without even realizing that's what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard is so darn good, in fact, and gives the impression of
such effortlessness, that his artistry can be missed, taken for
granted. Setting his novels so often among the underworld rabble of
Miami, Detroit, Atlantic City, N.J., and LA may give the whiff of
sameness but pay it no mind. Plunge in and enjoy. Breathe deep the
aroma of gunpowder and laundered money, after-hour bars and
fear-sweat _ and don't mind that man behind the curtain. It's just
Elmore Leonard, once again manipulating people's basest motivations
for our grand entertainment, and getting away with murder.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
