<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SLAUGHTER-HONORS0910-     09-09 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAUGHTER-HONORS0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WW II vet finds honor after 54 years of shame
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITMAN, Ga. _ A World War II veteran with a Purple Heart and
Bronze Star has finally gotten the white discharge papers that
eluded him for more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   When J. C. Slaughter, 78, left the Army in 1946, he was given
what he thought was a dishonorable discharge, printed on blue
paper. Honorable discharges are printed on white. Although
Slaughter had won medals, including the Combat Infantry Badge, to
him the blue paper _ which indicates a discharge under ``other than
honorable'' circumstances _ was the only memento of his military
service that counted.
</P>
<P>
   It was his blue badge of shame.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never knew anything about Daddy's military service,'' said
his only child, Viola Slaughter-Frazier of Lake Wales, Fla. ``He
never discussed that time.''
</P>
<P>
   About 15 years ago, Slaughter finally told his daughter what had
happened. She began trying to right what she felt was a wrong done
to her father.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, an Army review board recommended Slaughter's
discharge be upgraded to honorable, making him eligible for
treatment in a veteran's hospital, a free headstone and burial in a
national cemetery, said W. W. Osborn, who reviewed Slaughter's case
for the Army's Review Boards in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter grew up in the tiny Pidcock community west of Quitman,
finishing the fifth grade before quitting school to help on the
family farm. He was 20 and married when the Army drafted him to
serve in the infantry in 1942. A month after being sent into combat
in Italy, he was wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``They started firing at us and we got the order to withdraw,''
Slaughter said. ``But we couldn't so we started to dig in.''
</P>
<P>
   The first mortar shell fell three feet away but didn't go off,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second one went 'boom' and knocked the other guy right out
of the foxhole and killed him dead,'' Slaughter said. ``It blew a
big hole high up here on my leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter spent three months in a Naples, Italy, hospital, then
returned to his unit though his leg hadn't healed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was still raw and had stitches in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was assigned to a field kitchen. ``But another officer told
me to get up to the front lines. I told him I wasn't able to make
it, that my leg wouldn't hold up,'' Slaughter said.
</P>
<P>
   He sustained ``multiple, moderately severe, penetrating shrapnel
wounds to his right thigh'' and was also suffering from mental
trauma, an Army report said.
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter said he wasn't fit for combat. He believed he would
been killed because he couldn't move around well.
</P>
<P>
   Army authorities said it would serve no purpose to punish
Slaughter for disobeying the order because he was, one report said,
``a soldier whom the medical experts in effect say is not normal
under battle stimuli. This soldier had been wounded and this wound
was no doubt the cause of his unusual fear and nervousness.''
</P>
<P>
   The Army court martialed him, gave him a life sentence and sent
him to an Italian prison.
</P>
<P>
   During his two years in prison, Slaughter's wife divorced him,
sending Viola to live with his mother. Prison life was grim and
food was scarce.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote his mother, asking her to send him a cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``They read my letter and put me in the sweat box for 14 days,
just for asking for a cake,'' Slaughter said. Slaughter's life
sentence was reduced after another military psychiatrist examined
him in March 1946, and also found his punishment unreasonable.
Slaughter, he said, was ``rather inarticulate and reacts with naive
directness to most situations . . . if restoration (to the Army) is
not considered it is recommended that he be separated from the
military service with a white discharge on the basis of mental
deficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months later, Slaughter, over 6 feet tall but weighing
just 135 pounds, was shipped to Texas, given his blue discharge and
told to go home.
</P>
<P>
   He bought a bus ticket to Birmingham, Ala. ``I had to get Mama
to wire me some money to make it the rest of the way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He moved in with his mother and Viola, then 4. He later married
a woman who helped him raise his only child. He farmed and did
construction work, eventually making $5 an hour. His wounded leg
always bothered him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept feeling something in there and I kept picking and
pulling and finally pulled some stitches out,'' he said. ``I still
have a shell fragment in my leg now. It bothers me whenever it
clouds up.'' Until he was 70, he'd never seen another doctor, his
daughter said. ``I finally made him go,'' she said. Slaughter's
sense of shame over his blue discharge bothered him most, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although his discharge was actually ``other than honorable,''
Slaughter always believed it was dishonorable.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Army has given him an honorable discharge, people
keep asking how much money he'll get. He doesn't know, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to build a six-room house for me and my wife,'' he
said. He and his wife, Bertha Mae, live in the cramped frame house
built 100 years ago by Slaughter's grandparents on flood-prone land
near a railroad track. Bertha Mae, now 74, does shift work at a
factory.
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter will receive no financial restitution, Osborn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court martial was legal,'' Osborn said. ``We're not saying
anything wrong happened to him back then. We're saying the
situation is now unjust. I'm terribly sorry there's not a pot of
gold associated with this. The guy could have a Medal of Honor and
the Army wouldn't give him enough money to build a house.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Osborn said, Slaughter did disobey a direct order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very essence of military discipline depends on people
doing what they're told,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter's daughter doesn't agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did to my daddy was wrong and they knew it was
wrong,'' she said. ``I guess I'll just have to keep fighting until
they make it right.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
