<HEADER>
A7486 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-09 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS: ARIZONA, MARYLAND, CONNECTICUT, LOUISIANA, 1976 
</HEADLINE>
   By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arizona GOP Race Rife With Dirty Tricks
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Ariz., is not running for re-election this
year in his state's 1st Congressional District. But the betting is
that the district will remain in Republican hands _ unless the
Republicans battling for their party's nomination in Tuesday's
primary self-destruct and the lightly regarded Democratic nominee,
David Mendoza, ekes out a victory come the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the five Republican hopefuls _ Susan Bitter Smith and Tom
Liddy _ have been accusing each other of engaging in convoluted
dirty tricks. To wit:
</P>
<P>
   Liddy, a lawyer and the son of G. Gordon Liddy (he of Watergate
dirty tricks infamy), says Bitter Smith, a cable television
executive, slipped him a file that contained personal information
about a third candidate, Jeff Flake, former executive director of
the Goldwater Institute. As Liddy tells it, Bitter Smith then urged
him to leak the file to reporters, something he says he refused to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter Smith contends she gave the file to Liddy only after he
requested it. She says she received the file only after one of her
campaign workers obtained it without her knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Flake has steered clear of all this, saying only that he has no
secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, The Arizona Republic, the state's leading
newspaper, suggested that Liddy and Bitter Smith resolve their
differences by taking lie detector tests.
</P>
<P>
   Both agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The tests were given on Monday _ by different examiners, with
each candidate helping to word the questions.
</P>
<P>
   And?
</P>
<P>
   Both passed _ and immediately pledged to focus on issues in the
remaining days before the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Prayers Are Answered If Only Symbolically
</P>
<P>
   Religion is back in the political news, this time in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   A lengthy drought there has parched fields and forests that
usually are all but awash in water, killing crops and leaving piney
woodlands ready to explode in fire. So 10 days ago, Gov. Mike
Foster issued an official proclamation asking Louisianans to pray
for rain.
</P>
<P>
   That was too much for Joe Cook of the Louisiana chapter of the
American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   Cook told The Advocate of Baton Rouge that the governor, a
Republican, had crossed the constitutional line that separates
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Foster countered that elected leaders all over the United States
often called for prayers in times of disaster and hardship. Cook,
he suggested, should ``get a life.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, some sprinkles fell.
</P>
<P>
   Did the prayers work?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rained today, didn't it?'' the governor replied.
</P>
<P>
   The Same Old Song With a Different Beat
</P>
<P>
   During the 1976 presidential campaign, when President Gerald
Ford was trying to fend off a challenge by Jimmy Carter, Ford's
White House chief of staff, Dick Cheney, helped draw up the defense
plan.
</P>
<P>
   So would that old plan provide some insight into what Cheney
might now be telling his running mate, Gov. George W. Bush?
</P>
<P>
   The plan is not available, if it ever existed on paper. But
after the election, Cheney wrote a lengthy paper on how Ford ran
the race, and that paper is at the Ford presidential library in Ann
Arbor, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Cheney was advocating 24 years ago:
</P>
<P>
   Erode Carter's support by portraying him as not experienced
enough to be president. Lure him into debates that leave him
appearing ``fuzzy and indecisive'' and out of his depth when asked
for ``specific views on major national issues.'' Exploit
perceptions by some voters that he is arrogant, lacks humility and
tries to be ``all things to all men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believed,'' Cheney had said, ``that support was susceptible
of erosion once the public came to know him better.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoa! Isn't that Al Gore's plan?
</P>
<P>
   Nasty Divorce Battle Finds Home in Politics
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Albert R. Wynn of Maryland's 4th Congressional District
almost certainly will win a fifth term this fall. He is a black
Democrat and his district, on the outskirts of Washington, is
mostly black and mostly Democratic. Further, his Republican
opponent, John Kimble, who is white, has failed in two earlier
challenges to draw more than 15 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kimble is no quitter. In his first run, he offered to
pose nude for Playgirl magazine in an effort to gain attention and
raise money. This time around he has recruited the congressman's
estranged wife, Jessie, to work in his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And some work she is doing ...
</P>
<P>
   The Wynns are in a bitter divorce and child custody battle.
Jessie Wynn, who is black, has this to say in a 20-second message
that Kimble is circulating in the 4th District by random telephone
dialing:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, this is Jessie Wynn, wife of Congressman Albert Wynn.
Albert Wynn does not respect black women. He left me for a white
woman. Please send your donations to Kimble for Congress. Help us
defeat Albert Wynn.''
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Wynn also appears in a photo posted on Kimble's Web site.
She is standing next to a red banner that reads, ``Al Wynn left his
black wife and child for a white woman.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimble acknowledges he is ``playing the race card'' with the
Jessie Wynn attacks. He says it's the only way to beat the
congressman.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn's response:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hell hath no fury ...''
</P>
<P>
   A Nader Supporter Voices 2nd Thoughts
</P>
<P>
   The way Bert Garskof of Bethany, Conn., saw it during the 1996
presidential election, another Connecticut boy, Ralph Nader, was
the best man for the job. So Garskof, a psychology professor at
Quinnipiac University, working on the Internet, worked with Nader
supporters in a dozen states.
</P>
<P>
   That was then. This is now _ and now Garskof has a problem. He
is married to the sister of Sen. Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate that while Nader, now as in 1996, has no chance
of becoming president, he has enough support to steal some votes
from Al Gore in some states, no small thing in a close election. Or
as Garskof put it the other day, something he helped start now has
``a potential to hurt something I believe in.''
</P>
<P>
   What to do?
</P>
<P>
   He has begun warning Nader supporters not to ``throw away''
their vote on a ``dream,'' arguing that Nader, for all the good
things he supports, like a cleaner environment, cannot win. Go with
someone who can win, he says, go with Al Gore and brother-in-law
Lieberman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
