<HEADER>
A7498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NICARAGUA-LAND-ART-2T     09-09 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NICARAGUA-LAND-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMONG UNPAID WAGES OF A REVOLUTION: COMPETING CLAIMS ON LAND IN
NICARAGUA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) By DAVID
GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAGAROTE, Nicaragua _ Where Emilio Aguilar once raised cattle,
hundreds of families now raise their children.
</P>
<P>
   Small houses line bumpy dirt roads cut through what were the
pastures of Aguilar's 200-acre ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar fled to Honduras after the Sandinistas declared him a
counterrevolutionary in 1979, and since then mayors in this town
about 25 miles northwest of the capital of Managua have handed out
plots to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilar returned to Nicaragua in 1991 to reclaim his land, or at
least get compensation. In 1993, the government offered him 15-year
bonds with a face value of $340,000, but he refused to settle
because the securities were denominated in Nicaraguan cordobas, a
currency that has lost about half its value since then.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Aguilar is intent on suing the mayors who gave away his
ranch. If that day ever comes, Exhibit A could be the site of the
courthouse itself, since it is in the middle of his old spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put the courthouse here saying it was to impose justice,
but they did it on stolen land,'' said Aguilar, 65. ``I feel this
is all a joke. If there was justice, they would have gotten this
legally.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade after the elections that removed the
Sandinistas from power, thousands of Nicaraguans _ as well as about
900 American citizens and even the descendants of the country's
former dictator, Anastasio Somoza _ are grappling with the legacy
of the Sandinista revolution: confiscated land, homes and
businesses that were distributed to peasants and party loyalists
alike.
</P>
<P>
   While few people expected to get back all they owned, even
skeptics decried what they described as convoluted, lengthy
administrative and legal processes that too often result in paltry
settlements paid in low-value government bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Untangling the property disputes has proved vexing for the
government, which has little cash and lots of concerns about the
social unrest that could result from dislodging thousands of people
who acquired land through urban development plans and agrarian
reform laws that were legitimate at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine having to say to someone, `You have to leave the land
you had for the last 15 years of your life,''' said the foreign
minister, Eduardo Montealegre, whose own family has yet to recoup
its confiscated properties. ``You either have to resolve it with
new land from the state or pay bonds to the old owners. It is not
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Nicaraguans said that resolving complex and competing
property claims is the biggest hurdle to attracting foreign
investment in the Western Hemisphere's second-poorest nation.
(Haiti is the poorest.) The task grows more complicated with time
because current property holders are selling the land to new buyers
_ including the president, Arnoldo Aleman, who purchased a farm
from an agricultural cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is happening in this country regarding property is
serious denial of rights,'' said Lino Hernandez, the president of
the Permanent Commission of Human Rights of Nicaragua. ``If there
is no solution to the property question, there will be no security
or investment in this country. Ten years have passed, and we feel
powerless that we cannot find a solution to this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In its 11 years in power, the Sandinista government confiscated
about 170,000 properties, including many that were seized right
before it relinquished power in 1990 to the administration of
democratically elected President Violeta Chamorro. Property claims
began soon after she took office, increasing under pressure from
American lawmakers who urged her government to settle claims of
Nicaraguans who became American citizens while in exile.
</P>
<P>
   Finance Minister Esteban Duque Estrada did not respond to
repeated requests for an interview, nor did the official in charge
of evaluating property claims. The Finance Ministry's Web site
indicates that more than 7,000 people have filed claims for 17,000
properties, with almost 6,800 claims pending resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Most claims that have been resolved were settled with 15-year
bonds that currently trade for about 20 cents on the dollar of
their face value. Not many more landowners are willing to wait 15
years for the bonds to mature and for the government to pay their
face value. There were expectations that the bonds would be
bolstered by profits from the sale of state-run industries, but
Aleman's administration scuttled those hopes.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the plan had proceeded, it would have meant little to
the Willey family of Tampa, Fla. In 1951, John Willey, a
Californian who moved to Nicaragua to mine gold, set up an electric
company in Matagalpa. The company stayed in his family until the
Sandinistas nationalized it in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the power company had 6,000 customers. It has since
grown to about 32,000 customers, and on Tuesday the government is
scheduled to sell the company to private investors for anywhere
from $500 to $1,000 a customer. Willey's heirs have been waging an
unsuccessful battle to receive what they regard as a fair price for
their share of the company. While they estimate they could be
entitled to as much as $9 million, the Nicaraguan government in
1998 offered them bonds with a face value of 2.3 million cordobas,
then about $216,000, but which they could have sold immediately for
only $38,000 _ about half what they had been offered in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did my grandfather give a lot to that country, but he
built it for his descendants, and I think the Nicaraguan government
should be fair,'' said Carrie Willey-Gagnon, Willey's
granddaughter. ``I don't know if we're ever going to get anything
at this rate. I do not believe the Nicaraguan government is willing
to give up a chunk of what they believe is their property.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite letters from U.S. diplomats and congressmen, the
Nicaraguan government has yet to resolve the issue.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government could withhold foreign aid if it felt that
claims on confiscated properties were not being resolved, but it
issued a waiver earlier this month that kept the aid flowing. At
the same time, the U.S. government has urged Nicaragua to take
steps to increase the value of the bonds and make them a more
attractive option.
</P>
<P>
   But a bill recently introduced by Rep. Benjamin Gilman, R-N.Y.,
would require the U.S. president to submit to Congress the 50 most
pressing claims by U.S. citizens and prevent the president from
overriding a block on aid until the claims had been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is the Nicaraguan government has grown
complacent,'' said a congressional staff member. ``They think they
will automatically get the waiver and that they are somehow
entitled to it. But this cannot be business as usual. People are
very upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Montealegre, the foreign minister, said that the Aleman
administration had resolved more than 1,300 property claims _ at
least four times the number managed under Chamorro.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that one or two particular cases have not been
resolved does not mean others have not, and we are making an effort
to resolve all,'' he said. ``It is complicated. We have problems in
health, education and housing. We have much poverty the Sandinistas
left us with. It has set us back years. No country is giving us
foreign aid to pay for property. The majority of the people
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sandinistas, now in a strained alliance with the Aleman
party in the National Assembly, said they favored efforts to
compensate people whose property was given to others. But they also
said it was important that the country continue its current program
of granting land title to thousands of people who are occupying
small plots of land for homes and farms. Edwin Castro, a Sandinista
member of the National Assembly, said that land titling was as
important as reparation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we legalize it, and if we want to talk about guarantees to
private property, then we should talk about guaranteeing the
property of all people,'' he said. ``But you cannot raise the flag
of private property to favor 500, 50, or 20 claimants to the
detriment of a half million people.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was any failure in the revolution, Castro added, it was
not proceeding quickly enough with granting property titles to new
owners.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people seeking to recover property are relatives of
the dictator dislodged by the Sandinistas. Led by Luis and
Alejandro Sevilla-Somoza, two U.S.-born nephews of the dictator
Anastasio Somoza, the Somoza family has so far had no luck, saying
their case is politically untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   The Somoza nephews insisted that the bulk of their properties,
from stock holdings to vast farms and estates, were obtained by
their grandfather legally. Like others who have been frustrated in
reclaiming their land, they have bought some of it on the open
market. They said they wanted their day in court, however, to begin
to clear the family name.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the last excuse of the revolution,'' said Luis, ``the
evil Somozas who raped the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The family, like others who have lost property, said Sandinista
officials benefited from the confiscations, including party leaders
who still live in luxury homes taken from exiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, what have they done?'' said Alejandro.
``They transferred the wealth from one group to another group. And
who pays for it? The people of Nicaragua.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro dismissed the idea of returning property to the former
dictator's relatives or to his soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ask about returning the property of the National Guard
or the Somoza family,'' he said. ``That's why there was a
revolution. No one with a historical consciousness would accept
that Versailles should be given back to the French royalty. No one
would dare say that because it would be a historical absurdity.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``For Sale'' signs are tacked to fence posts and telephone poles
along the road to El Volcan, a 257-acre farm that belonged to
Genaro Molina's family until the Sandinistas gave it to an
agricultural cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest business for the cooperative farm these days is
selling real estate, as members of the cooperative sell parcels to
people seeking to build houses. With developments being built to
accommodate a flood of people from the city, the region is rife
with speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people who have bought from the cooperative are an
American citizen, the sister of a judge and the leader of a
political party.
</P>
<P>
   Molina and the government have yet to agree on how much he
should be compensated for the land, so last year Molina decided to
take back a tiny piece, where he built a guard house and put up a
sign warning potential buyers that the property is in litigation.
Since then he has been able to buy back some of the land from the
cooperative for about $5,700 an acre, less than half the $14,300 an
acre he thinks it is worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took this part by force, so let them take me out,'' Molina
said. ``The Molina family is clear. We will take this to the end.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
