<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-ART-3TA     09-09 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAMARANCH-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMARANCH: OLYMPIC SAVIOR OR SPOILER? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ When the Summer Games begin here on Friday,
Juan Antonio Samaranch will preside over his final Olympiad before
retiring next year, having transformed the modern Olympic movement
to where it has never been more successful, or more threatened.
</P>
<P>
   When Samaranch, the former Spanish ambassador to the Soviet
Union, became president of the International Olympic Committee in
1980, the organization was nearly bankrupt and was caught in a
maelstrom of boycotts that continued through the 1984 Summer Games
in Los Angeles. Now, as Samaranch prepares to step down next July
at age 81, the IOC generates $900 million a year in revenues,
mostly from television and corporate sponsorship. NBC television
alone will pay $3.5 billion to broadcast the five Games between now
and 2008.
</P>
<P>
   Boycotts are no longer a serious threat; cities are eagerly
bidding to play host to the Games; corporations are shelling out
$50 million apiece to become official Olympic sponsors; athletes
can build long, lucrative careers as professionals; and women are
involved in larger numbers than ever as administrators and
participants.
</P>
<P>
   During his presidency, Samaranch has increased the number of
female IOC members from zero to 13 and the percentage of female
Olympians from 21 percent to 42 percent. Athletes from 199 nations
will participate in Sydney, compared with 80 at the 1980 Summer
Games in Moscow, which more than 50 countries, including the United
States, boycotted.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Pierre de Coubertin, the French baron who
founded the modern Games in 1896, Samaranch ``has been the most
significant leader in modern Olympic history,'' said John MacAloon,
an Olympic historian and professor of social sciences at the
University of Chicago. ``The greatest single accomplishment has
been a kind of political maturity, an ability to deal with
political elites, heads of state, industrial elites. That was
something the movement never really had.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the IOC, the Sydney Games will reach a record
audience, about 3.7 billion of the 3.9 billion people worldwide who
have access to television. Even David D'Alessandro, the president
and chief executive officer of John Hancock and Samaranch's most
vocal corporate critic in the wake of the Salt Lake City bribery
scandal, has signed on for another four years of Olympic
sponsorship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling in the end was that the Games were going to emerge
hurt, but not fatally wounded,'' D'Alessandro said. ``I'm
encouraged that what the Olympics stand for continues to grow. No
one really believes in the efficacy of professional sports. There
are an awful lot of clouds around college sports. The Olympics are
the last kind of major sport people can believe in the purity of.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Olympics have been devalued by scandal and
the pervasive use of performance-enhancing drugs, and they have
grown so big that they have become in some ways unmanageable for
the host cities. Sydney, which will welcome 700,000 visitors,
10,438 athletes and 21,046 media representatives, struggled with
its train service and airport baggage handling system even before
the crush of arrivals began. And the New South Wales state
government, which is underwriting the Games, had to issue bailouts
of $56.7 million in May and $84.8 million in June to organizers
because the cost of the Sydney Games had escalated to $1.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While almost no one believes the Olympics will end any time
soon, Olympic officials, sponsors and independent experts cautioned
that a failure to address these threats could affect the survival
of the Games in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will ever be again a golden age of the
Olympic movement as existed between the Games of Los Angeles in
1984 and Atlanta in '96,'' said John Krimsky, a former executive
director of the United States Olympic Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Donna de Varona, a gold medalist in swimming in 1964, has long
been an activist for women's sports and a prominent figure in the
fight against doping. She said she sees troubling similarities
between the current Games and the ancient ones, which had problems
with professionalism, corruption, cheating and bribery before
collapsing after a millennium in 393 A.D. It was 1,500 years before
the Games were revived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are on parallel tracks,'' de Varona said. ``I think
the Games are coming to an important crossroads.''
</P>
<P>
   Corruption Uncovered  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corruption, drugs and the unwieldy size of the Games can be
attributed to two things, Samaranch's supporters and detractors
say. First, in his attempt to return the whole world to the
Olympics after crippling boycotts in the 1970s and 1980s, Samaranch
made a number of decisions based on strategy or expediency rather
than principle. Second, he seldom said no.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch also made a habit of co-opting his enemies, saying,
``It is better to have them inside than outside.'' But sometimes
that strategy came back to embarrass him.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Claude Ganga of Congo Republic had been an anti-apartheid
activist who led the African boycott of the 1976 Summer Games in
Montreal. In 1986, Samaranch made him a member of the IOC, and
problems with African participation dissolved. But last year, Ganga
came to represent the most brazen example of the corrupted bidding
process.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ganga, an investigation revealed, accepted more than $300,000 in
cash payments, medical treatment, travel expenses and even
doorknobs and knee-replacement surgery for his mother-in-law while
Salt Lake City was trying to win the bidding for the 2002 Winter
Games.
</P>
<P>
   How did Samaranch, a man of such political savvy, allow the
bidding process to become so corrupted, leading to the resignation
or dismissal of Ganga and nine other of the IOC's 113 members?
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons, say those who have studied the
Olympic movement or who know Samaranch. Samaranch is an imperial
man who likes to be pampered, said John Lucas, an Olympic historian
and retired professor at Penn State University.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Ramsamy, an IOC member from South Africa, said Samaranch has
longed for a Nobel Peace Prize and perhaps in the final years of
his presidency he did not want to ``rock the boat'' and threaten
his legacy. Samaranch was a sports bureaucrat and a parliamentary
leader in Spain during Franco's dictatorship, D'Alessandro noted,
when a good deal of corruption was tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Samaranch had snapped his fingers, this wouldn't have
happened,'' Lucas said. ``He either was unaware, looked the other
way or thought it was harmless. What we need is an IOC that is
incorruptible, like Eliot Ness made the FBI. We need a group of
individuals wedded to the Olympic principles, nonpolitical
individuals who cannot be bought.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch said in a recent interview that he should probably
have retired after the 1992 Summer Games in Barcelona, Spain. Yet
in 1995, he pushed through a rule change that raised the age limit
for president so that he could continue. It was also Samaranch,
having realized the seriousness of the Salt Lake City scandal, who
pushed through a number of reforms. The leader who in the past had
been secretive and autocratic threw open the IOC's books, pushed
through term limits and persuaded members to vote against visiting
the cities that are bidding on the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our organization was hurt, but not the Olympic Games,''
Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
   Polling done by the IOC and the USOC shows that people have made
a separation between corrupt officials and the Games themselves.
Mitt Romney, the venture capitalist brought in to save the Salt
Lake City Games, said that the scandal, construction noise and
traffic problems had made him uncertain whether he would vote to
hold the 2002 Winter Games in Utah if he had to make the choice
now. But he also said that Salt Lake City was obligated to put on
the best Games possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the Olympics as the last great demonstration of peace in
the world,'' Romney said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sydney Games carry some of the same tarnish as Salt Lake
City. Sydney won the 2000 Summer Games by two votes over Beijing;
the night before the vote, Sydney officials promised $35,000 apiece
to IOC members from Kenya and Uganda. And both Australian IOC
members were implicated during the recent scandal investigations,
one for excessive travel in the Salt Lake City case and for helping
to write dossiers about his fellow members; the other for giving
his daughter a preferred place in the Olympic torch relay.
</P>
<P>
   The Salt Lake City scandal also confirmed for a number of
athletes and their representatives what they had believed all
along, that they were a low priority with the IOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Olympics could end as far as I'm concerned,'' said Jos
Hermens, a distance runner for the Netherlands at the 1972 Munich
Games who is now a sports agent. ``They have no meaning. It's a
false dream. They build the illusion of brotherhood, but it's just
a commercial venture. It's a bunch of old people misusing
old-fashioned dreams for their own purposes. It's like a cult.
These people are addicted to power.''
</P>
<P>
   How the power shifts after Samaranch's retirement will be of
great interest to U.S. corporate sponsors, which account for about
70 percent of the IOC's commercial income. D'Alessandro, of John
Hancock, said that given the scrutiny of the Salt Lake City scandal
by the American sponsors, Congress and the media, anti-American
sentiment within the IOC has never been higher. If this sentiment
keeps the Games from returning to the United States soon, he said,
American sponsors will drop out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to be careful not to have the American public turn
on them,'' D'Alessandro said. ``When you enter a Faustian bargain
with sponsors, you better have people around who understand
Faustian bargains.''
</P>
<P>
   Drug Problems  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At an IOC meeting in East Berlin in 1985, Samaranch presented
Erich Honecker, the East German president, with the highest honor
he could bestow, the Olympic Order. It was another pragmatic move
by Samaranch, who, a year after the Eastern bloc boycott of the
1984 Games in Los Angeles, was seeking to head off further boycotts
at the 1988 Summer Games in Seoul, South Korea. It worked. East
Germany competed in Seoul the year before the Berlin Wall fell.
</P>
<P>
   But awarding the Olympic Order to Honecker, an honor that had
also been bestowed on Manfred Ewald, who was president of the East
German Olympic Committee, was roundly criticized as giving at least
tacit approval to state-sponsored doping _ a system that was long
suspected and has since been revealed in courts and in released
documents.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Ewald was convicted of masterminding the doping program
in East Germany and was given a 22-month suspended jail sentence.
In a country where sport was used to validate Communist ideology,
the doping system affected as many as 10,000 athletes, many without
their knowledge. A number of the athletes now have heart, kidney
and liver problems.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to curb the East German doping program, which was an
open secret, ``is the Olympic movement's biggest failure,'' said
Rob Housman, an associate of Gen. Barry R. McCaffrey in the White
House drug policy office. ``They knew this stuff was going on. For
years, it was willful blindness.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only after the French police uncovered widespread doping at the
1998 Tour de France did an embarrassed IOC rededicate itself to the
problem of performance-enhancing drugs. For too long, the IOC
treated the issue as a public relations problem instead of a drug
problem, said Frank Shorter, the 1972 Olympic marathon champion,
who will head an independent drug-testing agency in the United
States after the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every 14-year-old kid knows that to be in strength and
endurance sports, if he wants to go on with his career, `I have to
go on these drugs,''' Shorter said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug use has become so pervasive that cheaters have been caught
recently even in table tennis, badminton and synchronized swimming.
Samaranch suggested last year that only drugs that are considered
harmful to an athlete's health should be banned. An uproar
followed, and he backed down. He created the World Anti-Doping
Agency, meant to be independent of the IOC, then decided he wanted
to head the agency. Governments around the world, however, rebuffed
his attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC did make one significant change for the Sydney Games,
approving a blood test for the endurance drug known by its initials
as EPO, which is believed to be widely used in distance running,
cycling and swimming. Independent monitors will also try to make
sure positive results are not covered up, which had been widely
suspected in the past. ``We've come a long way, but we've got a
long way to go,'' said McCaffrey, the White House drug policy
director.
</P>
<P>
   Drug tests will not be available in Sydney for human growth
hormone, insulin growth factor and products that serve as a kind of
artificial blood.
</P>
<P>
   Testing still remains so deficient that athletes cannot prove
their innocence, and athletes at the Sydney Olympics will have to
live with the suspicion that accompanies successful performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, the IOC is scared about what could happen if a
large number of great athletes were caught,'' said Ian Thorpe, the
Australian teen-age swimming sensation and an anti-drug advocate.
``What would their image be? I think something has to be done in
the long term or the Olympics will be absolutely ruined.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch's resolve on the drug issue was again called into
question last month when the International Amateur Athletic
Federation, track and field's world governing body, cut in half the
two-year ban on Javier Sotomayor, the Cuban world record-holder and
1992 Olympic champion in the high jump. Sotomayor tested positive
for cocaine at the 1999 Pan American Games. Cocaine can serve as a
stimulant during competition. Samaranch kept quiet, allowing a
known drug user into the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been helpful to say, `I won't allow this athlete
into my Games,''' said de Varona, the 1964 swimming champion and a
member of the World Anti-Doping Agency's ethics committee.
``Instead, he turned his head and compromised himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Matters of Size
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch has lobbied the presidents of North and South Korea to
march as one country during the opening ceremonies on Friday in
Sydney. Iran and Iraq, also mortal enemies, will file into the
stadium, one behind the other. More than any other moment in sport,
the opening ceremonies of the Olympic Games demonstrate the
possibility of an international community. The growing size of the
Games, however, has threatened their ability to be well organized.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago in Atlanta, bus drivers frequently got lost and
the IBM computer system could not deliver results in a timely
manner. Anita DeFrantz, an American IOC member, suggested that
Sydney residents avoid using the city's buses and trains for
non-Games activity.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, known as ``gigantism'' among Olympic officials, has
limited the number of cities that can afford to be host of the
Games and has become so acute that significant changes in the
organization of the Games are being proposed. Princess Anne, an IOC
member from Britain, has called for the removal of all team sports.
A number of people have suggested rotating the Games among a few
cities or establishing a permanent site.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch opened the Olympics to professionals after the 1988
Seoul Games as a way to bring the world's best athletes to the
Games. This ended what many believed was the hypocrisy of
amateurism and allowed athletes to build careers over several
Games. But it also made athletes less dependent on the Olympics;
they can now earn a living in their sports, which have yearly
competitions and world championships that offer prize money.
</P>
<P>
   Professionalism also has created tedium in some sports; in
basketball, for example, the American men's Dream Teams have gone
unchallenged. The end of the Cold War, too, has eliminated the
supercharged political drama that once accompanied competitions
between the United States and the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see the Dream Team there, the NHL players, I think the
Olympics has lost its purpose, perhaps,'' said Bruce Arena, coach
of the U.S. men's national soccer team, who was the Olympic coach
in 1996. ``When millionaires are winning gold medals all the time,
it takes away from the Olympics I remember 40 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Olympics were growing so large and unmanageable, the
IOC separated the years in which the Winter and Summer Games took
place after 1992. Sponsors and various national Olympic committees
were finding it prohibitive to spend so much money in one year.
Now, there is a Winter or Summer Games every two years.
</P>
<P>
   But the increased frequency has cost the Olympics their novelty,
and they must compete for attention on crowded sports calendars.
This is especially true this month, when the Games coincide with
baseball's pennant races and football in the United States and
soccer in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've lost the symbolism that this is a powerful event, held
once and only once every four years, and an important connection
with a kind of Greek and calendar model in which people live their
lives in four-year increments,'' said MacAloon, the Olympic
historian.
</P>
<P>
   A year from now, none of this will be Samaranch's problem. It
will be up to the next generation of leaders to combat the problems
of corruption, drugs and size. Relevancy could also become an
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing one has to guard against is that over time,
professional events, or events that have commercialism, have run
their course,'' D'Alessandro, of John Hancock, said. ``We've seen
it happen in the NFL and the NBA. They wax and wane. The Olympics
have been on the rise. There's going to be a trough period where
there may not be as much interest. That's a challenge for the new
players.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
