</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FTC-VIOLENCE-REPORT-415&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC SAYS INAPPROPRIATE ENTERTAINMENT IS MARKETED TO YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Federal Trade Commission plans to release a
report on Monday that harshly criticizes the film, recording and
video game industries for marketing violent, adult-rated
entertainment to young people, said several officials familiar with
the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that, despite voluntary rating and labeling
systems adopted over the years, all three industries have used
marketing strategies to entice young consumers to buy products that
the industries themselves deem inappropriate. They do this largely,
the report contends, by placing advertising in publications and
television broadcasts that appeal to youth.
</P>
<P>
   In its recommendations, the FTC does not call for legislative
remedies or tougher regulation, each of which could run afoul of
First Amendment protections of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   But the report does call on the entertainment industry to adopt
stringent policies _ including the threat of sanctions _ that would
prohibit the marketing of violent movies, recordings and video
games to children. The officials said the report encourages the
industry not to advertise on television programs that are popular
with children under 16 or in time slots when they are most likely
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   It also calls on producers and retailers to better educate the
public about their rating and labeling systems. Individual
retailers, it says, should enact rules, like those adopted recently
by Kmart, Wal-Mart and Toys ``R'' Us, that prohibit the sale of
mature-rated video games to anyone under 17. The report also
recommends that the industry not market to children any action
figure from R-rated movies or M-rated video games.
</P>
<P>
   While the report was tightly held this weekend, some on Capitol
Hill said they had been informed of its essential thrust.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an ongoing, knowing, systematic marketing of
adult-rated products to an underage audience,'' said Sen. Sam
Brownback, R-Kan., who called for the investigation. ``It's along
the lines of how Joe Camel is marketed to children.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., who has also been active on the
issue, said, ``They are going to find that there has been a
conscious targeting of children with violent media content.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton requested the review more than a year ago in
the aftermath of the massacre by two teen-agers at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., and after other school shootings where
the assailants were thought to be desensitized to violence.
</P>
<P>
   FTC Chairman Robert Pitofsky will release the report and hold a
news conference on Monday morning. Clinton plans to comment on the
findings at an event in Westchester County, N.Y., later that day.
</P>
<P>
   And on Wednesday, the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science and
Transportation, which is led by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., will
hold a hearing on the report. Among those scheduled to testify are
Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., the Democratic vice-presidential
nominee and a longtime crusader against the marketing of sex and
violence.
</P>
<P>
   A number of industry leaders are also expected to testify,
though many top film studio executives have thus far declined to
attend, according to committee aides. The entertainment industry
has been jockeying with Washington for years over violent content.
Some members of Congress, including Lieberman, have threatened
stricter regulation while industry leaders have argued that no
other business has so constrained its own sales by agreeing to
voluntary ratings and labeling.
</P>
<P>
   The officials who are familiar with the report said that much of
the most damning information came from the industry's own files.
The trade commission analyzed marketing plans for a number of
adult-rated products and found evidence that advertising strategies
were devised at least partly with youngsters in mind, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the R-rated movies that were studied, nearly two-thirds had
marketing plans that included children who are not supposed to see
the films without a parent, the officials said. Of the M-rated
video games studied, more than half had such plans. For recordings
with parental advisory labels, the figure was about a quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC also found that retailers _ whether movie theaters or
video game stores _ do not always pay much attention to ratings.
Mounting an undercover operation using youngsters under 17, the FTC
found that the children could obtain tickets to R-rated movies
about half of the time they tried. About 85 percent of the time,
the children were able to buy M-rated video games, which the
industry has determined are suitable only for those 17 or older.
</P>
<P>
   Eric London, a spokesman for the FTC, declined to confirm the
details of the report. But, he said, ``This report goes far beyond
percentages and the most interesting part is some of the evidence
based on the industry documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, said he had not read the report but resented the obvious
analogy to the government's treatment of the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tobacco kills people,'' he said. ``And tobacco is not
protected by the First Amendment. I don't want us grouped with
tobacco, and that's what these recommendations do.''
</P>
<P>
   Valenti said that children have such pervasive access to
television that it would be difficult, and unfair, to restrict
advertising to times when youngsters would not see it. ``I have no
doubt that our companies have made mistakes in the past,'' he said,
``but to make the leap from a trampoline and say that it's the
policy of our companies is outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Lowenstein, president of the Interactive Digital Software
Association, said surveys show that most video game players are
over 18, and that 90 percent of those who buy video and computer
games are adults. Therefore, it is the responsibility of parents,
he said, to pay attention to the violence ratings the industry has
imposed on its members.
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein said his group had recently formed an advertising
review council to monitor and police industry practices, and that
it does not condone the marketing of mature-rated videos to
underage consumers. But, he said, ``recommendations that put the
government in the position of regulating people's access to content
is something we would be deeply troubled by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
