<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINE-KIDNAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR HOSTAGES RELEASED BY PHILIPPINE REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ More than four months after 21 people were
seized in their beach clothes from a remote diving resort, the last
four Westerners were freed Saturday from the Philippine jungle by
Muslim rebel kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   The ransom for the final French, German and Finnish hostages was
reported to be $1 million each, part of $25 million promised to the
kidnappers by Libya, which has acted as a go-between.
</P>
<P>
   Gaunt and bearded, Marc Wallert of Germany raised his arms in
the air when he stepped off a helicopter after 140 days in
captivity. ``It feels great!'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the hostage-taking is not over. The gunmen are still holding
two French television journalists who trekked into the mountains to
interview them in July and 12 Filipino evangelical Christians who
paid $3,000 plus 50 sacks of rice to be allowed into their camp to
pray.
</P>
<P>
   The last of the original 21 hostages _ the lone Filipino among
them _ also remained in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   A separate band of kidnappers from the same rebel group, Abu
Sayyaf, is holding an American, Jeffrey Schilling, 24, a Muslim
convert from California who went to visit them, apparently out of
curiosity, on Aug. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Over the months, the kidnappings have been marked by
incompetence, violence, secret payoffs and fitful releases
punctuated by dozens of new kidnappings. Promises have been made
and broken as the kidnappers have feuded and fought among
themselves over their spoils.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's release effort almost collapsed when two go-betweens,
accompanied by the chief kidnapper _ a man nicknamed Robot because
he can dance like Michael Jackson _ were ambushed by men with
automatic weapons and grenade launchers. Government negotiators
said one bodyguard was killed and eight others wounded, along with
a large number of civilians.
</P>
<P>
   The chief Philippine negotiator, Roberto Aventajado, said the
attackers were a rival rebel faction. Though he refused to say so,
the go-betweens were believed to be carrying ransom money with
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were not sure at all of being released today,'' said one of
the freed hostages, Stephane Loisy of France. ``We heard the
shooting where we were located. And suddenly we were taken in a car
and we were actually freed.''
</P>
<P>
   The remaining hostages face an uncertain future. The releases so
far have been slowed by demands for more and more money and by the
kidnappers' fears of a military offensive once their hostages are
gone.
</P>
<P>
   The military has held back in response to the demands of the
Western governments whose citizens were being detained. With the
release of the last of those hostages, Vice President Gloria Arroyo
Macapagal said Friday, ``it's possible that we may change our
tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   A Libyan envoy, Rajab Azzarouq, said negotiators would now seek
the release of the two French journalists. According to local
reports, they were not released Saturday because the Libyans
declined to pay for them. Negotiations for the release of Schilling
may be even more difficult. He is being held by a faction that has
tortured and killed previous hostages and that is reported to be
angry at the American, who is said to have argued with them and
tried to break out of his holding pen.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has stated that as a matter of policy, it
would not pay ransom or make deals for his release. In response, a
spokesman for the kidnappers repeated a threat to kill him, telling
a local radio station this week, ``The United States may have a
policy, but we also have our own policy.''
</P>
<P>
   With the going rate for the hostages set at $1 million each, the
spokesman said earlier that he thought an American ought to be
worth 10 times that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Kidnapping for ransom is a well-established business in the
islands of the Sulu Sea, which have been home to pirates and
bandits for centuries. Abu Sayyaf, a tiny breakaway rebel band,
seized the vacationers, along with several local workers, from the
a Malaysian island on April 23.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnappers received $5.5 million for their first 11 releases
of Malaysian and German hostages, the Philippine military said.
Libya paid another $6 million two weeks ago for six more Westerners
_ a German, two South Africans and three French women.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they have been paid for releasing a dozen other
journalists who were seized when they went to interview the
hostages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
