<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-BACH0910-COX     09-09 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BACH0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Bach the man' is lost in 'Bach the musician'
 &HT;    By Michael Barnes
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Christopher Wolff's biography of Johann
Sebastian Bach, published on the 250th anniversary of the
composer's death, is so dry it could absorb the Elbe, Oder and
Rhine rivers of his native Germany. That's an obvious exaggeration,
but it indicates the obstacles to enjoying this important
biographical achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff, an eminent scholar and dean of Harvard University's
graduate school of arts and sciences, has written a thorough
examination of Bach's professional life. His detail-conscious
account relays musical programs for particular occasions, duties
and compensations for musicians as well as relations among patrons
and performers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he left out the Bach.
</P>
<P>
   We learn little about the man, who, admittedly led a circumspect
personal life (1685-1750) and who devoted his available energies to
playing, composing and teaching music. Although Wolff, through his
prodigious research, can tell us which days Bach skipped school and
the floor plan of his Leipzig apartment, he does not animate the
man whom many serious musicians consider history's greatest
composer.
</P>
<P>
   The outline of Bach's story: Born of a Thuringian family of
professional musicians, he excelled at school but did not attend
university. He lost his parents at a fairly young age and,
monitored by his older brother, forged into the family business. He
earned his way through a series of church, municipal and court
appointments. First known as a keyboard virtuoso, he gained renown
as a composer of instrumental and vocal music and finally as a
practical theorist, whose technical and stylistic innovations still
nourish our understanding of tone, harmony and structure.
</P>
<P>
   As the subtitle of his biography, ``The Learned Musician,''
suggests, Wolff wants to elevate Bach's stature as a practical
theorist, glorifying the author of ``The Art of the Fugue,'' ``The
Well-Tempered Clavier'' and other studies. Consequently, Wolff
devotes several pages to Bach's education in Latin schools and his
later relations with the faculty of the University of Leipzig.
</P>
<P>
   Wolff builds to a view of Bach as manifesting the perfectibility
of humans through harmony in music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Characteristic of Bach's manner of composing,'' Wolff writes,
``is a way of elaborating the musical ideas so as to penetrate the
material deeply and exhaustively.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, Wolff's approach is exhaustive, if not exactly harmonious.
He provides images of the cities where Bach lived and the churches
where he played, along with maps, calendars and innumerable
scholarly notes. Yet he fails to string a narrative continuity, and
his conditional phrases _ ``we can imagine,'' ``if anything can be
said for certain,'' ``quite conceivably'' _ madden.
</P>
<P>
   This biography belongs on the shelf of any serious musician as a
source of reputable reference material. Nevertheless, it would no
more interest the general reader than a 600-page list of goods sold
in the Leipzig market during the early 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
