<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7517 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-ADS-STRATEGY-850     09-09 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ADS-STRATEGY-850(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING NEGATIVE WITH A LAVA LAMP 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Harold Kaplan, a Madison Avenue advertising
executive who is an unpaid consultant to Gov. George W. Bush's
campaign, said the ideal way to attack Vice President Al Gore
popped into his head in late August when he was reading the
obituary of the creator of the Lava Lamp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `Lava Lamp. Oh, my God! What a great visual!''' Kaplan
recalled. ``I thought a Lava Lamp was a very good metaphor for
Gore. It can be whatever you want it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's script, which is part of the rhetorical ammunition that
the Bush campaign has stockpiled in Austin, Texas, opens with a
bubbling, oozing Lava Lamp, intended to conjure images of
debauchery in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The announcer says: ``Some politicians are like Lava Lamps,
constantly changing. Always saying what you want them to say. Take
Al Gore, for example. He says he's now for tax cuts. That's
enlightening. Over the last eight years, Al Gore voted to raise our
gas taxes. Kept the marriage tax on couples. Even raised Social
Security taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   This 30-second commercial was one of a series of suggested
scripts obtained by The New York Times from people not involved in
the campaign. The scripts were proposed by Madison Avenue
advertising executives who are advising Bush's media team. They are
nicknamed the ``Park Avenue Posse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lava Lamp advertisement has never been broadcast. And it
probably never will be.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McKinnon, Bush's top media adviser in Austin, was
unapologetically dismissive of the commercial, saying: ``That's not
nearly under consideration. I looked at it for about five seconds
before I realized it wasn't worthy of consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   But the discussions about the advertisement _ no matter how
fleeting _ underscore a fundamental predicament facing the Bush
organization as it heads into the most intense eight weeks of
advertising of the campaign. Campaign officials have concluded that
they have no choice but to run advertisements attacking Gore _ and
they have already started.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are facing the hard part: how to go negative without
making the commercials appear too harsh. It is more of a challenge
for Bush than for Gore, because the Texas governor had vowed to run
a campaign on a positive note.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to even go negative has got to be a tough one for
him,'' said Jane Hall, who teaches politics and the media at
American University's school of communication. ``When he does, he
turns himself into the carping Washington politician that he said
he didn't want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall questioned the effectiveness of the Lava Lamp commercial,
saying, ``To do a negative commercial saying he keeps changing is
like fighting the last war. Gore has repackaged himself and seems
to have sold himself as his own man.'' Besides, she added, ``I'm
not sure people are even going to know what a Lava Lamp is. Isn't
that the '60s or '70s?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush officials and consultants, and officials at the Republican
National Committee, are wrestling with a variety of options, from a
commercial that shows Gore turning into a chameleon to one
questioning the validity of his budget plan.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign has convened endless meetings and focus groups to
settle on how best to take on Gore. But the reality, according to
several people involved in the process, is that there is no
definitive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not sure what we're going to run next,'' conceded one
Bush official in Austin. ``We have various things we're
considering.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon insisted that there was a carefully considered
strategy, saying, ``We have a very clear sense of direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that striking the right tone was a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a sense of what voters think is fair, and produce ads
accordingly,'' he said. ``You always want to try and produce
something that is relevant and credible with voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, a creative director at Young &AMP; Rubicam who met Bush
during the 1988 presidential campaign, spoke more bluntly about the
problem facing the campaign: ``The struggle is that a negative ad
can backfire on you. There's this harsh, mean tone that's wrong and
you just don't want to do that. The governor has set a very
positive tone.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican officials have criticized as too sarcastic a
Republican Party commercial _ sanctioned by the Bush campaign _
that ridicules Gore with humor and cites his fund-raising visit to
a Buddhist temple. But McKinnon defended the commercial and said,
in fact, that it might have helped Bush close the gaps in some
polls in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you from research that that ad tests very well,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Murphy, a veteran Republican ad maker who was a strategist
for Sen. John McCain in the primaries, said it was difficult for
any campaign to sort through ideas and settle on the right tone of
attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem you get in advertising is that much of the advice
you get is very bad,'' said Murphy, who is now a strategist for the
Senate candidacy of Rep. Rick Lazio of New York. ``The hard part is
being able to pick the very good from the overwhelmingly bad.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It has become something of a tradition for campaigns to look to
Madison Avenue for creative input. In May, the Bush campaign formed
the Park Avenue Posse, a group of advertising executives that has
volunteered to advise McKinnon and Stuart Stevens, his colleague in
Austin. The group is led by and was named for Jim Ferguson, the
president of Young &AMP; Rubicam, who lives on Park Avenue in New York.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon and Stevens are in frequent contact with members of the
group, and have often taken their advice in developing commercials,
particularly ones that ran early in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very involved,'' McKinnon said. ``We have a political
way of looking at things, and they're in a different box. They have
fresh ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of those ideas, like the Lava Lamp commercial, may seem a
little too fresh for the Austin consultants.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon not only discarded that commercial but other scripts
from the posse.
</P>
<P>
   In one proposed advertisement, a chameleon flashes on the screen
and the announcer says: ``This is a chameleon. It takes on the
color of any place it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Then an image of Gore, frozen, appears. The announcer says,
``This is a politician, which does the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, footage of Gore recalling his days farming tobacco. ``I've
shucked it, hucked it, sold it, smoked it,'' he says. Then the vice
president says, ``I will never support the tobacco industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcer then says, ``Chameleon. Politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Then back to Gore, who says, ``I helped invent the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcer closes: ``Let's elect a leader this time. Not a
politician.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that commercial, McKinnon said, ``It was something I
instantly recognized as not worthy of consideration.'' He would not
elaborate on why he objected to the advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon also had little patience for suggested commercials that
tethered Gore to the Clinton administration's doomed health-care
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the health-care crisis in '93?'' the announcer says
in one proposed ad. ``Clinton and Gore promised a plan that would
put a national health care card in every wallet. Still waiting for
yours?'' Someone on the screen is shaking a wallet with no card in
it.
</P>
<P>
   Defending his judgments, McKinnon said, ``I've got 150 scripts
lying around here.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Kaplan, who has handled accounts for the Army and
Kentucky Fried Chicken, said he was ``just shocked'' that his and
other scripts had been leaked to the press. ``I've been so good
about guarding our secrets.'' And he was still hoping that the lava
spot would be produced and broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we may produce it,'' he said. ``But who knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
