<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CHILL ISN'T GONE BETWEEN BILLS' JOHNSON AND FLUTIE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rob Johnson of the Buffalo Bills was taking a beating. By the
end of the third quarter in the brutal opener against a
hard-hitting Tennessee Titans defense, Johnson had a noticeable
limp and looked woozy. It got so bad that some of his teammates on
the sideline were saying to each other, ``Better get Flutie
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Flutie, the 5-foot-9-inch miracle worker, is the backup
quarterback, but he is sidelined with a groin injury. There would
be no Flutie saving the day. During a timeout, Johnson slowly
wobbled toward the sideline. Waiting for him was Flutie, who patted
Johnson on the back, and then followed him, consulting, offering
advice. Johnson nodded, listening.
</P>
<P>
   It is a scene repeated numerous times across the National
Football League _ a starter and a backup talking about strategy.
Except that, in the case of Johnson and Flutie, the scene betrayed
reality. The relationship between Johnson and Flutie is as cold as
a Buffalo winter. As one teammate put it: ``They tolerate each
other, but they don't like each other. They don't talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The dislike is rooted in the competition between the two, which
has been going on for years. Flutie replaced Johnson as the starter
several years ago, and then Johnson recently replaced Flutie.
</P>
<P>
   But their relationship chilled even more after Flutie made some
questionable _ and selfish _ comments to a Canadian sports network
in the weeks after the Bills' loss to the Titans in the playoffs
last season. ``I honestly believe that if I would have been
playing, we could have, would have, won,'' Flutie said.
</P>
<P>
   To say that he would have made the difference shows Flutie's
confidence, but it also demonstrates his self-centered tendency,
something Johnson pointed out in an interview with Penthouse
magazine. Asked to respond to Flutie's remarks, Johnson said, in
part: ``I think what Flutie said was more of an insult to the
entire team. That's just the type of guy Doug is. He's not much fun
to play with. You just have to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Johnson-Flutie saga is just one of several awkward
situations between starting and backup quarterbacks.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, Kent Graham, the former Giant, is the starter,
but it is no secret that coach Bill Cowher will most likely start
Kordell Stewart at some point. The relationship between Graham and
Stewart, the starter last season, is cordial.
</P>
<P>
   With the New York Jets, there is no controversy because Vinny
Testaverde is the entrenched starter, but the backup, Ray Lucas, is
extremely unhappy that the team drafted Chad Pennington, and Lucas
has made his unhappiness known.
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, Ryan Leaf and Jim Harbaugh have a good
relationship, but some Chargers believe it will only be a matter of
time before Harbaugh starts, especially since few of the players
like Leaf. In Cleveland, Tim Couch, the franchise's No. 1 pick, is
struggling, and could be replaced by his backup.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback situation in Washington is rife with potential
for ugliness, even though everyone in the Redskins' organization,
including the two throwers themselves, the starter, Brad Johnson,
and the backup Jeff George, say there is no acrimony between the
two.
</P>
<P>
   When asked how to avoid keeping things from getting tense,
Johnson said: ``It's just being relaxed. Knowing that when you come
into meeting rooms, no one is trying to stab each other in the
back. It's just being able to see a guy in the hallway and being
able to say hello without them trying to duck to the other corner.
That makes a big difference. You're not looking for friendship, but
it definitely helps.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is extremely competitive, but he also has one of the
most pleasant personalities of any player in the league, so that
will help the situation. However, Johnson's patience will be tested
because George is notorious for his unwillingness to sit on the
bench and be quiet. It is not a question of if George will complain
about being a backup, but when.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie can be equally politically incorrect. There has been
anti-Flutie talk in the Bills' locker room for more than a year,
which first became public when the former Bills wide receiver Andre
Reed criticized Flutie for being selfish on Reed's Web site before
Reed left the organization.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his comments to Penthouse, Johnson recently
backed down from his words that Flutie is not much fun as a
teammate. ``I said that week it wasn't much fun because he
obviously wasn't in a very good mood,'' Johnson said. ``He was
doing a lot of complaining, and it wasn't good for the team. That
week, I did say he wasn't very pleasant to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   About Flutie's comments being an insult to the team, Johnson
said, ``It was insulting to me personally, but as a team you have
to feel that there are 21 other guys out there making plays. We're
a unit. We're 53 guys. To say one guy would have made the
difference? That's what I meant.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently both players are making nice. But how long will that
last?
</P>
<P>
   Dayne Disputes Fine
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants running back Ron Dayne has been fined
$10,000 by the league for his unexcused absence at this year's
rookie symposium, an NFL official confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne has appealed the fine, and a decision on the appeal is
pending, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Dayne maintained that he missed the symposium because of an ear
infection that prevented him from traveling on an airplane. Dayne
did not provide the excuse in a timely manner, which led to the
fine. The NFL also does not believe Dayne's reason.
</P>
<P>
   A decision on the appeal should come within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two Grudge Matchups
</P>
<P>
   When quarterback Akili Smith was passed over by the Cleveland
Browns in the 1999 draft in favor of Couch, he made it clear that
one day the Browns would regret the decision. In the 2000 draft,
Peter Warrick, the Florida State wide receiver, was passed over by
the Browns in favor of Courtney Brown, the Penn State defensive
lineman. Warrick was also unhappy about being passed over.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Smith and Warrick play on the same team, the Cincinnati
Bengals, and they meet the Browns on Sunday, which means they both
get a chance to prove just how wrong the Browns may have been. Both
tried to play down any bitterness, but what Warrick said earlier
this year cannot be erased.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick predicted the Bengals would be 1-0 after Sept. 10, and
since the Bengals had the unusual bye week in Week 1 and play the
Browns on Sunday, Warrick was obviously saying they would beat the
Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson in Motivation
</P>
<P>
   Following the 27-14 loss to the Indianapolis Colts last week,
Kansas City Chiefs coach Gunther Cunningham met with his team.
According to a coach who was present, an extremely emotional
Cunningham basically said that he was going to do everything he
could to make sure the team never had a loss like the one to the
Colts again. And he said that if he did not get the job done, he
would quit and make way for someone else who could.
</P>
<P>
   From those words came a Fox television report that Cunningham
had considered resigning but was dissuaded by his wife. Cunningham
said that the report took his words out of context.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches, from the high school level to the pros, say all the
time that if they are not getting the job done, they will quit. It
is a motivational tactic, a way to get players to fight for them.
In an interview with One-on-One Sports Radio Network on Friday, the
former Jets Coach Bill Parcells said to some of the teams he had
coached the same thing that Cunningham did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1422EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7526 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PALESTINIANS-INDEPEND     09-09 0283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALESTINIANS-INDEPENDENCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS MEET ON STATEHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ A Palestinian leadership body opened a two-day,
closed-door assembly in Gaza City on Saturday, at the end of which
they are expected to defer the declaration of Palestinian statehood
originally set for next week.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Palestinian Central Council acknowledged that
they were prepared to give the peace negotiations an extended lease
on life.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging state is internationally acknowledged, but many
world leaders told Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, this
summer that they prefer to see it formally born through a process
of negotiations and not declared unilaterally.
</P>
<P>
   Such a declaration would probably provoke an Israeli reaction,
such as an annexation of West Bank settlements, and jeopardize the
troubled peace effort. Arafat would also risk losing the
international financing that is bankrolling the formation of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian leaders originally set Sept. 13 as the deadline by
which they would declare an independent state. That is when the
interim Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement, already extended from
May 4, 1999, expires. It is unclear whether they will set a new
deadline in their assembly this weekend, or simply leave the matter
vague so that they would not be forced to announce and cancel
another proclamation.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Gaza, Arafat said the peace effort
would continue. ``As President Clinton has pointed out, and with
his good effort, this peace process will continue here in Palestine
and in the area, with the participation of the Americans and some
of our Arab brothers,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
