<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DISBARMENT-1100&AMP;ADD(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ANGRY AND DISPIRITED OVER POSSIBLE DISBARMENT, FRIEND SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ During his final months in office, President
Clinton will remain enmeshed in a battle over his Arkansas license
to practice law that friends and associates say has left him
especially angry and dispirited.
</P>
<P>
   The disbarment trial will occur in Little Rock, Ark., possibly
this fall, and has several elements that friends said have deeply
troubled Clinton. One of the president's concerns, they said, is
that disbarment would be both a lifetime stigma and a definitive
verdict for history. It would also be the result of a proceeding
difficult to portray as a groundless and partisan vendetta, which
is how the president and his allies characterized the investigation
by Ken Starr, the independent counsel, and the Clinton's
impeachment by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the issue will be fought in Arkansas, his home
state, making it even more hurtful, the friends said.
</P>
<P>
   One longtime friend of the president said Clinton was ``livid,
off-the-wall angry'' about the disbarment proceedings. On more than
one occasion, the president would be ``in a terrific mood'' until
the disbarment issue came up, the friend said. ``His mood
immediately darkens,'' said the friend, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, this friend said, is especially concerned that if he is
disbarred, he will go down as the first president in American
history to lose his law license while in office, a punishment that
was not even visited upon Richard Nixon, who surrendered his
license after he left the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Another longtime Washington associate of Clinton who spoke only
on the condition of anonymity said that the president's pointed
unhappiness over the disbarment case also reflected a kind of
weariness and annoyance that the Senate's failure to convict him
after his impeachment did not end the grind of formal legal
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought, well, we all thought, this thing was over with,''
this person said.
</P>
<P>
   Two associates said that President Clinton was so stunned on the
afternoon of May 22 when he learned that an Arkansas bar committee
formed by the state Supreme Court had recommended Clinton's
disbarment that he responded by likening the recommendation to the
imposition of the death sentence for a minor crime.
</P>
<P>
   When asked to comment on how the president was reacting to the
disbarment case, the White House provided a statement from John
Podesta, the chief of staff, that said the president was ``focused
first on doing his job and what he can get done in the next several
months and on making sure the Democratic campaigns are successful
in the fall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other matter he is leaving to his lawyers, where it
belongs,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear if Clinton will have to testify in his own
behalf or will want to do so. Either way, the proceedings of the
case, Neal v. Clinton, may be televised from the Pulaski County
Courthouse in Little Rock. And they will most likely occur while
Clinton is still in office, making it especially uncomfortable for
him, one of the friends said.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Skip Rutherford, Clinton's longtime friend from Little Rock who
is heading the committee that is soliciting money for and
overseeing the construction of the Clinton Library in the east end
of town, raised the possibility this summer that the president
might choose to move the library elsewhere out of disgust with what
is happening to him in his home state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us are asking, and we think he should be asking,
whether it's worth it to bring this project here,'' Rutherford had
said in an interview. Rutherford, who speaks often with Clinton,
said that it seemed awful to many of the president's supporters
that he was being treated this way in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford said that the library could be built at Georgetown
University in Washington, where Clinton was an undergraduate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Rutherford's comments, it is highly unlikely that plans
to build the Clinton Library in Little Rock will change.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, during the Democratic National Convention, the
Clinton raised at least $10 million for the library at a Los
Angeles fund-raiser and he recently told interviewers that after he
left office he expected to spend about two days a week in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   END OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   The disbarment proceedings might also influence whether the
president faces other legal problems after he leaves office. Some
legal analysts have said Robert Ray, who succeeded Starr as
independent counsel investigating Clinton's conduct, might be less
inclined to indict Clinton on perjury charges if he has already
been punished through disbarment or by having his law license
suspended. Ray has impaneled a new federal grand jury in Washington
to consider whether Clinton should be prosecuted for lying in the
Paula Jones case, which was also a subject of his impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Two complaints triggered the Arkansas disbarment proceedings,
one filed by a conservative legal group and the other by Susan
Webber Wright, the federal judge who presided over Jones' lawsuit
against Clinton alleging sexual misconduct. In a January 1998
deposition in that case, Clinton testified under oath in Wright's
presence that he had not engaged in a sexual relationship with a
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1998, Clinton acknowledged in a public statement that
he had an inappropriate intimate relationship with the intern but
maintained that he had told the truth in the deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Wright disagreed, fining him $90,000 for contempt and referring
the matter to the Arkansas bar.
</P>
<P>
   The committee recommended the disbarment, rejecting lesser
sanctions of a suspension of his license or a reprimand, a penalty
that Clinton had suggested he might have accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Among the legal issues that may come up in the hearing is
Clinton's decision not to contest Wright's sanction against him for
contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Because Clinton did not challenge the judgment, it is unclear
whether he is now prohibited from arguing that he did not lie under
oath.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Brill of the University of Arkansas Law School at
Fayetteville said that the judge hearing the case might rule that
Clinton, in essence, waived his right to repeat that argument
during disbarment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The other major issue in the case will be an argument over the
severity of the punishment. In papers filed in Arkansas on Aug. 29,
Clinton's lawyers said that even if what the bar committee had
accused him of was true, disbarment was far too harsh and was
disproportionate to the punishment the state had meted out to other
lawyers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``A sanction of disbarment would be excessively harsh,
impermissibly punitive and unprecedented in the circumstances of
this case,'' wrote the lawyers, David Kendall and Nicole Seligman
of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers also suggested in the filings that Clinton had not
waived his argument that he did not technically lie.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas bar committee disciplines about 100 lawyers each
year and disbarment is used almost solely in cases involving the
theft of client money. Although most of the legal precedents favors
the president, there are other considerations that could influence
the judge hearing the case.
</P>
<P>
   Using a recently revised judicial ethics code, the state Supreme
Court upheld the disbarment of a lawyer in 1998 who committed
insurance fraud, saying, ``There is simply no place in the law for
a man or woman who will not tell the truth even when his interest
is involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, another issue is whether lawyers who hold public office
like Clinton bear a greater ethical burden than lawyers who do not.
The commentaries to the code under which Clinton is charged hold
that ``lawyers holding public office assume legal responsibilities
going beyond those of other citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The case for disbarment will be argued by Marie-Bernarde Miller
before Arkansas Circuit Court Judge Leon Johnson, who agreed to
preside over the case after several other judges on the Circuit
Court disqualified themselves because they have been active in
Arkansas politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
