</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-MONTANA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: FLY-FISHING IN MONTANA MAKES INDELIBLE MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAY OTTULICH  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My wife's family reunion out West in Wolf Point was a great
excuse for a fishing trip back to Montana after a four-year
absence. Joan did not have to twist my arm. We left New York, where
I am a guide on the Fourth of July, and tag-teamed up for the
marathon drive to the Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Joan and me, we had my daughter Cassi and her equally
horse-crazy friend Kylee Larabee, a dairy farmer's daughter who had
never been to the West. They both kept occupied for hours on end
commenting upon or photographing every lone horse or herd we
passed. We made a scenic jog, air heavy with the scent of sage, up
through Theodore Roosevelt National Park in North Dakota, a
colorful series of eroded badlands in the drainage of the Little
Missouri River.
</P>
<P>
   We took a deliberate detour off the pavement and crossed the
Montana state line fittingly on a gravel track winding below clay
bluffs along the cottonwood bottomlands of the Missouri River. At
Bainville we hit U.S. 2, known in Montana as the ``high line,'' the
major east-west drag that has become the de facto Main Street of
every town below the Canadian border to Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   There is really no fluvial trout fishing on the high plains of
northeastern Montana. What trout to be found exist, few and far
between, in reservoirs and large stock ponds. So when we arrived in
Wolf Point, I was itching to wet a line and do as the natives do:
fish for northern pike. I teamed up with one of my former regular
fishing partners, Hugh Strait, an inventor of local note known as
Gizmo, and my brother-in-law, Ole Brown.
</P>
<P>
   We traveled down a gravel road through greasewood flats toward
the Missouri Breaks. Rain had fallen abundantly on this corner of
the state this year and the rolling hills were uncharacteristically
green. Unfortunately, the same rainfall had made our goal _ the
Redwater River _ difficult to fish.
</P>
<P>
   We crossed the Redwater over a trapezoidal concrete ford
designed with three culverts embedded, to pass water through during
low water and sloped such as to allow water over the top during
floods. We left the gravel and bounced down a serpentine clay track
to the confluence of the Redwater and the Missouri. A small,
cryptic hand-lettered sign at the dead end greeted us stating, ``If
it rains you stay.'' Ole translated: rain on the clay gumbo made
traction, even with four-wheel drive, impossible, and you would not
be getting out until it dries. Oldtime family fishing camp-outs
always had a shift watcher who did double duty stoking the fire and
watching for thunderheads. At the sign of any ominous cloud the
whole camp would be awakened to strike tents and bug out.
</P>
<P>
   Attaching a 5-inch steel shock tippet to my fly line and keeping
an eye peeled for rattlers, we systematically worked the banks of
the Redwater for its storied 20-pound northerns. My favorite pike
fly, an 8-inch-long barred synthetic yellow hair contraption called
fittingly a ``Barbie Doll head'' proved fruitless. Conditions being
as they were with clarity nil, you would have had to hit the pike
right on the nose.
</P>
<P>
   Family commitments over, and 560 miles farther west put me back
on ``home waters'' _ the glacial Kootenai River. I was a
professional driftboat guide there for a number of years. Rising
300 miles to the north on the Pacific slope of the Canadian
Rockies, the Kootenai runs south and makes a loop through Montana
and Idaho. We used to say that the Kootenai gave Montana a little
piece of British Columbia. The river, incidentally, also harbors
the only native strain of rainbow trout in the state. I watched the
quality of the fishing rise and fall directly as a result of the
unnatural and ecologically unfriendly operations of Libby Dam.
</P>
<P>
   The average size of a 3-year-old trout in 1996 was a pitiful 8
to 9 inches. After a long evening on the river I was delighted to
have caught and released an unusual number of fish between 12 and
15 inches. Dave Blackburn, an old friend, outfitter, fly shop
pioneer and fishing partner, attributes the rebounding of the
Kootenai to the relatively flat flows during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weed beds have developed and flourished in areas where there
was previously no habitat whatsoever,'' he said, explaining why,
``with the old water faucet approach to flow management.''
</P>
<P>
   During that regime, a high flow lasting six to eight weeks or
more at a time during peak power production would be abruptly shut
off, stranding millions of pioneering aquatic insects high and dry
in the dewatered areas. Ramping, the practice of gradually
decreasing flows, allows the benthic community to migrate back.
``We now have a special spring flow for endangered white
sturgeon,'' Blackburn said. This, in effect, mimics the natural
spring runoff of a free flowing river.
</P>
<P>
   On my last day, I drifted through the Riverside Riffle
downstream enough to clear the current seam and rowed back up on
the slack waterside to anchor. We hopped out and wet waded, casting
our flies out towards the pod of feeding fish. An absolutely
magnificent 18-inch cutthroat trout dashed up, struck the
tarantula, gave a spirited fight and was released unharmed, another
timeless memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
