</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILADELPHIA'S TROUBLED SCHOOLS OPEN AS STRIKE THREAT LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ This city's deeply troubled public schools
reopened near cliff's edge this week as the teachers union
authorized a strike in the face of a powerful new bargaining-table
coalition of state and city political leaders determined to
overhaul the system.
</P>
<P>
   The 21,000-member union is fighting demands for contract
concessions, including the introduction of a pay-for-performance
teacher rating like those increasingly being invoked by politicians
across the nation to improve schools.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the School District of Philadelphia, acting
under crisis-driven changes in city and state law, is negotiating
with the explicit backing of Mayor John F. Street and Gov. Tom
Ridge. In the past, ranking elected officials played a sideline
role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly a big stick,'' said David L. Cohen, a chief
strategist of the city-state bargaining initiative, referring to a
new state law, Act 46, designed to shake up the balance of power of
traditional contract bargaining in the 210,000-student system.
</P>
<P>
   With the contract deadline past, an emergency court order has
kept the parties bargaining, but only on a day-to-day basis as the
city's anxieties mount. The order runs out on Monday night, with no
certainty that it will be extended. The union argues that Act 46
violates the state constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The act, designed to narrow the union's bargaining room,
prohibits the temporary extension of the old teacher contract
provisions and benefits. It empowers the governor to take over the
city system if necessary to keep the schools open and to pursue
reforms in the event of a strike.
</P>
<P>
   The law was enacted by the state Legislature in 1998, after a
school-aid fight with the city, in the name of improving plummeting
reading and math scores here and in 10 smaller districts in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   But the Philadelphia Federation of Teachers maintains that the
act was passed by the Republican legislature without fair public
debate to bust the power of the teachers union in this Democratic
city. Other city union leaders have expressed support for the
teachers, who last struck in 1981 for 51 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to strike; the picket signs are in the schools,''
said Ted Kirsch, the union president who heard thousands of members
roar approval for a strike rather than surrender prerogatives of
their old contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about survival of the union, sure, but also survival
of public education in this city,'' Kirsch said in an interview.
``A state takeover could mean the charterizing of schools and the
dismantling of the public system.''
</P>
<P>
   While fighting the Republican governor and Statehouse, the union
must also confront Street, a Democrat who won City Hall last
November after vowing to address the public's deep frustration with
the school system. At that time, voters also approved a city
charter change that gave the mayor far greater power over the
schools by allowing him to appoint the nine-member school board in
charge of the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this goes down, Mayor Street takes the hit,'' Kirsch said
of the political responsibility for a strike and potential state
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the as yet unspecified performance-pay innovation, the
state, city and school district are also challenging current
seniority protections by allowing principals and supervisors a
stronger say in where teachers are assigned. The city also wants to
increase the teachers' work day by 1 hour and 15 minutes, to 7
hours and 45 minutes, while adding five work days to the 190 in the
school year.
</P>
<P>
   But the pay-for-performance proposal clearly upsets the union
the most.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could settle a contract a lot more easily if that wasn't on
the table,'' said Jerry Jordan, the chief union negotiator. He
noted that the performance idea, while increasingly popular among
critics of public schools, is in only the experimental stage in a
few places like Cincinnati, Milwaukee and Colorado, and has no
track record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not make our teachers guinea pigs,'' Jordan said. He
noted that the old contract permitted principals to deny raises to
teachers considered subpar.
</P>
<P>
   Out in the district, students began classes on Thursday even as
their teachers monitored contract talks that continued into the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Benjamin Franklin High School, Arlene Fields, a mother
of a student and a nonunion consultant on parent involvement in
school affairs, pointed to the building and said, ``Don't worry,
they're still teaching and learning in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Fields, a proud city native, said the heightened city and state
involvement ``makes this year's contract talks a pretty potent
mix,'' but a promising one, too. She praised Street for daring to
get involved in the complex issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``But everybody needs to give a little for this to work out for
the kids,'' she said as a student politely volunteered to carry her
briefcase into the busy school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1430EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
