u k BC-EDIT-OLYMPICS-NYT &LR;      09-09 0477
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OLYMPICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE SYDNEY OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Sept. 10:
</P>
<P>
   When the 2000 Olympic Summer Games begin Friday in Sydney,
Australia, the season in the Southern Hemisphere will still be
winter, fading into spring. In addition to being the first Olympics
in a new century _ a new millennium _ the Sydney Olympics will be
the last Games in the era of Juan Antonio Samaranch. Samaranch,
head of the International Olympic Committee since 1980, will step
down, belatedly, early next year.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, Samaranch has transformed the Olympic Games
into a venue for professional athletes and into a marketing
juggernaut. Even as he put Olympics financing on a solid, if overly
commercial basis, he also allowed the IOC to attain a dismaying
level of corruption and insularity. His imperious management style
and insensitivity to ethical lapses will not be missed.
</P>
<P>
   The coming Games will also be one of the last Olympics, one
hopes, to be held in a city chosen by a crooked selection process
that has left the IOC and several of the cities that bid for the
Games, including Sydney and Salt Lake City, which will host the
2002 Winter Games, embarrassed. Overall, 1999 was a nightmare for
the IOC, whose cloak of secrecy was removed by the investigations
that resulted from Salt Lake City's flawed bid.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the IOC has created an ethics commission and
adopted other reforms. It committed itself to greater
representation from active athletes, and banned the site-selection
committee from visiting cities bidding for the Games to prevent
offers of free travel and other financial inducements from
municipal groups. Despite new drug-testing policies, however, the
IOC still struggles to keep pace with the bewildering proliferation
of performance-enhancing substances.
</P>
<P>
   The coming Games, and the natural ebullience of the Australian
hosts, may do much to restore the luster of the Olympics. That is
the way it usually goes. Each Olympics sets off an explosion of
activity years in advance _ the sale of television and advertising
rights, the construction of arenas, housing and transportation
systems. These things should serve to embellish the athletic
contests. But recently it has worked the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   It has been up to the athletes and the quality of their contests
to redeem the blunders of the host cities, the broadcasting
networks, the advertisers, and the local and international Olympic
committees. It has been up to the athletes to remind us that the
real contest at the Olympics is not for television rights or
product placement or viewer share, or, for that matter, national
medal totals. What matters are the Games, which will give the world
a chance to see athletes competing at the limits of speed, agility
and grace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0111 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7531 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     09-09 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS OF THE TIMES: METS ARE NOT HELPING TO KEEP HAMPTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When it's time for Mike Hampton to decide where he
wants to pitch next season, he'll remember Friday night's
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Not for his temper tantrum sparked by surrendering a two-run
eighth-inning homer to Scott Rolen for the Mets' 2-0 loss to the
Phillies and, after a walk, his removal. Not for flinging his glove
into the dugout. Not for slamming the gum-holder. Not for leveling
a plastic water cooler with his right forearm. Not for flinging his
cap into the runway as he stalked to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   No, he'll remember the frustration of a cut fastball that didn't
cut and spoiled what could have been an important slump-snapping
victory if the Mets' hitters had provided just a few runs.
</P>
<P>
   Over Hampton's last three starts, the Mets have supported him
with a total of only 3 runs _ his 2-1 triumph over Arizona and his
2-1 loss in St. Louis before Friday night's frustration on the eve
of his 28th birthday. But he didn't regret his outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't try to please anybody, I don't try to look good for
anybody,'' he said later. ``I show emotion once in a while. This
was one of those cases.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Hampton, whose Mets salary is $5.75 million, sifts
free-agent offers in the fall, he might prefer to join a team with
a more explosive batting order. Maybe the Braves or the Yankees, or
maybe he would just prefer to return to the Astros from whence he
came.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Hampton lost his first three Mets starts, he's had a
solid season. He's now 13-9 with a 3.19 earned run average, third
in the National League behind the Diamondbacks' Randy Johnson and
the Dodgers' Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   And Bobby Valentine, who said he didn't see all of Hampton's
outburst because he was on the phone to the bullpen, apparently did
not scold him. If the Mets hope to sign Hampton, it wouldn't be
wise to create a chasm between him and the manager, especially in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like everything Mike Hampton does,'' the Mets manager said.
``I think he's hit enough watercoolers to know how to hit `em. I'm
not upset with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, not every pitcher is an athlete. Some are just
that, a pitcher who couldn't play any other position in the big
leagues. But you could put Hampton, say, at first base or in the
outfield, and while he wouldn't be Mark McGwire or Ken Griffey Jr.,
he wouldn't embarrass himself. Or his team.
</P>
<P>
   Coming out of Crystal River (Fla.) High School as a two-time
all-state pitcher and defensive back, he spurned a a two-sport
offer from Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Just watching him pitch, you can see the athlete in him. In his
quick serious steps striding to the mound. In his compact windup.
In completing his follow-through with his glove in position to
field a grounder or line drive. In being ready to throw the next
pitch without any fuss.
</P>
<P>
   You can also see the athlete in him when he bats or runs the
bases. Some pitchers just wave the bat; he swings it with a
purpose. Some float around the bases; he sprints.
</P>
<P>
   But as a pitcher Hampton has proven to be even better than the
Mets thought when they acquired him to provide what they didn't
have a year ago: another ace in the marathon of the 162-game season
and then in the crucible of the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff is even better than I thought,'' Valentine said.
``His changeup is a power change because he throws it with a grip
on it. I knew his 86-, 87-mile-an-hour fastball moved a lot, but
he's shown a 92-, 93-mile-an- hour fastball when he needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wallace, the Mets' pitching coach, sees something else in
Hampton that sets him apart from many pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's got that look,'' Wallace said. ``That look that defines
so many great players. When you talk to him, he looks you in the
eye. He's a no-excuse guy. And when he's not pitching, he's still
competing. He's a prankster; he's sarcastic in a fun way. And if
you come back at him, he welcomes it.''
</P>
<P>
   As a left-hander, Al Leiter understands Hampton's personality
better than others might.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike and I have that goofiness, that humor that only a
left-hander appreciates,'' Leiter said. ``There's a certain
lightheartedness among us left-handers on this team _ Mike, myself,
Johnny Franco, Glendon Rusch, Dennis Cook. It's a lightheartedness
that's goofy, geeky, whatever you want to call it.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was nothing lighthearted Friday night about Hampton's
reaction to Rolen's homer and being removed. ``He threw a great
game,'' Mike Piazza said, ``but obviously, one mistake killed us.
He made a bad pitch to a good hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Mets had scored a few runs before that bad pitch, Hampton
would not have been so frustrated. And when it's time for him to
decide where he wants to pitch next season, he'll surely remember
those zeros on the scoreboard.
</P>
</TEXT>
