<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7533 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-EMMY0910-COX     09-09 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freshman hit `West Wing' deserves honors
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The battle lines are drawn: It's the White House
vs. the mob, straight vs. gay.
</P>
<P>
   The winners will take home television's prized statuettes during
tonight's telecast of the 52nd annual prime-time Emmy Awards,
starting at 7 on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   In the best drama series category, NBC's freshman political
drama ``The West Wing'' is tied with HBO's mobster saga ``The
Sopranos'' for most nominations (18). Vying for best comedy series
are NBC's ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' which has 11 nominations, and HBO's
``Sex and the City,'' which racked up nine nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally the Emmys kick off the new fall TV season, but
this year's late-arriving Summer Olympics has delayed premieres
until October. Bummer. At least tonight's show, hosted by acerbic
wacko Garry Shandling, will get us in the mood for the eventual
arrival of new shows and remind us why we spend so much time
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Shandling, who won an Emmy for writing his ``Larry Sanders
Show,'' promises to be irreverent but not subversive and to keep
the lumbering, three-hour-plus program moving along.
</P>
<P>
   ``I empathize with all those people sitting there not caring
about the categories they're not in,'' he said in Los Angeles
recently. ``Actually, I hope they don't give out any awards. They
should just lock the doors and let me do three hours of stand-up.
The people in that audience would be the real `Survivors.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Voting by members of the Academy of Television Arts &AMP; Sciences
usually ranges from whimsical to traditional. Safe bets such as
``Frasier'' and ``ER'' are frequent winners. There's no predicting
how the academy folks really voted, but here's how they should have
cast their ballots:
</P>
<P>
   BEST COMEDY SERIES
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: ``Everybody Loves Raymond'' (CBS), ``Frasier,''
``Friends,'' ``Will &AMP; Grace'' (NBC); ``Sex and the City'' (HBO).
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Frasier'' is still fabulous, the buzz this year is on
the gay-themed chuckles of ``Will &AMP; Grace'' and the hetero-horny
humor of ``Sex and the City.'' Between these two, ``Will &AMP; Grace''
wins hands down. It's smart and funny with lovable, quirky
characters and super-choreographed slapstick. The bed-hopping and
profanity on ``Sex and the City'' were funny at first but not so
much anymore.
</P>
<P>
   BEST DRAMA SERIES
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: ``The West Wing,'' ``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``ER'' (NBC);
``The Practice'' (ABC); ``The Sopranos'' (HBO).
</P>
<P>
   Creator Aaron Sorkin thought a TV show that debated policy
issues such as gun control and school vouchers would never fly, but
``West Wing'' soared last season. Touching, sophisticated and
witty, this one deserves to beat the freshman taboo and win the big
one.
</P>
<P>
   TV MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: ``Annie,'' ``Tuesdays With Morrie'' (ABC); ``If These
Walls Could Talk 2,'' ``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge,'' ``RKO
281'' (HBO).
</P>
<P>
   Not a sterling year for TV movies, but these nominees were
worthwhile. By a squeaker, ``Dorothy Dandridge'' gets the nod _ for
bringing this complicated woman to life with fine acting and lavish
production values.
</P>
<P>
   MINISERIES
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: ``Arabian Nights,'' ``The Beach Boys: An American
Family'' (ABC); ``Jesus'' (CBS); ``The Corner'' (HBO); ``P.T.
Barnum'' (A&AMP;E).
</P>
<P>
   As much as I loved the stories and special effects on ``Arabian
Nights,'' I have to give the nod to ``The Corner.'' An edgy drama
about life on the mean streets, it wasn't fun but it was definitely
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR, COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Michael J. Fox, ``Spin City''; Kelsey Grammer,
``Frasier''; John Lithgow, ``3rd Rock From the Sun''; Eric
McCormack, ``Will &AMP; Grace''; Ray Romano, ``Everybody Loves
Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentimental favorite here is Michael J. Fox, who left his
sitcom last season to battle Parkinson's disease and spend time
with his family. But equally deserving _ and a year overdue _ is
Eric McCormack. Perfect timing, perfect delivery, perfect
performance.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS, COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Jenna Elfman, ``Dharma &AMP; Greg''; Patricia Heaton,
``Everybody Loves Raymond''; Jane Kaczmarek, ``Malcolm in the
Middle''; Debra Messing, ``Will &AMP; Grace''; Sarah Jessica Parker,
``Sex and the City.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm torn here because Jane Kaczmarek and Debra Messing are both
so good. There would be no Will without Grace, and Messing is the
closest thing we've seen to a classic clown since Lucille Ball. But
Kaczmarek has been around a long time and finally has a role worthy
of her talent. Malcolm's mom will go down in TV history as the
funniest anti-nurturer ever.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR, DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Dennis Franz, ``NYPD Blue''; James Gandolfini, ``The
Sopranos''; Jerry Orbach, ``Law &AMP; Order''; Sam Waterston, ``Law &AMP;
Order''; Martin Sheen, ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm morally opposed to this category because two of the best
dramatic actors on TV weren't nominated: Billy Campbell of ``Once
and Again'' and Rick Schroder of ``NYPD Blue.'' The two nominees
from ``Law &AMP; Order'' are fine fellows, but the series doesn't
require much acting. Dennis Franz has won a zillion times, so it's
between neurotic gangster James Gandolfini and complex commander in
chief Martin Sheen. Give the Emmy to Sheen. He's played lots of
politicians, none better than Josiah Bartlett, and he classes up
the small screen.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS, DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Lorraine Bracco, ``The Sopranos''; Edie Falco, ``The
Sopranos''; Amy Brenneman, ``Judging Amy''; Julianna Margulies,
``ER''; Sela Ward, ``Once and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   No question, this category belongs to Sela Ward. Going for the
gut is risky business and can result in a display of off-putting
hysteria rather than bone-deep, raw emotions. Ward aims true and
nails it every time.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK PICKS FOR SUPPORTERS . . .
</P>
<P>
   Best Supporting Actor, Comedy _ Sean Hayes, a k a ``Just Jack''
on ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' should win. Other nominees: Peter Boyle,
``Everybody Loves Raymond''; Brad Garrett, ``Everybody Loves
Raymond''; Peter MacNicol, ``Ally McBeal''; David Hyde Pierce,
``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   Best Supporting Actress, Comedy _ Megan Mullally, as the rich
lush on ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' should win. Other nominees: Jennifer
Aniston, ``Friends''; Lisa Kudrow, ``Friends''; Kim Cattrall, ``Sex
and the City''; Doris Roberts, ``Everybody Loves Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   Best Supporting Actor, Drama _ Richard Schiff, Toby on ``The
West Wing,'' should win. If you saw the episode about the homeless
Vietnam vet, you know why. Other nominees: Michael Badalucco, ``The
Practice''; Steve Harris, ``The Practice''; John Spencer, ``The
West Wing''; Dominic Chianese, ``The Sopranos.''
</P>
<P>
   Best Supporting Actress, Drama _ Allison Janney, tough as nails
and soft as a pillow as C.J. on ``The West Wing,'' gets the nod.
Other nominees: Stockard Channing, ``The West Wing''; Nancy
Marchand, ``The Sopranos''; Tyne Daly, ``Judging Amy''; Holland
Taylor, ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
