</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7534 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-BOOKS-THUNDER0910-COX     09-09 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-THUNDER0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two New York Times reporters go inside an Asia on the cusp of
change
 &HT;    By Joseph Albright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After winning a Pulitzer for their splendid
reporting on China during the Tiananmen Square uprising, the New
York Times husband-and-wife team of Nicholas D. Kristof and Sheryl
WuDunn moved to a new assignment in Tokyo in the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   Already fluent in Chinese, they force-fed themselves Japanese
and put their three little children in Japanese schools. Then they
set out to cover what looked like it might be the big story of the
decade: the rise of Superpower Japan.
</P>
<P>
   But then came 1997. The bubble popped. Japan and the rest of
Asia keeled over into a recession that even now hasn't fully ended.
And Kristof and WuDunn found themselves parachuting all over Asia,
trying to explain to puzzled New York Times readers not just why
Japan's juggernaut economy slammed into reverse but also why
Thailand's currency wilted under hedge fund pressure, and why
seemingly rock-solid Indonesia fragmented overnight into
pitchfork-wielding mobs.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kristof and WuDunn have wrapped up their findings about the
Asian economic crisis in a deftly written journalistic explainer
called ``Thunder from the East: Portrait of a Rising Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone thinking about doing business or pleasure in the Orient
will find this illuminating _ and a bit scary. With its peripatetic
reach and its focus on the quirky socioeconomic underside of Asia,
the book strikes me as a fitting update for ``Inside Asia,'' the
1939 best seller by the late John Gunther, one of my favorite
journalistic storytellers.
</P>
<P>
   For me, the high point in ``Thunder from the East'' was its
lavish depiction of a 10-course meal at an insanely expensive
Japanese restaurant called Kiccho. Dinner cost the two
correspondents and their American businessman host $600 apiece, not
counting drinks, geisha, tax and tip. Talk about prime beef: The
steak cooked on the hibachi for course seven came from Japanese
farmers who massage the steers' backs to make the meat more tender.
</P>
<P>
   However close to absolute perfection the meal was, the authors
called restaurants like Kiccho ``an emblem of a rotten system''
that have helped pull Japan into economic crisis. The
``ridiculous'' meal checks are invariably picked up on corporate
expense accounts out of unregulated shareholders' money. That sort
of entrenched profligacy is part of why the authors believe that
``Japan is slowly fading'' as an economic, cultural and political
influence over Asia. So eager are Japanese companies to curry favor
with their best customers that they continue to present
``institutionalized bribes,'' often in the form of a beautifully
lacquered box containing a rare Yubari melon (a little like a
cantaloupe) that can cost up to $1,100 per melon.
</P>
<P>
   From the eccentricities of decadent, rich Tokyo, Kristof and
WuDunn lead us on a safari through some of Asia's sadder hellholes
_ like a village in northeastern Thailand where a ``no-nonsense
peasant'' is forced to sell her 15-year-old granddaughter to a
Bangkok brothel for $40 in order to collect food for the rest of
her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ruthlessness of Asian capitalism sometimes offends me. . .
.'' writes Kristof. ``But in a strange way, I find something
impressive in the way people can face the most wretched choices
and, rather than remain paralyzed, can choose what they see as the
least-worst and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kristof and WuDunn are describing the people they met and
events they saw, they are fascinating. They carry us to the
suddenly impoverished countryside in Indonesia, where in town after
town the inhabitants turned into wandering lynch mobs, using
machetes to whack off the heads of neighbors suspected of being
sorcerers. And on again to a mud-brick village on China's Yellow
River, where dozens of children are physically stunted and mentally
retarded, evidently because of toxic effluents from the local
fertilizer factory.
</P>
<P>
   My biggest knock on ``Thunder from the East'' is its
heavy-handed title, along with its shaky premise that Asia is
inexorably gaining on the West.
</P>
<P>
   This is how they put it: ``We do believe that in myriad ways
Asia will be a more important place, and that it will gradually
displace the United States as the `center of the world.' '' They
also write, ``the next World War, if there is one, will almost
certainly begin in Asia'' and ``Asia is likely to wrench economic,
diplomatic, and military power from the West over the coming
decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Here I think the authors may have fallen into a snare that has
too often bagged foreign correspondents (myself included).
</P>
<P>
   Let's say you have filled notebooks with pages of wonderful
color and great quotes about some bizarre place that you may have
risked your digestive tract (or maybe your life) to find.
</P>
<P>
   Now the problem is how to make your story appeal to the
multitudes of zoned-out readers in the United States. So what do
you do when you fire up your laptop? Too often you push too hard to
craft a catchy ``nut paragraph'' (journalists' lingo for a premise
or conclusion). Then you shout it at the top of your lungs in hopes
that someone out there will notice the color and quotes you
traveled so far to collect.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: If you just want to get a feel for how life really
is in Asia, you'll find this book a good read. But don't get hung
up on its cosmic predictions about what might happen in Asia in the
year 2040.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
