</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FIRES-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CALLS FOR MORE SPENDING TO PREVENT WILDFIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After what he called ``one of the worst fire seasons in
memory,'' President Clinton said Saturday that he would seek to
more than double federal spending on wildfire programs in the year
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   He asked Congress for nearly $1.6 billion to aid affected
communities and to try to prevent future blazes.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was in part an attempt to bounce back
politically after weeks in which Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
have come under sharp criticism from Republicans, including Gov.
George W. Bush, for what their critics say is a pro-environment
bias that has increased the fire risk.
</P>
<P>
   Even as cooler weather and rain have begun to dampen this year's
flames, concern about fires and their aftermath remains intense
across the West, in a season that has already burned more than 6
million acres.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's call for more spending may have been aimed in
particular at voters in California, Washington and Oregon, which
are seen as important to Gore's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saving lives and property is, and will remain, Priority 1,''
Clinton said in his radio address on Saturday from New York City.
He said next year's wildfire budget should jump to $2.8 billion, up
from $1.2 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   About $700 million of the additional money would go to replenish
accounts depleted by the cost of fighting fires during a year
likely to have the most devastation from fires in half a century.
Other increases would extend relief to hard-hit communities and pay
for efforts to restore the worst of the fire-ravaged areas, and _
in what administration officials have portrayed as a hallmark of
the plan _ greatly increase programs aimed at reducing fire risks
by thinning overgrown forests of their smallest, most fire-prone
trees, while leaving the largest, most fire-resistant trees behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our administration has taken a new approach to protect
communities and reduce wildfire risks by getting rid of the forest
underbrush that has accumulated over the last century,'' Clinton
said. He added, ``We want to work with communities to expand these
efforts, in an environmentally sensitive way, particularly in those
areas at greatest risk of wildfire.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan, described in a report submitted to the president by
Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman, did not say how widespread the program expansion would
be. Current thinning efforts, which rely on prescribed thinning by
mechanical means and controlled fires, cover 2.4 million acres a
year, a fraction of the 40 million acres of public land that remain
at catastrophic risk of fire, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
   An estimate by the General Accounting Office has put the total
cost of a thinning effort at $12 billion over 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, Clinton conceded that this year's fires did in
part grow out of past policies, but he pointed the finger at the
nearly 100 years in which federal managers emphasized forest
suppression over forest health. The Clinton administration began to
move away from that approach five years ago, through policies that
have emphasized preventive fires and mechanical cutting. Some of
those fires started by government forestry officials in routine
maintenance blazed out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The president's critics have argued that the best way to make
forests healthier would be by permitting more timber sales on
public lands. But the White House made clear that it was rejecting
that approach, saying that the report from Babbitt and Glickman
favored alternatives that ``can successfully reduce fire risk
without relying on increased commercial logging.''
</P>
<P>
   A report late last month by the bipartisan Congressional
Research Service found no link between logging and fire risk, but
critics have questioned that conclusion, saying that the damage
from this year's fires could have been reduced if more timber
harvesting had been permitted.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, commercial loggers harvested about 3 billion board
feet of timber from public land, a sharp decline from almost 13
billion board feet harvested in the late 1980s. One reason for the
decline was increased attention by the Clinton administration and
the federal courts to environmental concerns, such as the risk to
the habitat of the spotted owl.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Bush has been among those saying that the
Clinton administration's policies were at least in part to blame
for the severity of this year's fires. Bush has vowed ``to put our
national forests back to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate over logging and fires is likely to become even more
prominent in the days ahead as Congress takes up the
administration's request. Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, who is
chairman of the Senate Forests and Public Lands Management
subcommittee, has already called for hearings to examine the
prospect of increased timber cutting on public land.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Saturday, a spokesman for the timber industry, which has
close ties to Western Republicans, described the administration's
approach as a good first step toward recognizing the importance of
reducing fire risks. But the spokesman, Michael Klein of the
American Forest and Paper Association, said it would be a mistake
to shut his industry out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commercial logging is a dirty word for them, but it works
pretty well on our private lands, which provide jobs, healthy
forests and just as many fish and wildlife habitats as do public
lands,'' Klein said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for thinning forests has been shaped in large part by a
program under way in Flagstaff, Ariz., which has won support from
some business and environmental groups, but which is opposed by
other environmentalists on the grounds that it could pose dangers
to animal habitat.
</P>
<P>
   At least one other forestry expert, however, praised the
administration's stepped-up approach: ``They're talking about a
strong program for mechanical thinning and prescribed burning, and
that's exactly what these forests need,'' said Michael Goergen,
director of forest policy for the Society of American Foresters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
