<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7538 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-RFK-MRSCLINTON-2TA     09-09 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RFK-MRSCLINTON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT KENNEDY'S '64 CAMPAIGN MAY HOLD LESSONS FOR MRS. CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He stepped out of the shadows of another political
era one morning last week, a familiar silhouette walking at the
side of Hillary Rodham Clinton along the Hudson River in the Upper
West Side neighborhood that had so rallied around his father,
Robert F. Kennedy, when he ran for senator 36 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Robert F. Kennedy Jr., the son of the 1964 Democratic candidate
for the Senate, had been recruited by Clinton's campaign to talk
about the environment, but it soon became clear that that was not
the only reason for this news conference. Without prompting,
Kennedy began reminiscing about his father's campaign and his
success in overcoming the accusations of carpetbagging and the
``hatred of my father'' that he had found in New York in the summer
of 1964.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scene shimmering with history, and evocative of the
battle Clinton finds herself in today. Kennedy, like Clinton, was a
polarizing figure seeking to represent a state where he did not
live, a first-time candidate for public office whose last name,
more than anything else, accounted for the honor of his nomination
to run for senator from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's supporters routinely offer up the election of Robert
Kennedy as the case study that demonstrates that she can overcome
the difficulties that have arisen in her campaign. The first lady
has spent hours studying newspaper clips from the 1964 campaign, an
aide said, and lessons drawn from the Kennedy candidacy have shaped
much of what she has done these past 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the seeming symmetry between these two races, the
candidacy of Robert F. Kennedy is arguably more a tale of caution
than of comfort for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The characterizations of Kennedy as a carpetbagger emerged from
the moment he announced his candidacy at Gracie Mansion _
demonstrators carried signs that said ``Bobby Go Home'' _ and they
festered until the very end of the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should you represent a state where you cannot even vote?''
asked a full-page newspaper advertisement bought by Democrats
supporting the Republican in the race, Sen. Kenneth B. Keating. The
editorial pages of the state's major newspapers, in particular
those of The New York Times and The New York Herald Tribune,
opposed Kennedy's march into New York every step of the way,
dismissing him, in the words of one Times editorial, for
``attempting to use New York and the senatorial office in a
relentless quest for greater political power.''
</P>
<P>
   For Robert Kennedy in 1964, and for Hillary Rodham Clinton
today, the label carpetbagger was really shorthand for a general
condemnation, expressed in startlingly similar terms: They were,
according to their critics, ambitious, opportunistic, ruthless (for
Kennedy) and untrustworthy (for Clinton).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Kennedy won that race in 1964, but by 720,000 votes in a
year when President Lyndon B. Johnson carried New York by 2.5
million votes. In addition, Kennedy was running against a
64-year-old white-haired incumbent who, while respected and
popular, ran a clumsy campaign in the critical final week. Without
Johnson at the top of the ticket, Kennedy might very well have
lost, or have won by even fewer votes, largely because of the
attacks on his residency, according to his associates at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a huge thing,'' the younger Kennedy said in an
interview. ``As a 10-year-old, I knew what the word carpetbagger
meant, and where it came from. It was part of the conversation in
our house every day. I remember for my father's birthday, people
giving him carpetbags as presents. It was a constantly resounding
theme during that campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Kennedy's Senate campaign, R. Peter Straus, said
he came to view Kennedy's Massachusetts residence as perhaps the
biggest obstacle to winning the election. ``It was a big issue,
this carpetbagging thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Straus sounded much like Clinton's advisers, though he would not
offer any direct comparisons with Clinton's situation, noting his
own particular relationship with the first family. (Straus is
married to Marcia Lewis, the mother of Monica Lewinsky.)
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats today, mindful of the lessons of Kennedy's 1964
victory, say they believe that the single most important factor in
determining Clinton's success in her race against Rep. Rick Lazio
will be how well Al Gore fares against George W. Bush in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While leaders in both parties say it is highly likely that Gore
will defeat Bush in the state, it seems improbable that he will
come close to matching Johnson's 2.5 million-vote cushion against
Sen. Barry Goldwater in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Even at that, it is doubtful that Gore can do for Clinton what
Johnson did for Kennedy. Voters these days are more independent,
and a vote for Gore may not necessarily guarantee a vote for
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, although Clinton is the wife of a sitting
president popular in New York, Bobby Kennedy was the brother of a
martyred president, running for office less than one year after
John F. Kennedy was killed. The trauma of that assassination
shadowed Kennedy wherever he went in New York that fall. ``You
couldn't vote against Robert Kennedy without seeing the presence of
John Kennedy,'' said William J. vanden Heuvel, former deputy
representative of the United States to the United Nations, who was
deputy manager of the Kennedy campaign.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything else, it was the assassination of his brother
that led Robert Kennedy to examine his own future.
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton today, Kennedy, who was the U.S. attorney general,
was approaching the end of his time in Washington, and at the age
of 38, he wanted to follow the path that his brothers had taken
into elective politics. Some upstate Democratic leaders began
floating Kennedy's name as a prospective opponent to Keating, who
stood as a difficult target for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's initial interest was not in running for the Senate,
but in maneuvering to become Johnson's vice-presidential nominee.
That June, in what was seen in Washington as a signal to Johnson,
Kennedy announced that he did not want to be considered for the New
York Senate nomination. But Johnson's dislike for the younger
Kennedy was deep and well known, and at the end of July, the
president announced that would not consider any sitting Cabinet
member as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It was now the middle of the summer, and Kennedy had to move
fast. He could not realistically run for office in his home state,
Massachusetts, because its voters had already elected Edward M.
Kennedy senator. So Robert Kennedy flew to New York, met with Mayor
Robert F. Wagner and won his support to enter the race, instantly
eclipsing the Democrat who almost certainly would have won the
nomination, Rep. Samuel S. Stratton, from upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy found himself under immediate attack _ for much the same
reason that Clinton is criticized now. ``People have been standing
in line at the World's Fair longer than my opponent has been a
resident of New York,'' Keating declared.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy set out to address the problem, with a kind of road map
that Clinton seems to be following 36 years later. He began a
tireless schedule of travel across the state, seeking in 10 weeks
to become a familiar fixture in New York, as she did over 15
months. He established a residence, though with so little time, he
was forced to rent, rather than buy, a home on Long Island and a
hotel suite in Manhattan. He had begun so late that he could not
change his registration from Massachusetts to New York, so he could
not vote for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy confronted the carpetbagger issue directly when he
accepted the party's nomination, much the way Clinton did in
formally announcing her candidacy. ``For every citizen who is a New
Yorker by birth, there is one who is a New Yorker by choice, or
whose parents were,'' Kennedy said at the nominating convention.
``I am in the second of that category, and so was Thomas E.
Dewey.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy had one critical advantage over Clinton: he had
spent many of his first 20 years growing up in New York: in
Riverdale, a Bronx neighborhood, and in Bronxville, in Westchester
County. One early campaign stop was a visit to what had been the
family home in Riverdale, with a young John F. Kennedy Jr. at his
side.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Clinton faced other difficulties as newcomers in New
York. Kennedy, like Clinton, was frustrated by his difficulty
capturing support from Jewish voters. That was a major reason, a
Kennedy adviser said, that Straus, who is Jewish, was made campaign
chairman, a highly visible job.
</P>
<P>
   Keating attacked Kennedy for not having a voting record, using
some of the same language Lazio has used to try to discredit
Clinton's credentials. Kennedy responded by rummaging through his
years at the Justice Department for accomplishments to cite, much
the way Clinton has engaged in a reclamation project from her years
as first lady, although without the advantage of having Cabinet
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates tried to undermine their opponents in nearly
identical ways: Clinton by tying Lazio to the conservative
Republican policies of former House Speaker Newt Gingrich, Kennedy
by linking Keating to the conservative policies of Barry Goldwater,
though Keating never endorsed Goldwater.
</P>
<P>
   And Kennedy, like Clinton today, was a celebrity as much as he
was a candidate, attracting swarms of New Yorkers _ though,
Kennedy's aides would later acknowledge, not necessarily voters _
wherever he went.
</P>
<P>
   Upstate, people turned out in the middle of the night, some
wearing pajamas, for a glimpse of Kennedy. At the nominating
convention, ``we had press tables perpendicular to the stage, and
we're writing our stories and fans start jumping on the stage,
running along this long table where all the press was, to get to
him,'' recalled Milton Hoffman, a veteran New York political
journalist and columnist who is a member of the editorial board at
The Journal News in White Plains. Hoffman compared the scene to the
night Judy Garland performed at the Westchester County Center.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Kennedy evoked the memory of what had happened
the year before in Dallas. ``He looks and sounds just enough like
his murdered brother to send a ghostly flutter through the New York
crowds,'' James Reston wrote in The Times. ``When he rode through
the bustling traffic of Manhattan today, people stopped on the
sidewalks as if they had suddenly seen an apparition.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, perhaps the most striking _ and the most curious _
similarity is the deep hostility stirred by both candidates,
particularly among some voters who would presumably be their
obvious supporters. Robert Kennedy Jr. struggled at length with
that question in a telephone conversation, saying that Clinton's
difficulties in this race raised unresolved questions about the
animosity his father had found in so many parts of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``The accusations against him are the same kind of accusations
about Hillary: that he was opportunistic, a carpetbagger, that he
is only running because he wants to run for president,'' Kennedy
said. ``The intensity of feeling with my father's race, and the
almost inexplicable intensity of feeling toward Hillary Clinton.
People who ought to like Hillary Clinton, but don't, and can't
really explain why, but just kind of have a visceral reaction to
her _ that's the same kind of thing that I remember from my
father.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who should have liked him, but didn't,'' he continued.
``I remember reading The Village Voice when I was a kid and being
horrified. The cartoons and that kind of stuff, and how vicious the
attacks were.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy sighed. ``You explain it to me,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
