<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7541 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-EMMY-MAIN0910-COX     09-09 1421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY-MAIN0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Politicians and mobsters are favorites for this year's Emmys
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Can a beefy mobster whack the president of
the United States?
</P>
<P>
   That's the juiciest question to be answered on tonight's 52nd
annual Emmy awards. Both ``The Sopranos,'' HBO's gritty mob series,
and ``The West Wing,'' NBC's intelligent political drama, are up
for 18 awards. Of course, we all know Tony Soprano could easily
whip Martin Sheen's President Bartlet in a back-alley brawl. But
this is the stodgy Emmys, for crying out loud! An awards show where
conventional wisdom _ and old-fashioned common sense _ are often
tossed aside like last week's People magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question, though, is: Will anybody care? The ratings
for last year's Emmys were the lowest since 1990. Viewers, no
doubt, were fed up with seeing the same cast of characters winning.
Helen Hunt! Kristen Johnston! Dennis Franz! David Hyde Pierce! John
Lithgow!
</P>
<P>
   Ugh!
</P>
<P>
   After last year's critical backlash, the folks at the Academy of
Television Arts &AMP; Sciences ditched the blue-ribbon voting panels
that required judges to watch hours of tape over one weekend while
cooped up in a hotel. Now, judges can watch tapes wherever they
want.
</P>
<P>
   The result? More than 3,500 voting members participated this
year _ nearly three times as many as last year's total. But, more
important, there's a better crop of nominees. ``Will &AMP; Grace'' _
one of last year's major snubs _ received 11 nominations. Last year
it got only one. ``Sex and the City's'' nominations zoomed from two
to nine. And, thankfully ``NYPD Blue,'' a perennial best drama
candidate, was left off the ballot. Too bad the judges didn't do
the same for the woefully mediocre ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who's gonna win? As usual, it's a big crapshoot. But that
won't stop me: Here are my picks for who will win, who should win
and who got dissed.
</P>
<P>
   BEST DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: ``ER;'' ``Law &AMP; Order;'' ``The Practice;'' ``The
Sopranos;'' ``The West Wing''
</P>
<P>
   What will win: After feting David E. Kelley last year, ``The
Sopranos'' finally gets an award it can't refuse, even though it
was more deserving last season.
</P>
<P>
   What should win: ``The West Wing'' for making me believe in our
political system again. Don't you wish Martin Sheen was really our
president?
</P>
<P>
   What was overlooked: No other drama moved me more than ``Once
and Again,'' a complex _ and achingly realistic _ ensemble drama.
And when will thick-headed voters stop driving a stake through
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer's'' heart?
</P>
<P>
   BEST COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: ``Everybody Loves Raymond;'' ``Frasier;''
``Friends;'' ``Sex and the City;'' ``Will &AMP; Grace''
</P>
<P>
   What will/should win: Toss a coin. All are top-notch and
laugh-out-loud funny. But ``Frasier'' was wildly inconsistent. So
was the raunchy ``Sex and the City.'' Academy judges still don't
seem inclined to give ``Raymond'' its due. That leaves ``Friends,''
which has been ignored far too long for the hilarious comedy
machine it is.
</P>
<P>
   What was overlooked: The zany ``Malcolm in the Middle `` almost
single-handedly revived the tired sitcom genre, with its
distinctive, delightfully off-center point of view.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR _ DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Dennis Franz (''NYPD Blue''); James Gandolfini
(''The Sopranos''); Jerry Orbach (''Law &AMP; Order''); Martin Sheen
(''The West Wing''); Sam Waterston (''Law &AMP; Order'')
</P>
<P>
   Who will/should win: Fuhgetaboudit . . . Gandolfini whacks the
competition. I dare you to take your eyes off him while he's on
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS _ DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Lorraine Bracco (''The Sopranos''); Amy Brenneman
(''Judging Amy''); Edie Falco (''The Sopranos''); Julianna
Margulies (''ER''); Sela Ward (''Once and Again'')
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: The fabulous Falco gets the gold for the second
consecutive year. On a male-dominated show, she more than holds her
own.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: As the wonderfully flawed Lily Manning, Ward
plays a rich, full-bodied character with style, grace and delicious
sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Too bad no one takes Sarah Michelle Gellar's
stellar acting seriously on ``Buffy.''
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR _ COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Michael J. Fox (''Spin City''); Kelsey Grammer
(''Frasier''); John Lithgow (''3rd Rock from the Sun''); Eric
McCormack (''Will &AMP; Grace''); Ray Romano (''Everybody Loves
Raymond'')
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Not only will Fox nab the sentimental vote, he'll
also be treated to the night's longest standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Grammer remains a comic genius, even after a
spotty year.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Ryan Reynolds of ``Two Guys and a Girl'' . .
. OK, just making sure you're paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS _ COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Jenna Elfman (''Dharma &AMP; Greg''); Patricia Heaton
(''Everybody Loves Raymond''); Jane Kaczmarek (''Malcolm in the
Middle''); Debra Messing (''Will &AMP; Grace''); Sarah Jessica Parker
(''Sex and the City'')
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Kaczmarek's kooky mom character is a lovable
standout.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Heaton's quiet brilliance has made ``Raymond''
one of TV's best comedies.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Nobody in what is a historically weak field.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR _
</P>
<P>
   DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Michael Badalucco (''The Practice''); Dominic
Chianese (''The Sopranos''); Steve Harris (''The Practice'');
Richard Schiff (''The West Wing''); John Spencer (''The West
Wing'')
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: It's neck-and-neck between Chianese and Spencer.
And the winner is . . . Chianese by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: The mesmerizing Harris for getting snubbed the
last two years when the competition wasn't as steep.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Dennis Haysbert was smooth, menacing,
charismatic and a surprisingly pitch-perfect singer on CBS'
canceled ``Now and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS _ DRAMA
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Stockard Channing (''The West Wing''); Tyne Daly
(''Judging Amy''); Allison Janney (''The West Wing''); Nancy
Marchand (''The Sopranos''); Holland Taylor (''The Practice'')
</P>
<P>
   Who will/should win: The late Marchand played a delightfully
scheming mom we all loved to hate. A quick question: Why in heck
was Channing nominated in the best supporting actress category when
her first lady character is only a recurring one?
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR _ COMEDY
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Peter Boyle (''Everybody Loves Raymond''); Brad
Garrett (''Everybody Loves Raymond''); Sean Hayes (''Will &AMP;
Grace''); Peter MacNicol (''Ally McBeal''); David Hyde Pierce
(''Frasier'')
</P>
<P>
   Who will/should win: If Hayes doesn't dance away with that
16-inch statue, I'm launching an investigation. No one steals
scenes _ or does impromptu Cher impressions _ better.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: As Eric's grumpy dad on ``That '70s Show,''
Kurtwood Smith cracks me up whenever he opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS _ Comedy
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: Jennifer Aniston (''Friends''); Kim Cattrall
(''Sex and the City''); Lisa Kudrow (''Friends''); Megan Mullally
(''Will &AMP; Grace''); Doris Roberts (''Everybody Loves Raymond'')
</P>
<P>
   Who will/should win: Like Sean Hayes, Mullally knows how to take
over a scene by simply arching an eyebrow or shaking those
delicious hips of hers.
</P>
<P>
   Who was overlooked: Wendie Malick is the funniest character on
NBC's ``Just Shoot Me'' _ and that includes David Spade.
</P>
<P>
   BEST MINISERIES
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: ``Arabian Nights;'' ``The Beach Boys: An American
Family;'' ``The Corner;'' ``Jesus;'' ``P.T. Barnum''
</P>
<P>
   What will/should win: ``The Corner'' was the most powerful,
gut-wrenching TV event of the season. Period.
</P>
<P>
   What was overlooked: Are you kidding? The academy had a hard
enough time finding four other worthy nominees.
</P>
<P>
   BEST TV MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: ``Annie;'' ``If These Walls Could Talk 2;''
``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge;'' ``Oprah Winfrey Presents:''
``Tuesdays With Morrie;'' ``RKO 281''
</P>
<P>
   What will win: ``RKO 281.'' The judges' love affair with HBO
continues.
</P>
<P>
   What should win: Yes,''Tuesdays With Morrie ``was sappy and
predictable, but so what? Jack Lemmon _ America's grandfather _ was
magnificent as a dying college professor who bonded with his
one-time student.
</P>
<P>
   What was overlooked: Showtime's ``Strange Justice'' examined the
sordid Clarence Thomas/Anita Hill affair with dignity, intelligence
and raw power.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
