</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMY-Q&AMP;A0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Meet the guy who counts Emmy votes
 &HT;    By Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Only three people know tonight's Emmy
winners. All of them work for Ernst &AMP; Young, the Los Angeles
accounting firm that compiles and tabulates the votes. Jeff Rosen,
an Ernst &AMP; Young partner, is one of those three accountants. Of
course, we tried our best to get a tight-lipped Rosen to spill the
beans about tonight's winners.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm an inquisitive TV critic. I want a scoop. Give me the
name of one winner. I'll hook you up with Yasmine Bleeth. I can do
it, you know.
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm sorry, I can't tell you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Not even for Yasmine Bleeth?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nope.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Tabulating and compiling votes sounds like a pain in the
butt. Is it?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, how many accountants get to be on TV? But it's a very
detailed job because everything has to be triple checked.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's it like being on TV?
</P>
<P>
   A: It depends on the producer of the show. Sometimes it's a
quick Rose Bowl Parade wave. But last year (WWF wrestlers) Steve
Austin and The Rock interviewed us and ``TV Guide'' said it was one
of the most clever part of the Emmys.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How was The Rock?
</P>
<P>
   A: He was a genuinely nice guy. At the rehearsal, a disabled boy
wanted to meet him. There were no press people there and he needed
to catch a plane and was running late, but the boy's mother came up
to him and asked him to meet her son. He got out of his limo and
walked a long way just to meet the kid.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you ever scored with this line: ``Hey, babe, I'm an
accountant for Ernst &AMP; Young and I know all the Emmy winners?''
</P>
<P>
   A: (laughs) No, because I don't think that would work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have you ever been bribed before?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. But some reporters who have been covering the Emmys for a
long time will jokingly say, ``Come on, if you tell me now, I can
start writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does Ernst &AMP; Young keep you from blabbing?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm a partner in the firm and we know that it's both an honor
and a responsibility to make sure everything is done perfectly. We
never even consider spilling the beans.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You help tabulate the votes for TV's best shows, yet you
don't watch much TV. Don't you find that ironic?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is kind of funny. Often I have to ask people on the stage
who is the person I'm presenting the envelope to, even if they're
well known. Benjamin Bratt (''Law &AMP; Order'') is the nicest guy in
the world, but I had no idea who he was.
</P>
<P>
   Q: The only other Ernst I know is Ernst Stavro Blofeld from the
James Bond movies. Do you ever tease Ernst about that?
</P>
<P>
   A: No, never. But he's long gone. This firm's been around for
over 100 years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why do people think all accountants are stuffy?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't know. They'd be surprised if they really knew. We're
more outgoing than people think.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
