<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7544 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-ARCH0910-COX     09-09 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ARCH0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Family gives Buford-Bailey winning inspiration
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The answer to a tearful, head-shaking,
luck-cussin' Olympic question could be found a couple of days ago
in the living room of a home in Huber Heights.
</P>
<P>
   On the couch was Georgianna Buford and in her wheelchair was
daughter, Crystal. They are two women who have had a lot to do with
the success of Tonja Buford-Bailey, the Dayton hurdler who is
headed to her third straight Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
   Tonja has admitted it herself. Her mom and her sister _ who, at
31, is a year older than she _ have given her the mettle to medal.
One has provided the backbone and other has given her the legs _ so
to speak.
</P>
<P>
   That inspiration was evident at the Olympic Time Trials in
Sacramento seven weeks ago. That's where Buford-Bailey put on a
performance many thought was not possible. Her performance prompted
an emotional question from a stunned, unexpectedly-beaten
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it went:
</P>
<P>
   While Buford-Bailey won the bronze medal in the 400 meter
hurdles at the 1996 Olympics in Atlanta, she then disappeared from
competition for two years as she nursed some injuries, then gave
birth to her son, VJ, who now is a couple weeks shy of 2.
</P>
<P>
   When she finally returned to the track in early 1999, her
hurdling form was a mess and the results were worse. After coming
into the Atlanta Olympic Games with the second fastest time in
history _ her 52.62 seconds was just 1/100th of a second off the
world record _ she ran a 60.8 in the 1999 Prefontaine Classic. When
she was 14, she had run faster.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't get much better and early this year when she
turned in a disheartening 58.9 at her first big meet. It was around
that time that she made one of her frequent trips from her home in
Dallas back to Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had come back to train with her old coach at Illinois for
a while, but she was running terrible,'' Georgianna said. ``She was
turning in times she got back at Meadowdale (High) and she was
crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were riding in the car on the way to the Fairfield Commons
Mall and I could see it in her face. Even though they think you
don't, a mother knows what's in their children's minds. She wanted
to quit. She could go back home with her husband (former pro
football player Victor Bailey) and her child and have a superb
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her 'OK, you want to quit. But let me ask you one
thing. When they line up to race in Sydney _ and they're running
times that you ran _ are you still going to be happy for them or
will you cry?' She said, 'I'll probably cry.' That's when I said,
'Then you can't quit. Not on those terms.'
</P>
<P>
   And she didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into the Trials, she had begun to improve and that
finally got her into the eight-woman finals _ where only the top
three finishers would win a trip to Sydney. Coming off the eighth
hurdle in what was a 10-hurdle race, Buford-Bailey was sixth and
almost certainly out of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I panicked,'' Buford-Bailey said, ``but then I just thought,
'Forget form. Go after them and catch one at a time.' ``
</P>
<P>
   By the last hurdle, she still was fifth. But with a final sprint
to the tape, she passed Michelle Johnson and then _ just a stride
from the finish _ Joanna Hayes to finish at 54.70. Sandra Glover
was first at 53.33, Kim Batten was second.
</P>
<P>
   Among those beaten was Yvonne Harrison, whose heritage,
Georgianna said, could have assured her a spot on the Jamaican
team. She chose the United States instead because the opportunities
are more lucrative here and she figured her chances of winning were
good since Buford-Bailey, especially, seemed to be a sitting duck.
</P>
<P>
   But the duck turned into a swan and afterward a disconsolate
Harrison tearfully wondered: ``How did that happen?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer was right there in Huber Heights. While Buford-Bailey
certainly is inspired by her son, her husband and her other
siblings, no one has given her more than Georgianna and Crystal.
</P>
<P>
   Although she now has a decent paying job as a prison guard at
the Warren Correctional Institution in Lebanon, Georgianna said
early on, life was anything but decent. She had come from a
background of abuse and spent her first eight years in an
orphanage. By age 16, she'd quit school and had her first child.
After five more children, she was divorced in the mid 1980s. Six
months later, Crystal was diagnosed with muscular dystrophy.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the children to work jobs, get good grades and delve
into sports, she eventually saw each child pursue a college degree.
At present, even Crystal _ who maneuvers her wheelchair into an RTA
bus each week day _ is just two courses away from a degree at
Sinclair Community College. Georgianna herself is completing a
degree as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids saw how hard it was for me, but we stressed one
thing,'' Georgianna said. ``It was that there's always something
better just ahead. And the way to get it was to draw strength from
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   And the font of that fortitude has been Crystal, who was
diagnosed with muscular dystrophy at 15 and relegated to a
wheelchair 18-months later.
</P>
<P>
   ``She and Tonja are close,'' Georgianna said. ``There's a
special bond there. They talk on the phone a lot. I think Tonja
draws on the same thing I do. Crystal has a great attitude. She
lifts us all up out of the gutter.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Tonja has talked about what her sister means to
her: ``Every race I run, every day I train _ I'm doing it with my
sister in mind. We're just a year apart and that could just as well
be me. She's a beautiful person and she taught me a lot. The way I
look at it, the strength taken from her has been given to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Crystal smiled at such assessment: ``Now she's got the legs for
both of us.''
</P>
<P>
   After Buford-Bailey qualified for the Olympics at the 1996
Trials, she ran into the stands and gave her sister her medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so sweet,'' Crystal said.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Crystal's condition has not improved. Her hands and
fingers curl inward, as do her feet. But rather than lament, she
shows off her long, ornately decorated fingernails.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real, too,'' she said proudly, with a gleam in her
beautiful eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same look that got her sister _ according to Mom _
voted one of the world's most beautiful athletes at a track meet in
France.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonja called me last night from a meet in Europe,'' Crystal
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her mom shook her head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah Crystal gets it all,'' Georgianna said. ``I haven't
gotten my medal yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgianna has gotten a lot of other things though. She told
stories of her first Olympic trip _ to Barcelona in 1992 _ when
Tonja was one of the youngest athletes on the American team. While
Tonja didn't make the final, mother and daughter had a good time
afterwards. Georgianna told of kibitzing with Dream Team basketball
stars Scottie Pippen, Charles Barkley and Patrick Ewing and of
being befriended by Jesse Owens' daughter.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, she told of the ``unbelievable feeling'' that came
as she watched her daughter win an Olympic medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time, I'll be truthful. I wasn't sure if she was gonna
make it,'' Georgianna said. ``When I saw her way back there at the
Trials, I was worried that was it. But the old home girl pulled
through for us. In the end, I should have known she would have
something extra.''
</P>
<P>
   She did.
</P>
<P>
   A mother's backbone and a sister's legs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
