<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-RUN-JACOBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING JACOBS WILL NOT BATTLE MASTERKOVA IN 1,500 METERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRISBANE, Australia _ Finally, Regina Jacobs would break the
cycle of brilliant Olympic trials and unsatisfying Olympic Games.
At 37, she was at the peak of her running career. Having won a pair
of silver medals in the 1,500 meters at the world championships,
she would challenge for gold in the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   All those expectations dissolved Saturday when Jacobs announced
from her home in Oakland, Calif., that she was withdrawing from the
American Olympic team because of a viral infection in her lungs.
She could not breathe properly in training, she said, and an
insufficient oxygen supply gave her no chance of challenging the
defending champion in the metric mile, Svetlana Masterkova of
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Masback, the chief executive officer of the U.S. track and
field federation, called the development ``a terrible loss for the
U.S. team and for her, given how hard she had worked to get to this
moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Another gold-medal favorite, the world-champion shot-putter C.J.
Hunter, remains questionable after undergoing orthoscopic knee
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second major meet from which Jacobs has withdrawn.
She missed the 1995 world track and field championships in
Goeteborg, Sweden, with a foot problem. Now she is out of the
Olympics in the metric mile, having previously finished 10th at the
Atlanta Games and having failed to make the final in 1992 and 1988.
Shayne Culpepper, who finished fourth at the Olympic trials in
July, will replace Jacobs in Sydney, but she has no expectation of
winning a medal.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jacobs, winner of both the 1,500 and the 5,000 meters at
the Olympic trials, who seemed to have a real chance to bring the
American women their first Olympic gold medal in the 1,500 meters.
She had won silver medals at the 1997 and 1999 world championships,
overcoming an iron deficiency with supplements and a change in
diet. A more efficient stride encouraged her that she could finally
challenge Masterkova's blistering kick in the 1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs set an American record of 14 minutes 45.35 seconds in the
5,000 meters on July 21. In hindsight, some track experts Saturday
questioned why Jacobs, who has a history of allergies and illness,
subjected her body to the stress of that 3.1-mile race at the
trials when she had no intention of running the event in the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said her respiratory troubles began Aug. 11, three weeks
after the Olympic trials, where she finished 14th out of 16 runners
in a 3,000-meter race in Zurich, Switzerland. Her time of 8:50.12
was 24 seconds behind the winner, Gabriela Szabo of Romania.
</P>
<P>
   After a regimen of antibiotics, Jacobs appeared to have
recovered from the viral infection, according to her agent, Emanuel
Hudson. But on Tuesday she grew exhausted after two repetitions of
a planned workout of 9 x 500 meters, he said, and a doctor's
examination showed she was breathing at only 65 percent of
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped to get it under control before Sydney, but we seem
to have run out of time,'' Jacobs said of her relapse. Hudson, her
agent, said: ``She told me, `My chances of medaling are zero and
none, and I don't want to waste a spot on the team.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1528EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
