<SLUG> BC-NY-PESTICIDE-VICTIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER COMPLAINT OF ILLNESS, MAYOR DEFENDS SPRAY EFFORTS
</HEADLINE>
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani acknowledged on Saturday that
a woman had been treated at an emergency room on Monday after she
complained of being sprayed with a pesticide used to kill
mosquitoes that spread the West Nile virus. But the mayor said
there was ``obviously a discrepancy'' between the city's spraying
schedule and the woman's account of when she was sprayed.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, whose account was published on Saturday in the Daily
News, was quoted as saying she was drenched with the pesticide at
10:45 p.m. last Sunday as she stood on West 58th Street in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The News article, coming amid controversy over widespread
pesticide spraying that the city has undertaken to ward off an
outbreak of the West Nile virus, said the woman, an artist whom the
newspaper did not identify, had been sprayed at point-blank range
by a passing city truck. As a result, it said, she experienced
severe nausea and eye problems and feared more serious long-term
effects because she has a form of asthma that reacts to chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Saturday, the mayor was joined by Health
Department officials who shed little light on the incident other
than to say it was under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know this person,'' said Dr. Benjamin Mojica, the deputy
health commissioner, although he also declined to identify her,
citing patient confidentiality. ``We intend to follow up with her
and see how she is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But the officials said the woman's version conflicted with city
records, which show that spraying in the area where the incident is
said to have occurred did not begin until shortly before midnight
last Sunday, at least an hour after the woman said she was sprayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody started spraying early, they shouldn't have, and
we don't think they did,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor also said that incidents like the one described in
the Daily News might be unavoidable because of how much spraying is
taking place. Health officials predict they will need to continue
spraying the pesticide, Anvil, across the city for at least another
month, or until mosquitoes that carry the virus are killed by
subfreezing temperatures. The mayor said it was the responsibility
of New Yorkers to ``pay attention to announcements, since the
spraying is not going to stop if you are standing there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
