<SLUG> BC-ELECTIONS-PERKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL RACES NOT JUST ABOUT POWER, BUT PERKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To hear party leaders and candidates tell it, the
Nov. 7 battle for control of the House of Representatives is all
about shaping the nation's future.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also about personal power and perks, choice offices and
close-in parking.
</P>
<P>
   Seniority outranks partisanship in Congress, where members move
up in status and into better offices based on their years of
service. Those moves come at the expense of colleagues who've
retired, died in office or been defeated at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to move every two years,'' said Gene Smith, chief of
staff for Rep. Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills. ``We're always on
the lookout for more office space.''
</P>
<P>
   So whatever the outcome of the election, the Capitol's
furniture-moving crews will have their hands full between November
and January, when the new Congress convenes.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, who faces no GOP opposition for a 10th term, has offices
in the maze-like Rayburn Building, one of three marble-clad
complexes used by House members and their staffs.
</P>
<P>
   Rayburn, built in 1965 with such conveniences as private baths,
tops the House office pecking order. Closest to the Capitol and the
site of most committee hearing rooms, it also sports an electric
subway that transports members to the House floor for votes.
</P>
<P>
   The Longworth Building, completed in 1933, is the second-most
desirable office locale. The smallest complex, it is prized for its
architecture and reviled for its sketchy elevator service and lack
of windows with decent views. It is linked to the Capitol and other
offices by a pedestrian tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the barrel is the Cannon Building. Built in
1907 and much the worse for decades of wear, it stands the farthest
from the Capitol. It sports a poorly designed fifth-floor addition,
built in 1913 and known as ``The Gulag.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Sechrist, a 20-year veteran House employee who works as
press aide to Rep. Joe Baca, D-Rialto, thinks a lot these days
about Cannon's fifth floor and its evoked images of Josef Stalin's
Siberian prison camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to be moving, but we're hoping for the
best and hoping we don't end up in Cannon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of seniority, Baca has been on borrowed time since
November, when he was elected to fill out the term of the late
George Brown, who had been in Congress since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   House rules allowed Baca to temporarily move into the
Capitol-view digs held by Brown, who died during his 18th term.
</P>
<P>
   But, come late November - should Baca win re-election - he and
every other House member with eyes on a better office will be
placed in lottery groups based on seniority. Veteran members will
draw numbers and choose first, with Baca's current office among the
prime pickings.
</P>
<P>
   Baca will be well down the list, in a lottery pool of
second-termers.
</P>
<P>
   Newly elected freshman members will get the dregs.
</P>
<P>
   The parking pecking order will also shift in November, with
senior members and staffers seeking indoor spaces closer to their
offices and junior aides to freshmen hoping they can park outdoors
within walking distance of Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Smith cautioned that even the best House offices pale in
comparison to corporate suites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood depictions of Congress make it look like we live in
luxury,'' she said. ``In reality, these offices are very small,
plain and crowded with staff.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, competition for prime space is fierce.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who has worked in Congress for 25 years, recalled her
days working for the late Rep. Gillis Long, D-La., who died in
office in 1985. ``We had people coming around to check out our
office the day after he passed away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Luxury is the watchword for a handful of Capitol offices that
will change hands if the Democrats regain the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., the odds-on favorite for speaker
under a new Democratic regime, would supplant GOP Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., in a spacious complex that includes a covered
outdoor porch.
</P>
<P>
   Also at risk is the ornate Capitol office, replete with a
fireplace, that is now occupied by Rep. David Dreier, R-Covina,
chairman of the House Rules Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats are hoping there won't be a
replay of the acrimony that marked the GOP's 1995 takeover.
</P>
<P>
   Former Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and other GOP members took
out 40 years of frustration by sacking hundreds of Democratic
staffers and even removing the portraits of legendary Democratic
lawmakers from committee room walls.
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic victory in the Nov. 7 election guarantees a new
round of firings. The attorneys, policy analysts and other aides
who work for House committees are, for the most part, Republican
appointees and have no civil service job protections.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Brad Sherman, D-Woodland Hills, sees a more peaceful
scenario for the next Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to see a chastened Democratic Party when we take
over next year,'' Sherman said. ``We have spent four years
wandering in the wilderness and have learned some important
lessons.''
</P>
<P>
   The winning party is going to have a razor-thin majority and
could easily face going back to the minority in coming elections,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days we had some Democrats who acted like they were
going to be in power forever. This time, we're not going to get
anything done unless we work with the other side in a bipartisan,
moderate and fiscally responsible manner.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
