<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: WHEN IT COMES TO SPENDING, OLD HABITS DIE HARD 
</HEADLINE>
  By   MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Yankees stockpiled one new player after another this
season, their cash register kept ringing up higher and higher
numbers. Except this was the register that was paying out cash to
the players.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' payroll, which began the season at an already
record $92.5 million, was spiraling sky high, soaring to heights
unknown to baseball management. The game's first $100 million
payroll was a work in progress. Where it would end up nobody knew.
</P>
<P>
   As higher and higher numbers were published, the Yankees brass
became more and more uncomfortable. They protested that the numbers
did not reflect the actual dollars they were spending. They were
correct, but the annual salary reports produced by management and
the players association have never used actual dollars spent. They
have always attributed a player's entire salary to the team that
has him Aug. 31, even if he was traded to the team that day.
</P>
<P>
   With computers able to determine payrolls in any form desired,
both sides could change their systems, but they retain the way they
have always done things for that very reason _ that's the way they
have always done things. It has been the only way to compare
payrolls and average salaries of the 2000 season, say, with
previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Using the traditional, if outdated, method, the Yankees this
season have a payroll totaling an unheard of $112 million. That
figure is based on the 25 players who were on their major league
roster and the eight players who were on the disabled list Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   But in terms of actual dollars spent, the Yankees are paying
their players $102.5 million this season. That's about $10 million
less than advertised, but it's not going to placate the critics
among baseball officials and other owners who complain that the
Yankees' salary expenditures are out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The actual dollar figure is computed by determining how many
days of the 182-day season players have been with the Yankees and
what portion of their salaries that time represents.
</P>
<P>
   The total includes not just the salaries of Aug. 31 players but
those of everyone who has played for the team this season, from the
$12,357,143 for Bernie Williams and the $12 million for David Cone
to the $4,395.60 outfielder Luke Wilcox was paid for his four days
on the Yankees' roster in July and the $5,553.57 Ed Yarnall earned
in his five days with the team in April and July.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the two totals comes primarily from the
salaries of the five major players the Yankees acquired in June and
July. David Justice, Denny Neagle, Jose Vizcaino, Jose Canseco and
Glenallen Hill have 2000 salaries totaling $19.75 million, but the
Yankees will pay them $9,210,164. In addition, they will pay Neagle
$250,000, under a provision in his contract, because he was traded.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees added two other players in July and August who had
been released by their previous teams, so they are paying Dwight
Gooden and Luis Polonia prorated shares of the $200,000 minimum
salary. The team gets their services for a total of $160,439. They
are paying another newcomer, Luis Sojo, a mere $135,989, meaning
the 10 new players _ 40 percent of the roster _ will cost the
Yankees $9,756,592. Sounds like a bargain, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   And then, take the Minnesota Twins. Their payroll is less than
the combined salaries of the left side of the Yankees' infield,
Derek Jeter and Scott Brosius. Unlike other teams, the Twins did
not add minor leaguers to their September roster. They have 25
players on their roster and one on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The 26 players have combined salaries of $14,887,500. Eighteen
of the 26 players have six-figure salaries that start with a two.
Eleven of those salaries range from the $200,000 minimum to
$207,500.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, when Calvin Griffith owned the Twins and the owners
first began discussing revenue sharing, George Steinbrenner, the
Yankees' big spender, said he would be willing to share his revenue
if Griffith would allow him to aid in the operation of the Twins.
If Carl Pohlad, the present Twins owner, let Steinbrenner help him,
would the Twins have a $100 million payroll?
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STAYING ON TOP IS THE HARD PART
</P>
<P>
   Flash: Braves Won't Finish First Forever!
</P>
<P>
   That startling revelation emerged from the mouth of Tom Glavine,
the only active player who has been with Atlanta for every one of
its eight consecutive division championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to win forever,'' the 34-year-old pitcher
said. ``We're not going to win our division for the rest of
baseball. Sometime we'll lose, but I hope it doesn't happen until
after I'm not playing anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine offered that observation a few days after the Braves
reclaimed first place in the National League East from the Mets.
The Braves' second-place status on the last day of August and the
first day of September made them appear to be mortal. It even had
people raising the possibility of the Braves being a wild-card
entry in this year's playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it creeps in there,'' Glavine said, when asked if the
Braves ever think wild card and not first place. ``But your
ultimate thinking is you want to win your division, do whatever you
can to win your division. If you fall short, I guess you accept
wild card and try to get to the World Series from that position.''
</P>
<P>
   If there had been any reason for the Braves to let wild-card
thinking creep in, it seems to be gone now. The Mets just can't
seem to deal with the prosperity of first place or being an inch
away from first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mets are a good ball club,'' said Glavine, a 19-game
winner, who could also win his third Cy Young Award. ``They've been
a good ball club. They've been a threat. They've done the same
thing as we have. They've gotten better over the years. They've
made changes before and after the trading deadline that improved
their depth.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge the Mets have mounted the last few seasons has
been good for the Braves, Glavine added.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have somebody knocking on your door like that,'' he
said, ``it tends to keep you focused and pushing hard for where you
want to be, not to take things for granted. The closer the Mets
get, we find a way to play better and win. It's the competition
thing. It forces you to raise the level of your game so that you
can achieve what you want to achieve.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Summertime Slides
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners had seemingly claimed first place in the
American League West for themselves. A month ago they increased
their lead to a season-high seven games. They had withstood
Oakland's challenge, and they simply had to gain their share of
victories the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that was the Mariners' trouble. From that day to Saturday,
the Mariners won seven games but lost 18, helplessly watching their
lead dwindle to two games.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets pulled a version of the Mariners' slide. From the day
they snatched first place from the Braves until Saturday, they
played seven games and lost six.
</P>
<P>
   After tumbling out of first place the last day of July, then
falling three games behind, the Arizona Diamondbacks rallied and,
with the aid of a seven-game winning streak, pulled within half a
game out Aug. 20. Since then? They won five, lost 11, falling as
far back as eight and a half games.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds, one of the most disappointing teams this
season, seemed to be headed in the right direction, finally, when
they closed within four and a half games of first place. But after
standing that close to first Aug. 13, they won 12 and lost 13.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers, who lost 23 of their first 32 games, inched
past .500, finally, on Sept. 1. When they won the next day, they
were incredibly only four games behind in the wild-card race. Then
they lost four of their next six games and slipped six back.
</P>
<P>
   CHASING MILESTONES
</P>
<P>
   Todd Helton of Colorado did not have a good week in his quest to
hit .400. He was down to .386 entering Saturday's game, meaning if
he goes to bat at the same ratio he has until now, he will have to
hit .488 (39 for 80) to finish at .400. A week ago he had to hit
only .449 the rest of the season to get there.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, Darin Erstad of Anaheim had to average just under
two hits a game to break George Sisler's record of 257 hits in a
season (1920). He had a bad week, too. Now he has to average 2.25
hits a game to eclipse Sisler.
</P>
<P>
   NOOFFICIALINFORMATION.COM
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball, whose Web site on the Internet has been
majorleaguebaseball.com, has gained the shorter version it had
desired from a law firm with the same initials, mlb.com. But that
does not mean its Internet policies will change with the name.
</P>
<P>
   When the site carries news articles about player contracts and
salaries, financial details are first expunged. Chipper Jones signs
a six-year extension with Atlanta for $90 million? Don't look for
those numbers at mlb.com.
</P>
<P>
   The reason given? Baseball does not officially divulge player
salary information, so even if it appears in, say, an Associated
Press article, mlb.com will not be responsible for anyone learning
the details on its Web site.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
