u a BC-NY-MOMA-LABOR-650&AMP;ADD     09-09 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MOMA-LABOR-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE ENDS AT MUSEUM OF MODERN ART 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The union representing 250 striking workers at the
Museum of Modern Art voted Saturday to end its 134-day walkout,
just hours after reaching an agreement in which both sides made
significant concessions.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's workers applauded the contract, which awards an 18
percent wage increase over five years and promises to give jobs
back to any union members furloughed when much of the museum is
closed during a five-year, $650 million expansion and renovation.
Some employees will be assigned to a temporary museum to be set up
in the Long Island City section of Queens.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the museum granted the union's demand, aimed at
increasing the union's strength, to require all new professional
and administrative workers to join the union or pay union dues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm elated,'' said Michael Cinquina, a buyer for the museum's
bookstore and a member of the negotiating team for the union, Local
2110 of the United Automobile Workers, which represents 250
archivists, assistant curators, librarians, bookshop workers and
others at the museum. ``It's all that I hoped for. It made every
day we stayed out worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's chief negotiator, Robert Batterman, said the
agreement was a compromise. ``I think it's a fair settlement,'' he
said. ``There were no winners.''
</P>
<P>
   Batterman said the museum achieved its goal of having more
flexibility in overseeing a health plan for both management
employees and union members. He said that despite the union's
opposition, the museum obtained the right to unilaterally impose
changes in health coverage. One caveat is that any changes made to
union members' coverage would also apply to management employees.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached at 3 a.m. Saturday after a 15-hour
negotiating session, ends a bitter dispute in which half the
workers crossed the picket line and the museum was forced to cancel
numerous fund-raisers, concerts and screenings. Museum officials
said the strike did not hurt attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders said they pressured the museum into showing more
flexibility at the bargaining table by enlisting 150 prominent
artists to back the strikers, and by lining up City Council members
to delay, and perhaps block, a zoning variance that the museum
needed for its project.
</P>
<P>
   They also insisted that they emerged victorious in the
negotiations on health coverage, saying that management changed its
stance and finally acknowledged that the union had the right to
bargain collectively about changes in the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Batterman said the union, and not management, was on the
defensive and had suddenly shown more flexibility. He said the
union was hurt by the decision of many construction unions to allow
workers to do demolition work for the museum's expansion despite
the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   The negotiating session, which began at noon on Friday, was the
first face-to-face meeting of the two sides since the strike began
on April 28.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Wheeler, the director of the United Auto Workers in New
York, said that some strikers grew dispirited when many workers
crossed the picket line. But he said the strikers were helped
greatly by support from other unions.
</P>
<P>
   Maida Rosenstein, president of Local 2110, said, ``I don't think
the museum anticipated that this group would stay out and be as
steadfast as they were.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the museum was eager to have the strike settled in
September because several new exhibits are opening and it would be
harder to mount those exhibits with many employees not working.
</P>
<P>
   Batterman said the museum was so frustrated by the deadlocked
talks that he took an unusual step: He asked a union official to
serve as a mediator, an idea welcomed by the museum workers union.
</P>
<P>
   That official, Bruce Raynor, secretary-treasurer of the Union of
Needletrades, Industrial and Textile Employees, worked closely with
federal mediators on Friday to help settle the dispute.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Batterman denied that the museum was affected by a letter in
which 150 prominent artists, including Robert Rauschenberg and
Steven Spielberg, voiced support for the strikers. He also insisted
that the museum was not worried that the City Council would block
the zoning variance it was seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the museum's union, working with the New York City
Central Labor Council and the New York state AFL-CIO, had gotten a
majority of the City Council's Manhattan members to hold off on
recommending the variance. Typically, the full City Council does
not grant variances unless the members from the affected borough
recommend it.
</P>
<P>
   In its last proposal before the strike began, the museum offered
a 3 percent raise for each of three years. The union demand a 5
percent raise in the first year, and 4 percent for the next four
years.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement calls for a 3 percent raise in the first year, and
4 percent or $1,100 in the second year, whichever is greater. In
the third, fourth and fifth years, there will be a 3.5 percent wage
increase. Workers' salaries range from $17,000 to over $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement leaves open the option that it will run longer
than five years if the expansion project takes longer than that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
