u p BC-MRSCLINTON-LABOR-NYT &LR;      09-09 0578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSCLINTON-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON REVELS IN UNIONS' ATTENTIONS DURING LABOR PARADE 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton was the belle of New York
City's somewhat belated Labor Day parade Saturday, just as union
leaders had planned.
</P>
<P>
   As tens of thousands of union members marched up Fifth Avenue,
to the accompaniment of salsa bands and bagpipes, many marchers and
union leaders hailed Clinton as a friend of working families.
</P>
<P>
   Along the parade route, though, Clinton received only mild
cheers and a few jeers from onlookers, who stood on the sidewalk
behind police barricades. After she walked the route, she returned
to the staging area, where thousands of workers were still waiting
to join the parade, and they enthusiastically chanted her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Hillary,'' said Manfred Spikereit, who was among a
group of 100 members of the electrical workers union who rode
motorcycles in the parade. ``She's pro-union. I like what she
stands for and I like how she loosened up in recent months.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the enthusiasm union leaders voiced for the
first lady throughout the day showed that they planned to mount a
full-scale campaign and get-out-the-vote effort for her this fall.
Several unions had placards printed, reading Labor for Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   The parade stretched from 44th to 72nd Street, and officials
with the New York City Central Labor Council, which sponsored the
parade, estimated that there were more than 200,000 marchers.
</P>
<P>
   In publicizing the parade, Randi Weingarten, its chairwoman and
the president of the United Federation of Teachers, said one of the
march's main themes, besides promoting Clinton, was that nearly
300,000 New York City municipal workers want a contract soon.
</P>
<P>
   Among the marchers was a sea of teachers wearing bright red
T-shirts, while thousands of members of District Council 37, the
giant union of municipal workers, wore green T-shirts. The back of
all their shirts said, ``We all deserve respect and a fair raise.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Central Labor Council did not invite Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, a Republican, to the parade, even though mayors are
traditionally invited and walk at the front. Clinton walked in the
front line, sandwiched between John Sweeney, president of the
AFL-CIO, and Brian McLaughlin, president of the central labor
council.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the labor council has scheduled the parade for
the Saturday after Labor Day. Union leaders decided to stop holding
the parade on the traditional Monday holiday because so many union
members did not want their three-day weekends cut short for the
march. In addition, union leaders had voiced frustration that on
Labor Day, Manhattan's streets were largely empty, meaning there
were few onlookers to be impressed by labor's show of strength.
</P>
<P>
   At a breakfast for 300 labor leaders Saturday morning at
District Council 37's headquarters in downtown Manhattan,
McLaughlin praised the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary Rodham Clinton has been an advocate of everything we
believe in for all of her adult and professional life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent much of the day beaming, seemingly delighted to be
the focus of so much enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, after marching the parade route, Clinton went back
to 45th Street, climbed atop a flatbed truck and used a megaphone
to speak to hundreds of members of Local 3 of the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
