u i BC-MIDEAST-STATEHOOD-BOS     09-09 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-STATEHOOD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS EXPECTED TO DELAY STATEHOOD DECLARATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The expected birth of a new Palestine is likely to
be delayed Sunday, with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat pushing a
new, compressed time frame for progress on Mideast peace before
declaring statehood.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian Central Council began meeting in Gaza Saturday
to consider Arafat's move to postpone Wednesday's self-imposed
deadline to announce statehood.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the delay was expected Sunday, and the
government-controlled Palestinian media predicted the statehood
declaration would be put off until at least Nov. 15, providing a
narrow opening for the peace talks to get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The debate occurred on a day in which all sides tried to send
signals that the peace process _ stalled despite President
Clinton's separate meetings last week with Ararat and Israel's
prime minister, Ehud Barak _ was still proceeding. Clinton and
Barak met again in New York Saturday, following the United Nations
millennial conference.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat told the Palestine council Saturday that low-level
negotiations with the Israelis would shift into high gear Sunday or
Monday and would last for five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat also said statehood would be declared unilaterally if
those talks are not fruitful, an official at the closed-door
meeting said. Israel has threatened to annex parts of the West Bank
and Gaza Strip if statehood is declared outside the peace
framework.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat's moves left analysts wondering whether he is exercising
brinkmanship or losing a historic opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader arrived in Gaza Saturday morning from the
UN conference without a breakthrough _ and with a deadlock over the
sovereignty of Jerusalem, which both Israelis and Palestinians see
as their capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``For your information, we already have our state and we will
continue to do so,'' Arafat told reporters in Gaza after a
welcoming ceremony with all the military trappings of a state.
</P>
<P>
   Just outside the hearings of the 128-member Palestinian council,
commentators and officials portrayed the delay in the official
declaration as a near certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Votes are not yet in,'' Palestinian Cabinet minister Nabil
Shaath told CNN. ``But the general tendency is to delay, to give
the peace process another chance.''
</P>
<P>
   If Arafat did declare statehood Wednesday, a date that both
Arafat and Barak set last year for an overall peace agreement, he
would have to do so unilaterally, a move that many feared would
cause a regional conflagration to erupt. For this reason the
international community, at the UN conference and in other meetings
over the summer, has put intense pressure on Arafat not to
unilaterally declare statehood.
</P>
<P>
   They have urged the 70-year-old Palestinian leader to continue
to try to find a framework for reaching a final peace agreement
that would include the status of Jerusalem, the fate of Israeli
settlements, the final drawing of borders, and a solution to the
Palestinian refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
   It would not be the first time Arafat has delayed a declaration
of statehood. Last year, he announced that May 4, 1999 was a
``sacred date'' that marked the end of the five-year ``interim
phase'' of the peace process and the point at which he would
declare a state. He pulled back from the brink then, as he is
expected to now.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a sense in many corners that time is running out
and that the events of this week will be critical in determining
the fate of the six-year-old peace process.
</P>
<P>
   If the deadline is postponed to Nov. 15 or plans are set for
perhaps a vague declaration of sometime before the end of the year,
the parties will have only a matter of weeks to reach a point where
they feel they have a peace deal that would be accepted by their
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has made a tremendous personal and political
investment in the peace process throughout his two terms, has
little time left left in his presidency to shore up a deal and
present what will be a massive aid package to the US Congress
before it ends its session in October.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also feels the political clock ticking.
</P>
<P>
   When the Israeli parliament reconvenes next month, Barak faces a
dramatic challenge to his power, and possibly the toppling of his
government, by the religious and conservative parties who feel he
has already compromised too much in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   The player least squeezed by time and political pressure is
Arafat _ and in this sense the moment weighs heavily on him.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat is a ``master of tactics,'' said Mahdi Abdul Hadi,
director of the Palestinian Academic Society for the Study of
International Affairs in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week at the United Nations he showed he was on equal
footing with all of the world's leaders. And for the first time
ever, he has begun discussing the idea that there would be someone
after him who would carry on the fight,'' Hadi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows that he can wait longer if he needs to to declare a
state,'' Hadi said. ``He wants the symbolism of statehood, but he
is going to play it out a little bit longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Hadi and other Palestinian observers point out that a unilateral
declaration of statehood would also have resulted in a potentially
disastrous scenario. Israel controls the electricity, the water,
the borders, and most of the jobs in the Palestinian sector and
could cripple an already struggling Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has also vowed that Israel would reassert its military
control over areas of shared sovereignty in the West Bank if Arafat
unilaterally declared a state _ a prospect that both sides agree
would likely result in war.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Heller, chief researcher at Tel Aviv University's Jaffe
Center for Strategic Studies, said he is troubled by what appears
to be ``no long-term, coherent strategy'' on the part of Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arafat is simply improvising one day to the next and
postponing the hard decisions,'' Heller said. ``He is making a
calculation that over time the Israeli position will erode, but I
think that is a miscalculation that will end in a missed
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller also dismisses Barak and Clinton's assertions that the
time is ``now or never.'' He believes there is an inevitable
momentum toward the declaration of a Palestinian state and
ultimately toward a peace agreement that will end the 52 years of
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process has not failed, and it won't fail for a simple
reason: No one can give up,'' Heller said. ``No one can throw up
their hands and walk away. Our fates are too closely intertwined
for that to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
