<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7645 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FOLLOWUP-NYT &LR;      09-09 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FOLLOWUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAFIOSI HAVEN BECOMES FASHIONISTA'S HEAVEN  
 STILL SEEKING PAYMENT FROM BERNARD GOETZ 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Bylines follow individual stories.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As SoHo seeps eastward and NoHo southward in Lower
Manhattan, Amy Chan, a women's accessories boutique at 247 Mulberry
Street, is typical of the chic shops and cafes that have been
moving into northern Little Italy, now promoted by real estate
marketers as NoLIta.
</P>
<P>
   But while most who enter the trendy turf of Amy Chan _ with its
python-patterned pocketbooks and fashionable belts _ simply see one
more attractive shop, some have their sights on the site's past,
said Candace Mohr, the store's manager. They ``ask me silly
questions, like `Did you find any bodies here?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Chan occupies the space previously known as the Ravenite
Social Club, a lair from which John Gotti, the Mafia leader,
masterminded murders, plotted rackets and was toadied to as the
Gambino crime family boss.
</P>
<P>
   The notorious mobster, dubbed the Dapper Don, reigned there from
the mid-1980s until his 1990 arrest. Convicted of murder and
racketeering, he is serving life in prison without parole.
</P>
<P>
   But the storefront space has been paroled from its previous
role. The government confiscated the building, and two years ago
sold it to a group that sought a different kind of street-level
occupant.
</P>
<P>
   And so, gone is the bunkerlike brick facade that hid the Gambino
doings, replaced by glass that invites peering in. Gone are the bar
and card tables, in favor of handbags designed by Chan and
Chinese-themed lanterns and a reproduction of an Andy Warhol
portrait of Chairman Mao.
</P>
<P>
   Mohr, who sports tattoos of snakes in a place where the past
talk was often of rats, told of ``the weird ones who come in and
take pictures of the floor,'' a cracked and patched expanse of tile
preserved from the Ravenite days.
</P>
<P>
   And she and Ashley McGovern, a sales clerk, recalled another
visitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us what went on here,'' McGovern said. ``He said the
bar was here, the card tables were there.''
</P>
<P>
   He told them his name was Joe the Hat.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOSEPH P. FRIED
</P>
<P>
   Still Seeking Payment From Bernard Goetz
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Cabey, who was awarded $43 million by a jury for his
injuries from being shot by Bernard H. Goetz in a Manhattan subway
train in 1984, has not received that money from Goetz. Cabey and
three others were shot by Goetz, an electrical engineer, while
riding the subway. Goetz, who used an unlicensed handgun, told the
police that he feared the young men were going to rob him.
</P>
<P>
   Cabey, the most seriously wounded, was paralyzed and suffered
brain damage. Goetz was acquitted of assault and attempted murder
in 1987 but was convicted on a weapons possession charge. In 1996 a
civil jury found the shooting unjustified and awarded Cabey $43
million. Goetz later filed for bankruptcy, but a judge said he
still had to pay his victim.
</P>
<P>
   Cabey's lawyer, Ronald L. Kuby, said that he has retained a law
firm that specializes in debt collection to pursue Goetz who, he
said, ``appears to be living in voluntary squalor, still on the
West Side.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone, Goetz declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cabey's mother, Shirley, had known all along that there was
little chance of getting money from Goetz, Kuby said. ``It was very
important to her, all those years, that people know that her son
never did anything wrong to Bernard Goetz, that Bernard Goetz was
the criminal,'' he explained. ``That's what the verdict
established, and it gave her a tremendous sense of well being.''
</P>
<P>
   _ TINA KELLEY
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
