<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LUBBERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM LUBBERS, 75, LAWYER FOR U.S. LABOR RELATIONS BOARD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Lubbers, the National Labor Relations Board's
general counsel from 1979 to 1984, died on Aug. 26. He was 75 and
lived in Bethesda, Md.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was an abdominal aortic aneurysm he suffered at his
home, his son Jeffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Lubbers was a lawyer with the labor board from 1952 until he
retired in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   As general counsel, he was involved in the resolution of one of
the longest union disputes in American history. The dispute began
after the Darlington Manufacturing Co. closed its mill in
Darlington, S.C., in 1956, after the workers voted to be
represented by the Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
   The plant was owned by Deering-Milliken Inc. of New York. The
union contended that the closing was illegal and that it was at
least partly intended to discourage unionization of other textile
plants.
</P>
<P>
   After much litigation, the U.S. Supreme Court upheld charges of
unfair labor practice. The union had sought $20 million in back pay
for the former Darlington workers. Lubbers proposed $5 million, and
he announced in 1980 that each side had agreed that the sum, to be
paid by Milliken &AMP; Co., formerly Deering-Milliken, would go to the
500 surviving former employees or the heirs of those who had died.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Cedar Grove, Wis., Lubbers was an infantryman in
World War II. He received both his bachelor's and law degrees from
the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his son Jeffrey, of Takoma Park, Md., Lubbers is
survived by his wife, Val; another son, Kevin, of Bethesda; two
daughters, K. Darcy Lubbers of Santa Monica, Calif., and Sherry
Lubbers of Manhattan; four brothers; and three sisters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1746EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
