<HEADER>
A7648 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-MEETING-NYT     09-09 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS STRUGGLE TO GET OUT OF A LOSING STATE OF MIND 
</HEADLINE>
  By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The door to the Mets clubhouse stood locked as the
minutes ticked by after Friday night's loss to the Philadelphia
Phillies. But when the door finally opened, the Mets admitted that,
despite their struggles, it was not a tirade by Manager Bobby
Valentine that kept the door closed, but a simple and upbeat
message, advising his players to stop thinking and start playing.
</P>
<P>
   The September slump is familiar to Valentine, who has seen it in
each of the last two seasons. And the way out is not panic or
pressing, but simply playing. The message, delivered with far less
vitriol than Mike Hampton's exit from the mound in Friday's 2-0
loss, was easy to hear for the team, but still hard to live by.
Even moments after Valentine expressed his plea, players were still
wondering how they would escape the offensive doldrums that have
grounded a team that had slipped into first place just over a week
ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some frustrated guys in here, I mean nobody more
than myself,'' Mike Piazza said. ``It's a frustrating game when you
get away from things that have been working for you. For a lack of
better term, you just start pressing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have gone into the abyss together. Batting .220 without
a home run or a run batted in in the team's seven games in
September, Edgardo Alfonzo is the hottest of the regulars. Piazza
is batting .200 over the span with one home run and one RBI. Robin
Ventura, mired in a season-long struggle, is 2 for 25 (.080).
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby told us to just think that we are a pretty good team,''
Alfonzo said. ``We didn't win with one guy. We've got nine guys
playing, 25 guys in the room, and everybody is trying to be the
hero. Things are not working that way. We're trying to do too
much.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mets self-destructed on Friday night, unable to get a timely
hit and stranding 11 runners in being shut out by 5 pitchers,
snapping the Phillies out of their eight-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Hampton as a stopper did little when he had one
hit in three times at bat, making him as dangerous a hitter as any
in the lineup. With each loss, the Mets hear more talk of the
September struggles of the past two years. The four-and-a-half game
lead on Arizona in the wild-card race suddenly does not seem so
secure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the kind of learning experience you want to go
through,'' Piazza said of the team's experience the past two
seasons. ``I just think we're learning too much. That's the bottom
line. We're not feeling sorry for ourselves. We're not making
excuses. We just have to go back to playing good baseball.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hampton showed his frustration on Friday with his outburst,
hurling his glove into the dugout as he stalked off the field,
slamming around the dugout as he dislodged a pair of water coolers
with a blow from his right forearm. But his frustration was only
the most visible among the players. If Valentine is maintaining a
cool demeanor, he might be the only one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike showed frustration when he left the field, as did I when
I popped up, as did other people,'' Todd Zeile said. ``Slamming
bats or helmets or whatever, that doesn't necessarily help anything
except alleviate some of the frustration. This team is not taking
this lying down by any means. This is a frustrating endeavor.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1748EDT &QL; 
