A7649 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BOATING-WEBSITES-NYT     09-09 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOATING-WEBSITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR INFORMATION, SAILORS NOW HAVE THE OPTION OF DOCKING ON THE WEB
</HEADLINE>
 By HERB McCORMICK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the last Around Alone _ the solo round-the-world boat race _
the winning skipper, Italy's Giovanni Soldini, showed his prowess
not only at the helm but also on his laptop computer. Soldini spent
hours poring over his favorite Internet weather Web sites, and his
ability to predict favorable systems and trends proved to be a
significant advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is not only altering the way offshore racers like
Soldini play the game; it is also changing the way recreational
boaters pursue their pastime. With dozens of boating Web sites, it
is now possible to enjoy a satisfying maritime experience without
going anywhere near the water.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the sport's most ambitious entities _ Quokka.com,
SailNet.com and Boats.com _ have spent millions of dollars building
and staffing their respective sites. All three are seeking to
attract a wide-ranging audience, and business-sustaining revenue,
in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   Quokka Sports, based in San Francisco, burst onto the sailing
scene in 1997 with innovative Internet coverage of the Whitbread
Round-the-World Race, which attracted nearly two million individual
visitors. Quokka has since gone on to cover other sports, as well
as yachting events like the America's Cup and the BT Global
Challenge (btchallenge.com), a race made up of amateur sailors who
pay to compete. Leg 1 of the BT race, bound for Boston, begins on
Sunday from Southampton, England.
</P>
<P>
   Quokka has demonstrated that, given the right content, Internet
users will log on to boating-related Web sites in significant
numbers. Essentially, the business plan behind SailNet.com and
Boats.com is to attract viewers with technical advice and
information, boat and product reviews, and features, and then to
entice them to buy equipment or services like boat financing or
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies differ somewhat in how they strive to fulfill
those orders. For customers of SailNet, which is based in Mount
Pleasant, S.C., the site is a full-service chandlery of marine
goods that includes its own in-house sail loft and rigging shop.
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce is also central to the plans of Boats.com, which has
a 70-employee staff and is also centered in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The marine industry is ready to benefit from an online
marketplace,'' said Rolando Esteverena, the company's chief
executive officer and Silicon Valley veteran.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike SailNet, however, Boats.com _ which has a home page that
includes separate links for sailing, powerboating and fishing _
does not own a separate retail division. Instead, Boats.com views
itself as an online hub where yacht brokers, boat dealers, marinas,
sailmakers and other marine service businesses can participate in
an open marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Boats.com has received exclusive, and somewhat
controversial, endorsements from the National Marine Manufacturers
Association and the Marine Retailers Association of America.
Critics of the arrangement say that trade associations should
remain neutral, an allegation that Esteverena has dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Comparing it with SailNet, Feuerstein wrote: ``Boats.com will
work on a referral model, earning small finder's fees for helping
consumers locate boats for sale and referral fees from third-party
marine product retailers. While Boats.com's margins are lower, it
will not incur the expense of owning and operating its own retail
operations.''
</P>
<P>
   Sailors like Giovanni Soldini do not trouble themselves with
these Web vagaries; the Internet thus far has simply been a place
to find worthwhile information. Companies like SailNet and
Boats.com are betting the house that, next time he needs a pair of
sailing shoes or anything else nautical, he will also come clicking
their way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
