<HEADER>
A7658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT     09-09 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BOSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROSIUS AND PETTITTE POKE HOLE IN THE AURA OF MARTINEZ
</HEADLINE>
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Scott Brosius was one of the first Yankees to come out
for pregame stretching &UR;  &LR; on Saturday. The sun was out, Brosius' good
friend Andy Pettitte was getting ready to pitch against the Boston
superstar Pedro Martinez, and Brosius had an edgy smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``So the Red Sox think that they're going to win because Pedro
is pitching,'' Brosius said, without any prompting. ``OK. We'll
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Bearing his quiet determination, Brosius came to bat in the
seventh inning, after Martinez had shut out the Yankees for six and
two-thirds innings, and blasted a three-run homer into the screen
above the left field wall _ accounting for their first runs in a
5-3 victory. Pettitte pitched 8 innings, allowing six hits, picked
up his 18th victory and became the first pitcher to defeat Martinez
twice in the same season since the Mets' Bobby Jones in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He had to wait out a fidgety ninth, however, as Mariano Rivera,
pitching for the third straight day, gave up two two-out runs
before retiring the side. This made Jose Conseco's two-run homer in
the top of the ninth the winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the American League East would seem to be a matter of
time now for the Yankees, with their lead over Boston at eight
games and their magic number for clinching down to 16.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez (16-5) has more victories than any major league pitcher
since the start of the 1996 season, with 88 _ just one more than
Pettitte, who ranks second in that category. But Brosius'
conviction was probably based on the Yankees' success against
Martinez as much as Pettitte's recent outings. The Yankees have won
the last three games started by the Boston ace, the pattern in the
games generally the same: They force Martinez to throw a lot of
pitches early in the game, driving up his pitch count and tiring
him, and if they cannot beat Martinez, at least they could hope to
get him out of the game in the middle innings and then pound away
on the Red Sox' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte follows Roger Clemens in the rotation and Orlando
Hernandez follows Pettitte, and if the playoffs were to begin this
week in Yankee Stadium, that trio probably would start in that
order. They are all pitching exceptionally, they are all strong,
and it may not be a coincidence that all three have spent some
weeks on the disabled list this season, because of injuries that
have limited their innings.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen of the 19 pitches Pettitte threw in the first inning
were fastballs, and he generally stifled the Red Sox' offense,
matching zeros with Martinez. If the Yankees are going to beat
Martinez, Joe Torre said before Saturday's game, they would have to
do so by getting a strong pitching performance and eking out a
couple of runs.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1807EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0151 </DOCNO>
