<HEADER>
A7659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-DOGS-NY     09-09 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-DOGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WHEN DOGS ARE MORE IMPORTANT THAN PEOPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  By   BRENT STAPLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  I moved to Brooklyn 15 years ago and have since spent several
mornings each week walking, running or just greeting the day in
Prospect Park. In recent years, these tranquil mornings have been
too often disrupted by snarling dogs who are permitted off their
leashes in the early morning during what the park system refers to
as ``courtesy hours.'' In the last year alone, I have been cornered
four times by ill-behaved dogs _ two of them pit bulls _ who were
clearly unfit to run loose in a public park.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The owners of such dogs rarely apologize and sometimes behave as
belligerently as their animals. The owner of a big, menacing boxer
promised to kill me when I told him I would mace the dog if it
charged me again. A few weeks later, the owner of a frothing German
shepherd declined to leash his dog _ essentially using it to corner
me, while he advised me to stay home during ``courtesy hours'' and
lectured me on the dog's right to be free.
</P>
<P>
   Dog groups in Brooklyn and elsewhere are fighting to head off
new dog regulations and to preserve the privileges they now enjoy
in the public parks. But those privileges will remain at risk
unless the owners can learn to balance the needs of their animals
with the needs of the human beings with whom they share New York
City's public spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Animal welfare officials estimate that there are a million dogs
in the city _ or roughly one canine for every eight human beings.
The number of dogs will continue to grow, thanks to new federal
regulations that allow the 430,000 people who live in New York City
public housing to own dogs. In 1998, the chairman of the New York
City Housing Authority tried to block the measure, arguing that
public housing's dog problem was already out of control, even with
rules that limited dog ownership to the elderly and the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 years, the number of dog bites reported to the
City Health Department has ranged from 6,000 to nearly 11,000 a
year. The number of biting dogs taken into custody by animal care
officials grew by nearly a third between 1996 and 1999, as more and
more New Yorkers who were ill prepared to train and handle such
dogs acquired them anyway. Testifying before the City Council last
year, the city's health commissioner, Dr. Neal Cohen, concluded
that New York had ``failed to adequately protect the public from
biting dogs.'' Cohen supported a Giuliani administration bill that
would have required liability insurance for pit bulls _ which are
responsible for about a third of all bites in the city _ and made
it easier for the city to confiscate vicious and biting dogs
generally. Dog groups have blocked the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The practice of allowing dogs to run free in city parks during
the early morning and late evening evolved informally during the
1970s and 80s, when the parks were suffering from neglect and dog
owners felt safer than other people about entering the overgrown,
crime-ridden spaces. The ``courtesy hours'' continued after the
parks were cleaned up and patrons returned. But the last few years
have seen considerable friction between dog owners and park
visitors who want to picnic, sunbathe or exercise without being set
upon by wayward animals.
</P>
<P>
   With too few park officers to cover all the boroughs, city park
authorities rely on loosely organized groups of dog owners who use
peer pressure to bring owners into line. Conscientious dog owners
routinely chase down others who break park rules and fail to clean
up after their dogs. But, fearing that poorly behaved dogs will be
euthanized, dog owners sometimes suppress news of even serious
maulings that should be reported to the police.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1999, a Brooklyn woman named Sarah Lowe was badly
bitten by a dog that was part pit bull and roaming off its leash in
Prospect Park. The dog clamped down so fiercely that it fractured
Lowe's wrist. After six months of physical therapy, Lowe may yet
require surgery to correct the damage.
</P>
<P>
   A dog that breaks the bones of an adult could kill a small
child. But instead of filing a police complaint right away, Lowe
says she negotiated with the dog's owner, who agreed to muzzle the
dog. Lowe waited two months before she reported the attack to the
police _ and said she did so only after finding that the dog had
bitten someone else and was still roaming the park unmuzzled.
</P>
<P>
   The dog that bit Lowe is listed in the police report as a pit
bull mix named Ozzie. But as recently as two weeks ago, I
encountered this dog bounding through the park playing fetch, as
wary walkers moved aside. A man walking his own dog warned: ``Keep
out of his way. That is one dangerous animal.''
</P>
<P>
   The police and the health department hold the ultimate
responsibility for controlling dogs proved to be vicious. But if
owners wish to keep their privileges in the parks, they will need
to show as much concern for public comfort and safety as for the
rights of their animals.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 1815EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CONDO-EVICT0910-COX     09-09 1750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONDO-EVICT0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Condo dispute ends in settlement
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ It took more than two years and nearly a million
dollars, but a local condominium finally got rid of the resident
deemed too disruptive for condo life _ a boy with muscular
dystrophy, a motorized wheelchair and a disregard for the hot-tub
rule.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, two weeks before his spinal fusion surgery, Dorian
Kallen, now 14, and his family moved out of Oceancrest Condominium
Apartments and into a spacious single-family home.
</P>
<P>
   The $245,000 home was purchased with part of the $650,000 the
condominium paid the boy's family to end what had become one of the
more notorious condo disputes in Palm Beach County history.
</P>
<P>
   It attracted the intervention of Florida's attorney general, the
U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development, the Florida
Commission on Human Relations and the Palm Beach County State
Attorney's Office to halt the eviction of the boy and his family
from the condo two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the boy's single mother, Marie-Clotilde ``Cloe''
Couturier Kallen, had been renting a unit at Oceancrest, where she
lived with her handicapped son, then 12, and her daughter,
Kassandre, then 14.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years the Kallens had been renters at Oceancrest,
some of the older residents had come to resent the handicapped boy
and his sister, who would invite other kids to play with them at
the condo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think those children have any supervision,''
board member Gloria Rodkin would later testify in a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The condo security staff began compiling complaints against the
boy: He was too loud in the communal TV room. He was heard using
the F-word. He and his friends tried building a fort in the condo
bushes. He would use his motorized wheelchair to tow boys on
skateboards in the condo lot. He was seen punching all the buttons
on the elevator.
</P>
<P>
   He was even written up for being seen on another floor of the
condo. In one complaint, a resident of the sixth floor said he
instructed the boy and his friends: ``They had no business being on
any floors other than where they live, unless they have a specific
reason, in this case, they had none.''
</P>
<P>
   The handicapped boy said he just went to the sixth floor to
enjoy the panoramic view.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play there. I just go there . . . to look,'' he
testified. ``The neighborhood. The houses and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But what really drew attention were the complaints about the boy
that seemed directly related to his disability.
</P>
<P>
   NUMEROUS COMPLAINTS
</P>
<P>
   He was repeatedly cited for using the condo's hot tub, in
violation of the rule that made it off-limits to kids under 14.
</P>
<P>
   His mother had appealed to the condo board, saying the boy's
doctors said the warm water was therapeutic for his illness. But
the board took a no-exceptions line, or as one board member put it:
``We're not a health facility, we're a private home.''
</P>
<P>
   Others told the boy to ride the service elevator, he said, so he
wouldn't scratch the passenger elevator with his chair. Another
photographed the marks the boy's chair made on a lobby bathroom
door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know if your wheelchair came into contact with the door
while you were trying to open it?'' the condo's lawyer asked the
boy in a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I open doors,'' the boy explained.
</P>
<P>
   He was cited for riding his wheelchair over the grass and
suspected of intentionally tracking dog feces into the lobby from
his wheels. The security guards accused him of taunting them, by
ringing the lobby buzzer for admittance into the building, but then
leaving before they could get up from their desk to open the door
for him.
</P>
<P>
   The boy said he wasn't taunting, he just got tired of waiting
for the security guards who let the family know they were there for
surveillance, not to help the boy get in and out of the building _
a task he couldn't perform on his own due to the door configuration
and the weakness in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The boy testified that he was left stranded outside the building
about 20 times while the security guards failed to answer his
rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of those times, did the guard see you there?'' the
condo's lawyer asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you sure?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh-huh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How are you sure?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I rang the bell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Was the guard doing something, or anything, during those 20
times?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe sometimes reading the newspaper,'' the boy said.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of waiting for the guard, he'd maneuver his
wheelchair through the parking garage entrance, where he would be
written up for creating a dangerous situation with the residents
trying to park their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ATTEMPT TO BUY CONDO BLOCKED BY BOARD
</P>
<P>
   The situation came to a head when the boy's mother tried to go
from a renter to a buyer at Oceancrest. Under the rules, the board
would have to approve the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the board blocked it, citing the numerous complaints it
had compiled against her children. The board members, backed with
their secret file of complaints, thought they were on solid legal
ground.
</P>
<P>
   They had no idea what a mess, though, was about to begin.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation for the circus that would follow had nothing to
do with the boy or his disability.
</P>
<P>
   It had to do, some say, with the infamous lobby remodeling of
1997. A year before the attempted eviction of the handicapped boy,
the condo board passed an unpopular $456,000 special assessment for
remodeling. The assessment led to a recall petition of the condo
board, which nearly succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when the hard feelings started here,'' said former
resident Bill Burgess, the husband of a former board member.
``After that, there were always two cliques here.''
</P>
<P>
   When word got out that the board was trying to oust the
handicapped boy, his most ardent supporters turned out to be the
same people who had a year earlier tried to oust the board over the
remodeling.
</P>
<P>
   So the board members looked at the fight over the handicapped
boy not as a question of accommodation of the disabled but as a
political ploy by their enemies to stir the pot of discontent at
the condo.
</P>
<P>
   The board dug in, taking a hard line against the boy, seeing him
as a proxy for its enemies in the building. An anonymous mailing
was sent to residents that referred to the boy's mother as the
``stooge'' of the anti-board faction in the condo.
</P>
<P>
   But the way it played to the rest of the country was far
different. The story of the condo's fight to kick out the boy was a
black eye for the 161-unit condo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Condo board tells sick boy to leave,'' was the headline of the
story in USA Today, which showed photos of the family.
</P>
<P>
   They received words of support from around the country, none
more bizarre than a radio disc jockey in Kansas City who sent a
representative to Oceancrest to sneak into the condo pool area and
defecate in the hot tub while reporting his actions via cellular
phone to the radio show's audience.
</P>
<P>
   Two condo residents discovered the results of the prankster's
deed as well as a bumper sticker for the radio station on the
bottom of the hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   NEIGHBOR AGAINST NEIGHBOR
</P>
<P>
   The ugliest fighting, though, was neighbor-to-neighbor at
Oceancrest. Rita Malm, the wife of a former board president and the
reputed ringleader of the anti-board faction, got notes in her
mailbox calling her the Wicked Witch of Oceancrest.
</P>
<P>
   She complained to Jupiter police, who gave her plastic gloves so
she could preserve fingerprint evidence on the mail she received.
</P>
<P>
   A board member wrote a letter, threatening legal action to
anyone spreading the rumor that he has used the condo hot tub as a
place for having sex.
</P>
<P>
   Others warned the board to end their battle against the
handicapped boy and his family before it ended up in an expensive
legal battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this mess ends up in the courts, I want you to know I will
personally bring the board into the court and expose what you have
done to me personally and other residents with blatant lies to our
character,'' resident Sunny Newman wrote three board members.
</P>
<P>
   It did end up in court. Efforts to mediate a quick settlement
failed. The boy's mother completed the purchase of the condo at
Oceancrest, despite the board's wishes, and in December 1998, she
hired a lawyer, John Hart, who sued the condo in federal court for
discrimination by not allowing the boy in the hot tub or making the
front entrance accessible to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, it was a good healthy fight,'' the mother
said last week. ``But toward the end, it started deteriorating.
Some people had so much animosity toward us.''
</P>
<P>
   She said someone let the air out of her tires more than once.
Her license plate registration sticker was stolen. And her son
still got written up for using the hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year and half ago, he had no curvature of his spine, by this
summer it was 56 degrees,'' she said. ``I know he needed the
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   SETTLEMENT REACHED
</P>
<P>
   So this spring, she agreed to a mediated settlement, taking the
money offered _ less than she thought she could get at trial but
enough to put her son in a house of his own with his own pool and a
hot tub she plans to add.
</P>
<P>
   The spinal surgery has left her son nearly immobile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I won the lottery,'' she said. ``He needs to be
moved 12 to 15 times every night. I have to get up in the middle of
the night to move him. To pay somebody to do that would be about
$100 a night _ that's a lot of money to get to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   But Couturier Kallen, who works a full-time job as a massage
therapist, isn't complaining. Especially about her new
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live on a cul-de-sac, and there are other teenagers on the
block,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile at Oceancrest, the condo association now owns the
family's old condo. But residents haven't been told the terms of
the settlement or how it will be paid for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board hasn't given us anything,'' resident Betty Wienke
said.
</P>
<P>
   Board president Jim Walden didn't respond to requests for an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many of the combatants at Oceancrest have either
stepped down or moved away. Rita Malm and her husband, who refer to
their old home as ``Battlecrest,'' moved to another condo in
Jupiter last November.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far the people here seem very pleasant,'' she said. ``But
that's the way it always starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
