<HEADLINE>
BOSTON COLLEGE TROUNCES ARMY, MATCHING BLACK KNIGHTS' WORST
DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ Maybe Army should have reverted to the
wishbone against Boston College Saturday in the Black Knights' loss
at Michie Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Unveiling in its home opener a new coach, Todd Berry, and the
one-back, three-wideout passing offense that replaced the
run-oriented wishbone, which Army had used for 16 years, the Black
Knights came out throwing from the start.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chad Jenkins completed five of his first six passes,
and with Jenkins accounting for 47 yards on two passes, the Black
Knights drove 70 yards for the game's first touchdown on their
second possession. A reserve running back, Josh Holden, scored on a
slithering run along the right side.
</P>
<P>
   But that lead was short-lived as a Boston College backup
tailback, William Green, returned the ensuing kickoff 84 yards to
the Army 8-yard line. Then, Cedric Washington bolted up the middle
to score, and the Eagles were on their way to a 55-17 rout of the
Black Knights before a crowd of 37,544.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-point loss matched the worst home defeat ever for Army
(0-2), which was playing with only four days off after losing its
opener Monday at Cincinnati, 23-17. The Cadets were beaten, 45-7,
by Pittsburgh in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game was close throughout the first half. Had it not
been for a pass interception at Army's 32 late in the first quarter
and an ill-advised onside kickoff, the Black Knights could have
kept it closer. But the interception led to the Eagles surging
ahead 14-7. And the onside kick _ following a 27-yard field goal by
Brendan Mullen that had trimmed the deficit to 14-10 _ set the
stage for a 60-yard Eagles' drive. Mike Sutphin hit his second
field goal, from 24 yards out, to provide a 17-10 lead as time
expired in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Those 3 points turned out to be the first of 17 scored by the
visitors over a span of 37 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Following the second-half kickoff, Boston College quarterback
Tim Hasselbeck connected with wide receiver Dedrick Dewalt on the
first play for a 75-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 20 seconds later, Curtis Bolden, a B.C. linebacker, picked
off a Jenkins pass on Army's first play of the half and raced down
the left sideline untouched for a 22-yard touchdown. The Eagles
scored four unanswered touchdowns in the third period to take a
48-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles added a final touchdown late in the fourth period, as
did Army. The Black Knights' second touchdown came with two seconds
left when Curtis Zervik, the third-string quarterback, passed 12
yards to Clinton Woody, a freshman wide receiver, to cap a 63-yard
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played two different halves,'' Berry said. ``We should have
reacted better in the second half and we've got to make things
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck, a senior, connected on 14 of 21 passes for 256 yards
and 3 touchdowns, 2 of them by Dewalt. Hasselbeck's backup, Brian
St. Pierre, was no less effective, hitting on 6 of 8 passes for 89
yards. That added up to 335 passing yards to 193 yards by Army. The
B.C. quarterbacks did not thrown an interception; Jenkins was
intercepted twice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The loss was crushing to Army in more ways than the final score.
The Black Knights had played fairly well in losing to Cincinnati,
23-17, last Saturday in a game that was not decided until the
Bearcats scored a touchdown with 6 minutes and 11 seconds remaining
in the game. But Saturday, Army made too many mistakes on defense,
particularly in failing to put pressure on Hasselbeck and enabling
his receivers to get wide open repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   And the Eagles, now 1-1, who amassed 252 yards rushing, never
fumbled either in a turnover-free performance while the Black
Knights fumbled once and ran for only 161 yards, more than 100
yards less than they averaged last season, the last for the
wishbone and its last coach, Bob Sutton, now a linebackers' coach
for the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   B.C.'s passing was well abetted by the running of Washington, a
first-team Big East selection last year, who gained only 31 yards
against West Virginia last Saturday but who carried 15 times for
100 yards and one touchdown this Saturday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
