<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GRAND-PRIX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COULTHARD IS PATIENT AS HE CONTENDS FOR TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 By BRAD SPURGEON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONZA, Italy _ A recent interview with David Coulthard,
Scotland's greatest hope for another Formula One driver's title,
was interrupted by a visit to the McLaren motor home of Jackie
Stewart, Scotland's last world champion.
</P>
<P>
   In a thicker Scottish brogue than he used before, Coulthard
said, ``Thaink ye for your kaind wairds,'' to Stewart, who that
week had predicted to the British news media that Coulthard was the
most likely driver to win the title this year.
</P>
<P>
   But that was just before the Belgian Grand Prix two weeks ago,
which Mika Hakkinen, Coulthard's teammate, won in one of his finest
races. Coulthard finished fourth.
</P>
<P>
   At the Italian Grand Prix here on Sunday, Hakkinen and Michael
Schumacher, who are first and second in the point standing, will be
the center of attention. Schumacher, in a Ferrari, set the fastest
lap in 1 minute, 23.770 seconds around the 3.59 mile circuit in
Saturday's qualifying session. Rubens Barrichello, Schumacher's
teammate was second fastest, and Hakkinen was third fastest.
Coulthard set only the fifth best time, behind Jacques Villeneuve.
</P>
<P>
   But with four races left, Coulthard is only 13 points behind and
with 10 points awarded each victory, the Scot is still a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you are a gambling man,'' Stewart said, ``you would say
that there's a better chance for David to win than for Mika.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Stewart sees it, Hakkinen's effort to win a third title
in a row, which no one but Juan Manuel Fangio has ever done _ and
that in the 1950s _ puts the odds in Coulthard's favor. And he
thinks Schumacher's Ferrari is not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Coulthard, for his part, is philosophical. Of course he wants to
win. But if he doesn't, at 29, he is still confident about his
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the development of my career, my driving, and
feel that my best is still to come,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to disagree with him about his career: with
three victories this season, it is already his best year.
</P>
<P>
   Coulthard started in Formula One at the Williams team in 1994,
replacing Ayrton Senna after the Brazilian died in a crash in the
San Marino Grand Prix at Imola.
</P>
<P>
   Coulthard won his first race the following year at the
Portuguese Grand Prix. But in 1996 he joined McLaren, leaving the
top team for one that had been in the doldrums since Senna left it
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``In hindsight, it would have been better to have stayed with
Williams,'' Coulthard said. ``I may have won a title had I stayed.
But I took a decision very early on to go with McLaren on the basis
that it may be a setback in the short term, but in the long term it
would be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Coulthard earned the team's first victory since 1993, at the
season-opening Australian Grand Prix in 1997, and then at the
Italian Grand Prix at Monza. But while he was getting into a
groove, Hakkinen, who had been racing since 1991 with no victories,
was struggling.
</P>
<P>
   So in the last race of 1997, at the European Grand Prix at
Jerez, the team asked Coulthard to let Hakkinen pass him to win the
race, and he did. In the first race of the following season, the
Australian Grand Prix, Coulthard was again asked to pull aside to
let Hakkinen win. It had to do with a pre-race team agreement
stating that the driver who first passed the first corner was
allowed to win the race.
</P>
<P>
   But the victory was all Hakkinen needed for a mentally
liberating start to what would become his first of two consecutive
titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if he'll ever give those back?'' Coulthard said
sharply in Spa two weeks ago. ``It would be nice if I had 11 wins
instead of nine.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he was not bitter about Hakkinen's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was at the right point in his career in terms of experience
and knowledge and support of the team to have himself a
psychological position to give himself an edge,'' he said. ``I've
been working to get myself in that same position.''
</P>
</TEXT>
