<SLUG> BC-BBA-FLORIE-INJURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON RED SOX'S BRYCE FLORIE UNDERGOES SURGERY FOR EYE INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Red Sox pitcher Bryce Florie, hit in the face by a line
drive in the ninth inning of Friday's game with the Yankees,
underwent surgery Saturday morning and, according to the team,
there is extensive damage to his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox released a statement from Bill Morgan, their team
doctor, who said that Florie's right eyeball was severely injured.
``There is some retinal damage that will be further assessed over
the next 24 to 72 hours to determine whether or not surgery is
required to repair the retina,'' he said. ``He has some bleeding
behind the retina, but the retina is not detached. Prognosis for
reasonable vision is guarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan also reported that Florie has three fractures around his
right eye socket that will require surgery, a nasal fracture, a
fracture of the medial wall and a fracture of the floor of the
socket.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Thompson, who hit the line drive, was shaken Saturday
morning, calling Manager Jimy Williams to check on Florie's
condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
