<HEADER>
A7665 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-NFLREPORT-WILLIAM     09-09 2024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFENSE GETS INK, BUT DEFENSE WINS CHAMPIONSHIPS
</HEADLINE>
 REPORT-WILLIAMS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defense still wins championships.
</P>
<P>
   In this new-age NFL, offense draws the headlines and offensive
players collect the awards. But it still comes down to how well a
team can defend.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't believe the old cliche still holds, consider how
the St. Louis Rams won the title last season.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Warner was the league MVP after throwing 41 touchdown
passes. Marshall Faulk was the NFL Offensive Player of the Year
after setting an NFL record with 2,429 yards from scrimmage. And
the Rams averaged 32.9 points per game in going 13-3 in the regular
season.
</P>
<P>
   But at crunch time, it was the Rams' unheralded and
underappreciated defense that saved the day.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFC Championship Game, the Rams scored only 11 points.
But their defense held the Tampa Bay Buccaneers to 6.
</P>
<P>
   Super Bowl XXXIV ended with Rams linebacker Mike Jones tackling
Tennessee Titans receiver Kevin Dyson at the 1-yard line to give
St. Louis a 23-16 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Offense got the Rams to the playoffs. Defense won them the
Lombardi Trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have defense,'' Hall of Fame linebacker Sam Huff
said. ``Defense wins football games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you realize that there are only two things an offense can
do? They can run, and they can pass. That's all they can do.
Coaches make this game complicated, but it's not a complicated
game. So if you're a defense, all you have to do is two things:
Shut down the run and shut down the pass, and then they've got to
punt. (Vince) Lombardi said if you control the ball, you control
the clock and then you control the game. He was as simple and basic
as you can get. It's rock-and-sock football, and that's what it's
all about. The team that does that the best, he always said, will
win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the best defensive team in the NFL _ the
Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Tampa Bay was the most dominating defense since the
1985 Chicago Bears. It carried a Bucs offense that scored a
touchdown or less in seven games, including four in which the
offense failed to reach the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come in and beat us, you've got to beat our defense,'' said
Bucs defensive tackle Warren Sapp, the NFL's Defensive Player of
the Year in 1999. ``That's the strength of our ballclub. We're
going to come put hats on them and see if they want to play with us
for four quarters.`
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs replaced two key starters from last season, opting for
potential over age. Middle linebacker Hardy Nickerson, who made the
NFC Pro Bowl team the past four years, left as a free agent for the
Jacksonville Jaguars when the Bucs decided it was time for
third-year veteran Jamie Duncan to have his chance. Defensive
tackle Brad Culpepper, who has 23.5 sacks over the past three
seasons, was released two weeks ago after Tampa Bay named former
first-round choice Anthony McFarland the starter.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing has changed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bucs beat the New England Patriots, 21-16, last week,
allowing only 88 rushing yards on 21 carries and sacking
quarterback Drew Bledsoe six times and knocking him down another
13. The last 27 times Tampa Bay has led going into the fourth
quarter, it has protected that lead 25 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year is a different year,'' said Bucs coach Tony Dungy,
a disciple of former Pittsburgh Steelers head coach Chuck Noll.
``It would be easy to say we're just going to stay the status quo,
but we didn't win last year, so we felt like we had to get better.
You're always worried about chemistry, but we felt like this was
the best way to go, that this would make us a better defense.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing the Bucs defense lacks is a nickname. The
``New York Times/ tabbed them ``The Brick Wall'' last week. In a
poll last year, the ``St. Petersburg Times/ offered several ideas
including ``Red Tide,'' the ``Warren Commission,'' ``Skull and
Crush Bones'' and the ``Pewter People Eaters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really don't need a nickname until we win a championship,''
weak-side linebacker Derrick Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   With their defense, the Bucs could have both by season's end.
</P>
<P>
   cjwilliams &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   Q&AMP;A ... WITH MIKE VANDERJAGT
</P>
<P>
   Indianapolis Colts kicker Mike Vanderjagt can't miss.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderjagt has made every field-goal attempt since the
Cincinnati Bengals blocked a 37-yarder on Oct. 24, 1999. Vanderjagt
hit from 23 and 40 yards in the season opener against the Kansas
City Chiefs, giving him a streak of 28 consecutive, not counting
the playoffs when he went 3-for-3 against the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter where they put it down at this
point,'' Vanderjagt said. ``I'm fortunate enough to continue where
I left off last year, and I feel just as much in rhythm now as I
did then. I'm feeling real good right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderjagt keeps count, and he knows who he is chasing. Gary
Anderson holds the NFL record with the 40 consecutive he hit in
1997-98 with the San Francisco 49ers and the Minnesota Vikings.
Minnesota's Fuad Reveiz (31) and San Diego's John Carney (29) are
the only other players in NFL history who have longer streaks.
Chris Boniol also had a streak of 28 consecutive field goals with
the Cowboys and the Philadelphia Eagles in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-eight and counting,'' said Vanderjagt, a Canadian who
began his professional career in the CFL. ``I'd like to get up in
the 30s. Second place is 31, so I'd at least like to get to 32.
Forty is a stretch. But we'll play it one at a time and see how
long it takes me to miss.''
</P>
<P>
   What is one word that describes your kicking style? Unique.
</P>
<P>
   What one word would friends use to describe you? Original.
</P>
<P>
   If you were commissioner for a day, what would you change about
the NFL? I'd widen the uprights.
</P>
<P>
   If you weren't playing football, what would you be doing? I'd be
running the point for the Raptors.
</P>
<P>
   Do you have any superstitions? Oh, I have a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   What are they? As soon as I get to the stadium every Sunday, I
walk up one hash, touch the uprights, walk down the other hash,
touch the other uprights and go inside. There are a lot more, but
that's the biggest one.
</P>
<P>
   What is the last book you read? Oh, good Lord. ``Catcher in the
Rye/ in high school, I think.
</P>
<P>
   What is your all-time favorite movie? ``Shawshank Redemption.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you see ``The Replacements''? I haven't seen it yet, but
I've seen the HBO previews for it. They've made the kicker look
wacky as all get out, which I guess is the stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   If you were on ``Survivor'', what would your luxury item be? A
portable TV. I can't live without TV.
</P>
<P>
   If you could invite two people, dead or alive, to dinner, who
would they be? Michael Jordan and Joe Montana.
</P>
<P>
   What's the first thing you notice in a woman? Whether she has
cankles or not. Cankles are where your calves slide right down into
your ankles.
</P>
<P>
   What's the first thing you notice in a football player? If his
shoes match.
</P>
<P>
   Would you spend $50 to watch an NFL game? Yes ... now that I can
afford it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore or Bush? I'm Canadian, so neither. Gore if I had a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' or ``Gilligan's Island''? ``Survivor''.
</P>
<P>
   Boxers or briefs? Boxers.
</P>
<P>
   QUICK HITS IN A RUSH
</P>
<P>
   Duce Staley had 201 of the Eagles' 306 rushing yards against the
Cowboys last weekend. With the game a blowout, he had only one
carry _ for 60 yards _ in the fourth quarter. He finished four
yards short of Steve Van Buren's team record and 74 behind Walter
Payton's NFL record.
</P>
<P>
   During a national conference call on Wednesday, Staley was asked
if he could have broken the NFL record if he had played the entire
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the record? I have no idea,'' Staley said.
</P>
<P>
   Told his hero, Payton, set the mark with 275 yards against the
Minnesota Vikings in 1977, Staley said: ``Oh, I don't know. I
probably would have passed out (before reaching 275).''
</P>
<P>
   The 109-degree, 26-carry day was no sweat for Staley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I only lost like 5 to 6 pounds, which was
surprising,'' Staley said. ``I thought maybe I lost a little more,
but I was able to get the water back in my system, and go get me a
massage (Tuesday) to try to bring my legs back around.''
ARCHAEOLOGICAL FIND
</P>
<P>
   The 3-4 defense has gone the way of the dinosaur in the NFL.
Only a handful of teams still use it. But the San Francisco 49ers,
whose base defense is a 4-3, experimented with three down linemen
during their 36-28 loss to the Atlanta Falcons last week.
</P>
<P>
   With 8:29 left in the second quarter, the 49ers moved veteran
linebackers Winfred Tubbs and Ken Norton inside and put pass
rushers Jeff Posey and top draft pick Julian Peterson at the
outside linebacker positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in it early and late, and we may or may not use it
again, in case (Carolina coach) George Seifert is watching,'' 49ers
coach Steve Mariucci said. ``We can't be so simple with our
defense. We want to disguise it. A new front, that really helps.''
QUARTERBACK CLASS
</P>
<P>
   The future of the NFL is in good hands. Five of the six
quarterbacks drafted in the first two rounds of the 1999 draft had
good opening days.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Cade McNown (102.7), Cleveland's Tim Couch (97.8),
Tampa Bay's Shaun King (86.6), Philadelphia's Donovan McNabb (81.0)
and Minnesota's Daunte Culpepper (65.5) combined for a 60.8
completion percentage, 937 yards, five touchdowns, three
interceptions and an 83.0 quarterback rating. They also rushed for
a combined 242 yards and five touchdowns on 34 carries. And only
McNown and Couch lost.
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati's Akili Smith, the No. 3 choice last year, makes his
debut Sunday. GETTING THEIR KICKS
</P>
<P>
   The first regular-season game at Paul Brown Stadium takes place
Sunday when the Bengals play host to the rival Cleveland Browns.
After the two exhibitions played there, kickers complained that the
Bermuda grass surface was uneven in places.
</P>
<P>
   They made only 3 of 8 field goals at Paul Brown Stadium in the
preseason.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the Lions' 21-13 victory against the Bengals on
Aug. 25, Detroit kicker Jason Hanson told Bengals kicker Neil
Rackers, ``Good luck kicking on this field.''
</P>
<P>
   TAKING STOCK (UP ARROW)
</P>
<P>
   Walter Payton. His NFL single-game record of 275 rushing yards
stands ... thanks only to the Philadelphia Eagles' defense, which
was so good that Duce Staley had but one carry in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Snyder's wallet. The Washington Redskins owner keeps
writing fat checks. Last week he gave $90 million to running back
Stephen Davis. Do you have change to spare, brother?
</P>
<P>
   (SIDEWAYS ARROW)
</P>
<P>
   Cincinnati Bengals. Hey, they didn't lose last week. Of course,
they didn't play either.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Rams uniforms. This is what you call winning ugly.
</P>
<P>
   (DOWN ARROW)
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Texans' logo. And you expect Aggies in this state to
support you? You might as well have Bevo on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Lambeau Field. What home-field advantage? The Packers were 39-3
there from 1993-98, including a streak of 25 consecutive victories.
Since then, they are 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball pennant races. Who cares? Football, America's real
pastime, is here.
</P>
<P>
   WEEK 2 AT A GLANCE THE BEST Jacksonville at Baltimore
</P>
<P>
   Noon
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens never have beaten the Jaguars, but that's about to
change. Baltimore's defense is good, and quarterback Tony Banks is
adequate. This could be the start of something great for the
Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Ravens, 16-10
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Giants at Philadelphia
</P>
<P>
   Noon, CBS
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have won their past three games _ against New
England, St. Louis and the Cowboys _ by a combined score of 103-54.
Only an emotional letdown stands in the way of four in a row for
the playoff-bound Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Eagles, 24-14
</P>
<P>
   Washington at Detroit
</P>
<P>
   3:15 p.m., FOX
</P>
<P>
   The Lions defeated the Redskins, 33-17, last Dec. 5 for their
first victory against Washington since 1965. It's now nine months
and another loss to the Redskins later. The Lions will keep it
close, but they still will suffer their 17th loss to the Redskins
in their past 18 meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Redskins, 20-17
</P>
<P>
   Last week: 3-0 nn
