<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SYNCHRONIZED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYNCHRONIZED SWIMMER'S JOURNEY INTO FREEDOM GAINS TRUE
INDEPENDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 SWIMMER-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a way, Anna Kozlova's Olympic odyssey began in a gas station.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. A gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling to Italy with the Soviet Union's national junior
synchronized swimming team, the then-15-year-old Kozlova looked out
of the window of the bus and saw the twinkling, busy lights of Fiat
gas tanks being filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything seemed so bright,'' Kozlova remembered. ``Russia is
so gray. But this all just really stood out. It was fascinating to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   She is 27 now, and Kozlova is about to join the growing
fraternity of athletes who have marched behind the Olympic flag of
two countries.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlova tells a story about another trip, when she journeyed
with her Soviet teammates to the 1989 world championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember watching the American athletes,'' she said, ``and
it was so fascinating to me. I remember watching them, the way they
prepared, the way they acted toward each other. And our team was
nothing like that. I realized that it was something that was really
missing in the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, a year after she finished in fourth place of the
synchronized swimming's duet competition at the Barcelona Olympics,
Kozlova traveled to California to train _ and to leave her native
Russia behind.
</P>
<P>
   Naively, she thought that changing citizenships would be no more
difficult than changing library cards. But she soon discovered that
the wait at U.S. immigration can seem as long as the Russian bread
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, I was too young and not smart enough to know that,''
Kozlova said. ``But then, I still never doubted my decision. It was
hard, but I knew it would happen someday.''
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 7, 1999, after the mandatory five-year wait, Anna
Kozlova became a U.S. citizen. As she recited the oath of
allegiance, tears streamed from her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The long wait had cost her a chance to compete in the 1996
Atlanta Olympics. It was frustrating, because Kozlova already was
recognized as the best synchronized swimmer in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   She had left her parents behind in Russia. Arvin Kozlov is a
professor at the Academy of Physical Education, while Natalia
Kozlova teaches university math.
</P>
<P>
   But both knew that with the political uncertainties at home,
Anna was making the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom was very positive,'' Kozlova said. ``She was always
talking about western culture, always talking about England and
France, always encouraging me to learn the language because, I
think, instinctively she felt that would be a better future.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad hoped I would come back. He would say, `You know, I'm
finishing our country house.' But he came here in October to visit,
and the first thing that came out of his mouth when we were driving
was, `I'm so glad you live here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The 20-year-old daughter that left St. Petersburg is now a
27-year-old woman. She lives in Santa Clara, Calif., where she
competes for Olympic coach Chris Carver as a member of the Santa
Clara Aquamaids, the Yankees of synchronized swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to basically become an adult in a different country, and
that was hard,'' Kozlova said. ``I had to get a job and work and
train, and I didn't have any money.''
</P>
<P>
   Anna found two angels in Lee and Paula Dyroen, the parents of
former world champion Becky Dyroen-Lancer. The Dyroens welcomed
Kozlova into their home, fed her, taught her to drive _ ``treated
me like I was their daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, when she could compete in open or invitational
competitions, Kozlova began winning every competition within reach.
At the U.S. Olympic trials, she placed first in both the individual
and duet events. Kozlova will team with Tuesday Middaugh in the
duet competition in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Kozlova left her former Olympic partner, Olga Sedakova, back in
Russia, but Kozlova said that she has experienced only a few cold
shoulders from her former countrymen at competitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're angry at me for leaving, but I do think
there's some jealousy going on,'' she said. ``It's because I was
able to make it here, have a better life or something, and can
compete for such a huge, grand country like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've developed a lot, especially artistically. I've learned a
different style of swimming. American style is very different from
Russian. Team skills are a very big part of the sport here. In
Russia, it's more individual.''
</P>
<P>
   Her new country, Kozlova attests, is everything she dreamed it
would be. Now that she is a U.S. citizen, Kozlova said, she has
time to think a lot more about things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the freedom a lot,'' she said, ``and the people,
how they treat one another. And I guess I appreciate just you
getting up in the morning and knowing you're here, safe, free and
can be what you really want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   And what Anna Kozlova really wants is to stand on the podium at
the Sydney Olympics and hear the ``Star-Spangled Banner''.
</P>
<P>
   She'll cry, she promises. It's been a long journey. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
