<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-WARMING0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A global quandary
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Arctic sea ice is 40 percent thinner than it was 30
years ago. Winter temperatures there are an average of 11 degrees
warmer than they were 30 years ago. This summer there were
unusually large expanses of open water at the North Pole.
</P>
<P>
   From the Andes to the Alps, mountain glaciers are retreating. In
the Rockies, yellow-bellied marmots, the traditional harbingers of
spring, have been emerging from their burrows a month earlier than
they did 20 years ago. Across North America, from the fire-scorched
West to the drought-parched Southeast, it was a summer of
discontent. Even the seas _ to a depth of 1,000 feet _ have grown
warmer over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Hints of a warmer world, now reflected in more than 400 climate
indicators _ from trees and coral reefs to ice cores and permafrost
_ grow more compelling every year. But even as evidence of global
warming builds, there are nagging new questions about how best to
prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, NASA physicist James Hansen was one of the first
scientists to link increasing carbon dioxide levels and other
so-called greenhouse gases to the threat of global warming. After
rancorous debate, in 1997 major industrialized nations acknowledged
the threat and signed the Kyoto Protocol, which committed them to
reducing carbon dioxide emissions from the burning of coal, oil and
gas by 5 percent by 2012.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate, which is due to resume in mid-November when 180
nations meet in the Netherlands to finalize the agreement, goes on
_ and Hansen, director of NASA's Goddard Institute for Space
Studies, has just added fuel to the fire. In a strategy for
controlling global warming proposed last month in the Proceedings
of the National Academy of Sciences, he contends that industrial
nations, which have yet to implement the proposed reductions, may
be aiming at the wrong target.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen still believes that carbon dioxide is responsible for
about half of the global increase in temperatures. But he says more
efficient heat-trapping gases such as methane, chlorofluorocarbons,
soot and ozone have been the chief man-made contributors to warming
in the past 30 years. And he says they are easier to control than
carbon dioxide, which can be reduced only by cutting the
consumption of fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   Man-made sources of methane include intensive agriculture, coal
mining and leaky gas pipelines. Chlorofluorocarbons, now being
phased out, have been widely used in air conditioners,
refrigerators and industrial applications. Soot and ozone are
produced by factories, power plants and automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's analysis has been greeted by headlines charging that he
had ``backtracked'' and ``flip-flopped'' on global warming. With
each nation's greenhouse strategies still subject to debate, his
ideas have been quickly seized by critics as one more reason not to
ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Watson, chairman of the U.N. Intergovernmental Panel
on Climate Change, says any suggestion that carbon dioxide is not a
major force in global warming would be a ``horrible distortion'' of
Hansen's analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Without discounting the role of carbon dioxide, Hansen says
global warming could be tamed without draconian cutbacks in the
consumption of fossil fuels. He says that two decades of sound
environmental policies are already making a dent in the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is that the growth rate of non-carbon dioxide
greenhouse gases has declined in the past decade,'' he says.
Chlorofluorocarbons, he points out, are already being eliminated
under another international treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If sources of methane and tropospheric ozone were reduced in
the future, further changes in climate due to these gases in the
next 50 years could be near zero,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   If those reductions were coupled with controls on soot and
industrial emissions of carbon _ and moderate cuts in carbon
dioxide _ Hansen says the rate of warming could be significantly
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's analysis is not yet a major issue in the U.S. election,
but it could be. Democratic candidate Al Gore's reputation as an
environmentalist is closely tied to his support of the Kyoto
accord. Texas Gov. George W. Bush has said he thinks the treaty,
which would require increased energy conservation and the use of
alternative fuels, is unfair to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappiness is not limited to industrialized nations. Because
the only way to reduce carbon dioxide emissions is to reduce fossil
fuel consumption in automobiles, factories and power plants, many
developing nations fear the accord could limit their growth.
</P>
<P>
   As difficult as the current target for reducing carbon dioxide
is, climate models suggest that it won't be enough to reduce the
global warming.
</P>
<P>
   British climate experts, in fact, say that even if everyone
complied with the treaty, it would take ``30 Kyotos'' to reduce
warming to an acceptable level.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
