<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
WHILE hOUSTON LIVES, COWBOYS' FUTURE IS GONE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those sweaty people down in Houston always have wanted to be us.
Don't expect an admission on this, but their envy has been thicker
than their smog. It's mainly about football, but overall, it's the
jock kingdom in general. Houston never has been able to come close
to us.
</P>
<P>
   Except, at the moment, I'm picking up a faint radio signal from
outer space. There's a lot of static, but I recognize that voice.
It's our nationally famous football bidnessman. It's Jerry, and
he's giving an urgent may-day call:
</P>
<P>
   ``Houston, we've got a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Do we ever. Don't spread this around, but Houston just got the
jump on us in football. Houston, with an NFL team that doesn't even
begin play until 2002, is currently situated exactly where Mr.
Jones would kill to be.
</P>
<P>
   The owner of the newly-named Texans is Bob McNair, who could buy
and sell downtown Dallas if he so desired. But what Jerry would
like at the moment is a mere swap with Bob.
</P>
<P>
   It's a guarantee that right here, right now, Jones would trade
his 53 Cowboys, and throw in a Stephen to be named later, in
exchange for the Texans, a team with no players.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the second Jerry made that proposal, McNair's laugh would be
heard all the way to Port Arthur. McNair ain't no fool. He knows
he's got exactly what Jerry wants, and exactly what Jerry might
never have up here:
</P>
<P>
   A new space-age stadium and a team with nary a salary cap
headache.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, we do have a problem. And ``problem'' is a tad mild.
What Jerry currently has, and privately he knows it, is a potential
football disaster. The Cowboys' salary cap, which seemed at least
under control, became an instant mushroom cloud hanging over Valley
Ranch after what happened in the first week of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Joey Galloway was a cap-buster even in good health. His $13
million signing bonus last spring represented a large gamble for
Jones. Now the receiver expected to put the get-up-and-go back in
the offense is lost for the season with a wrecked knee. Even worse,
quarterback Troy Aikman's future is in doubt due to a mushy brain.
One more hit ...
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' cap has been structured around Aikman. If he
retires, the cap crumbles, 49ers-like. Second-guess the Jones
financial planning all you want, but Jerry played a very
high-stakes dice game here. Look closely _ are the bones now
showing a pair of snake-like eyes?
</P>
<P>
   Throw in an awful on-the-field performance against the Eagles,
and this week from hell has been unprecedented for Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit, I'm checking my hole card more than anytime
since I've been involved,'' Jones said at mid-week. ``You go back
to '89 and '90, there was a lot of things stacked against us, but
the driving force for me in those hard times was the future. No
matter how bleak it got, I could look to our future, and that
carried me through dark days like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones didn't continue on that theme, but his point was obvious.
The future is gone. Jerry now lives in a football world of
what's-happening-right-now. Like Sunday in the Arizona desert where
two desperate teams meet. Look beyond right now, and Jones is
staring into football darkness. There's no wiggle room with the cap
and there's not even a first-round draft pick next June.
</P>
<P>
   In times like these, Valley Ranch loyalists swear by and stand
by Jones. The bleaker the situation, they say, the stronger and
more supportive Jones becomes.
</P>
<P>
   In war, that's the sign of a good leader. In football, that's
the sign of a good owner. Outside of Valley Ranch walls, however,
there's been 12 years of local debate about whether Jones is
qualified to be called either.
</P>
<P>
   If it's a popularity contest among the masses, even a
``stuffed'' ballot box might not be enough to give Jones a 50-50
split. But if it's a crisis, please be advised that Jerry is the
first guy you'd probably want to call.
</P>
<P>
   Even a longtime critic can identify and respect the obvious.
Those who don't or won't, you can put them in the uninformed
category.
</P>
<P>
   But now what, Jerry?
</P>
<P>
   With past problems for the Cowboys, Jones has always attacked
with brain-power, elbow grease and money. He will rarely come up
short in any of those areas. But as of last Sunday at Texas
Stadium, Jones has also never come up against what he now faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been left shaken,'' he said of the season's first week.
``It causes you to pull out your checklist and begin
second-guessing yourself on everything you've done. But I do know
there's a difference in being knocked down, and also being able to
deal with it. Our next step is to deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless, of course, he could slip down to Houston and trick Bob
McNair into ...
</P>
<P>
   Forget it, and also deal with this:
</P>
<P>
   Houston is now better off in football. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
