<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GLF-CANADIAN-OPEN-NYT     09-09 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-CANADIAN-OPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS IS OUT TO CONQUER ANOTHER COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKVILLE, Ontario _ Tiger Woods made plenty of birdies Saturday,
but he had plenty of company on the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   With an eight-under-par 64, including six birdies and an eagle,
Woods moved into a first-place tie with Grant Waite heading into
Sunday's final round of the Bell Canadian Open. Woods and Waite
were both 15 under par (201) for the tournament, a stroke ahead of
Stephen Ames and J.L. Lewis, who were tied for third at 14 under.
</P>
<P>
   But there were 20 players at nine under or better, meaning the
final round could be a wide-open shootout, particularly if
conditions remain near perfect for scoring. With the greens
softened by Friday's rain, and with many of the par-5 holes playing
downwind, players fired at the pins Saturday as if taking target
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Ames shot a nine-under-par 63, nearly tying the course record of
62 at Glen Abbey Golf Club held by Leonard Thompson (1981), Andy
Bean (1983) and Greg Norman (1986). Thirty-five of the 73 players
broke 70, and if they were not making birdies, they were losing
ground, like Sergio Garcia, who shot 70 and was 10 under for the
tournament, or Davis Love III, who shot 71 playing with Woods,
leaving Love at eight under, seven strokes behind.
</P>
<P>
   So with 18 holes left, it was difficult not to like Woods'
chances. He has won 19 consecutive PGA Tour events when he has held
or shared the lead after three rounds. He has won five of his last
seven starts, including three major championships.
</P>
<P>
   With eight victories this year, and with many of Woods' pursuers
unaccustomed to being in contention, Woods has an excellent chance
to join Lee Trevino (1971) as the only players to win the United
States Open, the British Open and the Canadian Open in the same
year. It would be another milestone in an incredible year for
Woods. But after watching so many players shoot low scores today,
Woods was taking nothing for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those guys haven't won many tournaments, but you
never know,'' he said. ``If conditions remain the same, you're
going to have to make birdies to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Making birdies was not a problem for the leaders Saturday. Woods
started his day well, making birdies on two of the first three
holes, followed by another birdie at No. 8 that came in most
unusual fashion. Woods hit a wild tee shot into the gallery right
of the fairway. His ball bounced off the head of a spectator,
Michael Donley of Ontario, and ricocheted 40 feet left, back into
the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Woods walked over to check on Donley, who was not bleeding and
who told Woods that he was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt bad for him,'' Woods said. ``When I first got over
there, he didn't seem like he was all there. That's
understandable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods took advantage of the favorable head bounce, hitting
his approach shot 3 feet from the pin to set up an easy birdie.
After birdies on Nos.11 and 13, Woods reached his favorite stretch,
the final four holes. On Friday, Woods had a remarkable
birdie-eagle-birdie-eagle stretch from No. 15 through No.18.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was not as good, but it was not bad. Woods birdied the
par-3 No.15 again, making a 12-foot putt, then he made eagle again
at the par-5 No.16, reaching the green in two shots and sinking a
15-foot putt. But at the par-4 No.17, Woods settled for par, and he
also made par at the par-5 finishing hole. Woods' second shot at
No.18 went into a greenside bunker, then Woods made a mistake,
flubbing his next shot and leaving the ball in the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get too cute with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods then got up and down from the bunker for par, but he was
forced to share the lead with Waite, who started the day with a
one-stroke lead and who managed to shoot 68 Saturday despite
struggling on the front nine. A native of New Zealand, Waite has
not won on tour since 1993, and he has never played with Woods in
the final round of a tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time I played with Tiger was when he was 17 years
old, when I could beat him,'' Waite said. ``I can't hit the shots
he hits, but Bob May proved at the PGA that it doesn't matter who
you are, if you post a good score, he'll have to play well to beat
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ames said there were no hard feelings between himself
and Woods after an incident this spring. Ames was quoted as saying
that Woods thought he was bigger than the tour, but Ames said he
was misquoted, and he apologized to Woods months ago. ``I sent him
a letter and I apologized to him in Dallas,'' said Ames, who could
have tied the course record had he birdied No. 18. ``I don't think
we're going to have our boxing gloves on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Woods had again accomplished what he wanted: putting himself
in position to win. Almost any player would be thrilled to win
three national Opens in a career. But Woods has a chance to win
three in one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
