<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0910-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore leads in tight race, poll shows
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore was leading 49 percent to 41 percent over
Republican George W. Bush in a Newsweek poll of likely voters
released Saturday. Gore was supported by 85 percent of Democrats
and 18 percent of Republicans. Bush had the support of 75 percent
of Republicans and 8 percent of Democrats. Bush had a 43-34 edge
among independents. The poll of 595 likely voters taken late last
week has an error margin of 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, state polls show: the race was virtually deadlocked
in New Hampshire; Gore maintains a slim lead in Illinois, and Bush
still has a 23-point lead in Texas. The state-by-state battle for
electoral votes is crucial because the winning candidate has to win
enough states to collect 270 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding his son's recent slide in the polls, former President
George Bush said the younger Bush shouldn't worry. ``I'm the living
expert on polls,'' the elder Bush said Friday at a Republican
National Committee luncheon in Norfolk, Va. ``They can go up and
they can go down. I don't think anybody had more of a roller
coaster ride than I did.''
</P>
<P>
   THEY'RE BACK ON THE BUS
</P>
<P>
   Democrats Al Gore and running mate Joseph Lieberman will cross
Ohio in matching yellow school buses on Tuesday, pushing a
back-to-school campaign message amidst television appearances and
nearly $10 million in fund raising efforts in the swing state. On
Saturday, Cincinnati supporters painted signs for what the
Democrats are dubbing their ``On the Road to an A+ Education'' tour
that takes off from a suburban Dayton middle school and ends at a
Cincinnati community college.
</P>
<P>
   GORE IN THE MONEY RACE
</P>
<P>
   Gore might be talking about education by day, but he will be
raising money by night this week as he combs the Northeast corridor
for cash. Gore will appear on two television talk shows _ Oprah
Winfrey on Monday in Chicago and David Letterman on Thursday in New
York. He also has fund-raisers in Philadelphia on Tuesday, Boston
on Wednesday and New York on Thursday that should raise at least $6
million. The fund raising comes as Democrats lag in the money
chase. Gov. George W. Bush has raised nearly $100 million, and
spent a record $93 million through the end of July _ more than
double Gore's expenditures. According to the Center for Public
Integrity, from January 1999 through May 31, 2000, Gore raised
$47.7 million, spent $39 million and had $8.2 million in cash. Bush
raised $87.5 million, spent $79.5 million and had $7.1 million on
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also will try to raise $1.5 million in a marathon of
four fund raisers on Monday in Bush's home state of Texas,
including a stop in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL PLEA SENT ON BEHALF OF YELLOW DOGS
</P>
<P>
   Fearing trouble raising a $1 million goal during Sen. Joseph
Lieberman's visit to Austin on Monday, John Thornton, general
partner at Austin Ventures and one of the hosts of a
$2,500-per-plate lunch with Lieberman, has blanketed the local
technology community with an e-mail asking for support. ``If you
are, shall we say, unsympathetic with the cause, have a good
chuckle at how hard we Yellow Dogs are having to paddle to stay in
the race with George W.'s Texas juggernaut,'' Thornton wrote.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN ENTERS BUDGET FRAY
</P>
<P>
   Republican Sen. John McCain, recruited by GOP leaders for their
budget fight with the White House, asked Americans to vote out any
lawmaker who would undermine the nation's surplus with wasteful
spending. In the GOP's weekly radio address on Saturday, the former
presidential hopeful expressed suspicions that both parties might
share guilt by the time this year's budget is enacted. He had
especially harsh words for President Clinton. ``The president is a
charming fellow, and a heck of a salesman,'' McCain said. ``But I
wouldn't buy a used car from him if I were you.'' Such rhetoric is
what Republican leaders had in mind when they talked McCain into
taking a more visible role in the GOP budget campaign, exploiting
broad voter appeal McCain exhibited in the Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   NADER ADVOCATES LEGALIZING MARIJUANA
</P>
<P>
   Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader on Friday
advocated the legalization of marijuana as part of an overhaul of
the nation's ``self-defeating and antiquated drug laws.'' Nader
joined with New Mexico Gov. Gary Johnson, a Republican, in
criticizing the nation's ``war on drugs'' as a failed policy for
fighting drug use. Nader supports lifting criminal sanctions for
marijuana possession. For other drugs, such as heroin, he advocated
further treatment and prevention programs. Bush and Gore have
opposed legalizing marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
