<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-MEN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS AWAITS ANOTHER `YOUNG GUN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ Ten years ago, a wide-eyed, 19-year-old
youngster beat some of the best veteran players of the day to win
the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Pete Sampras made sure history wouldn't repeat itself.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, who won the first of his record 13 Grand Slam
tournaments in 1990, made sure 19-year-old Lleyton Hewitt wouldn't
win his first at this year's Open with a 7-6 (7), 6-4, 7-6 (5)
victory in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras advanced to the final against another one of the tour's
young guns, Marat Safin, who defeated veteran Todd Martin, 6-3, 7-6
(4), 7-6 (1). The 20-year-old Russian advanced to the final of a
Grand Slam event for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to be in the final, but something is missing,'' he
said. ``I want to win here.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Hewitt, but he faced the same difficulty Safin will
experience Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The two youngsters are considered the future of the game, but
Sampras remains the best in the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-nine is still pretty young,'' Sampras said. ``Tennis
players historically are done at 29, 30, but I feel like I've got
the game that I can play for as long as I want because of my serve.
You can still do well in majors. It can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras not only still has considerable skills, but he also has
a wealth of experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last 10 years I've been through a lot of wars out
there, a lot of battles, I've won a lot of big matches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The experience was the difference against Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   The young Australian played Sampras to a virtual statistical
standstill, winning 116 points to his opponent's 126. But the 10
points that were the difference were the big points, and that is
where the veteran prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest point might have been in the first set tiebreaker.
Hewitt was up, 7-6, and serving for the set. He had Sampras on the
move and had an excellent chance to put him away with a forehand
winner, but instead he hit it wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've worked so hard for that set, and to have the point set
up and make an easy error, you feel frustrated,'' Hewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The frustrations built when he was broken for a 4-3 lead in the
second set, and they spiked in the final tiebreaker when Sampras
won the final three points with a forehand volley, an overhead he
took out of the air from deep in the court, and a big forehand into
the corner that Hewitt couldn't get back over the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my chances today and didn't capitalize, but Pete played
a great match,'' Hewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Experience didn't help Martin against Safin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played the big points better than me, and he played the
little points better than me,'' Martin said. ``I was fighting an
uphill battle all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin seemed oblivious to the fact that he was in the semifinals
of a Grand Slam tournament for the first time. He ignored the
pressure, and ignored the New York crowd that was solidly behind
Martin, so much so that they cheered the Russian's mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impressive to me that somebody can ignore what the
environment is, what the situation is, so well,'' Martin said. ``He
plays the first point of the match as loose as the last point of
the match, break-points as loose as he plays 40-love points.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin intends to be just as loose Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I have enough experience not to be very nervous in the
final,'' Safin said. ``I hope I will not be. But I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try to put him under pressure from the first point, to
return his serve, run for the balls even if I can't get them, to
show the guy that I'm going to fight for it. I don't want to make
him Christmas presents. It's very important he knows that I'm going
to be there from the first point until the last one.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin was able to do that last month in the quarterfinals of the
Canadian Open, when he defeated Sampras in a third-set tie-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   But as Hewitt discovered Saturday, Sampras is much tougher in
the final weekend of a Grand Slam event.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
