<SLUG> BC-OLY-BBO-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: BASEBALL  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Olympic officials determined that professionals would be
allowed to play baseball at the Sydney Games, there was talk of an
U.S. dream team, with visions of Ken Griffey Jr. and Mark McGwire
swinging away. Wrong. September is for pennant races stateside.
</P>
<P>
   The next idea was for an older, less dreamy team of sorts _ Wade
Boggs, Tim Raines and Chili Davis swinging out of retirement. Wrong
again. When USA Baseball picked its team last month, the only
prominent name was the manager, Tommy Lasorda. The rest were
largely unknown minor leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, recognized professionalism will change the face of the
competition. The Americans, Australians, Japanese and Koreans will
now have strong clubs with lineups gleaned from their professional
leagues, teams good enough to challenge Cuba, the longtime
powerhouse. The open era in Olympic baseball may not have yielded a
dream team, but it may foster baseball's most competitive, truly
worldwide series.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The designated hitter is used. Aluminum bats are now prohibited.
There is a mercy rule: Any team up by 10 or more runs after seven
innings is declared the winner.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   Each of the eight teams plays every other team once. The top
four advance to the semifinals. Winners meet in the final.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Think about the 1980 U.S. Olympic hockey team with Lasorda as
coach Herb Brooks. That is the approach of the Americans, who, with
an average roster age of 25, have decided to combat the experience
of the dominant Cubans with youth.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   With every country, including Cuba, many of the biggest names
are not going to Sydney. In the case of the Cuban team, there have
been defections. Pat Borders, the former Toronto Blue Jays catcher,
is the best-known U.S. player. The Australians will be led by David
Nilsson, an All-Star catcher for the Milwaukee Brewers last season.
Japan is sending eight players from its major leagues. The Cuban
third-baseman Omar Linares, long considered the best ``amateur''
player in baseball, returns for another Olympics. He will probably
be the most-feared hitter here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
