<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTREDAME-NEBRASKA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEBRASKA BEATS NOTRE DAME, 27-23 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ He had absorbed knee-wobbling hits on nearly
every play as he led ground-pounding scoring drives that were as
painful to watch for Notre Dame fans as a dentist's drill is to
hear. He displayed his sprinter's speed and vanished 62 yards and
into the end zone. So everyone, an awful lot of them in Nebraska
red, in sold-out Notre Dame Stadium knew as overtime started
Saturday that the Cornhuskers were going to win or lose with their
quarterback, Eric Crouch.
</P>
<P>
   Win the No.1-ranked Huskers did, 27-23, in overtime. Thanks to
Crouch.
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Irish had just taken a 24-21 lead after an
improbable second-half comeback when Nick Setta kicked a 29-yard
field goal. Now the Huskers were in trouble on third and 9 on their
24-yard line. Crouch had attempted only 14 passes on the day,
completing seven of them. Notre Dame Coach Bob Davie believed that
Crouch, who had already gained 99 yards on the ground, would run.
Instead, Crouch passed _ to tight end Tracey Wistrom for the 9
yards and the first down. That was good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big down and it was kind of weird,'' Crouch said. ``I
read Tracey's eyes as he went inside.''
</P>
<P>
   But what he thought next was better. Nebraska I-back Dan
Alexander banged 8 more yards to the Notre Dame 7. Now 80,232
people were on their feet, and Crouch knew it was time to call his
own number. He rolled left on the option, no back trailing him, and
sprinted to the corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   It was over, a game for once that matched the build-up as two
storied programs played on the grounds that spawned Rockne and the
Four Horsemen and a nation-topping eight victories over No.1-ranked
teams. But not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was racing through my mind,'' Crouch said after a
game in which he gained 106 yards on the ground, threw for another
103 and scored two touchdowns. ``You want to get over the goal
line. I saw daylight, the crowd was going crazy, the only option
was for me to run, and we get out of this place with a victory.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Nebraska had visited South Bend since
1947, and at least 30,000 of their red-clad fans came with them.
Though just 4,000 tickets were allotted to Nebraska fans, the
ribbons of red that bled through the crowd of 80,232 at Notre
Stadium showed that most of them found tickets at prices ranging
from $600 to $2,000. The Big Red infiltration did not go unnoticed
by the new Notre Dame athletics director, Kevin White.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I was colorblind,'' White said. ``I'm very
disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   No one really believed overtime was in the offing when, early in
the third quarter, Alexander thundered through the Irish line and
28 yards into the end zone for a touchdown to give Nebraska a 21-7
lead. At that point, the Cornhuskers had gained 200 yards on the
ground on their way to what on any other day would be an easy
victory producing 377 yards of total offense.
</P>
<P>
   But on the ensuing kickoff, Julius Jones stirred up the echoes
of the Irish mystique, the intangible responsible for big upsets
like the 1993 victory over No.1 Florida State. He had returned a
kick 45 yards that was a shoelace tackle away from a touchdown
earlier. This time, with the same return play on, no one touched
Jones as zipped 100 yards up the left sideline for a touchdown to
narrow the score to 21-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a couple of blocks and that's all it takes,'' said
Jones, who also rushed for 52 yards at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   After the Notre Dame defense stalled the Cornhusker offense on
two consecutive drives, it was another return specialist time to go
to work. With 12 minutes 48 seconds left in the game, Joey
Getherall gathered Dan Hadenfeldt's punt against his chest at his
17-yard line, bolted right past Nebraska's Justin Smith and looked
like he had a pretty good return. At midfield, he turned inside
looking for a few extra yards. He not only found them, but all that
stood in the way of him and the Nebraska end zone was the punter.
Getherall feigned left, Hadenfeldt fell right and the Irish had
their second return for a touchdown in less than 10 minutes, as
well as a tie score.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Nebraska's option offense was not rolling over the
Irish.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a stretch when were moving the ball on the ground,''
Nebraska Coach Frank Solich said. ``It came and went.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish, meanwhile, drove the ball 48 yards to the Nebraska
30, where they faced fourth down and a yard to go. They decided to
go for it. Quarterback Arnaz Battle had completed just three passes
all afternoon, but instead of running, the Irish and Battle tried
to hit tight end Dan O'Leary in the middle of the field. Battle's
ball sailed over his head. ``We tried to go for it all,'' Davie
said. ``We thought it was the right decision at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   By overtime, the Nebraska decision was to put the ball in
Crouch's hands _ something Solich says he will do often this season
as his Cornhuskers try to persevere all the way to the national
title game. ``Eric never gets excited,'' Solich said. ``You can
count on him to make the big play. When you put the ball in Eric's
hand down the stretch, you got a better chance of getting done.''
</P>
<P>
   He got it done. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
