<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7699 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-LA.LAFAYETT     09-09 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-LA.LAFAYETTE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLEWHITE COMES OFF BENCH TO LEAD TEXAS' ROUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Major Applewhite put a swift and decisive stop
to Texas' ongoing quarterback quandary, at least for one day.
</P>
<P>
   Summoned from the bench to relieve starter Chris Simms and erase
a surprising first-quarter deficit, Applewhite responded by leading
the sixth-ranked Longhorns on seven consecutive scoring drives to
turn the momentum Saturday in a 52-10 rout of Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite took the field on Texas' third possession with the
Longhorns trailing, 10-0, before a stunned crowd of 80,007 at
Royal-Memorial Stadium. He left after throwing for 315 yards and
four touchdowns, including a stretch that included a school-record
nine consecutive completions.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Applewhite handed the reins back to Simms with 10:09
remaining in the third quarter, Texas led, 45-10. The Longhorns'
offense enjoyed a 100 percent success rate under Applewhite (seven
drives, seven scores), allowing Texas to take control of the game
against a 45-point underdog coming off a 21-14 loss to Sam Houston
State, a Division I-AA school.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' dominance appeared in question during the opening quarter
as the Ragin' Cajuns moved 75 yards with the opening kickoff to
tally a field goal, then extended the lead to 10-0 when cornerback
Terrence Hunter intercepted a Simms pass and returned it 43 yards
for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The interception led to Simms' removal in favor of Applewhite, a
junior who underwent reconstructive knee surgery in January. At the
same time, Texas (1-0) shifted to a hurry-up offense with four wide
receivers that jump-started a stagnant offense and buried the
Cajuns (0-2).
</P>
<P>
   ``The momentum changed when we put Major in,'' said Texas coach
Mack Brown, who stressed that coaches still view their quarterback
position as a ``co-starter'' situation. ``I was surprised Major was
able to play as well as he did, coming off a knee operation. He
gave us a spark, but we also changed the offense when he came in.
That gave Major a better chance to spread people out and find more
open people.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite did that with ease, leading the Longhorns to 31
points in the second quarter. It marked Texas' most productive
quarter since the team scored 33 points in the second quarter
against Rice on Oct. 1, 1977.
</P>
<P>
   By time he exited, Applewhite completed 18 of 26 passes for 315
yards. He threw two touchdown strikes to both Artie Ellis and
Brandon Healy. He watched freshman Roy Williams (six catches, 105
yards) make a spectacular, one-handed grab of a 40-yard toss during
his stretch of nine consecutive completions.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Applewhite flashed the same type of form he has shown
with regularity for the past two seasons while leading the
Longhorns to a 17-6 record as a starter. But the
Louisiana-Lafayette game marked the first time a healthy Applewhite
did not take Texas' initial snap from center since Sept. 12, 1998.
That made Saturday's performance special to Applewhite, who
experienced contact for the first time since suffering a torn
anterior cruciate ligament in the Southwestern Bell Cotton Bowl on
New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had goose bumps when I came out on the field,'' Applewhite
said. ``I felt my nose tingle like I was going to cry, but I
decided, `This is not the time.' I felt like I'd been away from the
game so long, it sparked a new passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite took his passion and made things happen. He drew
praise from Simms, who said he felt ``like punching a wall'' after
directing two scoring drives in mop-up duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major played great. I didn't get much going,'' said Simms, who
completed 7 of 14 passes for 88 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But Simms did enough, in Brown's estimation, to keep alive the
quarterback rotation system for next week's game at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing two quarterbacks, everyone will have an
opinion each week and that opinion will change,'' Brown said.
``We're going to keep both of these guys going and upbeat. They
both played well enough to play (next week) at Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility of changing starters against
Stanford, Brown sidestepped the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might as well not ask,'' Brown said. ``I won't say
anything about next week, either. We feel like we've got two
starters and that's good enough for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if one starter was noticeably better than the other against
Louisiana-Lafayette.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
