u s BC-TEN-OPEN-MEN-HNS &LR;      09-09 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-MEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Sampras tries for 14th Slam crown vs. Marat
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By SCOTT KAISER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ There will be a latter-day Cold War meeting for the U.S.
Open men's singles title at Arthur Ashe Stadium today.
</P>
<P>
   American Pete Sampras and Russian Marat Safin earned berths in
the final with straight-sets wins Saturday. Sampras, a four-time
winner here, outlasted 19-year-old Lleyton Hewitt 7-6 (7), 6-4, 7-6
(5); Safin knocked off crowd-favorite Todd Martin 6-3, 7-6 (4), 7-6
(1).
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, seeded fourth, will be playing in his 16th Grand Slam
final and looking to extend his own record with a 14th title; the
20-year-old Safin, the sixth seed, is in his first Slam final. The
two have split a pair of matches, with Sampras winning here in the
fourth round in 1998 and Safin winning 7-6 in the third set of the
quarterfinals of the Canadian Open a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be an easy match,'' said Sampras. ``He
believes he can beat me, but this is a final of a major. That's why
I play the game, for moments like (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating Hewitt wasn't easy, either. The young Australian,
seeded ninth, hung with Sampras in each of the three sets and
should have won the first, but Sampras escaped that scare and then
used his championship experience to come up with big shots on key
points in the final two sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty lucky to get out of (the first set),'' Sampras
said. ``After I got the first set, my confidence grew and my
serving picked up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   After letting four set points escape late in the first set,
Sampras was down 7-6 in the tiebreaker. Hewitt hit a big serve
Sampras returned short, but an anxious Hewitt missed an easy
forehand. Sampras followed with a cross-court forehand for a
winner, then hit a service winner to take the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like I went for the right shot,'' said Hewitt of
his lost set point. ``I didn't play the percentages and didn't
allow myself a big margin of error on that point, but it's easy to
look back on it now and say, `Maybe I should have gone to his
backhand.' I had the point set up and made an easy error.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras broke Hewitt early in the second set, then lost only two
points on serve the rest of the way to take a commanding lead.
Hewitt showed his grit as he broke Sampras early in the third, but
Sampras returned the favor in the seventh. In the tiebreaker,
Sampras got a match point at 6-5 with a tremendous overhead from
just inside the baseline, then wrapped it up with a big inside-out
forehand to the corner that Hewitt couldn't handle.
</P>
<P>
   In the first semifinal, Safin continued to show poise beyond his
years in his elimination of the unseeded Martin. The 6-4 Russian
kept his game and emotions in check, and Martin _ coming off two
tough matches _ never looked like he was in the match despite the
close score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fighting an uphill battle the whole way,'' Martin said.
``He was better on the big points and better on the little
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin showed his usual power with 13 aces and 58 winners, but it
was his touch and shot selection that raised eyebrows. A number of
times he hit winning drop shots from the baseline, plus used an
effective topspin lob to negate Martin's serve-and-volley game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't going for too much,'' Safin said. ``I don't know why,
but I was just putting the ball inside the court and building the
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin, after an early break, closed out the opening set with a
sweet drop shot from behind the baseline and a big forehand winner.
Martin battled back from an early break in the second to get a set
point at 6-5, but Safin answered with a backhand passing shot and
eventually forced a tiebreaker. Safin got a set point of his own
there with a backhand winner after Martin's volley kicked up off
the tape, then Martin hit a service return long to put himself in a
hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even up a set point in the second set, I still feel like he's
so on his game that it's tough to handle,'' Martin said. ``I was
pretty impressed with his discipline playing from the backcourt.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin showed his determination by forcing another tiebreaker,
but that was his last gasp. Safin raced out to a 5-0 lead and then
closed out the match with a 133-mph ace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew (Martin was tired),'' Safin said. ``I felt it because
he made some easy mistakes and was late going to the net. He just
didn't move very well.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
