<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TV-COLUMN-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVE FROM SYDNEY, IT'S CBC. TAPED AND PACKAGED, IT'S NBC.
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of television schedule for every day of Games on
NBC, MSNMC and CNBC is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Olympic television terms, NBC is a tyranny, the Canadian
Broadcasting Corp. a democracy.
</P>
<P>
   NBC will tape every minute of the Sydney Games and package the
best for a five-hour prime-time show.
</P>
<P>
   All of NBC's morning and late-night coverage will be taped, as
will everything broadcast on CNBC and MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, NBC will show you what it believes you want to see.
</P>
<P>
   NBC even has minute-by-minute surveys that prove what you want,
and when you surf away when you're shown what you don't want. So if
you don't like what you see at 10:45 p.m., you must not be in the
majority.
</P>
<P>
   CBC will carry everything live. So march northward, you purists
_ you viewers who want results now, not 10 or 12 or 15 hours later
_ to Buffalo, Seattle, Detroit or Minneapolis, anywhere close
enough to the Canadian border to grab a CBC signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBS tried to block out the CBC feed coming from Vancouver
during Nagano,'' said Christian Haase, a spokesman for CBC,
referring to the 1998 Winter Olympics from Japan. ``People from the
U.S. write to thank us for showing the Olympics live.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're in Buffalo, you can watch the opening ceremony from
Sydney at 3:45 a.m. Eastern time. Or tune in to the women's
100-meter sprint final on Sept. 23 at 5:05 a.m. and the men's 100
meter final 15 minutes later. That men's 50-meter freestyle
swimming final you're looking for? That will be at 4:05 a.m. on
Sept. 22.
</P>
<P>
   By Oct. 1, with your body clock adjusted, watching the closing
ceremony at 4 a.m. should be no problem.
</P>
<P>
   This is the CBC way, and it is proud not to do it the NBC way.
</P>
<P>
   ``With so much information available and the Internet, it's
important to show it live,'' Hasse said. ``People here are used to
watching men's Olympic hockey at 2 a.m. or the men's 100 meter
final at 5:20. It's 2 1/2 weeks of magic.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasse said that during the 1998 Winter Olympics from Nagano, CBC
attracted 2.3 million viewers for the Canada-Czech Republic
semifinal hockey game, from 12:40 to 3:30 a.m. By comparison, the
prime-time ``Hockey Night in Canada,'' attracts an average
viewership of 1.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   CBC will carry some taped highlights of wee-hour action during
its morning show, from 9 a.m. to noon. In its afternoon and
prime-time broadcasts, from 5 to 11 p.m., CBC will show 288 hours
of live coverage, augmented by more than 200 hours from TSN, a
second Canadian network.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that CBC is paying $20 million for the rights
to the Sydney Games, compared with NBC's fee of $705 million.
</P>
<P>
   CBC viewers have a great advantage: The network's relatively
modest investment doesn't require it to time-shift the prime stuff
to prime time in order to earn back a gigantic rights fee.
</P>
<P>
   And if viewers look forward to track and field in the wee hours,
that is their choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are past time changes,'' Joel Darling, CBC's
Olympic executive producer, told The National Post, a Toronto
newspaper. ``If they want to see something, they want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is imperative for NBC to husband the best events for
maximum exposure and advertising rates for prime time. All those
NBC promotions urging viewers to watch marquee athletes like
Maurice Greene, Marion Jones, Lenny Krayzelburg, Ian Thorpe or
Stacy Dragila would be useless if the come-ons urged: ``Join us in
Sydney at 4 in the morning!'' You simply can't build a broad TV
viewership out of Joe Benigno's overnight listeners on WFAN.
</P>
<P>
   ``With virtually all of the finals of track and field, swimming,
diving and gymnastics taking place in the evening hours in
Sydney,'' said Dick Ebersol, the chairman of NBC Sports, ``the
decision was made early on with these Olympics that our most
important target was to reach the largest possible audience.''
</P>
<P>
   That audience exists in greatest numbers between 7 p.m. and
midnight Eastern time, not at 3 a.m. when an estimated 9 percent of
television sets in the United States are on.
</P>
<P>
   To alter that equation by carrying an Olympics from a site 15
hours away would be folly for NBC, as long as the network pays what
the International Olympic Committee wants. NBC, of course, made a
pre-emptive bid for the Sydney and 2002 Salt Lake Winter Olympic
rights in 1995 for a combined $1.2 billion, then returned a few
months later with a $2.3 billion offer for the 2004, 2006 and 2008
rights. Had NBC not come forward, the IOC likely would have sought
more in competitive bidding.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC and the Olympic movement could live easily without the
CBC's money, but not NBC's.
</P>
<P>
   For Sydney, NBC's $705 million payment accounts for 52.9 percent
of the worldwide TV rights. CBC accounts for 1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago in Atlanta, NBC's $456 million payment provided
50.7 percent of the $898.3 million total.
</P>
<P>
   Much as NBC is certain that its taped strategy will work, it
will be challenged more than ever by the Internet, which is more
important and pervasive than even two years ago at the Nagano
Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Various Web sites, including nbcolympics.com, will make results
instantly available, and photographs will be widely posted.
</P>
<P>
   NBC must hope that its bedrock philosophy _ that viewers are
more interested in the Games' video imagery and stories of athletic
sacrifice, triumph and failure than in who won or lost _ continues
to be viable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
