<SLUG> BC-OLY-CAN-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: CANOEING  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This sport involves men and women in two distinct disciplines:
sprint (flat- &QL; 
water) and slalom (whitewater). Two types of craft _ canoes and
kayaks _ are used in both. In the canoe, the athlete kneels and
uses a single-bladed paddle. In the kayak, the athlete sits and
uses a double-bladed paddle.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   There are 12 events in sprints, four in slalom. Women compete
only in kayak. The fiberglass-like canoes and kayaks are as small
as 13 feet 1 inch for slalom, 17 feet for sprints.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   With repechage (second-chance) heats no longer used in Olympic
sprints, the competition consists of heats, semifinals and finals,
all at 500 or 1,000 meters. In slalom, competitors race one at a
time through gates and rapids over a course of 300 to 600 meters.
Time penalties are assessed for missing or touching a gate. Total
time for two runs decides each slalom round.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Once the slalom course is set, practice runs are barred, so the
athletes walk alongside the course to determine how to approach
each gate. If they err, they may still survive because they get two
runs the first day and the qualifiers get two more the next.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   Medals choices are headed by Paul Ratcliffe of Britain and Mandy
Planert and Suzanne Hirt of Germany in slalom and Martin Doctor of
the Czech Republic in canoe sprints. The best Americans are Scott
Shipley of Poulsbo, Wash., and Rebecca Bennett-Giddens of Green
Bay, Wis., in kayak slalom and 41-year-old David Hearn of Bethesda,
Md., in canoe slalom.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
