<HEADLINE>
QUARTERBACK SELECTION NO LAST-MINUTE DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Although Texas coaches did not make public their
choice of a starting quarterback until game time, Chris Simms said
he was told before Saturday that he would take the first snap for
the Longhorns. He declined to elaborate, saying only that the word
came down earlier in the week.
</P>
<P>
   Major Applewhite, who came off the bench to spark the Longhorns'
52-10 victory, said he was resolute when told he would be benched
for reasons other than ailing health for the first time since Sept.
12, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided I could say, `Fine,' accept it and go pout. Or I
could remember that things in college football can change like
``that,'','' Applewhite said, snapping his fingers for emphasis.
``The good news is that roles will change. And the bad news is that
roles will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Louisiana-Lafayette, Applewhite threw for 315 yards and
a career-high four touchdowns. Texas coach Mack Brown said the
performance will not necessarily trigger a change in the starting
lineup for next week's game at Stanford. Both quarterbacks, will
play, Brown said. WAITING HIS TURN
</P>
<P>
   Texas wide receiver Brandon Healy, a fifth-year senior, made his
first career start a memorable one. Healy grabbed four passes for
88 yards and two touchdowns. Heading into the game, Healy had
caught just eight passes for 77 yards and one touchdown since
enrolling at Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was anxious to get the season started the right way,'' said
Healy, who credits watching NFL-bound teammates Wane McGarity
(Cowboys) and Kwame Cavil (Buffalo Bills) with helping hone his
moves. ``I have been able to watch a lot of great players in my
time here, and I have tried to take something from each of them and
apply it to my game.'' EXTRA SPECIAL TEAMS
</P>
<P>
   Special-teams breakdowns plagued the Longhorns in their 1999
season opener, with three blocked punts leading to a 23-20 loss to
North Carolina State. Not so against Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Brown praised Texas' special-team units for their ``best
performance'' in his three years at the school. Hodges Mitchell
averaged 8.6 yards on punt returns, 2.6 yards above the team's
average in 1999. Punter Kris Stockton averaged 48.0 yards per
attempt, with no blocks. Texas kickoff returners Victor Ike and
Ivan Williams combined to average 28.6 yards, more than nine yards
better than last year's mark (19.4). BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Texas coaches refer to their spread offense, which produced
eight consecutive scoring drives, as their ``one-minute'' tempo.
The formation is well named. Those eight scoring drives averaged
1:19 in length.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quarterback Jon Van Cleave, a freshman from Pantego Christian
Academy, completed 6 of 12 passes for 62 yards in his college debut
for Louisiana-Lafayette. ``You'll be seeing more of him,'' coach
Jerry Baldwin said. ``He looked pretty good out there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The Longhorns' 98-yard touchdown drive was Texas' seventh
scoring drive of 90-plus yards in three seasons under coach Mack
Brown. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
