<SLUG> BC-OLY-CYC-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: CYCLING  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was to have been the perfect Hollywood ending for the
coming movie on the improbable life of Lance Armstrong. Brash young
Texan rides his bike to the world road-racing championship; then
miraculously survives testicular cancer that had spread to his
abdomen, lungs and brain; then makes an amazing comeback and wins
the Tour de France last year and again this year; then wins a gold
medal in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Only the last scene is yet to unfold, and it may not happen. Two
weeks ago, the 28-year-old Armstrong was on a training ride in the
hills near Nice, France, when a car went out of control on a curve
and hit Armstrong and a training partner, Tyler Hamilton. While
Hamilton escaped with a few bumps, Armstrong suffered a broken
vertebra in the neck. His training was interrupted, the pain did
not leave and he skipped two European one-day races. He will decide
this week whether he feels fit enough to ride in two Olympic races.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, he seems to be leaning toward not riding. He does
not need the involvement because he has already raced in two
Olympics. In 1992, as a 20-year-old amateur, he finished 14th in
the road race. In 1996, as a pro and unknowingly racked with
cancer, he placed sixth in the time trial and 12th in the road
race.
</P>
<P>
   If he does ride, his best chance will be in the men's 29-mile
time trial, in which the riders race one at a time against the
clock. Armstrong won similar time trials in the last two Tours de
France. With or without Armstrong in the race, Hamilton, from
Marblehead, Mass., should be a medal contender.
</P>
<P>
   Three days before the time trial is the 148-mile road race,
which will have such Tour de France rivals as Jan Ullrich of
Germany, Alex Zuelle of Switzerland and Mario Pantani of Italy.
Because the essentially flat course is more suited to a sprinter,
Armstrong has called that race a lottery. If he rides it, he will
be a quarterback on the course, ad-libbing the strategy for the
U.S. five-man team and probably trying to set up a victory for
George Hincapie of Greenville, S.C., or Fred Rodriguez of Piedmont,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   There will be 18 cycling events: 12 on the track, four on the
road and two for mountain bikes. Eleven events are for men, seven
for women.
</P>
<P>
   Track events will be contested on a steeply banked 250-meter
indoor wooden track. The bikes will be flying perhaps 40 mph at the
end of the four-lap sprint, a tactical race that starts at a crawl,
and the eight-lap keirin, in which a motorcycle sets the pace until
the last 2 1/2 laps. The mountain-bike races are cross-country,
about 31 miles for men and 22 for women, with the average speed
maybe 12 mph. On the road, the women will cover 74.5 miles in the
road race, 19.5 miles in the time trial.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The strongest countries are Italy, the United States, Germany
and Canada on the road; France, Australia, Germany and the United
States on the track and France, Australia, Spain and Canada on
mountain bikes.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. medal contenders include Hamilton and Armstrong (if he
races) in the men's road time trial; Marty Nothstein of
Trexlertown, Pa., in the men's track sprint and keirin and Alison
Dunlap of Colorado Springs in the women's mountain-bike race.
</P>
</TEXT>
