<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: DIVING  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once a body of water controlled by high-flying Americans, the
Olympic diving tank has belonged to the Chinese since Greg Louganis
made the perfect exit in 1988 after so many perfect entries. Since
then, the only American to win a gold medal has been Mark Lenzi, in
1992 on the springboard. In 1996, the Americans could muster only
two bronze medals; Sydney should not change their or the Chinese's
luck.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   After 80 years of continuity, in which men and women competed
individually on 3-meter springboard and 10-meter platform, the
sport added four events in the 2000 Games. All four are
synchronized events, in which two teammates attempt to perform
identical dives simultaneously. In springboard, they dive of
side-by-side boards. In platform, they dive off the same platform.
The result is quite telegenic, which helps explain why ``synchro''
is getting its Olympic moment.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   As in 1996, 18 divers will advance to the semifinals in the
individual events. After five compulsory dives, 12 competitors will
then advance to the finals, where they will perform six dives of
their choice. The semifinal and final dives are then added together
to produce a diver's total score. There are seven judges, who award
scores of up to 10 points for each dive. Their scores are then
multiplied by a coefficient determined by the dive's degree of
difficulty, which range from the lowly 1.3 to the presumably
life-threatening 3.6. In synchro, there are only eight teams in
each event and no preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   There are five categories in springboard: inward, forward,
backward, reverse and twisting. In platform diving, there is an
additional category: the handstand. The key to success is being
able to juggle risk and perfection. A dive with a high degree of
difficulty with minor faults will outscore a simpler dive performed
flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   After retiring for the second time, China's Fu Mingxia, the most
successful diver of the 1990s, will attempt to become the first
diver to win five gold medals. Fu won her first gold medal in 1992
on platform at age 14 and then swept both women's events in 1996.
She will compete only on springboard in Sydney, and she is a
favorite in the synchronized event with Guo Jingjing. The Chinese
teen-ager Li Na is a rising (make that falling) star in the women's
platform, and her countryman Tian Ling will duel with the defending
Olympic champion, Dmitri Sautin of Russia, on the men's platform.
Sautin is also a favorite in springboard, along with the defending
Olympic champion Xiong Ni of China. Americans to watch include Mark
Ruiz on springboard and platform and Laura Wilkinson on women's
platform.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
