<SLUG> BC-OLY-JUD-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: JUDO  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like its fellow Olympic sports of wrestling and tae kwon do,
judo is one of the variations of hand-to-hand combat. It limits
mayhem, with no punching or kicking. Japan, which won eight of the
16 gold medals in the last world championships, should dominate.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   Direct-elimination competition will decide the seven weight
classes for men and the seven for women. Anyone who loses to a
finalist moves into a repechage (second-chance) competition for
bronze medals.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   A men's match can last five minutes, a women's match four. A
match ends immediately with an ippon, in which a player throws an
opponent on his back or holds him on his back for 25 seconds or
applies a hold that evokes submission. Lesser throws earn fractions
of a point. About half the matches end on an ippon, the other half
on points.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to get an opponent off balance so he can be thrown
to the mat. Some players are skilled mainly on their feet and
others do better working on the mat.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The strongest teams are the Japanese, Korean, French and German
men and the Cuban women. The United States ranks about 10th among
the men, 12th to 15th among the women. Jimmy Pedro of Boston, the
world champion in the men's 73-kilogram (160.6-pound) class, is
favored to give the United States its first Olympic judo gold
medal. The two best players are Japanese _ Shinichi Shinohara
(men's heavyweight) and Ryoko Tamura (women's 48 kilograms, or
105.6 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
