<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-SAI-$ADV11-NYT &LR;      09-09 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAI-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: SAILING  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1996 U.S. team had high expectations in its home waters, but
managed only two bronze medals in Savannah, Ga. The U.S. squad
hopes to return to prominence in Sydney. In 1992, the team claimed
nine medals in 10 classes.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the 11 classes compete in strict fleet-racing formats,
where the first boat to finish wins the race and scores one point.
Second place earns two points, and so on. Competition in each event
is based on an 11-race series, weather permitting, with the
exception of the 49er Class, which sails 16 races. The winner is
the boat with the lowest accumulated score at the end of the
series. After 10 races, each boat discards its worst two scores.
The Soling Class will run six fleet races and the top 12 boats will
advance to a boat-versus-boat match-racing tournament.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Early springtime weather conditions can present a variety of
conditions, from stiff offshore westerlies to light, shifty sea
breezes. With winds apt to bend unpredictably around the many
harbor headlands, and currents that in places can run up to a
knot-and-a-half, successful skippers will need to employ clean
starts and adapt quickly to the situations.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   In the Star Class, the American Mark Reynolds, the reigning
world champion skipper, will face stiff competition from Brazil's
Torben Grael and the hometown favorite, the Australian Colin
Beashel. In the Laser Class, Britain's Ben Ainslie; the Brazilian
Robert Scheidt; and another Aussie, Michael Blackburn, are expected
to wage an epic battle. In the 49er Class, the brothers Jonathan
and Charlie McKee should be strong medal contenders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
