<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK CAN'T PULL DODGERS FROM MIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Los Angeles Dodgers death march has brought
solemnness to everything and even Kevin Brown and Chan Ho Park, two
of the few consistent performers in this now dreadful season, are
part of it.
</P>
<P>
   Park and Brown have lost before but only because the Dodgers
failed to score runs. But a day after Brown had trouble against
Colorado, Park yielded six runs in the first inning, which was too
much for the stumbling, bumbling Dodgers to overcome in a 7-6 loss
to the Rockies on Saturday at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, five games out of first place on Aug. 29, are 10
games out and in fourth place. The Rockies (73-68) moved ahead of
the Dodgers(73-69), who could end up in last place considering they
lead San Diego by 3 games and have six remaining against the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   How much worse can it get? Well, Curt Schilling against Luke
Prokopec could give some insight to that, but that's not until
Tuesday in Arizona. For now, the Dodgers must deal with their fifth
straight loss and figure out a way to turn a $98 million bust into
something respectable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just enthusiasm,'' Dodgers left fielder Gary
Sheffield said. ``I watched these guys doing real well on TV when I
was sick. It seemed like they had fire in their eyes, like the
enthusiasm was there. I always say that if guys in the lineup are
not showing enthusiasm, not doing their jobs, give those guys on
the bench a chance to do it because when those guys come off the
bench, they're anxious to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to bring that enthusiasm out there on the field
and it's going to rub off on the other players. You keep going with
the same guys thinking it's going to change, and if it hasn't
changed now, it's not going to. Guys feed off each other, and guys
look up to veteran players.
</P>
<P>
   ``When veteran players are dragging and not playing with
enthusiasm, not playing with fire, the younger players see that and
they try harder and it makes them make mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the Dodgers came back from a 6-0 first-inning deficit to
pull within 7-6 on Chris Donnels' pinch-hit homer in the sixth, the
day was splashed with uninspired play and three errors, two by
shortstop Alex Cora.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for his career-high 16th win, Park (15-9) instead
allowed six hits and six runs as the Rockies sent 10 batters to the
plate in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Former Dodgers outfielder Todd Hollandsworth, who went 2 for 3
with a run scored and RBI for the Rockies, said he understands how
things could have gone south for his former team.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to make up this ground and it can be disheartening,''
Hollandsworth said. ``You feel like you're treading water because
the team in front of you is doing the same thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
