<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWM-ART-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: SWIMMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic of predictions of winning times for swimming
events is being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. and Australia _ with its stars Ian Thorpe, Susie
O'Neill and Kieren Perkins _ will battle for the unofficial team
title for most gold medals, although there are no engaging
head-to-head matchups looming. Both countries are strongest in
events where the other is weakest, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech bodysuits have also revolutionized the sport, creating
a flurry of world records.
</P>
<P>
   THE WOMEN
</P>
<P>
   This sport, more than any other in the Olympics, has been
tarnished for three decades by the use of performance-enhancing
drugs. Smaller amounts of synthetic steroids have more effect in
women than in men. All 32 medals won by East German women from 1968
to 1988 have been discredited by revelations in court and in
documents of the former country's state-sponsored system of doping.
About three dozen Chinese athletes were caught using banned
substances in the 1990s. Michelle Smith of Ireland, who won three
gold medals at the 1996 Summer Games in Atlanta, was banned last
year after testing positive for androstenedione, the steroid that
Mark McGwire used the year he broke the home-run record, and for
spiking a drug test with alcohol. Suspicion about possible drug use
will be high at the Sydney Games as well.
</P>
<P>
   Skepticism attends two female swimmers: Inge de Bruijn of the
Netherlands, a respected but not previously great swimmer who set
world records in the 50- and 100-meter freestyle and the 100-meter
butterfly this year, and the American Dara Torres, who qualified in
three sprints at the Olympic trials after being away from the sport
for seven years. Both swimmers have vehemently denied using illicit
drugs, and both attribute their success to maturity, rigorous
cross-training, better nutrition and the new bodysuits.
</P>
<P>
   At 33, Torres is the first American to participate in four
Olympics. She has an entourage of a dozen specialists, including a
swim coach, a nutritionist, flexibility experts, a mental coach and
a specialist in massaging her lymph system.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women are favored in only one event, the 800-meter
freestyle, where Brooke Bennett is seeking to repeat as Olympic
champion. Gold medals are possible in the sprints if Jenny Thompson
and Torres can overcome de Bruijn. Thompson is tied with the
speed-skater Bonnie Blair for most golds won by a U.S. woman _ five
_ but all of Thompson's victories have come in relays. She is
seeking individual titles in Sydney in the 100 freestyle and 100
butterfly. One of the most fascinating races of the Games will be
the 100-meter breaststroke, where Penny Heyns of South Africa will
attempt to hold off the 16-year-old Megan Quann of the United
States, who has said she will win and break the world record.
</P>
<P>
   THE MEN
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe will be a huge star if he wins, as expected, the 200- and
400-meter freestyle events. The 17-year-old Australian holds world
records in both. Kieren Perkins of Australia is also looking to win
his third consecutive Olympic title in the 1,500-meter freestyle. A
great rivalry will be renewed in the 50-meter freestyle between
Alexander Popov of Russia, the two-time Olympic champion, and Gary
Hall Jr., the iconoclastic American who finished second in Atlanta.
At the U.S. Olympic trials, Hall swam faster in the 50-meter
freestyle than Popov ever has in an eight-man race. A possible gold
medalist is Anthony Ervin of the United States, who is the first
swimmer of African-American descent to make the Olympic team. Popov
will also seek to win his third Olympic title in the 100 freestyle,
where Neil Walker of the United States and Hall will challenge for
gold medals. Lenny Krayzelburg of Los Angeles, whose family
immigrated from the former Soviet Union when he was 13 in 1989, is
the world-record holder in the 100- and 200-meter backstroke, and
should win both events in Sydney. Tom Malchow, who is 6 feet 7
inches, owns the world record in the 200-meter butterfly. Tom Dolan
is back to defend his Olympic title in the 400-meter individual
medley.
</P>
<P>
   SYNCHRONIZED SWIMMING
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Canadian women dominated the first four Olympic
competitions. Now the Russians, led by Maria Kisseleva, and the
Japanese are the favorites in the two events: the duet and the
team. Kisseleva may be distracted by a positive drug test for
ephedrine, which meant she had to give up her European duet crown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
