<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-MENSEMIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS, SAFIN IN FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One young gun down, one to go.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras ousted 19-year-old Lleyton Hewitt, 7-6 (7-4), 6-4,
7-6 (7-5), Saturday in a tough US Open semifinal. Sampras took care
of history at Wimbledon a couple of months ago with his record 13th
championship in a major tournament. Now he shoots for No. 14, a
fifth US Open title _ his first since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras will face No. 6 seed Marat Safin, 20, in the final
Sunday at 4 p.m. Safin, looser than loose, had no problem handling
the hoopla of his first semifinal in a major tournament and beat
Todd Martin, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 7-6 (7-1).
</P>
<P>
   Today's is a serving summit of the past, present, and future. A
showdown between the player who had an audience with the president
after his win, and a guy who said he's had to call several times a
day _ and spell his name each time _ to get a ride to the National
Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at two young guys who are going to be around for
many, many years,'' Sampras said. ``Lleyton has a good future. He's
got the tools. Safin is someone that has got a much bigger game,
serves huge. He's also the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The future, Sampras hopes, can wait.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras won his first title in a major at the US Open 10 years
ago at age 19.
</P>
<P>
   This final matches a pair of tiebreaker-tough opponents who were
long gone at this time last year. Safin lost in the second round to
Jiri Novak, and Sampras _ after hurting his back in practice _
withdrew and never made it to the starting line.
</P>
<P>
   This year, both have been fine finishers.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras is 7-0 in tiebreakers in this tournament. Safin is 5-1
and has won his last five.
</P>
<P>
   Something must give.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras beat Safin in straight sets here in the fourth round two
years ago. But the only other time they met, Safin beat Sampras in
a third-set tiebreaker in the Canadian Open early last month.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras avenged one loss in the semifinals _ Hewitt had beaten
him the last time they met going into Wimbledon _ and will try to
avenge another Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt didn't go quietly.
</P>
<P>
   In the first set, Hewitt was down, 4-5 and 15-40, on his serve
and held off three Sampras break points overall in the game. With
Hewitt serving at 5-6, Sampras again had a set point and again
couldn't get it.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt had a couple of set points in the tiebreaker, the best
while serving at 7-6. He moved in on a forehand and blasted it down
the line. Just wide. Sampras followed with a cross-court forehand
and then a service winner for the set.
</P>
<P>
   One service break decided the second set. Sampras was broken in
the second game of the third set, but got that one back in the
seventh game.
</P>
<P>
   It was back to a tiebreaker in the third set. Hewitt was up,
5-4, when Sampras took over.
</P>
<P>
   He had a forehand volley and then, when Hewitt popped up a
return, got up for an overhead from deep in the court. Hewitt put a
backhand into the net and the Sampras-Safin final was set.
</P>
<P>
   As impressed as he was by Savin's return of serve and the way he
handled himself, Martin thinks the youngster should get more of a
test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there will be a greater propensity on his part to
overhit,'' Martin said. ``Today, that wasn't really there. He saw
molasses across the street, wasn't too worried about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin had it all over Martin, all match.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played the big points better than me and he played the
little points better than me,'' Martin said. ``You know, the score
is 3, 6, and 6, but I was fighting an uphill battle the whole way.
Even up a set point in the second point, I still feel like he's on
his game, that it's tough to handle. You know, I was coming in
every point I could, and it was purely out of defense. I had to
attack in order not to get smoked.''
</P>
<P>
   Safin was serving and down, 5-6, in games when a Martin overhead
created the set point at the end of the middle set. A backhand
passing shot, a forehand volley, and then a nice lob that Martin
couldn't handle got Safin out of trouble and he won the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was broken early in the third set, but got it right back.
But Safin was way too good in that tiebreaker and finally finished
Martin off with a 133-mile-an-hour ace.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Safin didn't think he played that well. Then he
reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was playing horrible today,'' he said. ``I
couldn't find my concentration. I played without any pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what impressed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That someone can ignore what the environment is, what the
situation is,'' he said. ``He plays the first point of the match as
loose as the last point of the match, break points as loose as he
plays 40-love points. . . . So many opportunities that I had, I
actually made good plays. It seemed as though he was laughing at
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Safin will try to keep the pressure on Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just start from the first point to return his serve, run for
the balls even if I can't get them, to show the guy that I'm going
to fight for it,'' Safin said. ``I don't want to give him Christmas
presents.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras won't be expecting any.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
