</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-SOXBULLPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX BULLPEN IS THIN FOR STRETCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been few scenes at Fenway Park that approach the
horror of what took place Friday night, when Bryce Florie was hit
in the face with a line drive. Dick Pole was only 24 years old when
he was struck by a line drive hit by Tony Muser of the Baltimore
Orioles in 1975, and his career was over after the 1978 season, the
vision in his right eye never the same. The memory of Tony
Conigliaro sprawled in the dirt after being hit by a Jack Hamilton
pitch in 1967 still haunts generations of Sox fans.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Florie lies in the hospital, the bones around his right eye
shattered by a line drive hit by Ryan Thompson of the New York
Yankees, doctors offering only a guarded prognosis that he will
have ``reasonable vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Florie is 30. In February, he signed a two-year deal with the
Sox for $2.8 million, $1.35 million for this season. His financial
security, of course, is of small comfort while he ponders not only
whether he will be able to resume his career but whether his sight
will ever be the same.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the personal tragedy, the Sox are now left facing the
most taxing segment of their schedule _ three doubleheaders in six
days, including back-to-back day-night twin bills _ with their
bullpen suddenly in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Florie was hurt, the Sox were down Hipolito
Pichardo, who has a strained forearm that almost certainly is
related in some way to the elbow surgery he had last season, and
Rich Garces, who strained his right groin. Pichardo, already shut
down for a week in August, is expected to be out at least 10 days,
and with Garces, the hope is that he'll be back sooner than later,
but no one is sure.
</P>
<P>
   So what had been one of the strengths of this team now takes on
an uncertain cast, with more of the burden now falling on Rod Beck
and Tim Wakefield and minor leaguers Paxton Crawford and Rick
Croushore.
</P>
<P>
   Middle relief is an often overlooked component of a team's
success. The Yankees are Exhibit A. Yes, they have the best closer
in the game in Mariano Rivera, but the lefty-righty tandem of Mike
Stanton and Jeff Nelson has been unmatched in getting games to the
ninth inning _ which is why owner George Steinbrenner has been so
hot about their recent failures _ and the loss of swingman Ramiro
Mendoza for the rest of the season leaves the Yankees more
vulnerable than usual heading into October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play 20 or 30 years ago,'' said Sox closer Derek
Lowe, ``but the game is so different today. Before, you gave a
starter the ball and he went at least seven innings, even if he
threw 160 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, if a starter gets to the sixth and is struggling at
all, they get him out as soon as they can. Pichardo was a big part
of our pen, and so was Garces, who was maybe the most valuable guy
in our pen. They're very, very important, especially in the
playoffs, when there are so many tight games. You need to keep
those 2-1 games and 3-2 games from becoming 4-1 or 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what Mendoza did to us in the playoffs last year.
Twice he came into games with the bases loaded and we didn't score.
I think he was a huge reason they won last year. He's the kind of
guy who can come into a game in the second inning and pitch six
innings, or come in in the eighth for one inning. You know he's
going to get a lot of ground balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe if they don't have him last year, we go to the World
Series. That's how important the bullpen can be.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the Sox' bullpen is lacking Florie, Pichardo, and
Garces. The sorrow that his teammates feel for Florie also will
require a grim resolve to get the job done without him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prospects not promising
</P>
<P>
   Dan Duquette's announcement that the Red Sox have extended the
contract of Wayne Britton, the team's vice president of scouting,
through the 2003 season quiets the whispers that there was friction
between the two. Britton has been the scouting director for eight
years and scored big in his first two drafts when he took Trot
Nixon No. 1 in 1993 and landed Nomar Garciaparra, Brian Rose, Carl
Pavano, and Donnie Sadler in '94.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is one glaring hole in the Sox farm system, it is
this: the lack of position players who are anywhere near major
league-ready. First baseman Dernell Stenson, a third-round pick in
1996, is a legitimate prospect, the player closest to making a bid
for a roster spot next season.
</P>
<P>
   But after Stenson, there are only questions. Third baseman
Wilton Veras, who appeared to be a sure thing this spring, took a
giant step backward. Sadler has also invited serious doubts that he
will ever hit in the big leagues. Outfielder Michael Coleman, who
also was on the fast track at one time, fractured his wrist. If he
makes it, it probably will be with another club.
</P>
<P>
   At Double A Trenton, Shea Hillenbrand, a 10th-round pick in '96,
had a nice year at the plate for the Thunder and will go to the
Arizona Fall League, but so far the Sox have been unable to find
him a position, trying him at first, third, and catcher. Peabody's
Steve Lomasney got off to a dreadful start at the plate,
reinforcing some opinions that he strikes out far too much. He also
was hurt. The 23-year-old catcher, a fifth-round pick in the '95
draft, will need at least another year in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, the pickings are extremely slim for an organization
that repeatedly has claimed the key to any long-term success is a
productive farm system. Kids such as outfielder Lew Ford at Single
A Augusta, third baseman Tony Blanco (rookie league), and
outfielder Rick Asadoorian (rookie league) are too far away to
project with any certainty.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most promising position player in the Sox' system is
Juan Diaz, the slugging first baseman from Cuba, but he was not
home-grown. Diaz, who dislocated his ankle, came out of the
Dodgers' system after he was declared a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Managing _ for now
</P>
<P>
   It has been 58 years since there's been an entire baseball
season without a manager being fired, but job security is as
tenuous as ever for at least eight managers who may be out of work
by Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   The likely-to-be-fired list includes Larry Rothschild of the
Devil Rays, Jack McKeon of the Reds, Terry Francona of the
Phillies, Larry Dierker of the Astros, Gene Lamont of the Pirates,
Davey Johnson of the Dodgers, Felipe Alou of the Expos, and Buck
Showalter of the Diamondbacks. In addition, Jim Fregosi (Blue
Jays), Lou Piniella (Mariners), and Dusty Baker (Giants) are all
free agents after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Former PawSox manager Ken Macha, who played in the Pirates
system, is a Pittsburgh native (he went to Pitt), and is now
coaching for the A's, has been mentioned as a candidate for the
Pirates job. Diamondbacks broadcaster Bob Brenly, the former
catcher, reportedly was sounded out by owner Jerry Colangelo about
replacing Showalter, who was under fire even before Arizona's
September collapse. Former Sox boss Kevin Kennedy, a Southern
California native and friend of Dodgers general manager Kevin
Malone, has been mentioned as the successor to Johnson, though it's
not a given that Malone will survive a possible housecleaning by
Dodger boss Bob Daly. Baker, a longtime Dodger star, also is
rumored to be interested in going back to Los Angeles, but his
friends deny that, saying Baker has intense personal reasons dating
back to his playing days for turning down any future affiliation
with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   One rumor that refuses to go away is that the Sox are setting up
Jimy Williams to take a fall in order to clear the way for Alou.
Duquette is a big Alou fan, as is pitching coach Joe Kerrigan,
minor league field coordinator Dave Jauss, and ace Pedro Martinez.
Alou has told confidants that if he is fired by Expos owner Jeff
Loria, he'll sit home and collect the millions due him on his
contract. But he also has said privately that the Red Sox wanted to
interview him once before _ presumably when Williams was hired _
but the Expos denied Duquette permission.
</P>
<P>
   Alou's reputation is unmatched among his peers. White Sox
manager Jerry Manuel, who was a coach for Alou in Montreal, said
the experience was like going to Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals manager Tony La Russa also is a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``With no disrespect to Bobby Cox or Dusty Baker or whoever, if
we all had the same players, Felipe wins the most games,'' said La
Russa. ``I feel he's the best manager in this league. We know
better than not to be ready to play against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has a year left on his Red Sox contract, and he is a
lock to come back (if he wants to) if the Red Sox advance to the
postseason for a third straight year. But those ridiculous stories
about Williams's refusal to play Izzy Alcantara being so damaging
to the Sox' chances are indicative of how deep the rift between
Williams and Duquette has grown.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has to apologize to no one for the job he has done
here. And if the Sox are absurd enough to believe a change of
managers will be beneficial to the ball club, Williams's phone will
be ringing off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bleacher bums
</P>
<P>
   Shame on the pathetic fool sitting in the bleachers who, moments
after Florie was hit by Thompson's line drive, yelled, ``Hey, Beck,
you're next.'' . . . Oakland's rookie center fielder, Terrence
Long, told Boston native Howard Bryant of the San Jose Mercury News
that he was the target of racial epithets from the bleachers last
week . . . Grim doubleheader: Buster Olney, the Vermonter who
covers the Yankees for The New York Times, was a kid sitting about
20 rows from the field when Pole was struck by Muser's line drive
25 years ago . . . Sox players (not to mention a few press box
observers) have been reacting with hilarity at the wooden way
Fenway public address announcer Big Ed Brickley recites song titles
in the fans' daily voting for most popular tune (``Get DOWN On
It'') . . . To the question of whether Bret Saberhagen really
intends to come back next year after missing all of 2000, the
righthander has a ready answer: He already has begun the strength
and exercise program designed to get him back on the field next
spring. ``I won't have an offseason this year,'' said Saberhagen,
who is determined to take the time necessary for his shoulder to be
strong enough before he begins throwing again. ``This year, it was
rush, rush, rush, try to get back as soon as possible,'' he said.
``I want to give it a last go and see what happens. Spend two
months strengthening the shoulder without picking up a ball.'' . .
. As bad as his year was, Saberhagen says his close friend, Yankees
pitcher David Cone, had it worse. Cone endured a season-long slump
and then, just when it seemed he had righted himself, separated his
left shoulder last week. ``His year was a lot tougher than mine,''
Saberhagen said. ``I'm used to doing what I'm doing. I just didn't
get it done this year. The time frame just didn't work for us.''
Saberhagen said he isn't sure why Cone struggled so much this
season. ``It didn't seem like he was doing a whole bunch of things
wrong,'' Saberhagen said. ``If anything, I thought there might be
something wrong with his slider. Usually it's a bit sharper, but he
was leaving it up and over the plate more this year. A lot of it
becomes confidence, too. You get hit a few games in a row, you can
get in a rut. I'm sure he was hearing it from all sides, too.
George (Steinbrenner) and New York is a tough media market. And
then, when he finally gets things right, he gets hurt.'' . . .
Randy Johnson needs eight whiffs Sunday to become the 12th pitcher
in major league history to record 3,000 strikeouts. His first
victim was Orestes Destrade, then with the Pirates, on Sept. 5,
1988. Other milestone victims include Lance Parrish (No. 500),
Chuck Knoblauch (No. 1,000), Turner Ward (No. 1,500), Ben Grieve
(2,000), and Eric Davis (No. 2,500) . . . Chipper Jones of the
Braves has five home runs and a double in 15 career at-bats against
The Unit after his two-homer game Tuesday . . . That National
League Cy Young Award that was conceded to Johnson back in July
looks like it should end up in the hands of Billerica's Tom
Glavine, who will be bidding for his fifth 20-win season Sunday
afternoon against Montreal. At the All-Star break, when Glavine was
just 7-5, he didn't even figure in the trophy picture, as Johnson
was 14-2 with a 1.77 ERA and Glavine's teammate, Greg Maddux, was
9-2. Since then, Johnson has gone 3-4 and Maddux has won just five
of 11 starts. Glavine has won 12 of his last 13 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
