<SLUG> BC-OLY-TTN-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: TABLE TENNIS  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Mandarin Chinese, the term for table tennis translates to
``national ball,'' and the last Olympic tournament in Atlanta did
indeed bear a strong resemblance to a domestic competition as the
Chinese swept all four events: men's singles and doubles, and
women's singles and doubles. More domination is hardly out of the
question in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The gap between elite table tennis and Ping-Pong, the basement
variety of the game that the majority of us have sampled at some
stage, is as wide as the gap between a game of crazy eights and
world-class bridge.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   Same as in the basement. Matches are bet-of-five affairs and
games are won by the first player to reach 21. If a game is tied at
20, a player must win by two points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Two adversaries in the world championships once required more
than an hour to finish a single point. But table tennis is normally
a much more expeditious affair with its spinning, elusive serves
and aggressive topspin forehand drives. The objective is to keep an
opponent perpetually off balance by disguising shot direction and
producing rhythm shifts, sharp angles and drop shots.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   China's Liu Guoliang won the men's singles and doubles at the
1996 Games, and at age 24, he remains at the peak of his powers.
But the last year has been one of controversy and frustration.
Shortly after winning the men's world singles title last year, he
tested positive for the banned substance epitosterone. A legal and
medical marathon ensued, and Liu was finally cleared by the
International Table Tennis Federation in April. By then, he had
already lost to the 1992 Olympic champion Jan-Ove Waldner and his
Swedish compatriot Jorgen Persson as the Chinese were upset by the
Swedes in the world team championships. The women's singles
favorites are China's Wang Nan and her doubles partner, Li Ju.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2158EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7722 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-SCREENIN     09-09 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-SCREENING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCREENING IS STILL POROUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Whether or not the new blood-and-urine test for the
banned performance-enhancing drug EPO catches many cheaters in
Sydney, it's already been a deterrent. The Chinese last week yanked
an astounding 27 athletes from their team, all of them in endurance
events (distance running, rowing, swimming, and kayaking), where
abuse of erythropoietin is most rampant.
</P>
<P>
   If the test works as claimed, and insiders' estimates of EPO use
is anywhere near accurate, dozens of athletes should test positive
at these Olympics. But the record shows that virtually nobody gets
caught at the Games. After all the hype about state-of-the-art
testing, only two athletes (both women) were nailed in Atlanta. And
only 400 of the 10,000-plus athletes here will be tested for EPO.
</P>
<P>
   Though the new World Anti-Doping Agency is up and running, it
hasn't been in place long enough to make a difference. And until
it's completely independent from the International Olympic
Committee (vice president Dick Pound heads it), critics say, the
agency will never be effective.
</P>
<P>
   Though the IOC dismissed last week's 107-page report on Olympic
drug use from the National Center on Addiction and Substance Abuse
as hypocritical hectoring from the Americans, the report was
dead-on when it ripped the IOC and the international sports
federations for their ``crazy quilt of jurisdictions'' and
inconsistent policies for fighting doping.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the dopers have been winning the war for years. And
even if the EPO test is foolproof (and that's unclear), many
athletes reportedly have already switched to Hemopure, an
artificial blood substitute. And the IOC still has no test for
banned human growth hormones, which are believed to be widely used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, every performance in an endurance event is
suspect,'' former Olympic marathon champion Frank Shorter (who
chairs the new US anti-doping agency) told Time magazine last week.
``Things have to change, or we're going under. The Olympics will be
a freak show.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sunset for Samaranch
</P>
<P>
   It's swan-song time for IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch,
who is presiding over his final session this week after 20 years at
the top. The 80-year-old Samaranch, who took over from Lord
Killanin at the 1980 Games in Moscow, will formally step down at
next year's session _ in Moscow . . . Rave reviews for Sydney's
athletes' village, which Olympic insiders are calling the best
ever. The village, which cost $350 million to build, contains 1,000
houses and apartments and a dining hall that will serve 60,000
meals a day. ``It's not a village, it's a city,'' gushed Samaranch.
After the Games, it literally will be a city _ the suburb of
Newington . . . Though global TV viewership of these Olympics is
expected to be up by nearly 25 percent over 1996 (to a cumulative
3.7 billion), NBC is projecting a ratings decrease of roughly the
same amount, from a 21.5 to as low as 17.5. The reasons: The Games
aren't in the United States, they're two months later than usual,
and all the coverage will be on tape. Still, the network figures to
turn a small profit on its $700 million investment . . . The US
softball team's unbeaten streak is at 107 after the squad went 60-0
in its exhibition tour, mostly against local all-stars. The
Americans, who are favored to win gold again, haven't lost since
the 1998 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Splendid sendoff
</P>
<P>
   The US baseball team got a rousing adieu from Teddy Ballgame
himself before departing for the Games. Ted Williams talked to the
squad by speakerphone an hour before it boarded the plane in San
Diego. He told the players they should be proud to play for their
country _ and also offered some batting tips . . . Scratch that
idea of both Koreas marching together under the Olympic flag in
Friday's opening ceremonies. Though the South jumped at the offer
made by Samaranch during the countries' June summit, the North
never responded . . . How cold was it during the late Australian
winter? Cold enough that the turf on the soccer field in Canberra,
where the US men meet the Czechs on Wednesday, went into ``shock''
and had to be resodded . . . Phil Coles, the Australian IOC member
who was censured for his role in the Salt Lake bidding scandal and
had to quit the Sydney organizing committee, will be kept out of
the limelight at the Games. Though he'll get to present medals,
they'll probably be at kayaking, the event in which he was a
three-time Olympian . . . The comeback kid on the US Olympic team
is mountain biker Travis Brown, 30, who made the squad despite
breaking a shin when he slammed into a tree in Mexico in April.
After missing the 1996 Games with a broken collarbone, Brown wasn't
going to be kept out of another. So he pedaled an exercise bike
with one leg, went on training spins before he could walk, and was
back competing by June with his shin held together by screws . . .
For all the fuss over swimmer Jenny Thompson's pseudo-topless pose
for Sports Illustrated, so many Australian athletes are posing in
the nude that it's become ho-hum down under. The latest to bare
all: 18 of the Aussie paralympians, who wear little more than body
paint for their calendar . . . Now that Nova Peris-Kneebone has
made the Australian track and field team, half the country's
women's 4x400 relay could be made up of Aborigines. Peris-Kneebone,
who finished second to Cathy Freeman in the 400 meters at trials,
became the first of her race to win an Olympic gold medal when she
played on the field hockey team in Atlanta . . . Though they
expected jacked-up prices during the Games, Australian fans are
fuming over having to pay twice as much for meat pies, which they
gobble like hot dogs at sporting events. By US ballpark standards,
though, even the higher price is fairly cheap _ only $2.40.
</P>
<P>
   Material from wire services, the US Olympic Committee,
international federations, national sports bodies, and interviews
was used in compiling this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
