<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: TEAM HANDBALL  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long after the Canadian James Naismith dreamed up a winter-time
diversion called basketball, the Europeans went to work codifying
another winter-time diversion. Initially an 11-on-11 outdoor game
like soccer, team handball was first played at the Olympics in 1936
in Berlin at the Germans' request.
</P>
<P>
   By the time it returned to the Olympics in the 1972 Munich
Games, it had moved indoors and become a seven-on-seven affair. So
it has remained, and though it is still a relatively popular sport
in Europe, this routinely spectacular game has the lowest of
profiles on this side of the Atlantic (NBC will not be getting up
close and personal with the handball players). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   As in Atlanta, there are 12 men's teams in the field, but the
women's field has been increased from eight to 10. A quarterfinal
round has been added in both tournaments, which means that the top
four teams in each pool will advance. This also means pool play
counts for little, particularly in the case of the women (only two
teams will be eliminated).
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   An amalgam of indoor soccer and basketball, goals are scored in
team handball by players throwing a relatively small ball into a 3
meter-by-2 meter goal minded by a goalkeeper. Team handball is much
more high-scoring than soccer; much more low-scoring than
basketball. Croatia beat Sweden, 27-26, in the last Olympic men's
final; Denmark beat South Korea, 37-33, in the women's final. No
Americans will be scoring in Sydney: Neither the American men nor
the American women qualified.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
