<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-NOTREDAME-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTRE DAME CAN'T PEN STORYBOOK FINISH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ It came, as expected, on a sprint by Nebraska
quarterback Eric Crouch into the left corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But that was about the only thing that went according to script
Saturday at Notre Dame Stadium for the No. 1-ranked Cornhuskers.
</P>
<P>
   In a contest that tested their skills but probably damaged their
standing, it took a 7-yard TD sprint by Crouch in overtime to give
the Huskers a 27-24 victory over No. 23 Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch's winning score came after the Irish had taken the lead
for the first time on a 29-yard field goal by Nick Setta on their
overtime possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do believe in themselves,'' said Nebraska coach Frank
Solich, who watched in dismay as Notre Dame returned a kickoff and
a punt for scores in the second half to wipe out a 21-7 Husker
lead. ``There was never a doubt in their mind that they would get
it done.''
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the game had a strange feel. Nebraska, making
its first appearance in South Bend in 52 years, came out for
warmups to cheers from more than 30,000 Husker fans who had
traveled 10 hours across I-80, scoffing up so many tickets that
Notre Dame Stadium looked more like Lincoln's Memorial Stadium,
with many in the sellout crowd of 80,232 wearing red.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskers played the role of favorite at the start, with
Crouch rushing for the first of his three touchdowns on a textbook
62-yard option run that split the seams of the Irish defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Notre Dame, which came into the game a rare two-touchdown
underdog at home, responded, going 82 yards in 11 plays, with Tony
Fisher picking up the final 2 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish, using a game plan that Knute Rockne would have loved,
did not throw a pass during the drive.
</P>
<P>
   Taking its cue, Nebraska answered with a 65-yard march that
consumed 15 plays, 14 on the ground, with Crouch going the final
yard for a 14-7 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like a typical Nebraska win was in order when the
Huskers upped the lead to 21-7 in the third quarter on a 28-yard
run by tailback Dan Alexander.
</P>
<P>
   But then a potentially dangerous and fatal flaw _ if the Huskers
intend to compete for the national championship _ showed its face.
</P>
<P>
   In a pair of highlight-film plays, Notre Dame climbed back into
the game when Julius Jones took the kickoff following Alexander's
TD run and returned it 100 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   That was followed four minutes later by an 83-yard punt return
by Joey Getherall for a touchdown. Suddenly, with 12:48 left in
regulation, it was 21-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that point on, I never thought we wouldn't win the
game,'' said Notre Dame coach Bob Davie.
</P>
<P>
   The final seconds of regulation were as bizzare as the rest of
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   After the Irish had forced Nebraska to punt, Notre Dame had a
chance to win in regulation. But Davie chose the conservative
approach, staying on the ground as the clock rolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question it was the right thing to do it that way,''
said Davie, taking into account quarterback Arnaz Battle's anemic
passing performance (3 of 15, 40 yards). ``I wanted to get that
game into overtime to give us a chance. I did not want to put the
football in the air at that time. I would do it 10 out of 10
times.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish had the ball first in overtime, but after getting to
the Nebraska 8, the Huskers toughened and Setta kicked his field
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Nebraska's turn. Faced with the ruination of their
season, the Huskers took care of business, with Crouch sprinting
into the end zone for the winning TD.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing you want to do is get the ball in the end
zone,'' said Crouch. ``When you see that daylight, the overtime,
the situation, it was a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irish's feelings of disappointment were lessened by their
overall effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our opportunities to win this game,'' said Davie.
``It's disappointing. It was the kind of game you liked being in
that situation at the end of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Irish did not win a game they thought they could
have and arguably should have won. ``It's a bottom-line business,''
said Davie. ``And the bottom line is we didn't win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
