<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7834 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-NBANOTES-CONTENDE     09-09 1702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-CONTENDERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTENTION COULD EASE DISCONTENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Poets, writers, and conventional wisdom tell us that spring is
the season for rebirth and renewal. The NBA runs by a different
calendar, as we've witnessed in the last couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In Portland and Los Angeles, two individuals trying to resurrect
careers and rehabilitate images said they were ready to do both.
There was no accompanying laugh track in either case, only a
certain sense of deja vu.
</P>
<P>
   You can usually bank on some form of athletic contrition _ dare
we say honesty? _ at the start of training camp every year. A
player will own up to the fact that he had a lousy year, that he
was hurt, that he was mad at the coach, whatever. The other time
for such rare candor is when a player changes teams. That is what
we have now in the cases of Shawn Kemp and Isaiah Rider.
</P>
<P>
   Kemp, who basically cheated the Cavaliers for the last two years
when he stopped taking care of himself, stood before reporters in
Portland and said, ``It's going to be the rebirth of my career.''
Never mind that only a few months earlier, in his annual exit
interview with his then-bosses in Cleveland, he pledged to
``reinvent'' himself. Or, that three years earlier, he told
Cleveland reporters, ``I just look forward to coming here and
starting up another half of my career and playing better than I did
the previous eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cavs general manager Jim Paxson, ``Shawn was unhappy in
Seattle. The Cavs made a commitment to him. That same commitment
wasn't coming back. So (trading him) was the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Down I-5 a bit, in Los Angeles, the world champion Lakers
unveiled their latest acquisition, Rider, in a teleconference.
Rider basically has been a human carcinogen everywhere he's been,
including Atlanta under the notoriously even-tempered Lenny
Wilkens. He's been with Minnesota, Portland, Atlanta, and, now, the
Lakers. You guessed it; he's been reborn and found his niche,
finally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking long-term, not short-term,'' Rider told reporters
after signing a one-year deal. ``I'm looking for a new start.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he talked to coach Phil Jackson and was told, ``I
won't give you any problems if you don't give me any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   That, too, is old news.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said, ``We got ourselves a young man who's very
talented, who wants to make some changes in perception in how he's
been looked at as a ballplayer. He's given us some real good verbal
promises that he will do what it takes to do whatever he has to do
as a player and whatever spot he has to play in.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounded very familiar to Stan Kasten, the president of the
Hawks. As he put it, ``I would bet that you could replay what he
said out there and what he said here and you couldn't tell which
was which.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks acquired Rider from Portland last summer, then he tore
apart the team and was eventually released. But when you have his
talent, and his personality, there always will be a market. The
Lakers also got him for the NBA minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite what he did to us, he's a very likable, intelligent
guy,'' Kasten said. ``And I think it's a good deal for the Lakers.
He does have All-Star talent. And if it doesn't work out, you can
always release him. What have you lost?''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks had lost their season by the time they had to release
Rider. The Cavs lost theirs as well, and also saw diminishing
returns from a player they hoped would make them a contender in the
watered-down Eastern Conference. Kemp's salary and weight, however,
were on the increase.
</P>
<P>
   But, as both players said recently, those days are gone. They
are testament to the NBA axiom that talent never goes unnoticed or
unrewarded and that previous ``lapses'' are unimportant, if not
altogether meaningless. And as we've seen with Latrell Sprewell,
even the presumably incorrigible can be rehabilitated.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Backtracking
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks, by the way, soon could have a new but familiar name
in their front office: Dominique Wilkins. The Hawks' career leader
in five categories is talking with his original NBA employer about
a job in basketball operations. Wilkins played 12 years with
Atlanta, then was dealt to the Clippers during the 1994-95 season,
never to return. He also played with Boston, San Antonio, and
Orlando. Romantics say he never should have left Atlanta. ``He
wouldn't if his agent hadn't demanded a Larry Johnson contract,''
Kasten said . . . Many major league baseball players have pictures
of children and other family members in or around their lockers.
Red Sox outfielder Darren Lewis has one of Kevin Garnett. The two
have never met. Lewis is simply a fan of the Timberwolves forward.
``I have been following him ever since he came into the league and
try to see him during the season when they come to Oakland,'' Lewis
said. ``I love that he's always working to improve his game. Every
year I see him, he comes back with something new to his game. I
like that. I also like that he's proven people wrong about coming
out of high school.'' . . . The Bulls now can market their new
``M&AMP;M boys'' in Ron Mercer and Brad Miller. Just what they wanted
all along, right? The just-signed Miller stated that he'd never
played for a losing program, in high school, college, or the pros.
All good things etc. The Hornets aren't exactly losing sleep over
yet another defection due to monetary matters. They feel that
rookie center Jamaal Magliore could be even better, and they also
have several other big fellas on the roster . . . Rick Pitino did
an online chat this past week in conjunction with the new Celtics
Web site. He offered no eye-openers, but he did say that if he
could add one player to his team, it would be Tim Duncan. ``He has
all the attributes I like. He passes from the post. He plays
defense.'' Pitino added that he has no more books on his plate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Extra cheese
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of plates, Celtics GM Chris Wallace took Chris Carr out
to lunch _ to Papa Gino's. What, is Paul Gaston watching the
expense accounts? ``Not at all,'' laughed Wallace. ``Chris said he
knew of this great pizza and pasta place, so I said, `Fine.' ''
Wallace reports that Kris Clack, the team's second-round draft pick
in 1999 and participant in July's summer league, is exploring
options overseas. Frankly, the Celtics hope he goes because their
roster is full (16 players) and the 2-3 position is overloaded.
``It would be tough to fit him in,'' Wallace said. The Celtics
would retain Clack's rights if he went overseas. If he reported to
camp, the team would lose his rights if it had to release him . . .
The latest on Iakovos ``Jake'' Tsakalidis: It appears that the
Suns, who took him in the first round of the draft, and his
European team, AEK, will take the matter to arbitration in London
this month. AEK says it is not interested in a settlement,
believing it has Tsakalidis firmly under contract. The team owner
also has plenty of drachmas, mainly because he is one of the
largest yogurt distributors in Europe. There's also some bad blood
involved. AEK is upset about the ``Free Jake'' T-shirts that the
Suns unveiled, as well as Tsakalidis going public with his desire
to play in the NBA without running it first by his Greek team.
Tsakalidis, meanwhile, is working out in the Phoenix area and has
the NBA on his side in the arbitration process. One possible twist:
AEK may present evidence that Tsakalidis was 23 at the time of the
draft, which would be over the age limit for foreign players. The
Suns, and everyone else in the NBA, operated under the assumption
that he was 21 and that, too, was Tsakalidis's stance when he met
with league officials and Players Association officials prior to
the draft. In other words, the NBA doesn't care how old he is . . .
Chris Gatling may not be happy about being dealt to Cleveland, but
the sting already has been eased financially: He is paid in the
summer in one lump sum. His ``hesitation'' at jumping to join the
Cavs may well be tied more to a desire for an extension, not an
unusual request for a David Falk client . . . The agent for Pervis
Ellison reports that his client is healthy and eager to play this
season. Honest. Right now, however, it's a case of unrequited
affection, which should surprise no one. ``Yes, it's a bit of a
sell job,'' conceded Bill Strickland. ``But the best way for Pervis
to sell himself is by getting into a camp and having a team see
him. I know he has a reputation about being injured. But I have not
heard anyone question his talent. It's simply a matter of keeping
him on the floor.'' Strickland believes someone will extend an
invitation to Ellison, who is only 33 and, need we note, does not
have a lot of miles on the tires. In fact, Strickland said Ellison
agreed to go on the injured list last March _ at the request of a
teammate _ with what everyone knew was a phony back injury so
Walter McCarty could be activated. ``That was to his detriment,''
Strickland said. ``That didn't help his reputation. He made a
personal sacrifice. We'll see what happens. He's healthy now,
working out, enthusiastic and I'm hopeful and optimistic we can
find something for him.'' Stranger things have happened . . . We
would be remiss not to pass along the following comments of Tom
Wilson, president of the Detroit Pistons. Talking about the team's
image problem (season-ticket renewals are way down), he told Chris
McCosky of the Detroit News that Grant Hill, ``as great a player as
he was, wasn't a reflection of this city.'' (Uh, Tom, you play in
the suburbs.) ``This is a gritty city. Even white-collar people
think they are blue-collar people. We respond to Isiah Thomas, Bill
Laimbeer, Kirk Gibson. Guys who you knew wanted to do anything to
win.'' And Hill? ``Grant is a fluid, elegant basketball player. I
am not sure this city responded to that.'' Hill's first visit to
his former haunt is not until March 4. NBC has the game.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
