<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-FLORIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIE HAS SEVERE INJURY TO HIS EYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Red Sox pitcher Bryce Florie underwent surgery Saturday morning
for a severe eye injury, and following the nearly two-hour
procedure, the team physician said the 30-year-old reliever has
only a ``guarded'' prognosis for normal vision returning to his
right eye.
</P>
<P>
   Florie suffered what Dr. Bill Morgan called ``macular trauma''
to the right eye after being hit by a Ryan Thompson line drive in
the ninth inning of Friday night's 4-0 loss to the Yankees. Florie
will spend several days in the hospital and may face two more
operations. But seven words stood out in the four-paragraph release
from the Red Sox: ``the prognosis for reasonable vision is
guarded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible, just horrible,'' said Pedro Martinez, who, when
asked for his reaction, pounded his chest with his fist. ``I have
trouble talking about it. It's awful. You just pray to God that
he's healthy and that he can get back to being in baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Tim Wakefield, ``It's heartbreaking. It really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams said simply, ``I hope everything works out
for him physically so he won't have any further impairment.''
</P>
<P>
   No one, however, was more upset than Thompson, who was not aware
of the severity of the prognosis until after Saturday's 5-3 New
York victory. He had called the Red Sox clubhouse earlier in the
day to offer his best wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be hard for me, very hard, especially if the
guy isn't going to be able to see,'' Thompson said. ``I don't want
to take food off someone's table. We're all warriors and
competitors, but I don't want to end somebody's career. I have a
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgery, performed by Dr. Subhransu Ray at Massachusetts Eye
and Ear Infirmary, relieved pressure in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said there also was damage to the retina, which will be
assessed over the next two to three days to determine whether
surgery is needed. He said the retina was not detached, although
there was bleeding behind it. He also said Florie did not have
``entrapment of the eye within the socket,'' which he characterized
as good news.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the macular trauma, Florie also sustained three
fractures in the eye socket area (nasal, medial wall, and socket
floor) that will require surgery. The timetable for those
procedures will be addressed in the next three to five days unless
there is further swelling. In that case, doctors could wait another
two weeks, Morgan said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman at Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary told the
Associated Press that Florie was in stable condition and good
spirits. The hospital subsequently referred all calls on Florie to
the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The news was eerily familiar to Thompson, who 10 years ago got
hit in the face by a pitch from Russell Springer while playing in
the minor leagues in Dunedin, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fractured my eye socket and broke my nose in seven places,''
Thompson said. ``The doctor told me my face looked like someone had
crushed a Ritz cracker. So I sort of know how Bryce feels. It
wasn't very pretty. Mentally, it took me at least two years to come
back from it. But they threw me back into the lineup a week later
so I wouldn't be too screwed up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish Bryce well,'' he went on. ``When I get the chance,
I'll give him a call.''
</P>
<P>
   Florie never lost consciousness after getting hit Friday night
and was taken off the field in a golf cart, a towel covering his
face. He was seen briefly at the hospital that night by pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan, who spoke to Florie's father before the pitcher
went in for X-rays and surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty bad,'' Kerrigan said. ``It was hard to look at.
His face was really swollen. His lips were swollen. His right eye
was completely shut. He could talk, but it was an effort for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan said he figured Thompson's live drive was traveling at
110-115 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually saw the blood fly,'' Kerrigan said.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game, Williams said he chatted briefly with
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to do his job, trying to hit him hard, and
Florie was trying to get him out,'' said Williams. ``Then something
like that happens. It kind of puts things in perspective in life,
doesn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night's appearance was the 29th of the season for Florie,
who had an 0-4 record and 4.56 ERA. All of the appearances were out
of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Florie broke into the majors with the San Diego Padres in 1994
and also pitched for Milwaukee and Detroit. The Red Sox acquired
him on July 31, 1999, from the Tigers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
