<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-OLDTIES-BOS &LR;      09-09 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-OLDTIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS FEEL CONNECTED TO OLD TIES WITH PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Shakespeare would be better than sportswriters
at untangling the knots that link these two football families, the
Patriots and the Jets. The Montagues and Capulets may have feuded,
but that was eons before video cameras, sports talk radio, and
hordes of sportswriters eager to pounce on every twist of a plot
that has endless turns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, year by year, the knots that bind _ and blind _ these
football families grow knottier and knottier. The feud has
implications far from the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this recent scene:
</P>
<P>
   Al Groh had just finished a press conference at the Jets'
cramped little headquarters on the campus of Hofstra University.
Groh was much more relaxed than on the previous day, when the coach
had become irked at the endless questions from a large New York
media crowd about what he, time and again, called ``the soap
opera.'' Now the TV cameras were gone, and Groh was relaxing for a
few moments before getting back to work preparing his team for
Monday night's game against the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember that game?'' Groh was saying. ``Remember how we had a
big lead early in that game?''
</P>
<P>
   Clarification is needed. The ``we'' Groh was referring to was
not the New York Jets but the New England Patriots. The ``we''
referred to a beleaguered New England defense on the afternoon of
Oct. 6, 1996, in Baltimore. The Ravens quarterback, a certain
proficient passer by the name of Vinny Testaverde, had shredded the
Patriots' poor and porous defense in a wild game ultimately won by
New England, 46-38.
</P>
<P>
   But ``we'' had a big early lead, Groh went on, ``and the thing
about Vinny is if you let him throw a lot of balls, he's going to
complete a lot of balls. And I think if we had not been so far
ahead early, and not had to defend 25 or 30 passes in a row from
Vinny, we would not have been as stressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   But Groh was not done.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``that game probably had a lot to do with
Vinny being here.''
</P>
<P>
   Here.
</P>
<P>
   With ``us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, it's true,'' said Groh. ``When he became available a
couple of summers later, we remembered what he had done to us that
game. We knew what Vinny could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another weave of the tangled web. Vinny Testaverde is
quarterback of the New York Jets because of what he did one
long-ago afternoon to the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   And more weaves intertwine.
</P>
<P>
   During the Patriots' 1996 Super Bowl season, Groh was New
England's linebackers coach. The defense started to come around in
midseason after that horrible game against the Ravens, another
against Jacksonville, and still another against Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' Groh was saying, ``Bill had joined us that
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill.
</P>
<P>
   As in Bill Belichick, the extraordinary defensive mind with whom
Groh coached for so long with the Giants, Browns, Patriots, and
Jets. His close friend, but now the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   And now the words were flowing from Groh about how he and
Belichick, now the Patriots' head coach, and Bill Parcells, then
the Patriots' head coach and later the Jets' head man, had molded a
team that jelled in December and January, ``and my sweetest memory
of Foxborough was that Jacksonville game (for the AFC title). That
was a great, great day, and we played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Groh went on, ``I remember when the AFC trophy was presented to
the team and when I finally got my hand on it. Willie McGinest had
it, and he and a bunch of players were walking around the perimeter
of the stadium holding it up, showing it to the fans. Then I just
kind of went down to the sidelines and I just sort of stood there
and watched the whole scene _ the joy of the fans and the pride of
the players. And I'm just watching it and I remember saying to
myself, `In four years, to have gone from the worst record in the
league to going to the Super Bowl, it's so great.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed down there and watched it all. No one will ever need
to show me a movie or a picture of that day. I've still got it
clearly in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   There still is warmth in Groh's heart for Patriots defenders
such as McGinest, Chris Slade, Ty Law, Lawyer Milloy, and Ted
Johnson. Especially Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every once in a while,'' Groh says, ``there'd be a message on
my machine from Ted: `Coach, this is Ted. Nice job. You're doing
well.' And I'd call him up and say, `Ted, how are you doing?' I
wouldn't be doing any tampering, just seeing how he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did not play well in last Sunday's opener against Tampa
Bay, clearly rusty from missing the entire exhibition season with a
hamstring injury. Groh has seen the films and would like to get on
the phone again to tell Johnson his game will be back soon. But of
course, Groh can't.
</P>
<P>
   The ``we'' have become ``they.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Ted feels like I do,'' said Groh. ``Uneasy. Not on a
personal level, but on a professional level.''
</P>
<P>
   The chain of events that resulted in Groh becoming head coach of
the Jets in January _ Parcells resigning, and Belichick then
walking away on what was to be his first day on the job to take the
Patriots' position instead _ has been much written about. But just
as Groh will say he feels comfortable with Parcells, now director
of football operations, still working at the Jets' headquarters _
Groh says he frequently talks with Parcells about personnel and X's
and O's, and he'd be foolish not to take advantage of such a
bountiful resource _ there is another lingering presence a few
steps down the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jets locker room this past week, players talked openly of
how much they miss and respect the coach of the enemy, Belichick,
just as Patriots players three years ago said many of the same
words about the then-new coach of the Jets, Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Safety Victor Green called Belichick ``a genius.'' Cornerback
Aaron Glenn described the New England coach as ``a mastermind in
drawing up defensive schemes.'' And Testaverde recalled how
Belichick had endured the fiercest of storms in Cleveland by
benching Browns icon Bernie Kosar, eventually replacing him with
Testaverde.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a big game,'' Testaverde said. ``I don't
think either team's going to go out and just do the same old things
we've done against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily for the Jets, a home opener against an opponent
without an offensive line might be cause for salivation. Yet Jet
after Jet last week talked of how much they respect Belichick, all
having seen the schemes of their former defensive coordinator
frustrate opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Other old twists of the feud have loosened up as well. Jets
backup quarterback Ray Lucas, for one, talked of how pleasant it
was for him to go up to Foxborough last season and lead his team to
a 24-17 win ``because the coach on the other side (Pete Carroll)
gave up on me and didn't think I could play.'' Carroll is gone now,
however, and, said Lucas, ``I still have a lot of friends on that
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the other side of the soap opera.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Brisby, for instance, made a half-hearted effort to
satisfy media questions about whether he thirsts to show up the
Patriots, who cut him last month. The wide receiver said he
couldn't believe Drew Bledsoe said he had lost speed going down the
sidelines, and he wanted to show New England it had made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Brisby was much more passionate about how he misses receiver
Troy Brown. ``Troy and I were together all the time,'' said Brisby.
``You'd never see me and Troy apart. If you saw Troy, you saw me.''
</P>
<P>
   When he got home from Green Bay last Sunday and learned Brown
had run back a punt for a TD against Tampa Bay and played an
outstanding game, Brisby ached to do what he knew he couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to call Troy up and congratulate him,'' said Brisby.
``But I couldn't. Not this week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
