</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY POINTS ON BRUINS' COMPASS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Say what you will about the Bruins having holdouts yet again
(it's epidemic around the league), there are some aspects of the
club that have improved. Once the three arrive (and it's a
certainty that at least Joe Thornton and Sergei Samsonov will be
here, with Anson Carter a longer shot), the team will be
competitive in the Eastern Conference. A contender? Too soon to
say. Many things have to go right, all players have to reach their
potential, and the negativity surrounding last year needs to be put
to rest.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are the critical components that have to come
together if the Black and Gold are going to succeed in 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   --The team concept: For reasons no one can adequately explain,
there was none last season. Perhaps it was the multitude of
injuries, perhaps there were some wrong elements, perhaps it was
that nebulous term ``chemistry'' or lack of same. Whatever the
reason, this edition is going to have to figure out a way to master
it and embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need attitude, personality, approach, and accountability
to each other to become a team,'' said president/general manager
Harry Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, I feel comfortable with the individuals we have
but I'm waiting to see how we turn out as a team. I always felt we
had a team and that they had the attitude, they've always shown me
that. They didn't show me that last year.''
</P>
<P>
   --A good start: Everyone remembers the 0-5-4 beginning of last
year. It wasn't even the goalies' fault. In Byron Dafoe's absence,
John Grahame and Rob Tallas played very well, but the rest of the
club faltered. This year, with so much on the line, it can't happen
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first road trip is obviously very important, just like it
was last year,'' said Dafoe, who won't be sitting home in a
contract dispute this year. ``We need to get off to a good start
and get confidence back in this hockey club and in this city. It's
so much easier to continue playing the season when you look at the
standings and you're 10-5 instead of 5-10 just because when you hit
that ice before every game, you just brim with confidence knowing
you're one of the top teams in the league rather than clawing up
from the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   A strong start also is important for coach Pat Burns, who was
embattled last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the way things went last year and the heat Pat did take,
obviously we're all thankful he's back,'' said Dafoe. ``For him, as
well as the team, a good start is crucial just to get the pressure
off all of us. If we go 7-2 in our first nine games, we're putting
last year behind us, and who cares? It has nothing to do with this
year. That's why the first 5-10 games really are important.''
</P>
<P>
   --Mastering the basics, which include faceoffs: the Bruins were
dreadful in the circle last year because they were center-poor.
This year shouldn't be like that with Jason Allison healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I talked about, unfair criticism, last year,''
said Burns. ``At the end of the year, we just wanted to see
somebody's head roll so bad. It was unfair. We had nobody to take
faceoffs last year. We had one bona fide centerman last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian Rolston is not a centerman. We had him playing it. We
had Mikko Eloranta playing it. He is not a centerman. We had Robbie
DiMaio. We had one guy who could take faceoffs at one particular
part of the year and that was Joe. You're asking a 20-year-old kid
to go out there and win every faceoff and win the hockey game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people weren't paying attention to what was going on.
That's probably the worst thing. These kids tried hard but it's
difficult for a guy coming in from the American League to step into
the National League on a completely unexperienced team and expect
them to haul that team around.''
</P>
<P>
   --Size: The players lost to injuries were crucial in not only
skills but size. This edition, which has added mammoth defenseman
Peter Popovic and tough forward Lee Goren, among others, isn't
going to get pushed around. Last season, as Burns put it, there was
no one between the opponent and the Bruins' net. No one got in
anyone's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have size,'' said Burns. ``This team didn't hit
worth hell last year because we didn't have anybody to do it. I see
things like Joe Hulbig going around hitting people _ that's what we
want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't run out of bounds in this sport,'' Sinden said.
``You've got to know that some time or other you're going to get
caught between the boards and another player. If you watch the
playoffs, that's the way all the teams play. That's the way we've
got to play.''
</P>
<P>
   --Better team defense: Don Sweeney was the only blue-liner who
had a decent season last year. Some were burdened by injuries (Kyle
McLaren), some were worn down from being asked to do too much (Ray
Bourque), and some just looked confused (Hal Gill). Burns said he
is expecting Gill to come back strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to be a physical player this year,'' said Burns. ``If
he thinks he's going to finesse the puck around the rink, he's got
another thing coming. I watched him (Friday) and I saw things I saw
from him last year _ overhandling the puck. He came in here and
made the team because he kept things simple. He's got to use his
size, too. He's smart enough to come around and be aware of that.''
</P>
<P>
   --Additions: There are plenty, most notably Paul Coffey. He has
the credentials, certainly. He has the health now and he can sure
skate. Signing him was worth the gamble. Forward Andrei Kovalenko
should add something to the mix; he said he's expecting this to be
his best season ever. The Bruins will also have a healthy goalie.
Dafoe is back and says he'll be on top of things come opening
night. Sinden said he and Grahame could be among the best tandems
in the league if Dafoe plays like he did two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   So, how will it all come together?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make a team out of them,'' said Sinden. ``And
that's the chore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr drops anchor
</P>
<P>
   Flames goalie Grant Fuhr elected to retire after 19 NHL seasons
and will join Calgary as a goaltending coach. The 37-year-old Fuhr
won five Stanley Cups with Edmonton in seven years (1984-90), and
his departure leaves Coffey and Mark Messier as the only active
players left from that dynasty. Fuhr's frail knee just wouldn't let
him continue, and a Caribbean cruise with other sports stars made
him sure about his desire to end his playing career. ``The bottom
line was the knee would not do it anymore,'' said Fuhr. ``(The
Flames) let me make my choice. On the cruise, I got a chance to
talk to Steve Carlton, Ozzie Smith, and Harry Carson and other guys
and that was good. Everyone wants to leave on their terms. No one
wants to be forced out, so getting a chance to talk to them made it
easier.'' . . . There has been enough turmoil in Philadelphia with
the Eric Lindros and John LeClair sagas, so it made sense that
management would attempt to calm the upheaval by agreeing to terms
on a two-year deal with 23-year-old goalie Brian Boucher, who is
coming off an impressive rookie campaign. Owner Ed Snider joined
the negotiations late last week in an effort to get it done. The
Flyers are banking a lot on Boucher, with veteran John
Vanbiesbrouck having been traded to the Islanders. ``Brian played
such a big role in the success we had in the second half of the
season and in the playoffs that he's obviously very important to
us,'' said general manager Bob Clarke. ``With his age and his
relative inexperience, he couldn't afford to miss training camp, so
it's nice to get the contract done.'' LeClair, meanwhile, wants a
long-term deal and has given the team until midnight Sunday night
to get it done. If an agreement isn't reached, LeClair said he'll
play out his one-year contract (for a $7 million salary awarded in
arbitration) and become an unrestricted free agent next summer.
LeClair said he won't negotiate with the team during the season and
won't re-sign with the Flyers next summer, so this is their shot to
keep him. The other option is to trade him to a team that would
give him a long-term deal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coyote circling back
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how well goalie Nikolai Khabibulin
plays this year after a season away from the NHL. It appears
there's a good chance Khabibulin will be back with the Phoenix
Coyotes after sitting out last season in a contract dispute. Wayne
Gretzky, part of the new Phoenix ownership group, has said he would
like to get Khabibulin back in the fold. The goalie practiced last
week with his teammates for the first time in more than a year.
``With a commitment on his part, we'd like to get Khabby signed and
we're going to get Khabby signed,'' said Gretzky. ``We've had some
early positive conversations with his representative and that's
where we are now.'' . . . Seems like a common theme these days:
players on the outside looking in as training camp gets under way.
San Jose has more than a half-dozen restricted free agents still
haggling for deals. The Sabres' big ticket is center Michael Peca.
Word out of Buffalo is that the sides are vastly apart and that
Peca is seeking something in the neighborhood of $4 million a
season . . . The climate appears no better in New Jersey, home of
the Stanley Cup champions. Two crucial players are missing from
training camp: forward Jason Arnott and defenseman Scott
Niedermayer. Each is seeking $4 million a year, while the club is
willing to pay Arnott $2.5 million and Niedermayer about $3.5
million . . . One of the more poignant stories coming out of Bruins
camp comes from 21-year-old defenseman Denis Timofeev, a Moscow
native who was Boston's seventh pick in 1997. At the end of last
year, when he was playing in Greenville of the East Coast League,
Timofeev's family home in Russia burned to the ground. When the
blaze broke out, his parents were sound asleep, but the family dog
woke them and they escaped to safety. Tragically, the animal didn't
survive . . . The New York Rangers have a new GM in Glen Sather, a
new coach in Ron Low, and quite a few of the same players. A key
one _ goalie Mike Richter _ likely won't be ready for opening night
because of a left knee injury. Richter tore the anterior cruciate
ligament during last season's All-Star skills competition and
underwent surgery in April after it was clear the Rangers were not
going to the postseason. Low said he's expecting it will be late
next month before Richter is ready to go. ``It's something that the
doctors are going to have to have a big part in,'' said Low.
``We'll likely talk to them in training camp when we do the
physicals to see how far he has come along.'' . . . There isn't
much news to report with regard to Lindros, who remains the
property of the Flyers despite the prevailing wisdom that he'll
never play for them again. Lindros is in Ontario, continuing to
recover from multiple concussions. The belief is that once he's
healthier, he will be traded. It could be January before he's ready
to resume playing. The Flyers have taken steps to move on. ``This
team will play good,'' predicted Clarke. ``We're not going to roll
over and die because Eric Lindros isn't here. No one player can
replace a player of Lindros's stature but you hope the group
strength is going to be enough. Years ago, the NHL marketing
decided it would be `Wayne Gretzky and LA' and `Eric Lindros and
the Flyers.' Eric was put in that position whether he wanted to be
there or not. We never felt that way. We feel the strength of the
organization is the team.'' . . . 25 days to opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
