<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 22:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7838 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-VIKINGSB     09-09 2474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-VIKINGSBIRK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIMSON AND PURPLE BLEND NICELY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matt Birk isn't making use of his economics degree from Harvard
exactly the way he'd planned, but at least he's found some use for
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings' starting center is very likely the only
NFL player doing a weekly radio spot in which he dispenses stock
tips and investment advice. This he does on KFAN, a Minneapolis-St.
Paul area radio station, on a show called ``Matt's Money.'' To date
Matt hasn't made much money, because he's a former sixth-round
draft choice who commanded little attention when the Vikings
selected him three years ago. But that was then and this is now,
and now is his time in the center of the Vikings' offensive line, a
position he assumed this summer after the defection of two-time Pro
Bowl center Jeff Christy to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really wasn't the plan,'' Birk said. ``All the money I
spent on that degree. Someday I hope I'll use it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Birk keeps playing the way he's been playing, he may use his
economics expertise to renegotiate his contract, because
6-foot-4-inch, 304-pound, athletically gifted starting centers are
hard to find _ and finding them in Cambridge is probably hardest of
all. Yet that's where the St. Paul native ended up after two years
of high school football and a lifetime of academic interest, and
that's where the Vikings found him in 1998 long after ESPN's
coverage of the draft had ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heck, I was surprised to play in college, let alone the NFL,
so I was a little surprised to be drafted,'' Birk said. ``I only
started playing football in the 10th grade to be with my friends.
My family is not a football family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball is the only sport recognized in my household, which
is kind of nice because if I go there for a free meal or to get my
laundry done I don't have to talk football. I think they're
enjoying the ride right now, but I know when football is over,
they'll be more proud of me for what I do next.''
</P>
<P>
   What Birk does next may have to wait for quite some time,
however. After two years as a backup to Christy, Birk was thrust
into the competition to replace his former roommate this summer and
won the position quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, though, Birk wasn't expecting to win anything
but a plane ticket back home and a chance to begin what he expected
would be his real career on Wall Street after an unusual summer job
in Mankato, Minn., training camp home of the Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rookie I had that Harvard label and I wanted to drop
it,'' Birk said. ``When I came in as a rookie, I knew chances were
I wouldn't make the team. Not many late-round picks from Harvard
make it, but I don't focus on results, I focus on effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``My rookie year there were so many ups and downs. You have more
bad days than good. Every day you doubt yourself. Then you have a
good practice or you make a couple of good blocks and you think you
can do it if you can get consistent enough fast enough. Certainly I
went through some self-doubt that first season, but I got to play
half of the last regular-season game and held my own. That's the
moment I knew I could play at this level.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offseason, everyone knew Jeff was probably leaving, so it
wasn't a shock when it became official. A lot of guys play a long
time and don't get a chance like this. It was my spot to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Birk began the process of winning that spot when he arrived at
Harvard and began a workout routine that ultimately allowed him to
gain significant weight, developing from an admittedly ``lean'' 230
to a stout 304 in seven years. Had he not, there would be no place
for him along that purple line, because stout is the way they like
their linemen in Minnesota; Birk is almost a midget next to
346-pound guard David Dixon, 338-pound tackle Korey Stringer, and
308-pound tackle Todd Steussie.
</P>
<P>
   Birk's body began to change (with some assistance from the
Harvard weight room) as he led the Crimson to an Ivy League title
and 9-1 record his senior season that included the requisite win
over Yale. By the next spring, he was on his way to Mankato, not
Wall Street, and on his way to expanding his waistline, not his
stock portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   He is the first Harvard graduate to play in the National
Football League since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not exactly Nebraska,'' Birk said. ``One reason I think
I've made it this far coming from Harvard is that I had a great
(line) coach and the fact that everyone knows offensive linemen
mature later than guys at other positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a basketball player in high school, but once I got to
Harvard I hit the weights and was able to gain weight and still
keep my athleticism. There are tons of guys who are big and strong
but only a few can also move their feet. That's what makes an NFL
lineman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my friends from Harvard think this is pretty cool. One
of my roommates moved out here and he's living with me right now.
They're proud of me but they don't just see me as a football
player. They know there's more to me than that, which is
comforting. Otherwise football can beat you down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some days you get tired of thinking about football
because it's 80 hours a week, but if I was working on Wall Street,
that would be 80 hours a week, too. It's how I make my living. Who
would have predicted that?''
</P>
<P>
   Not so many years and pounds ago, nobody. Not even Matt Birk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shared honor
</P>
<P>
   Birk is not the only Harvard grad in the NFL. Linebacker Isaiah
Kacyvenski, a fourth-round pick of the Seattle Seahawks in April,
is a player Birk remembers from his college days. ``His locker was
next to mine one year at Harvard,'' Birk said. ``I haven't talked
to him, but to tell you the truth I'm kind of sad at losing the
dubious distinction of being the only Harvard grad in the NFL.'' .
. . Henry Thomas watched highlights of Minnesota quarterback Daunte
Culpepper running wild last Sunday and came to one conclusion.
``It's about time for me to retire when the quarterbacks are as big
as I am,'' the Patriots' defensive tackle said. Actually that's not
quite accurate, but Thomas isn't off by much. Culpepper, who in
last week's 30-27 victory over the Bears became the first Viking
quarterback to rush for three touchdowns in a game, stands nearly
6-5, weighs 255, and runs the 40 in 4.6 seconds. That makes him
nearly 3 inches taller and only 20 pounds lighter than Thomas, who
will be among the Patriots chasing Culpepper next Sunday. Also
doing some chasing will be ``undersized'' linebacker Tedy Bruschi,
who at 6-1, 245, will be giving away both height and weight to a
quarterback for the first time in memory. ``I've never seen a
quarterback like him with that size,'' Bruschi said. ``You can see
his strength just watching him on television. A guy like that
changes your mentality of tackling. Normally, you want to put a big
lick on a quarterback but with Culpepper you've got to think about
your tackling process. You want to be sure and get some cloth or
some leg and then hope for some friends.'' . . . Despite
Culpepper's size and speed, Bruschi said he would rather try to
tackle him than spend time chasing Doug Flutie. ``He's easier to
get a piece of than Flutie,'' Bruschi said. ``He's such a big
target, he may run over you, but at least you'll hit him. With
Flutie, you might whiff entirely.'' . . . Word out of Baltimore is
that the Ravens are pleasantly surprised at the play of Ben Coates,
so much that they played much of the game last Sunday using one
wide receiver, two backs, and two tight ends. Coach Brian Billick
has told quarterback Tony Banks that if he could get two more
completions a game this season, the Ravens would be a good team.
When the Ravens signed tight end Shannon Sharpe, Billick informed
Banks that he'd gotten him one of those extra receptions. Then he
went out and drafted Jamal Lewis and Travis Taylor and signed
Coates. One day in training camp, Banks lofted a touchdown pass to
Coates, then hollered to Billick and held up four fingers before
pointing to Coates, Sharpe, Lewis, and Taylor. In his mind, they're
worth four more catches a game. If so, the Ravens will rock . . .
Banks did not have a turnover last weekend, which is noteworthy
when you consider he fumbled 57 times and threw 50 interceptions in
the first four years of his career but has been nearly flawless
since midseason of a year ago . . . Sunday is a big game for
Billick's Ravens. The Ravens/Browns franchise has never beaten
division rival Jacksonville, going 0-10, and six of the eight
losses as the Ravens have been by a touchdown or less.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Emanuel rules
</P>
<P>
   Miami wide receiver Bert Emanuel has been the impetus for two
NFL rule adjustments in less than a year. The league has altered a
rule that caused the Dolphins to be penalized in their opener when
Emanuel was brought in as a short-yardage quarterback. Emanuel
wears No. 87, which is not considered a quarterback's number, and
hence he must report to an official before he enters, which he did
not do last week. He also was penalized because he was not listed
among the three quarterbacks on the active roster. The NFL ruled
last week that with all the shifting and multiple formations, it is
no longer realistic to enforce the number rule and so Emanuel
doesn't have to be listed as an emergency quarterback to play in
short yardage. Last year, it was Emanuel's diving ``non-catch'' in
the playoffs for Tampa Bay that led the league to lighten up on
rules regarding incompletions. On that play, he had control of the
football, but because the tip of it hit the ground, the pass was
ruled incomplete. ``Hopefully I won't be rewriting the whole rule
book,'' Emanuel said . . . Several NFL sources said last week that
Dick Vermeil harbors hopes of returning to NFL head coaching.
Vermeil has been publicly mum on the subject . . . It's unlikely to
happen, but it would be a writer's dream if Jets cornerback
Earthwind Moreland could somehow end up covering Patriots wide
receiver Shockmain Davis Monday night. If it happens, Dennis Miller
will have a dream opportunity to say something . . . Right tackle
Marvel Smith, a second-round draft pick, was the first rookie
offensive lineman since 1969 to start on opening day for the
Pittsburgh Steelers. That includes Hall of Fame center Mike Webster
and future Hall of Fame center Dermontti Dawson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No room for Gruber
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Tampa Bay tackle Paul Gruber gave up on his effort to
come back from the broken leg he sustained at the end of last
season, in part because he wanted the Bucs to let him finish his
rehab at their facility in Tampa but they couldn't because they
would have had to sign him, and that was a salary cap hit they
couldn't afford for a guy they weren't sure would ever play again.
Gruber refused to return to Colorado Springs, where he'd rehabbed
over the summer, and opted to end his career after 12 noteworthy
seasons. He had talked of retiring even before the injury but tried
a comeback so he would not go out this way. Reportedly, he was
curling 250 pounds with his good leg and only 50 with his bad one a
week ago . . . If he continues to turn the ball over the way he has
since the middle of last season, Jon Kitna won't be Seattle's
starting quarterback for much longer. He had five turnovers against
Miami last week and has thrown 16 interceptions and only eight
touchdown passes in his last eight games. Seattle is 1-7 during
that stretch, and as coach Mike Holmgren pointed out, ``This is not
the Civil Service.'' Holmgren met with Kitna and backup Brock Huard
and made it clear that if things didn't change, their roles would .
. . Dallas running back Emmitt Smith seems a lock to make history
Sunday night despite the Cowboys' many problems. He needs just 8
rushing yards against the Cardinals to become the third man in NFL
history to rush for 14,000. He would join Walter Payton (16,726)
and Barry Sanders (15,269) . . . With Troy Aikman out with the
ninth concussion of his career, the Cowboys have simplified their
terminology to make it easier for Randall Cunningham to run the
offense. The Cowboys are using Ernie Zampese's offense, in which
the pass routes are all numbered, but for Cunningham's benefit they
have added names to some of those routes. They also will reduce
their use of men in motion. Considering how they were smoked by the
Eagles last Sunday, simplifying the offense may not be the best way
to go, but offensive coordinator Jack Reilly felt he had no choice.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Settling in
</P>
<P>
   The feel-good story of the week is that Jeff Zgonina has an
apartment in St. Louis. That may not sound like much, but the
eight-year veteran has bounced around among five teams in his
career and has not lived in an apartment for five years. He has
been living in long-term hotels, including one across the street
from the Rams' practice facility for the past two years, but he's
moving into an apartment with his new wife at the same time he's
moving into the starting lineup for the first time in his career.
Zgonina will replace the injured D'Marco Farr against the Seahawks
Sunday. On hand in Seattle to see his son's first NFL start will be
Zgonina's father, who is battling pancreatic cancer . . . The plan
to limit Reggie White to 15 plays a game went out the window in one
week. Carolina head coach George Seifert had been adamant that he
would use the 38-year-old White only in rushing situations and
limited duty, but White was in for 37 plays against the Redskins
last week and asking for more snaps this week. Seifert did rotate
out his starting front four every three plays, however . . . No one
wants to admit it in Chicago, but running back Curtis Enis is close
to losing his starting job to unheralded James Allen. Enis, the
fifth player taken in the 1998 draft, carried only four times for
11 yards against Minnesota in a tight game seemingly tailor-made
for his ball-control style of rushing. Allen carried nine times for
60 yards . . . Also in Chicago, former University of New Hampshire
running back Jerry Azumah continues to make a name for himself as a
defensive back. He had one interception, a forced fumble, and a
knocked-down pass, and made two tackles in part-time duty.
Defensive coordinator Greg Blache says he wants to get Azumah on
the field more, but Azumah isn't ready to unseat starters Thomas
Smith and Walt Harris. The Bears hope he is ready by the end of the
season, because Harris can be a free agent next February and Azumah
would be a cost-effective solution to filling that spot.
</P>
<P>
   Material from personal interviews, wire service reports, other
beat writers, and league and team sources was used in compiling
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
