<HEADLINE>
MEDAL TABLES SHOULD TURN IN FAVOR OF US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ The last time Uncle Sam sent an Olympic team down
under, Ike was president and everybody was listening for CONELRAD
alerts. The world has turned upside-down since 1956: the Iron
Curtain is long gone and the United States figures to own the
eagle's share of the medals again when the Games of the XXVIIth
Olympiad end next month.
</P>
<P>
   Though the US hasn't topped the table at a foreign Games since
1968, that should change. The Americans won 101 medals in Atlanta,
a third more than either the Germans or Russians. Even allowing for
no home cooking, they could approach that total here, with a couple
dozen each in track and field and swimming. The basketball teams
should go double gold again, the minor leaguers should get baseball
back on the podium, and Jim Pedro of Lawrence, Mass., should make
history with the first judo gold by a Yank.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the US prospects:
</P>
<P>
   ARCHERY: No golds, but good chances for bronze with the men's
team and Connecticut teenager Karen Scavotto.
</P>
<P>
   BADMINTON: Kevin Han is a one-man band. With luck, he could win
a match or two.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL: With minor leaguers replacing overmatched collegians,
the US should make it back to the medal stand. If we sent the real
Yanks, it'd be a gold.
</P>
<P>
   BASKETBALL: The Dream Team days are over, but the men are still
the class of the planet and shouldn't lose a game. Tougher road for
the women, but they still should win their fourth gold since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   BOXING: Those four gold medals at last year's world
championships were asterisked by the Cuban pullout. Still, the US
figures to win golds with Brian Viloria (light flyweight), Ricardo
Juarez (featherweight), and Michael Bennett (heavyweight). That's
three times as many as last time.
</P>
<P>
   CANOE-KAYAK: The flatwater types are flat liners these days, but
Scott Shipley should fish a silver out of the whitewater.
</P>
<P>
   CYCLING: Chances for the first gold medal since 1984 all but
vanished when Lance Armstrong was hit by a car on the Riviera last
month. If he competes, Armstrong still could win something in the
time trial, and Marty Nothstein (track) and Alison Dunlap (mountain
bike) should be on the podium.
</P>
<P>
   DIVING: After medals (usually gold) in every Games since 1912,
this could be the year of the belly-flop. Mark Ruiz and the women's
synchro entries have an outside shot, but little more.
</P>
<P>
   EQUESTRIAN: The Americans made the medal stand in all three
events last time. This time, they may have to settle for one, in
the three-day team, which includes Bolton (Mass.)-bred Karen Lende
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   FENCING: No US woman has ever won an Olympic medal, but Iris
Zimmermann has a great chance at a bronze in foil. No chance for
the men, who haven't made the podium at a nonboycotted Games in 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   FIELD HOCKEY: Neither team qualified.
</P>
<P>
   GYMNASTICS: With only two of the Magnificent Seven back, there's
no chance for a women's team gold this time, but a bronze isn't a
pipe dream. The men haven't won a team medal since 1984, but Blaine
Wilson has a fine shot at a bronze in the all-around.
</P>
<P>
   JUDO: Pedro, bronzed in Atlanta, should upgrade to gold in the
lightweight class. Outside chances for the women, who've never
managed a medal.
</P>
<P>
   MODERN PENTATHLON: The US men haven't won an individual medal
since 1960, but rookie Chad Senior has an excellent chance.
</P>
<P>
   ROWING: The star-spangled flotilla managed only four medals on
home waters last time. That's unlikely to improve down under, but
the men's eight should win gold for the first time since 1964 and
silvers should come from the women's eight and lightweight double
(with Christine Collins of Worcester, Mass.).
</P>
<P>
   SAILING: The US sailors went from an astounding nine medals in
Barcelona to an appalling two in Atlanta. The form sheet says only
a couple this time, but one should be gold, from Paul Foerster and
Bob Merrick of Portsmouth, R.I., in men's 470.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING: One place where the NRA pays off. Half a dozen medals
are possible, with golds from Thomas Tamas in men's prone rifle and
Kim Rhode in women's double trap.
</P>
<P>
   SOCCER: The women are favored to repeat, but their draw (Norway
and China to start) is brutal. The men (captained by the
Revolution's Brian Dunseth) have never survived the prelims, but
with an all-pro roster that should change.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTBALL: The Americans have won every global title since 1982,
but the slaughter-rule days are over. The Australians are with them
from top to bottom now. The difference will be pitcher Lisa
``No-No'' Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   SWIMMING: The Yanks shocked everybody by winning 26 medals in
Atlanta but could do even better this time if they can hold the
form they had at the trials. Except for the relays, though, golds
will be scarce. Figure backstroker Lenny Krayzelburg for a pair,
plus Tom Malchow (200 butterfly), Tom Dolan (400 IM), and Brooke
Bennett (800 free).
</P>
<P>
   SYNCHRONIZED SWIMMING: Where have the Golden Girls gone? From a
lock to fourth. At best, a team bronze.
</P>
<P>
   TABLE TENNIS: Unless the US annexes Taiwan, no chance.
</P>
<P>
   TAEKWONDO: The Kay Poe-Esther Kim story is lovely, but it comes
with no medals.
</P>
<P>
   TEAM HANDBALL: Neither team qualified.
</P>
<P>
   TENNIS: Without Andre Agassi, there's no chance of triple gold
again. But Lindsay Davenport could repeat and the Williams sisters
have a strong chance in doubles.
</P>
<P>
   TRACK AND FIELD: Whether or not Marion Jones gets her five, the
Yanks figure to top the 23 medals they won last time. The men win
everything up to the 400, the hurdles, and relays, and a couple of
field events. The women take the sprints, the hurdles, and the pole
vault, and have good shots in the 1,500 and 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   TRIATHLON: Had Barb Lindquist made the team, an outside shot at
a women's bronze. Without her, it's an Aussie party. The men will
be happy to outswim the sharks.
</P>
<P>
   VOLLEYBALL: The women should be good for a couple of beach
medals, but without King Karch, the men will struggle. The indoor
teams are better, but out of podium range.
</P>
<P>
   WATER POLO: The word from the USOC's money people is produce
this time or else. Though neither the men nor women figured for a
medal six months ago, both have a shot at a bronze now.
</P>
<P>
   WEIGHTLIFTING: Cheryl Haworth, teen-age Samsonette, could win a
bronze. The men still aren't near the podium.
</P>
<P>
   WRESTLING: After winning eight medals (three golds) last time,
the Yanks may not win more than three, total. All should come from
the freestylers, with Cary Kolat the top hope. The Greco-Roman guys
may have to petition the Supreme Court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
