<HEADER>
A7842 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TUA-BOS &LR;      09-09 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TUA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUA THINKS HE CAN HAMMER LEWIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Tua learned when he was only 13 that he possessed the gift
of granting unconsciousness.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that he traveled eight hours to get to the New
Zealand national boxing finals, only to find there was no
middleweight opponent for him to fight. He was a champion without a
challenger, a circumstance he did not appreciate.
</P>
<P>
   So the young Samoan went looking for another fighter without a
fight, and he found one. The only problem was the guy was more than
30 pounds heavier than he was. Still, Tua volunteered to face him
and was told if he could make the weight, he'd get his chance. They
also told him he had two hours to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately he also had a powerful appetite that day _ and a
tool box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't make it the first time, but my trainer took me
outside and he handed me a small tool box,'' the International
Boxing Federation's No. 1 contender said last week, not long after
landing in Las Vegas from New Zealand to begin training for his
Nov. 11 showdown with undisputed heavyweight champion Lennox Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to put the tool box under my sweatsuit and zip it
up. He told me to make sure nobody saw it. I got on the scales with
my shoes on, in my sweatsuit, with the tool box under my jacket.
And I made it.''
</P>
<P>
   That night he also made the guy who might have been the
heavyweight champion of New Zealand go to sleep in one round. From
that point on, David Tua knew what he had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I discovered at an early age that I had something special,''
Tua said. ``It's a God-given talent I have to knock people out.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a gift rewarded only in one place. Only in the boxing
ring, which is where Tua will earn $3.5 million to try to render
Lewis null and void.
</P>
<P>
   That has already been done once by a far less formidable fighter
than Tua _ journeyman Oliver McCall knocked Lewis out with one
right hand _ so it would not be the most shocking thing to see
Lewis laid low. But the 35-year-old champion is a far different
fighter than he was six years ago. To many, he now seems
unconquerable, the best heavyweight in the world. With one
exception, Tua agrees with that assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the best out there,'' Tua said. ``He's the world
champion. He's got the belts (even though a court took one from him
and it ended up back around Evander Holyfield's waist). He's got
something to show for it when he says he's the best in the world. I
give the utmost respect to Lennox. But this is my time.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Tua believes it will soon be bedtime for Lewis, a brief
but concussive slumber induced by one of the thunderous left hooks
or right hands he has used to knock out 32 of his 37 victims
(37-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``When I land, you get knocked out,'' Tua said. ``If I have to
go 12 rounds, I'll go 12 rounds and get you late. Usually I'll get
you early. The second I sense fear or smell blood, I got to get you
out of there, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many observers believe Tua is a clear and present
danger to Lewis _ because of the combination of the challenger's
power and the champion's still-suspect whiskers _ others think Tua
may be the Samoan version of Michael Grant _ a figment of someone's
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Grant, you may recall, came into the ring against Lewis last
April heavily hyped as the champion's stiffest challenge. Less than
two minutes into the fight he was just stiff, floored and
semiconscious. He didn't make it out of the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Now people look at Tua's resume and see too many of the same
names Grant beat up on or their clones, and they wonder. Is he the
next Mike Tyson, or is he just a little man who will be exposed by
a very big heavyweight?
</P>
<P>
   Ask David Tua that question, and you risk unconsciousness
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have waited patiently for three years for my chance,'' said
Tua, his voice rising slightly. ``I fought my way to the No. 1
ranking. Grant's team maneuvered him there. They did it in great
style, but he was tailor-made for Lennox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a shorter fighter. I'm in your face all night. I'm
mentally tougher than Michael Grant. I'm in there to take you
out.''
</P>
<P>
   In two months, Tua will be in there with Lewis. If he takes him
out, the gift he first noticed at 13 will be revealed to the world
_ without the aid of a tool box.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arum bides his time
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arum has read and reread the lawsuit filed against him by
attorneys representing Oscar De La Hoya, a lawsuit he calls
specious when he's talking like a Harvard-trained lawyer and
something with a barnyard connotation when he's talking like a
boxing promoter. The suit seems to have no grounds. It alleges, for
example, that Arum has been in violation of the Muhammad Ali Act
since 1996. That would be difficult for even Don King to
accomplish, since the Muhammad Ali Act didn't become law until
2000. So after a week of ranting and raving about the disloyalty of
a fighter whom he has helped earn more than $150 million in purses,
including $46 million in his last three fights, Arum has taken a
new tack. The way he sees it, this is just a case of something
happening to him that has happened to everyone else associated with
De La Hoya who is not family _ but one significant difference. Arum
is protected. ``He's fired somebody every time he had a problem,''
Arum said of the former welterweight champion who is on a two-fight
losing streak and heading for three, as far as Arum is concerned.
``The only reason I never thought it would happen to me is it can't
happen to me. I've got a contract. I've got a contract with him,
and he and I both have a contract with Time-Warner (HBO's parent
company) in which he's a principal, not just somebody signing off.
If he just had a contract with me, he could probably get away with
this because there are ample ways for me to be protected. But he's
got a separate contract with me and Time-Warner, and he can't get
out of that.'' Why, one wonders, would he want to? De La Hoya has
made more money than any boxer but the top heavyweights since he
turned pro following the 1992 Olympics in Barcelona. He has won
titles in four weight classes and become both a multimillionaire
and a pop idol with recording contracts, TV offers, and endless
business opportunities. He also has a golden reputation Arum's
public relations machine helped build despite more than a few
youthful indiscretions with women and gambling. Yet De La Hoya has
bitten the hand that fed him, Arum says, because a group of
entrepreneurs convinced him he can show his fights on the Internet,
along with other sporting events, and form a company whose initial
public stock offering would make him a billionaire. ``I looked at
the deal for him before the (Shane) Mosley fight,'' Arum said. ``I
told them we didn't want anything to do with it. Oscar wasn't in
the room, so they convinced him I'm the impediment. You've got a
27-year-old kid who barely got a high school diploma convinced he's
going to be the Bill Gates of sports, but it can't happen. They
keep telling him his stock will be worth billions. You can't
compete with that, but it's not going to happen. If he wants to
fight again, he can't fight without me. It's as simple as that. I'm
not going away, and if he comes back I won't coddle him anymore. It
will be an arm's-length relationship. Maybe it always should have
been, but it was like father and son.'' . . . HBO is worried its
planned Jan. 20 rematch between De La Hoya and Mosley will not come
off. To protect itself, the cable network is working on a possible
December fight for Mosley against Arturo Gatti or Oba Carr if a
deal with De La Hoya and Arum cannot be worked out by Oct. 1. Arum
says it will not . . . In total, De La Hoya has dismissed managers
Shelly Finkel, Robert Mittleman, and Steve Nelson; trainers Emanuel
Stewart, Jesus Rivera, and Gil Clancy; business adviser Mike
Hernandez; and now his promoter. To Arum, this means they don't
make fighters like Marvin Hagler anymore. ``He was a pillar of
loyalty,'' Arum said of Hagler. ``A lot of that is coming from New
England. People there are practical and conservative. People in
California go for the Hollywood glitz.''
</P>
</TEXT>
