<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORSTROM SUPPORTS STUMPEL'S HOLDOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Mattias Norstrom was the only Los Angeles
King to miss training camp last year. He also was the only one to
play all 82 games of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Norstrom, who teams with captain Rob Blake on the club's top
defensive line, knows all about the kind of contract holdout that
has top center Jozef Stumpel back in Slovakia. He also knows how
skipping camp often is a players' best leverage in getting a better
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only time the sport and the business overlap, but
from a player's standpoint, this is when you have to secure your
future,'' Norstrom said Saturday before the Kings completed their
second day of training camp. ``I want Stumpy here as much as
anyone, but this is what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem facing the Kings is Stumpel is not Norstrom, one of
the league's best-conditioned players. Although he averages more
than a point a game when healthy, Stumpel missed 43 games the past
two seasons because of groin and knee injuries the club thinks
might have been avoided with better conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Teammate and fellow Slovak Ziggy Palffy saw Stumpel over the
summer and said he is in excellent shape, but management wants to
see for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to be here,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``When Matty got
here last year, he came into the season already our best
conditioned athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   Norstrom: ``I think it took about 10 games, though, to get in
game shape. The thing you really miss are the exhibition games.
They help you get your timing back that you just can't get in
scrimmages.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Norstrom is signed through the 2001-02 season, his
summer was not without controversy. Back in his native Sweden,
Norstrom was embroiled in a flap with the country's sports
federation over a request to submit to drug testing when several
players rented ice time.
</P>
<P>
   The NHL and the NHL Players Association had an agreement with
the International Ice Hockey Federation, which was consulted about
the drug testing.
</P>
<P>
   The matter was dropped, but the faces of Norstrom, Edmonton
goaltender Tommy Salo and several other NHL players were splashed
across newscasts and newspapers for several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we were right, seeing yourself in the paper for
four days straight was very painful,'' Norstrom said. ``I'm just
glad the controversy is over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
