<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-ARMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC HAS SOMETHING TO SMILE ABOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST POINT, N.Y. _ A howitzer erupted from just beyond the east
end of Michie Stadium when Army scored its final touchdown with two
seconds remaining. By then Boston College had rendered the
cannonade a mere formality as the Eagles subjected Army to a
double-barreled blast of their own, erupting for 41 straight points
_ including 28 in a third quarter filled with big plays _ to notch
their first victory of the season, 55-17, before a crowd of 37,544.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, which helped the Eagles absolve the sins of last
week's season-opening 34-14 setback at West Virginia, was BC's most
lopsided under fourth-year coach Tom O'Brien, and ranked as the
biggest rout by a BC team since a 66-14 trampling of Temple in
1993. But, as O'Brien noted, it came against a weary Army team that
was playing its second game in six days after dropping a 23-17
decision at Cincinnati Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, this team needed a victory,'' O'Brien said of his
Eagles, who will next host Navy Sept. 23. ``We came out in the
first half and we wanted to make sure that we established the run
and tried to make a conscious effort to become a physical football
team. Defensively, Army came out with a lot of different formations
and got us confused a little bit, but once we settled in to the
pace of the game with them, we played much better on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior quarterback Tim Hasselbeck made Army pay by accounting
for 312 of BC's 587 yards of total offense. He rushed eight times
for 56 yards (including a long of 30) and completed 14 of 21 passes
for 256 yards and three touchdowns, hitting Dedrick Dewalt (3
catches, 122 yards) for scores of 75 and 38 yards that broke the
game open in the second half and turned Army's home opener into a
long gray day for the Long Gray Line.
</P>
<P>
   More important, BC's offense committed no turnovers after having
five against the Mountaineers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he played with much more confidence,'' O'Brien said of
Hasselbeck. ``Our protection was much better and I believe we gave
him opportunities to make easier throws and, quite frankly, we
weren't playing West Virginia, not to take anything away from
Army.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, had BC's offense come out of the blocks and erupted for
55 points last week, the Eagles would be headed into their off week
2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing, actually, the two biggest things today were
we were able to run the ball and be physical, and we didn't turn
the ball over. When you do those two things, you're going to give
yourself a chance to win a lot of ballgames. Obviously, we would've
wanted to start out (at West Virginia) like we did today, but
that's just how the cookie crumbles, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior running back Cedric Washington, who twice challenged his
teammates during the week to step up their play, rebounded from a
lackluster 31-yard effort against West Virginia by recording his
sixth career 100-yard game with 15 carries for an even 100 and a
touchdown. He also factored into the passing game, making two
catches for 38 yards.
</P>
<P>
   After Josh Holden gave Army a 7-0 lead with a 16-yard run with
6:33 to go in the first quarter, William Green ripped off a
dazzling 84-yard kick return to set up Washington's 8-yard TD run
that tied it. Green, who rushed 17 times for 59 yards, gave BC a
14-7 lead when he capped a six-play, 32-yard drive, set up by
Willie Poole's interception, with a 3-yard TD run through a gaping
hole cleared by right guard Paul Zukauskas and right tackle Michael
Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our backs were against the wall and last night I told the
team, `Hey, are we going to back down, or are we going to come out
swinging?' '' Washington said. ``Today, I think we decided to come
out swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   BC's defense heeded Washington's message and delivered some
crucial blows by holding Army to 354 yards of offense, and knocking
out starting quarterback Chad Jenkins (sprained left ankle). The
Eagles also rang up five sacks (including two by junior cornerback
Lenny Walls) and three interceptions, the biggest of which was
Curtis Bolden's 22-yard return that came on the heels of
Hasselbeck's 75-yard TD bomb to Dewalt.
</P>
<P>
   After kicker Mike Sutphin, who was perfect on all seven
extra-point attempts, helped BC take a 20-10 lead at halftime with
field goals of 22 and 24 yards, Hasselbeck had the Eagles soaring
when he called ``Fullback Wheel'' in the huddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a play-action and they were playing a coverage called
`robber,' where the safety likes to come up to the line of
scrimmage,'' Hasselbeck said. ``Once I saw Ded get inside of their
corner, he was wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dewalt: ``Every time they call that play, my antennae just
goes up. It was the same play we ran for a 97-yard touchdown last
year at Virginia Tech. So when they called it, I was thinking 6.''
</P>
<P>
   Bolden, a sophomore linebacker from Dorchester, certainly had to
be thinking the same thing when he keyed on running back Michael
Wallace, stepped in front of Jenkins's flare pass, and converted
his first career interception into his first career touchdown, one
that proved to break Army's spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both teams were really tired and it was a gut-check
for both of us,'' O'Brien said. ``I didn't see a lot of quickness
on our part, but what Army asked their football team to do was
ungodly _ to play on Monday and come back on that short week and
play. I can't believe they did that to those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasselbeck closed out the productive third quarter with a 5-yard
scoring pass to sophomore Keith Hemmings (who caught his first
career TD) and a 38-yarder to Dewalt before redshirt freshman
Derrick Knight tallied his first career TD with a 13-yard run with
6:32 remaining. Army, though, managed one final score against BC's
second-team defense when Clinton Woody caught a 12-yard TD pass
from Curtis Zervic to touch off the howitzer.
</P>
<P>
   By then, though, the Cadets had been blasted by BC.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
