<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ROLSTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW BEGINNING FOR ROLSTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON _ For his entire career as a professional hockey
player, this always was the time of year when Brian Rolston found
himself in West Orange, N.J., at South Mountain Arena with the rest
of the New Jersey Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1993-94 season, during which he split his time between
the US national team and the Olympics before heading to New
Jersey's top AHL affiliate in Albany, N.Y., Rolston's home base was
that practice rink.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time he's found himself anywhere else in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely different for me, because this is my first
camp other than New Jersey that I've ever been to, but I'm
excited,'' said Rolston, who along with the rest of the Bruins
continued camp workouts at Ristuccia Arena Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Rolston had a roller coaster season last year. He began with the
Devils, who had a difficult lineup to crack, then was traded to the
Colorado Avalanche, whose roster was even tougher to make. In
March, when Ray Bourque asked to be traded to a Stanley Cup
contender, Rolston was one of those shipped to Boston in the
multiplayer swap.
</P>
<P>
   He played well in the final 16 games of the regular season, but
morale around the rink was low, injuries were plentiful, and there
was little Rolston could do to rescue the disastrous season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when I came here, the team was worn a little thin
at the end of the season, and I'm excited to have a new start
here,'' he said. ``I think we have some great players.''
</P>
<P>
   With three key members out of camp because of contract disputes
_ Joe Thornton, Sergei Samsonov, and Anson Carter _ there has been
little talk about the rest of the team. But Rolston said that's
just business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is talking about how Joe is not in camp, and that's a
big story, and everyone has been asking me about it, but it happens
everywhere,'' said Rolston. ``When I was in New Jersey, every year
I was there, there was someone holding out of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the players, at least, it's out of sight, out of mind. I
don't think the guys really worry about that. It would be nice to
start the season with everyone. It's business. We all know that.
Obviously they're key components and we want them back, but at the
same time, I don't think we're worried about it because we know,
eventually, they're going to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston said he understands the frustration of the fans and
those who feel it's a ``here we go again'' scenario, especially
since the club has had key members holding out the last three
years. However, Rolston said the glass should be looked at as
half-full, not half-empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very optimistic about our season,'' he said. ``We've just
got to come together as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Rolston, who was married in the offseason, stands to play a huge
role on the Bruins this year. Offensively, he did well with the ice
time he had last year. In 11 games with New Jersey, Rolston had
three goals and an assist. In 50 games with Colorado, he had eight
goals and 18 points. In 16 games as a Bruin, he had five goals and
four assists.. But it was a fractured, strange season for the
27-year-old, who was drafted by New Jersey (No. 11 overall) in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns promises that Rolston, as well as several others
who had a hard time on other teams, will have an opportunity to
flourish. ``He was in a situation where he got traded to Colorado
and he couldn't play there, he couldn't find a place in the
lineup,'' said Burns. ``He's like Mike Knuble (who couldn't crack
the Rangers' lineup and came to Boston in a deal for Rob DiMaio
last spring). Those are good signs for us. Those guys are getting
fresh starts on a different team. I think that's important. Rolston
goes from one team where he couldn't get into the lineup to a team
where he's a leader. That's a big step.''
</P>
<P>
   In the short time he was here, Burns said, Rolston showed a
great deal despite the less-than-perfect circumstances with so many
regulars injured. ``He's a player we can use in so many different
situations, which is good for us,'' said Burns. ``We might play him
on the point on the power play. Certainly, he can kill penalties.
He's going to get an opportunity to do it, whereas he didn't get an
opportunity in the other place. Do you see the talent on the
Colorado Avalanche? Have a look at their team. That's a tough
lineup to break. You're playing behind (Joe) Sakic, (Peter)
Forsberg, (Milan) Hejduk, (Alex) Tanguay _ it's tough to say how
much ice time you're going to get. And New Jersey was the same
situation. He was a third-line, fourth-line player. Here he becomes
maybe a second-line, some nights first-line player.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burns has been impressed with what he's seen from Knuble, whom
the coach termed the best player in Friday's scrimmage. ``Knuble
can do a lot of things I don't think he realizes he can do,'' said
Burns. ``He's a big, strong individual on the boards. He's a
physical player. Knuble scored three goals in the scrimmage because
he went to the net and looked for the puck. If he does that on a
regular basis, he's going to do that in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
