</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS' HAND FORCED ON SNAPPING DUTIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Nobody would do by choice what the Patriots are
doing this fall.
</P>
<P>
   No NFL coach in his right mind would field a team with one
center in its regular offense, another as a long snapper, and a
third when the quarterback drops into a shotgun formation. Nobody
in his right mind could be convinced it's the best way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Bill Belichick about this, and you conclude at least one
thing: He's still in his right mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it would be easier if we didn't have to do this,'' the
Patriots coach conceded when asked about his odd shifting of center
Damien Woody to guard and Jason Andersen to center whenever Drew
Bledsoe goes into the shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Even odder is that Andersen doesn't handle the normal long
snapping, to the punter and placekicker. That is done by Lonie
Paxton. Has there ever been a team in football history with a
whipper snapper, a medium snapper, and a long snapper? Center may
be complex, but come on.
</P>
<P>
   Andersen handles the short toss only, having become perhaps the
first designated shotgun snapper in NFL history. That is about as
specialized as a football position can get, and were it up to
Belichick, a former center himself, he wouldn't do things this way.
</P>
<P>
   The reason he has to is the normally reliable Woody looked a lot
like Chuck Knoblauch too many times this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But just how difficult is it to shift the center, arguably the
pivotal man in any offensive line, to left guard and put the backup
left guard in at center in a formation that is often used at the
most critical moments in a game?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two problems,'' Belichick said. ``One is it's an
assignment thing. The guard needs to understand what the center is
doing, and vice versa. Second, the techniques are different. A lot
of line play is footwork and positioning, so the technique is
important. The more fluctuation you have, the harder it is to do
things consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Consistency was a serious problem last Sunday against the Tampa
Bay Buccaneers, who sacked Bledsoe six times and knocked him down
14 more times. This was not all the fault of the center/guard
switch, however. The running game never got off the ground, either,
so there had to have been problems from end to end.
</P>
<P>
   How difficult is the switch for Woody, who is arguably the
team's most consistent offensive lineman when he's at his normal
position?
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, guard is easier because I don't have the ball to
worry about,'' said Woody. ``But I've been a center my whole life,
and the techniques at guard are different. So is the footwork and
the angles. Most teams play a 4-3, so when I'm at center I don't
usually have anyone in my face, either. At guard, the defensive
tackle is right there. It changes your aggressiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   To the average fan, guard is no different from center except the
center has to hand the ball to the quarterback before he starts
trying to push a 300-pound block of flesh out of the way.
Otherwise, offensive linemen are seen as interchangeable parts _
wide-bodied people who push around other wide-bodied people for a
living. What does it matter where you start pushing from? It may
look that way to the untutored eye, but nothing could be further
from the truth of a lineman's existence.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Smerlas is a five-time Pro Bowl nose tackle who made a
living making centers' lives miserable. He has studied that
position, as well as the guard's, and knows this: Shifting from
place to place is not the way to build consistent interior line
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensive linemen get a feel for each other and they work more
together, where defensive line is more helter-skelter,'' said
Smerlas. ``You break that continuity and it's like a hole in a cup.
No matter where it is, the water is going to leak out.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the center and guard positions, the techniques are very
different because the proximity to the guy you're blocking is very
different. Everything they do is different because of that
different distance. Their angles are different. Their steps are
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you keep shifting them back and forth, all the things
that come naturally are gone. As a defensive lineman, you love to
see guys moving in and out because they don't get as used to how
you play, either. There were guys who played me so often that when
I'd put my hand down in a certain way they'd call out the direction
I was coming.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots have not been in the shotgun that often, but the
shift has been made often enough to be noticeable, and it demands
different things from Woody and Andersen, demands that can take
away their edge of aggressiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to think which position you're at and do what
you've been taught,'' Andersen said. ``We do it in practice a lot
and we've been doing it for a while, so we don't think about it
much anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do need to know the position you're in and the play and
the technique for that play, and make sure you're using it. But it
works in practice, so it should work in the games.''
</P>
<P>
   But given his druthers, Woody would just as soon stay at center.
Not because of any doubts he harbors about Andersen but simply out
of personal pride, the kind that turned him into a No. 1 draft
choice two years ago and a starter from his first game in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long snapping isn't as easy as everybody thinks,'' Woody said.
``It's a matter of being comfortable with it. To a degree, the
problems I've had with it have been mental because it's all about
being comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shifting to guard when Jason comes in hasn't been a bad
transition for me, but sometimes I get a little frustrated when
they don't let me do it (shotgun snap). I just keep thinking
eventually the problem will be resolved and things will come
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do whatever the coaches want, but definitely, I assume,
eventually I'll do that part of it, too. Things will come around.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, when the Patriots want to fire out of the shotgun, a
former seventh-round draft choice will be the guy coming around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
