</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-PETTITTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE WON'T PLAY MATCH GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Yankees lefthander Andy Pettitte says that pitchers
battle only the opposing batters, that the idea of dueling the
opposing pitcher makes no sense. But surely the matchup has an
added dimension when the opposing pitcher is Red Sox ace Pedro
Martinez. Your margin of error is slim and you must yield as few
runs as possible, then hope for the best from your teammates
against the best pitcher in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, both things happened for Pettitte, who is now
garnering as much respect on the mound at Fenway Park as Martinez
does throughout the league.
</P>
<P>
   In a 5-3 victory at Fenway Park, Pettitte gave up one hit in the
first, second, and fourth innings. The Red Sox scored one run in
the third with a pair of two-out hits. Then Pettitte retired the
side in the fifth (striking out two) and the sixth (another K).
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what our guys showed, with the way Andy was pitching,
they didn't want to waste that effort,'' said Yankees manager Joe
Torre.
</P>
<P>
   They made certain it didn't go to waste in the seventh, when
Scott Brosius belted a three-run homer off Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   That would be more than enough for Pettitte, who gave up one hit
in the seventh and retired the side in the eighth before yielding
to Mariano Rivera in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The win not only improved Pettitte to 18-7 (second only to David
Wells in the American League in victories), it continued his
dominance of the Red Sox. He is 3-0 at Fenway and 5-2 with a 2.39
earned run average overall against Boston _ including 2-0, 0.57
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the start of the game, I was shaky, leaving balls over the
plate the first three innings or so,'' said Pettitte. ``Then I got
into a good groove and loosened up.''
</P>
<P>
   He scattered six hits over his eight innings, walked one and
struck out six. He allowed one earned run or fewer for the ninth
time this season and has won nine of his last 10 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hope you will get more (runs against Martinez), but you
don't expect too much more,'' Pettitte said. He added that after
Brosius hit his homer, ``I still pitched like I was down, 1-0. I
was able to keep my focus and it was nice to be able to finish
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's first jam came in the first inning, when Jose
Offerman walked and Carl Everett singled to center. But Nomar
Garciaparra grounded into a double play to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big inning,'' said Pettitte. ``I really didn't feel
sharp with my command but I made a good pitch right there to get
the double play. It was a good fastball into him. Obviously if they
score there and score later, getting a 2-0 lead . . . Pedro might
start pitching a bit different.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte said all of his pitches were working, and after the
third inning he began throwing changeups _ which he's hardly thrown
at all this season _ to keep batters guessing.
</P>
<P>
   He's had the Sox guessing the past two seasons _ his wins over
them include Game 4 of last season's American League Championship
Series _ but Torre downplayed the notion of Pettitte mastering the
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 18 wins, he's pitched everywhere well,'' said Torre.
``But he rises to the challenge. He had a pretty good hiccup the
first half of last year, where his confidence level was very low,
but he's made a hell of a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   And, though he said Martinez adds to the electricity of a Fenway
outing, Pettitte insists the idea of a battle between pitchers is
way off base.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to beat Boston, obviously, because they're in second
place,'' said Pettitte. ``But it really doesn't factor into who is
pitching. That's a nonissue as far as I'm concerned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
