<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX SINK LOWER IN EAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez and the manager played by Tom Hanks in ``A League
of Their Own'' share a favorite motto: ``There's no crying in
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the dejected Red Sox faithful who watched Martinez,
the team's designated savior, surrender a crucial game to the
dreaded Yankees Saturday, 5-3, as the Sox slipped a perilous eight
games behind New York in the American League East.
</P>
<P>
   And remind the Red Sox, whose fears were focused more on their
severely injured teammate, Bryce Florie, than their tenuous
position in the standings. They also fell into third place in AL
wild-card race, three games behind Cleveland and a half-game behind
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox learned that Florie, smashed in the right eye by a line
drive Friday night, underwent surgery Saturday at Massachusetts Eye
and Ear Infirmary. The prognosis for him regaining normal vision
was called ``guarded.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard on the squad,'' said catcher Scott Hatteberg. ``It
kind of deflates you.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the gloom, the Sox lost their way for the second straight
game against a yeoman Yankee starter, this one Andy Pettitte. After
Roger Clemens shut them out Friday night, 4-0, the
production-starved Sox finagled only one run off Pettitte in eight
innings.
</P>
<P>
   And when Martinez was asked after the game to identify the major
difference between the teams, he said, ``Pitching. They are
dominant, better than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, he said, ``I was trying to win with that one
run.''
</P>
<P>
   But he couldn't. After pitching superbly through six innings,
Martinez yielded a leadoff single in the seventh to Tino Martinez.
Two outs later, he walked Jorge Posada.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Martinez did not appear headed for disaster. Twice the
Yankees had pushed runners into scoring position, and Martinez had
struck out all four batters who tried to advance them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he thought he did the same in this jam as well, when he
threw Scott Brosius a cut fastball on a 1-and-2 count. Martinez was
certain the pitch nipped the outside corner. But home plate umpire
Fieldin Culbreth called it a ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had him,'' Martinez said. ``That one pitch cost me
the game. And the other pitch I threw after that.''
</P>
<P>
   On a 3-and-2 count, Martinez delivered his 115th pitch of the
day, a changeup over the plate. Brosius had swung and missed wildly
on two changeups earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said if I'm going to die with something, I might as well die
with something that made him look bad,'' Martinez said. ``I was
hoping I could get it by him.''
</P>
<P>
   No such luck. Brosius blasted the pitch into the left-field
screen for a three-run homer that turned Sox loyalists sullen in a
divided sellout crowd of 33,355 at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, manager Jimy Williams reminded reporters, Martinez
is not superhuman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro is Pedro,'' he said. ``But the Yankees are the Yankees,
and they aren't the world champions for nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The champs made it 5-1 in the ninth when two of their
late-season pickups whacked around Rod Beck and Tim Wakefield.
After David Justice doubled with one out, Jose Canseco struck a
mammoth, 439-foot home run over everything in left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss,'' said catcher Jason Varitek. ``But any
loss right now is a tough loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding high in June atop the AL East, the Sox have tasted New
York's dust since then, as the Yanks have pulled away behind
Clemens and Pettitte. With the victory Saturday, Pettitte (18-7)
joined Martinez as the winningest pitchers in the majors since 1996
with 87.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just couldn't score on Pettitte,'' Williams said. ``He was
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   At his toughest, Pettitte held the Sox hitless when they had
runners in scoring position, making the Sox 0 for 8 in the last two
games in scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The first chance failed when Nomar Garciaparra grounded into a
double play with one out and runners on first and second in the
first inning. Garciaparra noted later that the Sox outhit the
Yankees, 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more hits than they did,'' he said. ``The timely
hitting just didn't come out for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox squeezed a run out of Pettitte in the third inning when
Jose Offerman lined a two-out single to right and Carl Everett
lofted a towering shot to left that skimmed the wall, scoring
Offerman.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, the next batter in the order, might have had a
second chance to drive in a run had Everett settled for a double.
But Everett tried to take third as Justice threw toward the plate.
First baseman Martinez cut off the throw and trapped Everett in a
rundown to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   That was it until there two outs in the bottom of the ninth. In
another minidrama, the Sox rallied for two runs off closer Mariano
Rivera on a double by Dante Bichette, a triple by Troy O'Leary, and
a double by Varitek.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, pinch hitter Midre Cummings, represented the
potential tying run. But Rivera struck him out to deepen Boston's
hole in the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even with only 23 games remaining, several Sox players said
they are far from buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any shovels out right now,'' Garciaparra said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez echoed Garciaparra's optimism. But, citing the Yankees'
excellence, he added, ``We're going to have to play near
perfection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
