<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: TRIATHLON  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like Marion Jones, triathlon figures to play an outsized role in
its first Olympics. It might be a niche endurance sport with a
short history _ the first official triathlon was held in 1974 in
San Diego _ but it is a sport at which Australians excel and which
dovetails nicely with their sun-and-sea culture. The women's event
is the first gold-medal event of the Games; the men compete the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   A 1,500-meter swim in open water is followed by a 40-kilometer
bike ride and then by a 10-kilometer run. The first across the
finish line wins.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   Though Americans dreamed up the triathlon, they no longer
dominate. The most consistently successful man (at the Olympic
distance) is Britain's Simon Lessing, a four-time world champion.
His competition should come from his countryman Andrew Johns,
Dmitry Gaag of Kazakhstan and Australians Peter Robertson and Craig
Walton.
</P>
<P>
   The most successful women are Australians: Michelie Jones,
Nicole Hackett and Loretta Harrop. In the women's event, Magali
Messmer of Switzerland and Carol Montgomery of Canada are
considered threats. Sheila Taormina, one of the three U.S. women,
won a gold medal in a swimming relay in Atlanta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
