<SLUG> BC-BBA-ONBASEBALL-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE BALL DOESN'T COME APART AT SEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the division race wasn't over before the Yankees arrived,
it's a foregone conclusion now.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough for the Bombers. They've reached the stage
where they'd like to blow Pedro Martinez and the Red Sox off the
postseason landscape altogether. There's a rat in the house, and
not just the one that sprinted across Joe Mooney's garden Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said after the Yanks
beat Martinez at Fenway Park for the second time in 11 weeks, 5-3,
inflating the Bombers' lead in the AL East to eight games while
dropping the Sox to third in the wild-card sweepstakes, three games
behind the Indians and a half-game behind the A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pedro can pitch twice in a five-game series, maybe three times
in a seven-game series,'' Torre said. ``No question, whether he's
there as the wild card or as the division winner, you're at a
disadvantage. Not taking anything away from (Andy) Pettitte,
(Roger) Clemens, or Boomer (David Wells), he's been the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way you go out there and scuffle against him, you have to
pitch against him the way he pitches against you. That's the only
way to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt, either, Torre acknowledged, if you shut down
Nomar Garciaparra while you're at it. The Red Sox shortstop entered
this series hitting .448 against the Yankees this season. He went 0
for 4 against Roger Clemens and closer Mariano Rivera in a 4-0
Rocket masterpiece Friday night and took another 0 for 4 against
Pettitte and Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had luck against the Mets in a four-game series that we
swept in which Mike Piazza didn't get any hits,'' Torre said,
referring to the Mets' MVP candidate. ``There's a correlation
between winning and those guys not getting hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Nomar) is tough. We're making good pitches on him, and he's
hitting some balls right at people. We're glad we just have two
more games with him.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Yaz stretch run left in Nomar, he's hiding it
well. In his last 23 games, spanning 84 at-bats, Garciaparra has
two extra-base hits and has knocked in seven runs. In 52 games
since the All-Star break, he has knocked in 24 runs and hit six
homers.
</P>
<P>
   He went 15 games in a row without knocking in a run, a streak
that he ended Monday. But by the weekend, it had become a struggle
again. Friday night, with a runner on third and two out against
Clemens, Garciaparra crushed a ball to right that was caught. In
the first inning, with runners on first and third and one out, he
grounded into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   It would be his last chance to bat with men on base, as Carl
Everett (a .256 hitter since the break) tried to do something the
freshman physics class at MIT could have told him was impossible,
namely stretching a Wall-ball double to left into a triple.
Everett's misplaced zeal, perhaps inspired by the rarity of seeing
a Sox runner cross the plate, left Garciaparra in the on-deck
circle and Martinez with a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The way Martinez was pitching, that looked like it might be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets his fastball in the mid-90s like he did today,
there's not much you can do,'' Yankees right fielder Paul O'Neill
said. ``We saw him earlier in the season, when his fastball was
down a little, and he still was tough. Is there a pattern in the
way he pitches me? Yeah, he gets me out.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, who went down swinging on a fastball that was clocked
at 98 m.p.h. in the first inning, wasn't alone. Martinez had five
K's in the first two innings, six through three. The Yanks didn't
have a hit until David Justice blooped a single over Garciaparra's
glove in short center with two out in the fourth. Only Tino
Martinez, who twice reached on errors, advanced as far as second
base.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte, who is 18-7, was giving the Red Sox nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get down 1-0 (to Martinez),'' O'Neill said, ``a lot of
people say, `We'll get 'em tomorrow. But Pettitte kept us right
there. To beat Martinez any time, you have to have a great-pitched
game, too, and we got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then they got Pedro, too. Tino Martinez opened the seventh with
a ground-ball single up the middle, and with two outs, Jorge Posada
wheedled his way on via a full-count walk. That brought up Scott
Brosius, who is two years removed from his World Series MVP award
and was hitting just .236 entering play Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't matter what kind of year he's having,'' Torre
said, ``when it's late in the game, or a key game, it's deja vu
stuff all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius quickly fell behind Martinez 0-and-2 on two changeups.
His first at-bat, he'd lined out on a fastball. His second, he
fouled out with Martinez throwing only curves. Now, the changeup.
</P>
<P>
   ``By then,'' Brosius said, ``I've seen just about everything and
I'm fighting for dear life after that.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Martinez missed with one, two, three pitches, a
fastball and two cutters, the 1-and-2 offering just missing. With
the count full, Brosius guessed that Martinez might go back to the
changeup. Bingo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to keep my hands back, stay back, and try to see it,''
Brosius said. ``I think he left it up higher than he wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   It certainly touched down at a higher place than Martinez
intended, the left-field screen. Bombers, 3-1. Designated villain
Jose Canseco's two-run home run off Tim Wakefield made it 5-1,
while the reinforcements provided Jimy Williams by Dan Duquette
(Bernard Gilkey, Izzy Alcantara, and Midre Cummings) all went
quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, who had given Rivera a blow against the Royals because he
wanted his closer to have some rest, brought him in for the second
straight game with a four-run lead. That's a measure of his respect
for Fenway Park, but also how much these games meant to the
Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Pedro was a marked man. But unlike Tampa Bay, the
Yanks meant business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you beat Pedro when you come back late in the game,
sure, it's a great win for us,'' O'Neill said. ``But this team has
won too many games to think too far ahead. We're trying to win
games, and coming down the stretch, it's now an all-out sprint
where we try to win every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in first place. Us beating Boston, or us beating Kansas
City, it's still a win.''
</P>
<P>
   But no one fears the Royals in October. And if this keeps up, no
one will have to fear the Sox, either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
