<HEADLINE>
LEYRITZ OUT TO TRANSFORM DODGERS MENTALITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Utility player Jim Leyritz hasn't been much of a factor
since the Los Angeles Dodgers acquired him from the Yankees in a
June 20 deal for Jose Vizcaino. But he's been on championship teams
and understands what it takes to win.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz said one reason the Dodgers collapsed is the team is
still learning how to become a title-contending team, primarily in
the mental approach. He added the talent exists to compete on an
everyday basis, but the mental aspect needs work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a learning process,'' Leyritz said. ``From when
I've been on the outside looking at the Los Angeles Dodgers, it's
always been this team that had a lot of cliques. These guys are
over here, these guys are over here and these guys are over here.
It was never a full team thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was me looking from the outside. When I came here, I can
see the changes. Maybe the two years Fox owned them, it kind of got
out of whack. (Bob) Daly came in, and I think (general manager)
Kevin Malone has brought guys in here that want to win as a team. I
think it's gotten better, but I don't think it's gotten to that
next level yet. But it's definitely a more team-oriented ballclub
than I've seen in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz has been active in scouting meetings before each series
and making sure the information is digested in a useful manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I look at this ballclub, I look at ability first and this
ballclub definitely has that,'' said Leyritz, who built his
big-game reputation playing for the Yankees. ``We have to put it
together in the other facets of the game, as far as the mental
preparation, the scouting reports. It's one thing to have the
scouting report. It's another to make sure we go out and use it.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these guys aren't used to that and haven't seen it in
the past, and now they're learning to do that. Over the long haul,
it out. I've seen flashes of it. From the day I got here until now,
it's definitely been much better.''
</P>
<P>
   __ $100,000 outing: Even though Dodgers right-hander Chan Ho
Park had his worst outing in two months _ he allowed seven runs
(five earned) on 10 hits in five innings _ it was worth $100,000 to
him because he reached a pair of incentive mileposts.
</P>
<P>
   Park's contract calls for him to receive $50,000 for each of his
30th, 31st, 32nd and 33rd starts of the season. He also receives
$50,000 when he reaches 195 innings, 200 innings, 205 innings and
210 innings.
</P>
<P>
   By pitching five innings against the Rockies, Park, whose base
salary is $3.85 million, has amassed 195 innings. It was also his
30th start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   __ More marks in a loss: Third baseman Adrian Beltre's
second-inning homer was the Dodgers' 192nd this season,
establishing a single-season best since the club moved to Los
Angeles. . . . Chris Donnels' pinch-hit homer in the sixth was the
ninth by the Dodgers, tying the club mark. It was also done in 1983
and 1992. It was also Donnels' first homer since Oct. 1, 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2222EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
