<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: VOLLEYBALL  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Americans will be looking for signs of a rebirth. In the
mid- and late-'80s, the Americans were led by Karch Kiraly, a young
player from Southern California. In 1984 and 1988, Kiraly helped
the United States win consecutive gold medals. Then he started to
hit the beach looking for competition, and, perhaps coincidentally,
the United States slowly lost control of the sport to teams like
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the men's team did not even place among the top eight.
The women had fleeting success with a silver in 1984, but have been
overcome lately by teams from Cuba, Russia, China and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   The men's and women's competition will consist of 12 teams: the
top three teams from the most recent World Cup, five winners of
regional tournaments, three teams from Olympic qualifying and the
host nation. Two pools of six teams will compete in a round-robin
format. The top four teams in each pool advance to the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, indoor volleyball was almost forgotten in the hype that
swirled around the debut of beach volleyball. But now new rules are
intended to make volleyball more intense and television friendly.
For the first time, the defense can score, which raises the
intensity and puts more impact on each rally. There is also a
defensive specialist allowed on the floor, and that person will
wear a different-color jersey. The hope is the rule changes will
increase the flow of the game.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCORING
</P>
<P>
   The scoring has also been tinkered with beyond the elimination
of the old side-out format. In the first four sets, athletes now
play to 25 points, while the final set still goes to 15 points. The
set must still be won by two points, with no ceiling to the score.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   The addition of a defensive specialist gives teams a rover. The
rover can be anywhere in the backcourt but cannot serve, spike or
rotate in the front zone. A good specialist can give a team a lift
in rallies and more agility on defense.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban women's team, led by Mireya Luis and Magalys Carrajal,
are the two-time defending Olympic champions. They are the team to
beat, with Russia, China and Brazil in contention. Although they do
not appear to be in the chase for a medal, Tara Cross-Battle and
Logan Tom will lead the U.S. women.
</P>
<P>
   For the men, the countries with developed domestic pro leagues
should dominate. Italy, the Netherlands and Cuba are all in pursuit
of the gold medal. For the U.S. men to succeed, they will need
great performances from the remains of the 1996 team and newcomers
like George Roumain.
</P>
<P>
   BEACH VOLLEYBALL
</P>
<P>
   The site of the competition _ the glitzy Bondi Beach _ has been
almost as big a story as the event. That is hard to pull off. In
its second Olympics, beach volleyball's sex appeal has made it one
of the most popular new sports at the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament has a double-elimination format. Unlike indoor
volleyball, there are just two players on a team and points are
scored only by the serving team. The first team to score 15 points
wins. In the medal round, the first team to score 12 points wins,
and in the third set, a point is scored for every rally regardless
of who is serving.
</P>
<P>
   Kiraly, the player whose name became synonymous with beach
volleyball, separated his shoulder trying to earn a berth on the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Without Kiraly, the Americans will try to hold off the
Brazilians and the Aussies with the team of Dain Blanton and Eric
Fonoimoana.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. women will be led by the combination of Misty May and
Holly McPeak. Once again, the Australians, playing on their home
sand and led by Kerri Potthorst and Natalie Cook, should be
inspired playing in front of their countrymen. Brazil will also
pose a threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
