<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARL REMAINS BUST FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Scott Karl is rusty and needs time. The
Anaheim Angels have no time. So, what to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at our options,'' manager Mike Scioscia said
after the Baltimore Orioles riddled Karl and the Angels 10-3 before
22,332 fans Saturday at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the Angels, whose winning streak came to a halt at
three games, aren't long on options, either.
</P>
<P>
   So, Karl who's gone all of 2, 5 and, Saturday, 3 innings in his
three starts for the Angels since they acquired him last month from
Colorado, will probably continue to take his regular turn, 9.53
earned-run average and all.
</P>
<P>
   Which, Karl insists, is exactly what he needs to shake loose
from the mental agony of trying to pitch in mile-high,
hitter-friendly Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's there,'' Karl said of his missing stuff. ``That
makes it so frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole season has been this way. I'm healthy, my pitches
are breaking correctly . . . but I've gotten to the point I don't
trust my stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was getting knocked out in the Orioles' four-run
fourth inning and leaving with a 6-1 deficit.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't all his doing. A throwing error by shortstop Kevin
Stocker led to two unearned runs in the second. But Karl was cuffed
about for seven hits and he added to his problems by walking three.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels, meantime, managed all of three hits for six innings
against Baltimore right-hander Jose Mercedes, who helped as best he
could: He walked eight, five of them in one inning.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Mercedes (12-5) said, ``I have to say this is one of
the best games I've pitched. Eight walks and one run. I'll take
that anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels simply couldn't take advantage of Mercedes' bends,
grounding into four double plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five walks and one run,'' Scioscia said, replaying the third
inning, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Mercedes) was one pitch away from coming out of the game a
number of times,'' he added. ``We set the table well.''
</P>
<P>
   And un-set it just as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four double plays, obviously, takes the life out of a club,''
Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   So do four-run innings. The Orioles had two of them.
</P>
<P>
   As for Karl, the left-hander fell to 0-2 with the Angels, 2-5
for the season, counting his time in Colorado, which he described
as pret4%-H]v
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000909.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7939 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-WTL-$ADV11-NYT &LR;      09-09 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-WTL-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: WEIGHTLIFTING  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   She is 5 feet 10 inches tall, weighs 300 pounds and is only 17
years old. Her combination of strength, flexibility and
explosiveness also makes Cheryl Haworth the United States' best
chance for a women's medal as the sport makes its Olympic debut for
the female lifters.
</P>
<P>
   But men's weightlifting was included in the first modern
Olympics in 1896 and has been a part of every Games since then
except for 1900, 1908 and 1920.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   The snatch is the first of the two lifts. The bar is placed
horizontally in front of the lifter's legs. It is gripped
palms-downward and pulled in a single movement from the ground to
the full extension of both arms above the head. In order to be
considered a successful lift, the weight must be maintained in the
final, motionless position _ arms and legs extended, with the feet
on the same line _ until the referees give the down signal.
</P>
<P>
   The second of the two lifts, the clean and jerk, is executed in
two stages. In the first part, the clean, the bar is placed
horizontally in front of the lifter's legs. It is gripped
palms-downward and pulled in a single movement from the ground to
the shoulders while bending the legs.
</P>
<P>
   In the second part, the jerk, the athlete bends the legs and
extends them, as well as the arms, so as to bring the bar to the
full stretch of the arms, vertically extended. He returns the feet
to the same line _ arms and legs extended _ and waits for the
referees' signal to put the bar on the platform.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   If Haworth is hoping to make history, so, too, is Naim
Suleymanoglu. Nicknamed ``Pocket Hercules,'' Turkey's 5-foot
featherweight is trying to become the first weightlifter to win
gold in four successive Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Having come out of retirement last year, Suleymanoglu, now 33,
is currently ranked fourth in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Halil Mutlu of Turkey, who won the gold medal in Atlanta in the
56kg division, has dominated his competition and is expected to
defend his title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
