<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC CAPSULE: WATER POLO  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The water member of the soccer/hockey/basketball family can be
ultra physical. It certainly was in 1956 in Melbourne, the last
time the Olympics were held in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   A month after Soviet troops invaded Hungary to put down an
uprising, the Soviet and Hungarian water polo teams met in the
Olympics. The angry Hungarians made the game brutal, and there was
blood in the pool as Hungary won.
</P>
<P>
   THE SETUP
</P>
<P>
   There are 12 men's and six women's teams, each using seven
players, including a goalkeeper. The men will play two six-team
round-robins to qualify for playoffs, with the round-robin winners
meeting for the gold medal. The women, in their Olympic debut, will
play a round-robin, with the top four teams playing for the medals.
The men's pool is 30-by-20 meters (33-by-22 yards) and must be at
least 2 meters (6{ feet) deep. The women's pool is slightly
smaller. A game lasts four seven-minute quarters. Players are not
allowed to touch the bottom or sides of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   THE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   Much like basketball. Most scoring comes from counterattacks
(fast breaks), and if that is foiled, the next options are getting
the ball to the low post (the 2-meter position) or shooting from
the perimeter.
</P>
<P>
   THE NAMES
</P>
<P>
   The strongest teams are the Yugoslav, Hungarian and U.S. men and
the Australian, Dutch and U.S. women. Chris Humbert (6 feet 7
inches, 235 pounds) of Lodi, Calif., is perhaps the world's best
man at the 2-meter position. Coralie Simmons, an attacker from
Hemet, Calif., leads the U.S. women.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
