<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7953 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-ANTIOBIOTICRESISTANCE     09-09 1407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIOBIOTIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIBIOTIC RESISTANCE NOW IS A SERIOUS THREAT TO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
 RESISTANCE-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Hollie Mullin of
Olathe had her first taste of amoxicillin when she was less than a
month old, for an ear infection that was making her fussy and
disturbing her sleep.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her parents insisted on an antibiotic, even though her doctor
advised against it.
</P>
<P>
   Hollie's second prescription for antibiotics came just a month
later. And then she got another, and another. Seventeen
prescriptions in all by her first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   But Hollie's symptoms persisted, and her infection worsened.
</P>
<P>
   Exposed to so many antibiotics, pneumococcal bacteria in
Hollie's ears adapted to the drugs designed to destroy them. They
evolved into superbugs that none of the drugs could kill.
</P>
<P>
   Only one antibiotic was left in the arsenal: vancomycin, one of
the few drugs that could successfully attack such
antibiotic-resistant bacteria. Three times a day for 14 days,
Hollie received intravenous doses.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily that worked.
</P>
<P>
   Cases like Hollie's are becoming all too common, experts say.
Antibiotic resistance, the scourge of hospitals and nursing homes
worldwide, is now a serious threat to children as well.
</P>
<P>
   Cases among children are ``a major contributor to the prevalence
of (antibiotic) resistance as a whole,'' said Matthew Moore, an
infectious- disease expert who monitors antibiotic resistance at
the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Routine childhood problems such as ear and sinus infections are
becoming tougher and more costly to treat. The usual dose of
amoxicillin for ear infections now is three or four times what it
used to be to ensure that the bacteria are killed, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   And more threatening infections such as meningitis are yielding
less willingly to antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Drug-resistant infections are more likely to require
hospitalization. Hospital stays are longer. And the chances of
death are greater.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing two, three antibiotic-resistant cases a week in my
clinic,'' said Lloyd Olson, the infectious-disease expert at
Children's Mercy Hospital who finally cured Hollie with vancomycin.
``Ten years ago I never saw one.'' Sharing the blame
</P>
<P>
   Doctors and parents are to blame, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Parents insist that their children get antibiotics for colds and
other viral infections antibiotics cannot treat. And doctors are
far too willing to prescribe the drugs, even when they know they
will not be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've really painted ourselves into a corner with
antibiotic-resistant bacteria,'' Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   The CDC has a campaign under way involving drug companies,
health departments and managed-care organizations to get doctors to
use antibiotics more sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   Because children under 5 are so frequently doused with
antibiotics, they have the highest rate of antibiotic-resistant
infections of any age group _ as much as twice that of 20- to
40-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   Children also face the greatest risk of running out of effective
antibiotics, said Ronald Jones, a microbiologist with the Sentry
Antimicrobial Surveillance program at the University of Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Many newer antibiotics have not been adequately tested in
children; some older drugs cannot be used for children, because
they inhibit bone growth or cause joint swelling.
</P>
<P>
   The most pressing antibiotic-resistance problem in children is
an infection like Hollie Mullin's that is caused by pneumococcal
bacteria, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   These bacteria are the most common cause of ear infections in
children. When the bacteria invade deep into the body, they can
cause life-threatening blood infections, meningitis, pneumonia and
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Among patients at Children's Mercy, about 45 percent of serious
pneumococcal infections are antibiotic-resistant, hospital figures
show. Nationwide, about 25 percent to 35 percent of all
pneumococcal infections show some resistance. New weapons give hope
</P>
<P>
   There is hope in the form of a newly approved vaccine against
pneumococcal bacteria. In February the CDC's Advisory Committee on
Immunization Practices recommended it for all children under 2.
</P>
<P>
   Most insurance plans, as well as the federal Vaccines for
Children program, are covering the new vaccine. Kansas and Missouri
health officials expect to have it available for low-income
children by mid-September at local health departments, at public
health clinics and through doctors participating in Vaccines for
Children.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine protects against seven strains of the bacteria that
cause 80 percent of pneumococcal disease in children under 6. While
the vaccine is designed to prevent dangerous illnesses such as
meningitis, it may eliminate some ear infections as well.
</P>
<P>
   A study in California by the Kaiser Permanente HMO system found
the vaccine cut the overall rate of ear infections by 8 percent. It
lowered recurrent ear infections _ five or more in a six-month
period _ by 23 percent and reduced by 20 percent the number of
children getting ear tubes to drain infected ears. Excessive drugs
</P>
<P>
   There is plenty of evidence that doctors overprescribe
antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   Preschool children average four to eight colds per year, studies
show. About 70 percent of their upper respiratory infections are
caused by viruses and clear up on their own.
</P>
<P>
   But almost half the children diagnosed with these viral
infections get prescriptions for antibiotics _ even though
antibiotics kill only bacteria and are ineffective against viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Warnings about overprescribing may be working, however. A new
CDC survey of 2,500 doctors shows the antibiotic prescription rate
dropped 34 percent from 1989-90 to 1997-98 for children under age
15. The drop was 12 percent for common problems such as earaches
and bronchitis.
</P>
<P>
   But parental demands still play a big role in whether children
get antibiotics. One recent study found that when doctors thought
parents expected antibiotics for their child's earache, sore
throat, cough or congestion, they prescribed the drugs 62 percent
of the time.
</P>
<P>
   When doctors did not perceive a demand for antibiotics, they
prescribed them to only 7 percent of the children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I know any doctor who hasn't given antibiotics
against his better judgment,'' said Chris Pinkham, a family
practitioner in Kansas City. ``There's a great deal of pressure to
prescribe. Our society is not very tolerant of delayed
gratification.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkham said anxious parents often acted as advocates, demanding
antibiotics to make their child well.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case with Hollie Mullin's parents, Rob and Gail.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very, very unhappy baby. As first-time parents,
that's pretty overwhelming,'' Gail Mullin said. ``We wanted a quick
fix.''
</P>
<P>
   When Hollie's infected ears did not respond to amoxicillin, she
was switched to Augmentin, then Zithromax and Rocephin and
Gantrisin. Her doctors repeatedly suggested holding off on more
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mullins were uncomfortable with that advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would say, `Yeah, yeah,' and in 24 hours I would call in
tears and say she's really sick; put her on antibiotics,'' Gail
Mullin said. ``But we were only making Hollie more sick. We had
created a monster.'' Vaccine suggested
</P>
<P>
   Pneumococci resistant to penicillin and penicillin-related drugs
such as amoxicillin first appeared in Kansas City in 1993, said
Mary Anne Jackson, a physician and infectious disease expert at
Children's Mercy who is working with area doctors to reduce
antibiotic use.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson urges doctors to give children the pneumococcal vaccine.
And she suggests diagnostic tests, such as those available for
strep throat and flu, before prescribing antibiotics. The tests
help determine whether patients have a bacterial infection that
responds to antibiotics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're all trying to do the right thing, but
sometimes they get their arm twisted'' to prescribe antibiotics,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mullins said they had learned a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``You use an antibiotic when you shouldn't and the next time,
it's not going to work,'' Gail Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   Hollie, now almost 3, has been antibiotic-free for more than a
year. She has had a couple of colds, but her parents have not
panicked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, I'd have said, `Rob, she's sick. Let's take her to the
doctor.' Now we shrug our shoulders,'' Gail Mullin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
