<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECHS-HAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALUTING CZECHS' FREEDOM AT LANDMARKS TO LIBERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Also filed in ``i'' category)  
 By JOSEPHINE SCHMIDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Within sight of the statue that has symbolized
freedom to millions of immigrants, Czech-Americans from around the
country gathered on Saturday to meet Vaclav Havel, the man whose
words, wisdom and will gently edged communism from Czechoslovakia,
returning to them a nation and a spiritual home that many thought
they had lost forever.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood before the Manhattan skyline, Havel, the president
of the Czech Republic, said he had long known Ellis Island and the
Statue of Liberty only from literature and photographs.
</P>
<P>
   He evoked memories of those who came to United States to pursue
a new life _ including the Czech settlers who came to escape the
Hapsburg rulers in the 19th and early 20th centuries and who were
the subject of an exhibition that opened on Saturday at Ellis
Island.
</P>
<P>
   But Havel noted: ``The flame of liberty has been spreading
haltingly throughout the world; our country, too, has been free for
the last 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanka Kudej, of Westchester County, who fled Czechoslovakia
after Soviet troops invaded in 1968, said: ``We are so glad to have
back a republic of our own.'' Havel, she said, is the first
president whom many Czechs accept as their own. ``No other
president meant anything to us,'' she said. ``They were only
appointed. This one means freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of the 700 Czechs who traveled to New York from as far
away as New Orleans and Houston, the day offered a chance to get a
glimpse and perhaps a photo of the man who accomplished what few
thought would happen in their lifetimes. So many people were intent
on getting photos, or at least a good view of the president, in
fact, that when Havel _ who came to New York to attend the summit
of world leaders at the United Nations _ and his wife, Dasa,
boarded the ferry to Ellis Island at Battery Park, the boat listed
alarmingly to one side.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Kutil, of Queens County, did not seem so intent on getting
a photo, however. ``I came to say thank you to Havel,'' she said
simply, with her daughter and grandchildren nearby. She recalled
her arrival in the United States 30 years ago, in the wake of the
occupation by Soviet troops, and said she felt tremendous gratitude
toward this country. ``But,'' she said, ``I still feel Czech.''
</P>
<P>
   Zdena Hyblova Heller said that Havel helped reunite her with the
country she left in the 1950s, at the age of 16. When she first
arrived in the United States, she said, she was sure that nothing
would ever change in Czechoslovakia and that she could never go
back, so she turned her back on her Czech past. ``I wanted to be
part of America,'' said Hyblova Heller, a poet who lives in Rye,
N.Y. ``I didn't want to tear my heart out all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But after a peaceful revolution swept Czechoslovakia in 1989,
she returned for the first time, and regained a part of herself.
``I admire Havel, because we both stand for the same things,
basically,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He embodies the hope that the world underneath is somehow
good, and we can dig our way to it.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Ellis Island ceremony, the Havels went to the Bohemian
Hall beer garden in Astoria, N.Y., in Queens County, to plant the
Czech national tree, a linden, before sitting down for goulash and
several mugs of Czech beer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have much hope in those who have not been deformed by
communism,'' Havel said, referring to the generation that is coming
of age in the Czech Republic. ``Freedom is something they take for
granted. Once this generation takes power, that belief will pass
into public life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
