<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7960 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-NOTREDAM     09-09 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NEBRASKA-NOTREDAME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
No. 1 Nebraska survives OT scare against Notre Dame
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SOUTH BEND, Ind. _ Touchdown Jesus wept.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, much of South Bend probably was weeping Saturday
after Nebraska, the No. 1-ranked team in the nation, eked out a
27-24 overtime victory over No. 23 Notre Dame before 80,232 at
Notre Dame Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Irish were supposed to be outclassed and
overmatched against the mighty Cornhuskers, but on this day Notre
Dame, a team that in the past has has relied heavily upon its
storied history for inspiration in big games like this, was on the
verge of making a little history of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, though, the Irish could only come this close to
their biggest upset in recent memory, finally going down when
Nebraska quarterback Eric Crouch turned the corner and scored on a
seven-yard run to finally end Notre Dame's dreams of a miracle
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew it wasn't going to be easy coming into this stadium
and getting out of here with a win,'' Nebraska coach Frank Solich
said. ``It was a great ballgame. I think it lived up to all the
expectations the fans and the media had with all the publicity that
came with this game. I think both teams will be glad to move on
with the rest of their schedules after this one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers (2-0) are more than happy to move along after
almost blowing a 14-point second-half lead. They were considered
virtually invincible, even though they looked decidedly mortal
while sleepwalking through an opening-week, 49-13 victory over San
Jose State.
</P>
<P>
   The Irish (1-1), who entered the game as 13{-point underdogs,
took their first lead of the game at 24-21 after Nick Setta
connected on a 29-yard field goal on the opening series of
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Crouch's touchdown run came right in front of the Notre Dame
student section, most of whom were still frozen in their seats 20
minutes after the game, apparently unable to accept the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   And Crouch's touchdown happened in the shadow of Hesburgh
Memorial Library, on the side of which is the mosaic of Jesus that
is as much a part of the Notre Dame tradition as Knute Rockne and
the Four Horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something that I'll never forget, especially at a place
like Notre Dame,'' Crouch said. ``Just the aura that this place
has. It's real hard for any team rated No. 1 to come in here and
beat these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   But this game was less about mystique than it was about mistakes
_ most of which were committed by the Nebraska special teams, who
allowed Notre Dame to pull off a 100-yard kick return by Julius
Jones and an 83-yard punt return by Joey Getherall to rally and tie
the score.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an area that we're going to have to address,'' Solich
said of the Cornhuskers' special-teams lapses. ``We were, for the
most part, a very good special-teams team last season. But there
was some concern about that entering our fall camp, and those
concerns stayed with us in our first ballgame. And it's still
there, so that is an area we need to address.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a mistake in the Notre Dame pass coverage, though, that
wound up costing the Irish dearly. Faced with a third-and-nine in
overtime, Crouch found tight end Tracey Wistrom with a nine-yard
pass, giving Nebraska four new downs from the 15-yard line. Two
plays later, Crouch, who rushed for 80 yards, rolled left and ran
into the end zone untouched for his third touchdown of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that was the biggest play of the game,'' said Crouch,
who finished 7-of-15 passing for 103 yards, of his third-down pass
to Wistrom. ``That's something we've been working on ever since we
started working on our passing game _ the spread set.''
</P>
<P>
   Notre Dame coach Bob Davie appeared as stunned as the Irish
faithful in the postgame news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our opportunities to win this football game,
particularly with the kickoff return and the punt return,'' said
Davie, who is trying to return his team to national prominence
after a disappointing 5-7 record in 1999. ``It was disappointing,
obviously. To have an opportunity to beat the No. 1 football team
in the nation in your stadium, certainly it is disappointing to all
of us to not come out of there with a win.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a slight hint of controversy to this game _ when is it
ever otherwise at Notre Dame these days? The Irish got the ball
with 59 seconds left but opted to let the clock run out rather than
attempt a desperation play to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that without question that was the right decision to
put that game into overtime,'' Davie said. ``I would do the same
thing 10 out of 10 times again. We get the football back with a
minute left in the game, we have two timeouts and we have a
quarterback (Arnaz Battle) who has completed three passes on the
day (out of 15 attempts but with 107 yards rushing). I wanted to
get that game into overtime and give our team a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Notre Dame didn't completely stop the Cornhuskers'
attack, the Irish did slow it down in the second half. Dan
Alexander, who broke the 200-yard mark in Nebraska's opener, was
held to 112 yards on 24 carries. And Correll Buckhalter, who had
113 yards vs. San Jose State, was held to 43.
</P>
<P>
   The Cornhuskers began the half with a 14-7 lead and quickly
added another seven points when Alexander scored on a 28-yard run.
Jones then took the ensuing kickoff 100 yards for a touchdown to
pull to within 21-14 with 8:30 left in the third quarter, and
Getherall came back just over two minutes into the fourth quarter
with his 83-yard punt return to tie the score and throw a scare
into Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'd like to go through the season without any
tests, but that's the way it works,'' Solich said. ``We have gotten
better because of this football game. I don't think there's any
question about it. I think this will draw us closer together and
help us work on the goal that this team has.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter to me (where the Cornhuskers are ranked this
week). It matters to me if people don't recognize the quality of
game this was and what it took to win this game. Wherever we're at,
(No.) 1, 2 or whatever, we're ready to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
