<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7961 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXAS-LALAFAYETTE     09-09 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-LALAFAYETTE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Applewhite comes off bench to spark Texas in opener
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUSTIN _ Remember me?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no one actually forgot who Major Applewhite was, but
it seemed like his accomplishments the past two seasons as Texas'
starting quarterback had been filed under distant memory.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent memory of Applewhite on the football field was
of him writhing in pain, clutching an injured knee in an
embarrassing loss to Arkansas in the Cotton Bowl eight months ago.
And the two memories immediately before that were of him being
tossed around like a dish rag by Nebraska's Blackshirts defense in
a blowout defeat in the Big 12 Championship Game and of him
vomiting on the sideline before a loss at Texas A&AMP;M last year.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Applewhite, who did not start for only the second time
in 25 games, moved his file from distant memory to random access
memory, as he led Texas to a 52-10 romp over Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   The junior entered the game to a thunderous applause from the
80,017 in attendance, subbing for sophomore Chris Simms with 1:27
left in the first quarter and Texas trailing 10-0. By the half,
Applewhite had thrown for 246 yards and two touchdowns and Texas
scored 31 unanswered points, its most points in a quarter in more
than 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said that I didn't have a feeling that might
happen,'' Applewhite said of his not starting. ``There's more than
just one way to handle the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can say `fine' and just accept it, or you can pout, or you
can accept it and keep working hard, or you can accept and
understand that college football changes like (a snap of the
fingers). But just as quickly as things changed today, they could
change next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms didn't want to leave the game when he was pulled, but he
said he understood the move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized that Major was going in and he was going to go in
sooner or later,'' Simms said. ``The offense, we didn't get it done
when I was in there, and he came in and they got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no word from Texas coaches on the possibility of a
change in the starter for next week at Stanford, but Applewhite
definitely made a case for a switch, and it appeared to be as easy
as a snap of the fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Texas went into its ``one-minute'' offense, with Applewhite in
the shotgun, going without huddles after all completions.
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite, who completed 18 of 26 passes for 315 yards,
directed the Longhorns to seven consecutive scoring drives (none
that took longer than 2:19), before giving way to Simms midway
through the third period with Texas ahead comfortably 45-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them are starting quarterbacks, and we've said that
all week,'' Texas coach Mack Brown said. ``It wasn't that Major got
beaten out by Chris at all. It wasn't a competition. But we were
hoping that Chris would have a great day and Major would come in
and have a great day and we'd have them both ready for next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, what happened is Chris had some bad luck. Major
came in and had a great day, and Chris came back and had a great
day. So, we're back to where we started. We have two starting
quarterbacks and you might as well not ask, because I'm not going
to say anything about next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised that Major was able to play so well, coming
off a knee operation, and I was really pleased to see that for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The long unanswered question of who would start at quarterback
for the Longhorns was answered when Simms took the field with the
first unit for the first two series of downs, but things did not go
well.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns managed three first downs during their first two
possessions.
</P>
<P>
   After Louisiana-Lafayette took the opening kick and went 77
yards in 15 plays to score on a Brent Bergeron 21-yard field goal,
Texas moved into Ragin' Cajuns territory but did not convert as
Kris Stockton missed a 52-yard field-goal attempt.
</P>
<P>
   The next time the Longhorns took over, Simms, while scrambling
to his right, threw a poor pass that was intercepted by the Ragin'
Cajuns' Terrence Hunter and returned 43 yards for a touchdown to
put Louisiana-Lafayette up 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Applewhite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't jerk Chris because of the interception,'' Brown
said. ``We just felt like it would be a good time to settle
everybody down. We thought we'd still win the game (by a wide
margin), which would give us a chance to come back with Chris and
let him get settled.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms, who finished 7-of-14 passing for 88 yards, returned with
8:04 remaining in the third quarter to lead Texas on a four-play,
50-yard drive that he capped with a nice scramble and toss to
Hodges Mitchell for a 13-yard touchdown to end the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to look at the big picture,'' Simms said. ``I know
Major came out and (played well), but it's not like next week. I
have to go out and catch up with his yardage and whatever. It
doesn't matter. It's all about playing well and getting the `W.'''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
