<HEADER>
A7963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT     09-09 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PHILLIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILLIES BEAT METS, 6-3 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the frustration was going to show on the Mets
Saturday night, at least they expressed it safely. Unlike Mike
Hampton, who had toppled a pair of water coolers on Friday night,
Turk Wendell merely tossed his glove into the stands as he walked
off the mound, eliciting the few cheers from the Shea Stadium crowd
during the game. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had good reason to toss gloves, bats or just about
anything else they could find as their September troubles
continued. The bats were silent again, almost a given by now, but
on Saturday night, the gloves failed, too, or at least the glove of
the usually steady Edgardo Alfonzo. Alfonzo, the second baseman,
committed two errors in the seventh inning, helping the
Philadelphia Phillies to a pair of runs and a 6-3 victory that sent
the Mets to their third consecutive loss and their seventh in eight
games since the calendar rolled around to September.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets fell four games behind Atlanta, which played Montreal
Saturday night. In the wild-card race, Arizona picked up a game on
the Mets and is now three and a half games behind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo had just given the Mets their first run in two nights
with a two-out, run-scoring double in the bottom of the sixth,
evening the score at 1-1. But he allowed one ball to bound past him
and then another to slip through his hands. And the Mets had found
a new way to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets managed six hits off the former Met Robert Person and a
procession of Philadelphia pitchers, closing the gap to 3-2 on
Derek Bell's solo homer in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   It took just three outs to see that the Mets' troubles were not
going to be solved by closed-door meetings, just as they had not
been solved by the arrival of the league's worst team. A 2-0
shutout on Friday was followed by a closed-door meeting after the
game and then Saturday night by blanks from Person. In the first
inning, Bell was retired on a hard line drive that shortstop Alex
Arias went to his knees to snag. With two runners on and two out,
Robin Ventura battled from 0-2 to work the count full, and he
ripped a line drive down the first-base line, right at Brian
Hunter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Timo Perez drilled a single to right. When Bell
laced a 1-0 pitch back through the box for an apparent hit, Perez
was running, bringing Marlon Anderson over to cover second base.
Anderson easily scooped up the grounder, stepped on the bag and
started a double play to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing the same baseball we were playing when we won 30
out of 40 or 20 out of 30 and everyone said, `Gee, they're the most
well-balanced team,''' Manager Bobby Valentine said before the
game. ``We're the exact same team playing the exact same way, just
misfiring on a few hits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets got more of those line drives that could not find a
hole Saturday night, and at times they felt as if they were not
even being given the opportunity to hit the ball hard. In the
second inning, Mike Bordick signaled for a timeout just as Person
was starting his windup, but the home plate umpire, Travis
Katzenmeier, did not grant it. Bordick quickly adjusted, grounding
weakly to shortstop and then glaring at Katzenmeier as he ran to
first. Bordick returned down the baseline, arguing his case
unsuccessfully. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If their bats were not waking from their September slumber, the
Mets were at least hanging even thanks to the arm of Glendon Rusch
(9-11), as well as the glove of Bell. Rusch eased through the first
three innings, as Hampton had on Friday night. But Hampton was
undone by a two-run homer by Scott Rolen. This time, Pat Burrell's
bid for a solo blast was foiled by Bell, who snared the ball at the
top of the wall in right field. With that bit of help, Rusch
extended his string of scoreless innings to a career-high 16 as the
teams remained in a scoreless tie through five innings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But in the sixth inning, the Mets slipped over the fine line
they had been straddling and fell behind again as Burrell lined a
double just over the head of Perez, scoring Doug Glanville, who had
singled and stolen second.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets finally scored their first run in two nights, evening
the score at 1-1 in the bottom of the sixth when Matt Franco,
pinch-hitting for Rusch, worked out a walk and, after moving to
second on a groundout, scored on a double by Alfonzo.
</P>
<P>
   But Alfonzo uncharacteristically gave the run right back in the
top of the seventh, allowing a hard grounder by Bobby Abreu to get
through for an error, putting runners on second and third with none
out. Travis Lee then scored on a sacrifice fly to center by
Glanville, beating the throw from Perez. After an intentional walk,
Burrell lined a single to right to score Abreu.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, Hunter sealed the Phillies' victory with a
three-run homer off Armando Benitez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
