A7965 &Cx1f; kan-z
r n BC-ROBINSONLETTERS 2TAKES-KAN &LR;    09-09 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBINSON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT JOHN E. ROBINSON SR.'S PAST INDICATES A TALENT FOR
FORGERY 
</HEADLINE>
 LETTERS, 2 TAKES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Rick Montgomery  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At face value a 1985
letter bearing the signature of Lisa Stasi left a hopeful farewell
from a struggling young mother who has been missing ever since.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was typed by someone who used poor punctuation and a heavy
thumb on the space bar, leaving long gaps between words.
</P>
<P>
   The same gaffes appear in another goodbye _ a note signed ``Love
ya, Paula.'' That letter is thought to have been written about the
time Paula Godfrey vanished in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   But the most telling similarity: Both letters share the same
typeface _ a typewriter print with oddly shaped characters,
according to a document examiner hired last month by The Kansas
City Star.
</P>
<P>
   Those unusual ``j's'' and ``l's'' also surface on a 1984
document prepared by John Edward Robinson Sr. and filed with the
Kansas secretary of state's office.
</P>
<P>
   The letters of Stasi and ``Paula'' now are in the hands of
murder investigators, who list the two among the possible victims
of Robinson, suspected of being a serial killer.
</P>
<P>
   If genuine, the farewell notes would portray two 19-year-old
women who chose to leave the Kansas City area and build new lives.
</P>
<P>
   But doubtful investigators know that Robinson's past is a
criminal archive of suspicious paper. In fact, 30 years of court
records cast him as a prolific man of letters _ forged, fabricated
and otherwise faked.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of The Star, Stephen C. McKasson, a document
examiner who has worked for the Illinois State Police and the U.S.
Postal Inspection Service crime labs, studied nearly three dozen
photocopied correspondences, public documents and professional
certificates related to Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   What McKasson found, he said, appeared to be the handiwork of an
``intermediate'' forger and cut-and-paste artist _ clever enough to
use at least three different machines for typing documents but
clumsy enough to leave telltale traces of a common author.
</P>
<P>
   McKasson speculated that the letters purportedly written by
Stasi and ``Paula'' might have been composed on the same
typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   His guess: a common IBM Selectric on which users could install
different typefaces or fonts by replacing the type ball.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to the unusual ``J's'' and lowercase ``l's'', ``that's
a typeface I'm not familiar with,'' said McKasson, who has nearly
30 years of experience in identifying forgeries.
</P>
<P>
   Because The Star could provide him only photocopies of the
letters, however, McKasson said he could not determine with
certainty that the same typewriter was used.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Evans, the Kansas attorney leading Robinson's defense,
declined to comment Saturday. Paper chain
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 56, faces murder charges in the disappearance of Stasi
and in the deaths of four other women and a disabled teen-age girl
whose bodies turned up in barrels on property he controlled.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been charged in connection with Godfrey's
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   The letters may be part of prosecutors' efforts to establish
that Robinson _ a career con artist with a penchant for forgery _
took steps to make people believe that missing women linked to him
had left the area and were still alive.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson crossed paths with Stasi and her infant daughter
Tiffany in January 1985, as he was promoting a charity program
supposedly aimed at helping young mothers in need. Stasi's
relatives told police that Robinson made her sign blank sheets of
paper before she disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey had met Robinson several months earlier. According to
her father, Bill Godfrey, she disappeared after telling the family
she was headed to Texas to take clerical training courses arranged
by Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   The Star provided Godfrey's father a copy of the ``Paula''
letter, which the newspaper obtained in July from the widow of one
of Robinson's business associates. Bill Godfrey said the signature,
with its extravagant capital ``P,'' was not his daughter's.
</P>
<P>
   Godfrey reportedly worked for Robinson and thus might have had
access to an office typewriter. Stasi, however, appeared to have
known Robinson only a few days before vanishing from an Overland
Park hotel. He paid for the room after picking up Stasi and Tiffany
at a battered women's shelter, court records state.
</P>
<P>
   Other documents obtained by The Star point to a chain of
suspicious papers linked to Robinson having nothing to do with
missing persons, but which portray a man seemingly bent on
deceiving people.
</P>
<P>
   As far back as the 1960s, when he worked locally as an X-ray
technician, a variety of medical certificates on his office wall
raised the eyebrows of co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   McKasson examined photocopies of four certificates from medical
technologist associations proclaiming Robinson certified in X-ray,
nuclear medicine and medical laboratory technologies. His two-year
stint at a junior college in Illinois didn't provide such courses,
and trade organizations found no record of Robinson ever being
certified.
</P>
<P>
   McKasson said that the lettering of Robinson's name was
identical in all four certificates. That coincidence and
irregularities in the documents hinted at a cut-and-paste job, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Davis, a former neighbor of Robinson's, said he was not
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s Robinson took Davis to his Overland Park,
Kan., consulting office, which had a word processor, a paper cutter
and a photocopier. Robinson demonstrated how to cut a signature
from one letter, paste it to another and dab on correction fluid to
produce a phony document, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To my eyes, it looked ... good,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Robinson soon had a falling out when, according to
Davis, Robinson used his cut-and-paste skills to forge a letter
intended to cheat Davis' father out of money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
