<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7972 &Cx1f; kan-z
r n BC-ROBINSONLETTERS TAKE2-KAN &LR;    09-09 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBINSON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT JOHN E. ROBINSON SR.'S PAST INDICATES A TALENT FOR
FORGERY 
</HEADLINE>
 LETTERS, TAKE 2-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Rick Montgomery  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   Davis and Robinson soon had a falling
out when, according to Davis, Robinson used his cut-and-paste
skills to forge a letter intended to cheat Davis' father out of
money.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Godfrey and Stasi disappeared, Robinson was serving
probation on a 1981 conviction for stealing from an ex-employer,
Guy's Foods in Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   His probation officer, Steve Haymes, learned of Robinson's links
to the missing women and pressed Clay County prosecutors in 1985 to
revoke the probation and put Robinson behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson fought back, hiring a nonprofit organization to compile
a booklet outlining his civic deeds and volunteer activities for
Clay County Circuit Judge John Hutcherson's consideration.
</P>
<P>
   The booklet included several letters, including one seemingly
written on University of Kansas stationery by a dean. It thanks
John and Nancy Robinson for their $2,000 donation to an education
fund.
</P>
<P>
   University officials last month said they could find no record
of the Robinsons making such a donation. And even if the couple had
donated, a thank-you note would not have come from the university's
Office of Admissions, as indicated in the letterhead.
</P>
<P>
   Fishy letters, in fact, filled the Robinson booklet prepared by
the National Center on Institutions and Alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   A letter of reference signed by Joe Ensminger, who headed a
Kansas association of referees, chimed: ``I know John Robinson as a
fine person and am proud to call him a friend.''
</P>
<P>
   They did become acquainted when Robinson was a school volleyball
referee in the 1980s. But Ensminger said last week, ``I did not
write that letter.''
</P>
<P>
   How did it appear on Ensminger's own stationery, under the
letterhead of his organization _ the Sunflower Officials
Association?
</P>
<P>
   Simple, he said. When Robinson joined the organization, ``one of
the first things he said was, `You need some stationery and some
business cards. I'll get them for you,' '' Ensminger recalled.
``And he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Ensminger said his signature was ``a pretty good replica,''
except for one botched ``e'' and the fact that Ensminger's name
appeared at the bottom left corner instead of the bottom right.
</P>
<P>
   Document expert McKasson noticed slightly jittery, labored
penmanship in Ensminger's signature and in several other letters
included in the court booklet on Robinson. Such an effect might
result from tracing signatures on a light table, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awkward, tremorous, hesitant style to many of these
signatures, which certainly suggests slowness in the writing,''
McKasson said. ``They just look funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Case in point: a 1985 letter supposedly typed and signed by
``Linda White,'' unknown to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Robinson's own signature _ rushed and illegible
beyond its capital ``J'' and ``R'' _ Linda White's signature
resembles a grade school pupil's, with slow, rudimentary strokes.
</P>
<P>
   McKasson said forgers whose natural handwriting was sloppy
sometimes resorted to ``copybook form'' when concocting a
signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if they go back to concentrating how they were taught
to write in second grade, trying to bring back the letter forms as
they appeared on the blackboard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The content of the Linda White letter is as intriguing as the
signature.
</P>
<P>
   The writer described herself as a jobless, pregnant mother of
three when she met Robinson through a social-service contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Christmas eve, Mr. Robinson and his children brought boxes
of things over to the house,'' the letter stated. ``There were
socks, underwear and clothes for all the kids, several toys for
each of the kids and food for Christmas day and enough for a week
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could'nt (sic) believe that anyone could be so nice to
people they did'nt (sic) even know....I had my baby in January and
because of the help and encouragement I received from Mr. Robinson
and his wife, I decided to keep my baby....
</P>
<P>
   ``My family and I are greatful (sic) to the Robinson's (sic) and
it makes us all feel good to know that there are people like them
around.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the typographical errors and misplaced apostrophes _
which crop up in Robinson's own writings _ the computer-generated
look of the letter caught McKasson's eye.
</P>
<P>
   Its typeface, spacing and straight margins on both sides
replicated a 1982 letter to Boy Scout leaders, written and signed
by ``Your friend in Scouting, John Robinson.''
</P>
<P>
   Few word processors at the time were capable of producing such
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever computer Robinson used, ``it was darned-near state of
the art,'' McKasson said.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte Bowersock said she just followed orders.
</P>
<P>
   As a secretary for Professional Services Association _ a medical
consulting firm run by Robinson in the mid-1970s _ Bowersock was
instructed to type and sign fraudulent letters aimed at convincing
investors that Robinson's company was on a fast track.
</P>
<P>
   At least two of those letters prompted a federal grand jury to
indict Robinson for fraud. The jurors compelled Bowersock to
testify, but they did not indict her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 24 years old, five months pregnant and naive as all get
out,'' she said in a recent interview. She earned about $7 per
hour, a comfortable wage at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was literally paid to keep my mouth shut'' about the schemes
of her boss.
</P>
<P>
   Working in a Raytown office building also occupied by a dentist,
a lawyer and a financial adviser, Robinson provided Bowersock
handwritten scripts and ``several copies of different kinds of
letterhead,'' she said. ``He told me to find different typewriters
around the building'' to compose the letters.
</P>
<P>
   As Bowersock typed, Robinson tried to ease her suspicions. He
said he knew the people associated with the forged letters. Because
of their busy schedules, they had given their OK for Robinson's
company to write the letters and to sign their names, he assured
her.
</P>
<P>
   One letter that triggered Robinson's indictment was a phony
announcement from the dean of dentistry at the University of
Missouri-Kansas City, claiming that Robinson had been voted a full
professor.
</P>
<P>
   Another letter, purportedly written by an executive at Kansas
City-based Marion Laboratories Inc., suggested that the drug
manufacturer was considering acquiring Robinson's company.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge fined Robinson $2,500 and placed him on three
years of probation for defrauding investors.
</P>
<P>
   But he kept putting lies on paper.
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, while running a consulting firm called Equi-Plus,
Robinson allegedly sent inflated bills and doctored invoices to a
client wishing to market back-care seminars. Amid Robinson's firm
denials, his attorney, Ronald Wood, advised Robinson to secure
sworn affidavits from associates and subcontractors stating that
the invoices were legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson obliged. Wood presented the affidavits to a Johnson
County, Kan., judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They turned out to be bogus, too,'' Wood recalled. ``He makes
up a forgery to cover up other forgeries. I couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   A jury in 1986 convicted Robinson of theft by deception in the
back-care case. Another jury soon found him guilty of writing a
false document in an Arizona condominium swindle.
</P>
<P>
   Does this paper trail of forgery lead to murder?
</P>
<P>
   McKasson said the documents he examined did not prove that
Robinson killed anybody.
</P>
<P>
   But they may help authorities who hope to build a case that
Robinson is his own worst concoction _ clumsy con man and stealthy
serial killer, forged into one.
</P>
<P>
   The Star's Lee Hill Kavanaugh contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
