<HEADLINE>
UNWANTED RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 ... CORRECTS NEWSPAPER AFFILIATION (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Mo Vaughn's ninth-inning strikeout Saturday
was No. 157 for the season, breaking Reggie Jackson's single-season
Anaheim Angels record, set in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a career-high _ low? _ for Vaughn, who led the
American League in whiffs with 150 in 1995. He's headed for the
A.L. strikeout ``title'' again this season. And No. 2 in the A.L.
in strikeouts is Angels teammate Troy Glaus, at 139.
</P>
<P>
   Four times in his 10-year career Vaughn has fanned 150 or more
times.
</P>
<P>
   __ Not so Wise: Matt Wise will miss at least one turn in the
starting rotation because of ``a fatigued elbow,'' something the
rookie right-hander said shouldn't keep him sidelined too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It flares up once in a while,'' he said. ``Hopefully, it's
jujst a one-start thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise, who was scheduled to start this evening's game against the
Orioles, has made six starts since he was summoned from Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Al Levine (3-4) will take Wise's spot. It will be
Levine's third career start and second this year.
</P>
<P>
   __ Running away: Darin Erstad moved into 10th place on the
Angels' single-season runs-scored list when he walked and
eventually scored run No. 104 in the third inning. The club record
for runs in a season is 120, established by Jim Edmonds in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   __ Trading up: The Dodgers' Pedro Martinez-for-Delino DeShields
trade before the 1994 season may go down as the worst in baseball
history.
</P>
<P>
   But at least DeShields is showing again why the Dodgers had
interest in him.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday he had two hits and drove in three runs for the
Orioles. In his last 37 games DeShields is hitting at .348 clip
with 23 runs batted in and 19 runs scored. For the season he's
hitting he's hitting .302.
</P>
<P>
   ptsub Familiar tune
</P>
<P>
   Here's an example of real interleague
</P>
<P>
   Filling in at the organ Saturday for the Angels' Peggy Duquenel
was Nancy Bea Hefley, the Dodgers' longtime organist.
</P>
<P>
   __ Prince Hatch?: Manager Mike Scioscia has a new nickname for
his longtime buddy, the irrepressible Mickey Hatcher, the Angels'
hitting coach: ``Hatch Patkin,'' a spinoff on the late Max Patkin,
known as the ``Clown Prince of Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently Hatcher isn't wild about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got too many teeth,'' complained Hatcher, with his
characteristic smile. ``Max had only one tooth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
