<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-FOUNTAINWOES-KAN &LR;      09-09 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUNTAIN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM OF A RIVER FOUNTAIN FACES MANY PRACTICAL HURDLES 
</HEADLINE>
 WOES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Jeffrey Spivak and James A. Fussell  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ If it's Louisville,
Ky., on the phone, Kansas City might not want to answer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The reason: one towering but problematic fountain.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people lined Louisville's riverfront and jammed
bridges to see the flowerlike spray when it was first turned on in
1988. But over a decade, the fountain broke down continually. It
was turned off for good two years ago, and now Louisville officials
are trying to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   And Kansas City, of course, is in the market for a megafountain.
</P>
<P>
   A civic group involved in Kansas City's 150th birthday in June
proposed ``the world's largest river fountain.'' It was the most
visually compelling of the group's ``giant steps'' for the future.
Top foundations are interested in funding steps like the fountain,
and the first fountain-planning meeting is scheduled next week.
</P>
<P>
   The thing is, creating such a fountain is tricky and risky. Some
river fountains dazzle and others disappoint; some last decades and
others meet untimely deaths. Pittsburgh's gets shown on TV when
that city is host to Monday Night Football, and couples get married
next to Chicago's. Yet Louisville's and New York City's turned into
embarrassments.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson for Kansas City: A river fountain can be an
attraction, but only if it's working. So building one, authorities
in other cities say, can't be done cheaply or without careful
planning. The most successful ones don't even use river water _ and
Kansas City's may not have to, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do it willy-nilly,'' said Phil Miller, who has
studied river fountains as the construction manager for one now
being built along the riverfront in Dayton, Ohio. ``You need to do
it first-class.''
</P>
<P>
   When a KC150 committee unveiled the ``giant steps,'' former
Kansas Citian Win Koerper received a telephone call in Arizona.
``They've got your idea, Win,'' an old friend told him.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Koerper in the 1960s had tried selling Kansas City's
tourism bureau on a heart-shaped river fountain _ symbolizing the
``heart of America.'' He had developed a fondness for fountains
while working for fountain-loving Joyce Hall, Hallmark's founder.
Then he moved to Phoenix to run his own advertising firm there.
</P>
<P>
   Now he wants to resurrect his fountain idea in Kansas City _ and
this time, civic leaders are listening.
</P>
<P>
   Koerper will meet Tuesday with representatives from the Hall
Family Foundation, which is interested in financing the fountain,
and the City of Fountains Foundation, which is spearheading the
planning.
</P>
<P>
   The foundations and some other civic leaders regard a river
fountain as one way to draw Kansas Citians back to the Missouri
River. As Arthur S. Brisbane, publisher of The Kansas City Star and
co-chairman of the ``giant steps'' committee, explained: ``We are
the City of Fountains, to begin with, and...(the committee) saw the
river fountain as a way to recapture the river and riverfront as a
dramatic site for Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   With his fountain, Koerper foresees two water sprays going up
diagonally and then curving downward, forming the top loops of a
heart. Maybe, he thinks, it could be hundreds of feet high, like
the tallest fountains in the world. And maybe there could be a
covered boardwalk that juts into the river and screens sightseers
from the fountain's falling mist.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could be a pretty awesome experience,'' Koerper said.
``It could be like Niagara Falls.''
</P>
<P>
   River fountains can instantly become attractions, overnight
sensations, civic jewels.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, a 200-foot-high geyser off Point State Park in
the Ohio River ``has taken on the role as the signature feature''
of that city, according to a regional parks manager. In Chicago,
tourists gather every hour downtown to see an arc of water shoot
210 feet across the Chicago River for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, a 450-foot-high geyser in the East River off
Manhattan was seen as ``a majestic addition, matching the Empire
State Building and Radio City,'' according to the
publisher-turned-philanthropist who bankrolled it. And in
Louisville, after the Falls Fountain's popular opening, the tourism
bureau dubbed it the ``symbol of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Instant glitter and pride, with none of them costing more than
$5 million in today's dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Louisville's fountain stopped running after 12
problem-plagued years, and New York's lasted 17 years until it
stopped working in 1986. Pittsburgh's was off for most of 1996
because of damage from a flood. And another famed fountain built in
water, a 500-foot-high geyser in a Phoenix suburb called Fountain
Hills, was closed this year for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   So just what is Kansas City getting into? That depends on
whether Kansas City repeats other cities' mistakes, or learns from
them.
</P>
<P>
   The major pitfalls, according to a half-dozen officials involved
with other river fountains: using river water and underestimating
maintenance costs.
</P>
<P>
   River water is full of sediment and bacteria that clog filters,
burn out pumps and eat through pipes and nozzles.
</P>
<P>
   New York City's fountain spewed brown, sewage-tinged water until
city health inspectors demanded chlorination equipment; then the
chlorinated water drew fire from environmental activists.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh avoided those problems by tapping into a freshwater
aquifer some 50 feet below ground. Now Dayton is doing the same
thing for its star-shaped fountain. ``We were concerned we wouldn't
be able to operate with river water,'' Dayton's Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has a similar aquifer under the Big Muddy's flood
plain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be plenty of ground water down there,'' said
Robert Smith, a regulatory manager with the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   As for maintenance, river fountains require constant care. A
Pittsburgh official calls the daily routine of cleaning screens and
checking equipment a ``headache'' and like ``running a large
swimming pool.'' Then there are river logs that crash into such
fountains. Plus, electricity alone runs about $10,000 a month for
some river fountains.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville's Bingham family originally set aside $500,000 for a
maintenance endowment, but that fountain _ eventually ridiculed as
a ``wet elephant'' _ washed away that money in a few years. And New
York City's fountain philanthropist, George Delacorte, kept paying
thousands of dollars in repair bills until he decided to stop
paying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would expect that anything done would be endowed, and there
would be money set aside for its perpetual maintenance,'' said Bill
Hall, president of the Hall Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, boosters of a river fountain in Kansas City may face
some challenges that didn't turn up in other cities.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the Corps of Engineers won't allow a fountain in
the middle of the Missouri River, where it might disrupt barge
traffic. For another thing, the Federal Aviation Administration
might limit the height of the fountain because of the nearby
Downtown Airport.
</P>
<P>
   If so, it might stifle Kansas City's stab at ``world's largest
river fountain.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Guinness Book of Records, the world's largest
fountain, in or out of a river, is the 600-foot-tall Gateway Geyser
on the bank of the Mississippi River in East St. Louis, Ill. But
the tallest river fountain, at least in this country, is believed
to be Pittsburgh's, at 200 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Garney, a Northland developer and longtime City of
Fountains Foundation board member, summed up the situation best:
``I think a lot more work needs to be done to exhaust all the
possibilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
