<HEADER>
A7975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     09-09 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T BELIEVE THE PARTY LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They are unofficial holidays, arriving in New England every
fifth day. These Pedro Days have been part of the local culture for
only three years, but they have already been victimized by holiday
cliche: You have a barbecue, turn your sound system up to the
maximum, watch the fireworks, go home, and wait for the next
opportunity to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Pedro Martinez, the one-man parade, can do to you.
He is so consistent (58-16 since 1998) that a loss is surprising.
He is so good that you can find yourself in some ridiculous sports
arguments with Pedro as the subject. For example, try telling
someone that this season _ 16-5, 1.74 ERA _ is his best and they
just might call you an idiot. Imagine. You're saying a season in
which a pitcher has allowed 38 earned runs is his best and someone
thinks you're nuts for having that opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Being around Martinez also will lead you into some expectations
that are not normal for professional sports. It is simply not
normal for one great athlete to go out and dominate others, over
and over. Tiger Woods does it often, but not at every tournament.
Larry Bird didn't always do it. Michael Jordan didn't. Bobby Orr
didn't. Joe Montana didn't. Martina Navratilova didn't. But when
these local holidays come, with their ``K'' cards and chants and
merengue and items color-coordinated with the Dominican flag
(Saturday it was a Dominican-flag car at the corner of Yawkey Way
and Van Ness), the expectation is that things will go as normal.
</P>
<P>
   Even if normal as we know it is truly abnormal. A 1.74 ERA in
the year 2000? Nearly 230 more strikeouts than walks? A pitcher who
is always expected to win, give the bullpen a rest, and keep a
desperate team afloat?
</P>
<P>
   You don't usually see that in professional sports.
</P>
<P>
   If you are 28 years old and perform brilliantly most of the
time, that makes you a very good, young athlete. If you perform
brilliantly all the time, it makes you, basically, Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro is good. He's not Mozart.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday in Fenway Park, the Yankees beat Martinez and the Red
Sox, 5-3. Martinez lost when everyone, including some people in the
home clubhouse, expected him to win. Of course, not many players
will say that they expect Martinez to carry them, even though it
would be difficult for them to feel otherwise. They have the
equivalent of all-access passes, traveling across North America
with this pitching artist. We know he's good; they know the insider
details of his greatness, which allows them to put his mastery into
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   How could they not be guilty of leaning on him too much? They
can be forgiven for being Pedro dependents. Dan Duquette, though,
has no excuse.
</P>
<P>
   New York's win pushed its lead in the American League East to
eight games with 23 to play. That means the Sox are a $90 million
team that will need handouts to get where it is trying to go. If
the Sox are going to be a part of the playoffs this season, they
will have to fully embrace the second-place mentality. They will
have to equip themselves with wild-card vision, always looking at
other teams for help while trying to win themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Jimy Williams. The fatalistic, play-the-schedule
philosophy no longer is applicable.
</P>
<P>
   The best the Sox can do without anyone else's help is reduce the
New York lead to six games. They can do that by winning Sunday at
Fenway and Monday at Yankee Stadium. A win Sunday also would help
silence the strong New York presence in the Fenway seats. Yankee
fans have been so loud here that a pleased Joe Torre estimated that
they made up 30 percent of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough to start a fight,'' Torre said, referring to
the frequent tussles that usually end with handcuffs and police
escorts out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   Torre seemed relaxed before the game. He acknowledged that
winning three out of four against Boston would allow the Yankees to
pick up the scent of the division title. He said his team would
have to ``die'' with an eight-game lead this late. He mentioned
teams that have lost bulges like that, but behind his sunglasses
you could sense an ``It ain't gonna happen to us'' gaze.
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen to the Yankees because they are built
differently than the Sox. Their foundation is such that they never
would find themselves in the situation the Sox were in Saturday:
expected to win simply because one, 170-pound man was starting.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of dependence is not normal.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of dependence is not fair.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of dependence, most importantly, is no way to win a
championship.
</P>
<P>
   While the regional myth is that the Yankees are better because
they have more money to spend, the reality is that they are better
because they know how to spend the money that they have. If you
gave wads of cash to someone who didn't know anything about
fashion, they still would return from a shopping trip with bags of
bad clothes. Money is cool; you just have to know what you're doing
with it. Ask Peter Angelos and the fans in Baltimore about that.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the talk about George Steinbrenner's loot, New
York's best players were either developed in their farm system or
acquired in wow-look-what-came-up-in-the-laundry deals. Roberto
Kelly was traded for Paul O'Neill. Derek Jeter was the No. 6 pick
in the 1992 draft. Scott Brosius, the man who changed Saturday's
game by guessing correctly on a Martinez offspeed pitch, was a
player to be named in the Kenny Rogers deal. Bernie Williams,
Mariano Rivera, and Andy Pettitte _ Saturday's winning pitcher _
were draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Big Three were acquired via the draft (Nomar
Garciaparra), and trades (Carl Everett, Martinez). Duquette
deserves credit for that. But what about the rest of the team? Why
does he have so much money tied in to mediocrity? Is this all $90
million gets you these days? A great pitcher and hope that your
playoff prayers are answered? The money lament is convenient, but
it has nothing to do with the fact that the Sox still play poor
infield defense. That's the reason they lost to the Yankees last
fall, and they still haven't gotten better.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez smiled and, before leaving, said the team will still
make the playoffs. ``We beat Cleveland three in a row in the
playoffs, didn't we?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes. But they didn't have enough to keep winning. They had and
have the kind of team that could bring you a local, Pedro holiday.
The Yankees had the kind of team that could bring you a local,
World Series celebration holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail
at holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
