u s BC-OLY-SWM-THORPE-$ADV11     09-09 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWM-THORPE-$ADV11-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG FEET, BIGGER SPLASH FOR AUSTRALIAN  
 (FOR RELEASE MONDAY, SEPT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a country where swimming is the most popular Olympic sport,
where important meets draw prime-time television exposure and
exorbitant ratings, it is a 17-year-old named Ian Thorpe who has
Australia entranced.
</P>
<P>
   His trips to the movies and club-hopping nights on the town make
the gossip pages. Every woman he is photographed with draws the
kind of urgent conjecture that once attended May Day photographs of
the Kremlin hierarchy. When he travels, the hotel rooms on either
side of him are taken by security guards, lest overzealous fans
induce a hard day's night.
</P>
<P>
   The first evening of the Sydney Olympics, all of Australia will
be captivated by this 6-foot-5-inch, 210-pound teen-ager with size
17 feet, who will swim the 400-meter freestyle to win a gold medal,
and perhaps to lower his own world record of 3 minutes 41.33
seconds. The Thorpedo, as he is known, is also favored in the 200
freestyle _ his world record is 1:45.41 _ and he will swim for a
third gold medal in the 800-meter freestyle relay.
</P>
<P>
   So dominant is Thorpe that his teammate, Michael Klim, the 1998
world champion in the 200-meter freestyle, will skip the event in
Sydney. Thorpe is modest, mature beyond his years and quietly
confident. He is also a millionaire who enjoys dabbling in day
trading of stocks. Don Talbot, the 67-year-old Australian Olympic
coach, said he has never seen a more capable swimmer in five
decades of international experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a better swimmer than him,'' Talbot said at
the U.S. Olympic swimming trials. ``He's got a great feel for the
water. He makes it look easy. His maturity, that's what you notice.
He's 17, but he seems like he's someone in his 30s or 40s. It's
almost spooky.''
</P>
<P>
   But with expectation comes enormous pressure. If his reputation
is to remain buoyant, Thorpe must win a gold medal, maybe even more
than one, Talbot said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's coping, handling it well, but he's got to feel
pressure,'' Talbot said. ``Nineteen million people want him to win.
He's a young boy with an octogenarian's head. It's amazing. But
he's got to feel the pressure. In Australia, it's always been that
way. You're nothing until you win a gold medal. If you don't win
gold at the Olympics, you're not one of the greats.''
</P>
<P>
   Having a country's hopes resting on your shoulders, especially
with the Olympics in your hometown, can be a weighty burden. Thorpe
trained in the United States for part of this summer, seeking the
benefits of altitude and anonymity at the Olympic Training Center
in Colorado Springs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Australia, swimmers are treated like rock stars,'' he said
in a recent telephone interview. ``That's difficult to deal with at
times. It takes away my privacy. I don't have the ability to walk
down the street. I don't have the ability to get away from myself.
That's the hardest thing, dealing with being me. I can't get a
holiday from what I do. But I always look at the support as being
positive. I see it more as opportunity than pressure, as something
that pushes me as opposed to wearing me down.''
</P>
<P>
   He has told friends that he wants to retreat from the public
after the Olympics but so far has refused to live the life of a
reclusive star. After all, he is only 17, and it is every
teen-ager's inalienable right not to be bound by the walls of home.
Getting out is as indispensable as oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wanted to, I could stop swimming and stop being a public
figure,'' Thorpe said. ``I don't want to do that. I'm not willing
to give up what I have.''
</P>
<P>
   Like millions of other Australians, Thorpe learned to swim by
age 6 or 7. As Talbot explained it, 95 percent of the population on
the island continent lives within 10 miles of the coastline. ``We
better learn to swim,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe's older sister, Christina, was an elite distance swimmer,
and as Ian followed her to swim meets, he decided to take up the
sport himself. There was one slight problem. He was allergic to
chlorine and swam with his head out of the water. But, having
suffered bronchial pneumonia as a child, he found breathing easier
in the warm humid air of swimming pools, even if he had to battle
through sinus congestion and headaches.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe's father and grandfather had excelled at cricket, but he
stayed in the pool. His sister qualified for the Atlanta Olympics
but did not meet the time standard to compete in the 400-meter
freestyle. Ian, meanwhile, set 13 state records in 13 short-course
meets as a 12-year-old. By age 14, he turned professional,
encouraged by his mother, Margaret, a teacher, and by his personal
coach, Doug Frost. With a year of high school remaining, he took a
sabbatical the past year to prepare for the Olympics. Eventually,
he plans to study medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was becoming too much, the public and professional side,
and trying to study,'' said Thorpe, who ranked near the top of his
class. ``Education is so important, I didn't want to jeopardize it,
so I decided to defer my studies.''
</P>
<P>
   At the 1998 world championships, held in Perth, Australia,
Thorpe won the 400-meter freestyle at age 15, becoming the youngest
world champion ever. Earlier this year, he broke three world
records at the Australian Olympic trials. But the use of
performance-enhancing drugs is believed to be so pervasive in
Olympic sports that any remarkable performance in events such as
swimming and track and field brings immediate suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   Manfred Theismann, a German swim coach, said in February that
some people believed Thorpe was using banned substances.
Chris-Carol Bremer, captain of the German swim team, told a German
newspaper that he believed the size of Thorpe's feet could have
been produced by a drug such as human growth hormone. Both later
apologized.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe, who has been outspoken against the use of drugs, said
the despairing thing was that the current urine-based testing
procedures were so deficient that innocent athletes can no longer
prove their innocence. He said he would be willing to undergo blood
testing and have the samples stored until tests for human growth
hormone and other banned substances were approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really sad thing that happens in sport, athletes being
accused of something they don't do,'' Thorpe said. ``In a way,
they're complimenting me by saying I'm doing something at such a
level they don't believe I can get to without drugs. But it's
disappointing because a lot of children look up to me, and when
they see the media talk up the accusations, it puts negative
thoughts in children's minds.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe's large feet do help him swim faster, but it has nothing
to do with drugs, according to Australian sports authorities. His
feet are so flexible that he can touch his shin with his toes,
Talbot said. The surface area and flexibility of Thorpe's feet help
generate a great force to propel him through the water, high on the
surface, thus reducing drag, said Bruce Mason, a biomechanics
expert at the Australian Institute of Sport. He is also aided by
the bodysuits approved this year.
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe uses a six-beat kicking cycle, generally used by
sprinters at shorter distances; the turbulence created in the water
``is like being in a washing machine,'' according to the South
African swimmer Ryk Neethling. Daniel Kowalski, who won three
freestyle medals for Australia in Atlanta, said the agitation of
Thorpe's wash is such that he tries to avoid finishing second and
third in any prelims so that he will not be given a lane next to
Thorpe in the finals..
</P>
<P>
   Thorpe's stroke is nearly 9 feet long, so attenuated that Thorpe
needs only 16 strokes per 50-meter lap, compared with 20 that his
fellow Australian Kieren Perkins used to win the 1,500-meter swim
in Atlanta. Thorpe also watches videotapes of his performances and
boxes for cross training. But his greatest assets are his maturity
and emotional stability, said Clark Perry, the Australian team's
sports psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this age they tend to go up and down a bit, but Ian is very
level,'' Perry said. ``When he is swimming, he is not racing
others, he is racing Ian Thorpe.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   His face is ubiquitous in Australia, endorsing a phone company,
an airline, a bank, a cereal and an automobile. But Thorpe has also
been acclaimed for his generosity with children's charities and for
his visits to children's hospitals. One of his closest friends is
15-year-old Michael Williams, the brother of his sister's husband,
who received a diagnosis of non-Hodgkins lymphoma in 1997. Williams
has accompanied Thorpe to several recent meets and will be on hand
for the Olympics. His friend's struggle changed his own life,
Thorpe said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was diagnosed at a time when I wasn't training as fast as I
had in the past and I was questioning why I was swimming,'' Thorpe
said. ``Here was Michael, with a thousand tubes in him, having a
potentially fatal disease. The last thing he could do was get into
a pool. I was feeling sorry for myself. It made me realize that
life is so precious and you have to make the most of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent commercial featuring Thorpe showed him swimming with
seals in the same sleek, effortless manner. But, Thorpe has one
frailty as an athlete, Talbot said, it is his gawkiness out of the
water. Last fall, Thorpe fractured a bone in his foot while jogging
and had to swim for a while in a Fiberglas cast.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't run,'' Talbot said. ``Swimmers can't run. They should
never run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
