<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-WOMENFINAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS KNOWS WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three years ago, Venus Williams was 17 years old and
a surprise US Open finalist. And Martina Hingis took her apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh boy,'' Williams said. ``I didn't know what I was doing,
basically.''
</P>
<P>
   She sure knows now.
</P>
<P>
   Knows how to work over an opponent. Knows how to rally from a
slow start. Knows how to finish off a match. Knows how to dig out
shot after shot and, in the process, lock on to momentum. And knows
what it's like to pocket $800,000 in the last major tournament of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Williams knocked Hingis out Friday in the semifinals and
Saturday completed her Open task, pounding away at Lindsay
Davenport for a 6-4, 7-5 decision at Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight title in a major for Williams, who
also beat Davenport in straight sets at Wimbledon this summer.
``Wimbledon was something totally different. I just had a whole new
attitude,'' Williams said. ``It was like I was going there to win
it and I knew I was going to take it home and I did. But this two
weeks I've been a little shaky because I've been working hard but
things haven't always gone the right way. But I played the big
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams's Open title was also a family double. Serena Williams,
who lost to Davenport in the semifinals this year, won last year's
US Open. After shaking hands with Davenport last nigh, Williams's
next stop was the family box to celebrate with Serena. Soon, their
coach and father, Richard, joined her on the court and did a little
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Venus and Serena are the first two sisters to win titles in Open
history.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams lost to Hingis in last year's Open semifinals.
``Of course I wasn't happy,'' she said. ``I played horribly. I
still haven't gotten over that loss. Ever since then, I've changed
my attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus is on a tremendous run. After starting the season with
tendinitis in her wrists, and her father talking about how,
perhaps, she should retire, she has won 26 straight matches and
five tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Like she did in the semifinals against Hingis, Williams started
slowly. This time, she turned things around without losing a set.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was in deep trouble in the first set. And just like
that, she rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport won four straight games _ and broke Williams twice _
to race to a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I wasn't taking my opportunities very well,''
Williams said. ``I was just missing a bit too much, maybe even
hitting it a little too hard.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Williams _ perhaps fueled by her third foot fault _
reeled off six in a row herself.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was called for a foot fault on what would have been an
ace, and then double-faulted to 30-40. But she served and volleyed
to deuce. Davenport put a backhand into the net and Williams hit a
forehand winner.
</P>
<P>
   And now, Williams was on a roll. She won 19 of 24 points in one
stretch to win the six straight game.
</P>
<P>
   Her ground strokes were hit deeper and harder. Davenport had
problems with her backhand and serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``She runs it down and hits it hard back,'' Davenport said.
``It's hard to put balls away against her.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams broke Davenport two times and Davenport served again at
4-5. Williams got a point at the net for 15-30. And then Davenport
faltered again on her serve, giving the set away with two straight
double faults.
</P>
<P>
   Williams's run of games took her to a 1-0 lead in the second
set.
</P>
<P>
   And when Davenport went down, 0-15, on her serve, things looked
grim. So all she did was serve three straight aces and a winner to
get back on track.
</P>
<P>
   She broke Williams and Williams broke back and it was 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth game, Davenport had four break points, but this
time Williams escaped them all and held.
</P>
<P>
   That became the story of the match.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was serving at 5-5 and Davenport had her in a 15-40
hole. But then she hit a couple of forehands long. Williams threw
in an ace and Davenport couldn't handle another serve for the game.
</P>
<P>
   For the match, Davenport had 15 break points and converted three
of them. Williams was far more break-efficient. She converted five
of eight chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was breaking well enough,'' Davenport said. ``But I wasn't
serving well enough and holding my serve.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 5-6 and 30-30 and Davenport was serving to get it to a
tiebreaker. Williams got Davenport on the run again and she put a
forehand into the net. Then a backhand long, and it was over.
</P>
<P>
   And the Family Williams _ with Venus winning the title that
eluded her in 1997 _ had another major.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, she knows what she's doing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
