r n BC-SKYKING-KAN &LR;      09-09 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKY KING'S SONGBIRD LIES ROTTING AT AN AIRSTRIP NEAR CLINTON, MO. 
</HEADLINE>
 KING-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Jim Fisher  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   CLINTON, Mo. _ Can most baby boomers,
recalling those long ago Saturdays, ever forget these words coming
from the TV as a twin-engine plane skimmed toward them over the
Arizona desert?
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Out of the clear blue of the western sky comes Sky King!''
</P>
<P>
   Then the plane, which everybody knew was Sky's beloved Songbird,
would bank to the left, and the screen would fade to a
breakfast-food commercial.
</P>
<P>
   The show, its episodes shown over and over from the early 1950s
to 1966, combined cutting edge technology (aviation) with a tried
and true drama (the western). It had good vs. evil, Sky King's
rugged good looks, and _ rare for the time _ the portrayal of a
competent young woman, Sky's niece, Penny.
</P>
<P>
   The show's stars were Sky (Kirby Grant), Penny (Gloria Winters),
nephew Clipper (Ron Hagerthy) and, of course, the Songbird, a
Cessna T-50 with huge radial engines and a fuselage that seemed
almost an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   Sky is dead, killed in a Florida car crash in 1985, Penny lives
in Southern California, and Clipper's whereabouts are undetermined.
</P>
<P>
   The Songbird?
</P>
<P>
   It's five miles east of Clinton, at an airstrip, in three large
piles of duralumin, decaying wood, and steel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just rotted away,'' said Lawrence Ferro, owner-operator of
the Ranch-Aero airstrip.
</P>
<P>
   The plane has been here for 40 years, ever since Ferro paid $450
for it. He is the 15th owner of the plane, which was built in 1943
and used after the war almost exclusively on the West Coast, where
it became the Songbird.
</P>
<P>
   Now, at least once a month, Ferro said, he reads of people
happily investing six figures in identical airplanes, which have
become part of the World War II nostalgia boom.
</P>
<P>
   Although 5,200 of the odd-looking T-50s _ also known as the
UC-78 _ were built in Wichita, Kan., to train B-17 and B-24 bomber
pilots, only a handful remain. These days they're coveted for their
forgiving flying characteristics and their old-fashioned fabric,
wood and metal construction.
</P>
<P>
   Ferro said the Songbird sort of melted before his eyes _ the
skin covering peeled off, the wooden wing spars developed dry rot,
and the wind one day blew the plane into a nearby pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Ferro, with voluminous records on the ownership and history of
the ship, No. N67832, has always known he probably has the most
valuable T-50 of all, despite its disassembled state. For years it
has been a mishmash of two Jacobs radial engines, a tangle of
tubular steel and a jumble of engine cowlings, seat frames, and
other parts, all piled helter-skelter. Ferro says he has 99.9
percent of the pieces.
</P>
<P>
   So, Ferro said, it could be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've have people offer me $25,000 just for the paperwork,''
said Ferro. ``They've pulled out money and waved it in my face just
for the registration number. This plane does something to people.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual fact is that Ferro bought the plane in 1960 with an
eye toward exhibiting it _ refurbishing it, getting some seed
money, then maybe barnstorming at air shows. That hope went
aglimmering when the fifth owner of the Songbird, Paul Mantz, an
aviation legend as well as the technical adviser to the Sky King
series, was killed in 1965 in the filming of a movie called
``Flight of the Phoenix.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mantz was a friend of mine, and we were going to work
something out,'' said Ferro. ``Then he was killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mantz's death took the steam out of Ferro. He had a business to
run, and he could always use the occasional spare parts for his
crop-spraying operation. Plus, he said, he was far ahead of the
curve. In the 1960s, nostalgia for World War II was still a long
way off.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, fans of the old black-and-white series have
tracked Ferro down and visited about the Songbird. There have been
long letters offering suggestions about restoring the plane.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they usually come down to is me giving the plane away,
putting up most of the money, and doing the work,'' said Ferro.
</P>
<P>
   What has struck Ferro over the years is that while his Songbird
was replaced by a newer, sleeker Cessna 310B after the 1955-56
season, most aficionados of the show equate the old T-50 with the
series.
</P>
<P>
   That may be in part because Grant himself was an accomplished
pilot and owned another T-50. A studio mockup of a T-50 was used
for interior shots.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, while Grant gained a sort of immortality with his
portrayal of the flying rancher from Grover, Ariz., he played
mostly villains in his B-western movie career.
</P>
<P>
   Odder still was his first love _ music. An accomplished violist
and vocal soloist, he would be remembered by some in Hollywood as
the man who recorded popular songs with studio orchestras and then
worked with a crooner from Spokane, Wash., named Bing Crosby who
had difficulty reading music.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most famous of those songs, now a Crosby standard,
was ``Pennies from Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferro's Songbird last flew May 3, 1960. That day he had picked
it up at a Camdenton airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody could get it started,'' he said. ``We worked on it a
couple of hours and had it running. We left and came back, and I
looked at the gas caps. They were in a different position than I'd
left them.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we drained the gas. It had enough water in it so we would
have had real trouble once we got airborne. Somebody, I don't know
who, wasn't happy with me having that plane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
