<HEADLINE>
ANTIBACTERIAL CONSUMER PRODUCTS MAY DO MORE HARM THAN GOOD, SOME
SAY 
</HEADLINE>
 PRODUCTS-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Alan Bavley  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Using soaps and other
products that promise to kill bacteria seems like a good way to
avoid infection, but is it?
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not necessarily, researchers say.
</P>
<P>
   Triclosan and other antibacterial ingredients contained in a
growing number of consumer products, such as liquid soaps, are
coming under increasing scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The American Medical Association recently reviewed the
scientific evidence and found no data supporting the effectiveness
of these products.
</P>
<P>
   But there is growing evidence, the AMA said, that bacteria are
developing resistance to these antibacterial substances, and that
might predispose the germs to resistance against antibiotics as
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no scientific evidence I know of that triclosan in
soap is better than regular soap. Regular old soap and water is the
gold standard,'' said Charles Rock, a biochemist at St. Jude
Children's Research Hospital in Memphis, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Rock is studying the antibacterial properties of triclosan.
There's no doubt, he said, that triclosan would make a good
bacteria-fighting drug.
</P>
<P>
   But putting triclosan in soap would be ``like washing your hair
with penicillin,'' he said. ``To me, it's more of a marketing issue
than reality-based.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock has found that some bacteria are less susceptible than
others to triclosan. And Rock and researchers at other centers have
managed with relative ease to make strains of common disease
bacteria such as E. coli that are resistant to triclosan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clear implication of using triclosan is that it will lose
its effectiveness,'' Rock said.
</P>
<P>
   Soap manufacturers scoff at these concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Antibacterial personal-care products provide an extra measure
of protection for consumers at home and doctors and nurses in
hospitals,'' said Ed Kavanaugh, president of the Cosmetic, Toiletry
and Fragrance Association.
</P>
<P>
   For example, research published in a dental journal shows a
triclosan-fortified toothpaste, Colgate Total, helps prevent
plaque, tartar and gingivitis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-09-00 2321EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
