<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDER WILLIAMS TURNS ON AFTERBURNERS IN FIREFIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She's got wheels. Like chariots of fire. And wings on
her heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I've got wheels on myself,'' says Venus Ebone Starr
Williams, who takes another US Open trophy back to the House of
Williams in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla. She could probably run all the
way.
</P>
<P>
   Little Sister Serena got one last year, and now Big Sister Venus
catches up with her very own championship bauble.
</P>
<P>
   Venus sat here in Arthur Ashe Stadium a year ago, bundled in a
hooded sweat shirt and looking a glummer shade of glum as Little
Sister conquered Martina Hingis in the title bout, and pranced
victoriously. Venus, who'd lost to Hingis in the semis, was
supposed to be first _ but now she is again, adding this trinket to
her Wimbledon championship memento.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay Davenport, beaten, 6-4, 7-5 (after leading 4-1), is just
another hit-and-run victim to testify that you may dodge one
Williams juggernaut, but the other one is sure to crush you.
Davenport, the 1998 champ, had dethroned Serena in the
quarterfinals, and for a while she was headed that way once more.
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon Venus came on as a tidal wave inundating Davenport for
six consecutive games to a 1-0 lead in the second. With 23,219
onlookers gaping at her freewheeling, Venus floored it on the
floodlit green track to roar away to the title.
</P>
<P>
   It was an 85-minute firefight of two women who believe in
fighting fire with fire. Call the hook-and-ladder trucks and get
out of the way. However, Venus raised the temperature unbearably
with her scorching groundies, and turned a blazing engagement into
a major conflagration from which Davenport could find no relief.
Even an asbestos playsuit couldn't have saved her from heatburn _
and heartburn _ while Venus torched her as at Wimbledon.
</P>
<P>
   The wheels did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody runs down balls like Venus,'' concedes Davenport.
``Arantxa Sanchez Vicario gets everything back, too, but the
difference is that Venus hits them back harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus decided to play foot-in-the-door defense, standing well
inside the baseline to return serve, and the daring tactic spooked
Davenport. Nobody can look at Davenport's lustiest serves up close
and survive. Nobody but Venus. She caromed the deliveries back at
Davenport almost as soon as balls left her racket _ belting them
forcefully and deep, keeping Davenport on her heels.
</P>
<P>
   This made Davenport go for too much on serve, and miss in her
times of need.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but those whirring wheels of a thief's getaway car. Never
has a woman stolen so many points with her legs. Davenport would
blast to the corners, as she did against Serena, but the ball came
back too many times with length and heat. She made Davenport hit
too many balls, and finally miss on crucial points.
</P>
<P>
   A great defense became an overpowering offense.
</P>
<P>
   A good big woman beat a good little woman in Friday's semis:
Venus over Hingis. Saturday, a good big woman beat a good bigger
woman, and the beat went on _ 26 straight for Venus. Her prevent
defense was at its thorniest when she had her back to the goal
line: break points. Though Davenport had the turn-it-around
opportunities, she cashed only three of 15 breakers.
</P>
<P>
   Venus sagged during the fifth game of the second set,
double-faulting twice, but kept running through a seven-minute
ordeal of five deuces and four break points to stay ahead, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Venus speed across the court to transform the finest
shots into winners of her own must be dismaying to an opponent.
There's a lot of dismay in store for her colleagues as Venus
matures and reinforces her confidence. Although Medusa, the Women's
Tennis Association computer, lists Hingis and Davenport as Nos. 1-2
in the world, Venus, knocking them off in succession, makes the
computer seem hard-driven into a ditch.
</P>
<P>
   For all purposes, the 2000 season is over, even though the
Olympics and the Chase Championships remain. Venus, with her two
majors, is the lady of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm moving forward,'' she says. Moving, moving, moving as
no one else has moved.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport's dreams couldn't have been pleasant Saturday night.
There is Venus, crowding her, moving in to destroy her serve, and
rolling over her with those relentless, heavy-duty wheels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
