<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-09 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     09-09 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SUPER SATURDAY TURNS INTO WOMEN'S DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Super Saturday at the United States Open has always
been a noisy, hectic experience that often leaves me with a giant
tennis hangover, but as a concept, I can't knock it. The other
Grand Slams give the women their own day to play for the big prize,
but they also pay them less than they do the men.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a draw, and don't feel sorry for Venus Williams, whose
wait until dark yesterday was worth her first Open title, her
second straight Grand Slam victory, her 26th consecutive match
victory, and $800,000 worth of pocket money of which the government
will want its share.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you lower my taxes?'' Williams asked President Clinton
when he telephoned and apologized for not sticking around after
watching the men.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he'd try, to which Williams volleyed back, ``Should
I read your lips?''
</P>
<P>
   Political and social niceties don't come naturally to this
20-year-old burgeoning star. Her idea of engagement is to blast
away until she gets her way, as she did with Lindsay Davenport
after falling into a 1-4 first-set hole, on the way to winning,
6-4, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   It is no big deal if the Williams sisters don't bond with
Davenport and Hingis. Steffi Graf was no one's best friend, and
nobody will ask how Pete Sampras gets along with Marat Safin, whom
he'll meet Sunday afternoon for the men's title. It wouldn't kill
the Williams family, from Richard on down, to be a little more
gracious to their opponents, but as far as Venus Williams' tennis
goes, just hit her the damn ball. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By late in the third set of Sampras' 7-6 (7), 6-4, 7-6 (5)
victory over the Australian Lleyton Hewitt, that was pretty much
the attitude in Arthur Ashe Stadium. Come on, Pete, get on with it.
On the broadcast feed, one of the network announcers was even
overheard to say: ``I've seen enough of this. Let's bring on the
women.''
</P>
<P>
   When Davenport and Williams hit the court, Patti LaBelle's sonic
version of the national anthem caused a cloudburst and sent the
players back to the locker room to ignore each other some more.
Whom to blame? Not even the Republicans could pin this one on
Clinton, who had watched Sampras advance to his sixth Open final
from a luxury box.
</P>
<P>
   For the women, their patience was rewarded with more exposure, a
Saturday night live slot. They used to shoehorn the gals between
the men's semifinals, but anywhere you put them these days, the
final is the final. It stands on its own and it stands tall,
regardless of whom the men serve up in their semis.
</P>
<P>
   For almost two weeks at the Open, the men played the more
compelling matches and the women still got the majority of the
attention. From the second round on, 50 of the 60 women's matches
were won in straight sets. Seles-Capriati? Straight sets.
Hingis-Seles? Straight sets. Serena Williams-Davenport? Straight
sets.
</P>
<P>
   Lack of overall tour depth gives the women more of a name-brand
quality to their events. They consistently have the same players,
the star value, running through the draw at the major tournaments,
on any surface. The late-round matchups among the top-ranked
players are more than anticipated. They are counted on. And when
they deliver spectacularly, as Venus Williams and Hingis did Friday
afternoon, their primary rivalries grow. Momentum for the next
event builds. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to dispute the opinion of Sampras as the best
player of either sex, even if he hasn't won the French Open and, at
this point, is not likely to. It isn't Sampras' fault that the crop
of challengers in recent years has largely been a collection of
interchangeable parts, from one year to the next.
</P>
<P>
   Going for his 14th Slam victory, he dodged a first-set tiebreak
bullet Saturday, when Hewitt acted 19 with a short ball in the
middle of the court on set point. He went for too much and spanked
it wide. Then Sampras rallied from service break down in the third
set, and set up match point with two demonstrations of his
trademark athletic brilliance: a magnificent low backhand volley
off a blistering Hewitt backhand, and a leaping overhead winner off
a Hewitt lob a few feet short of the baseline.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras and Safin went off to meet the president, who was still
in United Nations Summit mode when he assured the 20-year-old
Russian: ``You have a bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary hope of the ``New Balls'' generation, Safin may be
ready to move up near the top and stick around a while. He presents
a formidable challenge for Sampras on Sunday, even if they didn't
know him from Yevgeny Kafelnikov at the Open's transportation desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called like three times,'' he said after beating Todd Martin
to reach his first Slam final in the morning semifinal, 6-3, 7-6
(4), 7-6 (1).
</P>
<P>
   ```Please, can I have a car to come to the stadium?'
</P>
<P>
   ```What's your name?'
</P>
<P>
   ```Safin.'
</P>
<P>
   ```Can you spell it please?'''
</P>
<P>
   It was a decade ago Saturday that that a 19-year-old Sampras
practically needed a name tag as he introduced himself as the
player for his generation, and beyond. By the time Williams and
Davenport struck their first evening ball, the Safin-Martin match
seemed as dated as Sampras' first Open title.
</P>
<P>
   It was a long, long day, but in the end, there was Williams
holding the trophy and her father doing some silly dance on the
court and Serena congratulating Venus from the family box the way
Venus congratulated Serena one year ago. Tennis is a Williams' and
a woman's world right now, and not even the world's powerful man
could argue with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many Rick Lazio commercials,'' Venus told the lame duck
president on the phone. ``Tell Hillary I said, `All the way.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
