   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MILLENNIUM SUMMITEERS: ADMIRABLE WORDS _ NOW ACT ON THEM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UN-`GLOBAL-HUMANISM'-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Will this week's largest-ever conclave of world leaders at the
United Nations' ``millennium summit'' in New York make a bit of
difference to the billions of victims of poverty, cruelty or war?
The United Nations is determined that it should, says Kofi Annan,
the U.N. secretary-general, who wrote the report that became the
basis for an ambitious declaration signed by the summiteers on
Sept. 8. If the summiteers actually succeed in making the rich
world a little less selfish in its dealings with the poor world,
all the puff and flummery will have been worthwhile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FUELLING INFLATION: HIGHER OIL PRICES ENDANGER ALL ECONOMIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OIL-STRIKE?-ECONOMIST-750&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suffering from a touch of deja vu? Oil prices have more than
tripled since the end of 1998; political leaders, including Bill
Clinton, are appealing to OPEC countries _ whose oil ministers are
meeting this weekend _ to increase production; France has seen the
return of long queues at gas stations, as truckers protesting fuel
prices block supplies. Such news flogs scary memories of the three
previous big oil-price shocks, in the early and late 1970s, and in
1990. Yet, oddly, hardly anybody seems worried about such a
prospect today. Nonetheless, at such times it is always prudent to
ask: ``what might go wrong?'' Will OPEC _ and our insatiable oil
consumption _ soon have us over a barrel? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 300-word optional trim at 750; 1,200 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MYANMAR'S VICIOUS JUNTA DESERVES CENSURE, NOT COOPERATION &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CENSURE-MYANMAR-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Few cities are as gloomy as Yangon, the rot-blackened capital of
Myanmar, known in better days as Rangoon and Burma respectively.
The one bright light amid the murk is Aung San Suu Kyi, the leader
of the National League for Democracy (NLD). Her nine-day protest,
trapped in a car on the outskirts of Yangon, and her subsequent
detention under house arrest, remind her countrymen, and the wider
world, both of the intransigence of the military junta and of the
fact that an alternative still exists, despite years of
oppression. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (775 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FROM SUNRISE TO SUNSET...GORE QUESTS, TESTS, NEVER RESTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GORE-ENERGIZER-BUNNY-ECONOMIST-375&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ America is the first society in the world that has
tried to organize itself on the assumption that human beings do not
need sleep. There are 24-hour news channels, 24-hour wedding
chapels, and, of course, 24-hour lap-dancing emporiums. So it was
only a matter of time before someone invented the 24-hour political
campaign _ and it is only right that that someone should be Al
Gore, the protege of the man who invented the ``permanent
campaign.'' If Gore is the Energizer Bunny of this campaign, George
W. Bush is the napster, taking his favorite feather pillow wherever
he goes _ an aide carries it in a special bag _ and pining if he
has to spend too many nights away from home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 175-word optional trim at 375; 1,150 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HEAD TO HEAD, NECK AND NECK: MOUTH-TO-MOUTH REVIVES RACE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NECK'N'NECK-GOREBUSH-ECONOMIST-625&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ America's presidential election has been
transformed. For much of the past year, it had seemed George W.
Bush's to lose. Now, however, it is Al Gore who is surging ahead in
the polls, with an average lead of three percentage points in most
and ten points in one. Suddenly, it is Gore who is forcefully
setting the agenda, while Bush stumbles on the hustings, getting
his billions and trillions muddled (twice) and blurting vulgar
things into open microphones. The phoney campaign is over, folks.
Election 2000 now promises to be the closest race in decades. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 3 optional trims, totaling 325 words; 1,450 uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEXAS DEMOCRATS: AN ENDANGERED SPECIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEX-MESS-DEMOCRATS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PARIS, TEXAS _ What would Sam Rayburn and Lyndon Johnson make of
Paris, Texas? This barren town in the state's northeastern corner
has long been the Mecca of Democratic Texas _ a place (pre-Gov.
George W. Bush) where an elected Republican was a contradiction in
terms. It was the stomping ground of Rayburn, the powerful speaker
of the House, who shepherded the New Deal laws through Congress;
Johnson, his protege, could always count on it. Yet in many ways,
Texas Democrats can longer say, ``we'll always have Paris.'' As in
hundreds of rural towns throughout the state, they have lost their
stranglehold, and watch grimly as Texas increasingly becomes a
one-party state for the Republicans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: TEXAS...and Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (825 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FROM HERE TO ETERNITY: WHO MERITS A MONUMENT _ SOLDIERS OR
SINATRA? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MEMORIAL-OVERKILL?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Who better deserves a prominent memorial: the
singer whose ``My Way'' launched a thousand karaoke bars, or his 16
million contemporaries who fought in the Second World War? For the
moment, it looks as if New York City will erect a statue of Frank
Sinatra before Washington gets around to building a tribute to the
troops whose ranks Sinatra joined only on celluloid. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (625 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (325 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SURFING THE NET IN SWAHILI: AFRICA GOES ONLINE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNET-AFRICA-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ An Ethiopian touts goats, Somalis in Kenya sell
henna and incense, a censored Liberian radio station defies the
government and a Namibian invites offers for a taxi license. All do
so on the Internet. Is Africa getting online? Not really: of some
360 million Internet users around the world, only 3.1 million are
thought to be in Africa, and most of them are either in South
Africa or north of the Sahara. But access is spreading fast,
perhaps even tripling over the course of last year. For the first
time, surfers can use the Net in Swahili. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (TIMELY for U.N. Millennium Summit _ 5th graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOX INHERITS A BETTER MEXICO, BUT PROBLEMS STILL LURK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ZEDILLO-LEGACY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Last Friday, when President Ernesto Zedillo gave
his final state-of-the-union address to Mexico's Congress, he had
much to be proud of. Back in 1994, he took over a country teetering
on the brink of economic disaster, and scarred by political
violence and guerrilla rebellion. On Dec. 1, he will hand over to
Vicente Fox a country that differs for the better. Whatever
Zedillo's shortcomings, Mexicans will have grounds for satisfaction
if their new president turns out to be as successful as his
predecessor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 300-word optional trim at 725; 1,150 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUBLIC VIRTUES, PRIVATE VICES IN CHILE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORALS-CHILE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SANTIAGO _ Earlier this year, MercadoLibre, a Miami-based online
auction company, found to its surprise that Santiago's underground
railway authority had vetoed part of its planned advertising
campaign in Chile. The state-run metro seems to have objected to a
poster proclaiming ``vendo mis pelotas,'' or ``I sell my balls.''
The veto was predictable; when it comes to public morality, Chile
has long been more straitlaced than its Latin neighbors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (450 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FLOURISHING HMONG OF MINNESOTA &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAOS-HMONG-MINN-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ST. PAUL, MINN. _ Drive through Frogtown, a seedy bit of St.
Paul, Minn., and the future of Laos is on display. On one side of
University Avenue is Foodsmart, a supermarket, owned by a Hmong
businessman. On the other is the office of the Hmong bookshop, a
Hmong chemist and dozens of other Hmong-run shops. Unlike their
relations in Communist-run Laos, the Hmong of Minnesota, some
70,000 of them, are evidently thriving. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Minneapolis-St. Paul, MINN.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WRECKING BALLS ARE DEMOLISHING OLD BEIJING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BULLDOZED-BEIJING-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Garrison Keillor was not quite right when he said that
only Americans pulled down old houses because they were too
difficult to clean. In the past few years, Beijing's municipal
authorities have been systematically tearing down centuries-old
neighborhoods of narrow alleyways to make way for souless six-lane
avenues and commercial buildings. Beijing, desperate to win the
contest to hold the 2008 Olympic Games, boasts about the
``greening'' and ``modernizing'' of the capital. In reality,
China's quest for modernity destroys much of the old in favor of
the ugly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIT THE ROAD, JAC?: FORD BOSS'S CAREER _ AND CREDIBILITY _
DEAD-ENDS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHREDDING-JAC-NASSER-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Last week, when the American press and broadcasters
were on a feeding frenzy over the recall of Firestone tires fitted
to Ford Explorers, Ford's pugnacious chief executive, Jac Nasser,
appeared in prime-time TV ads professing the company's commitment
to customers and their safety, and promising to do everything to
replace suspect tires as quickly as possible. Days later, a
defensive Nasser tried to duck his way out of appearing before a
congressional subcommittee investigating the recall. Was it
cowardice or arrogance? Whichever, unless somebody at Ford soon
gets this consumer-safety issue under control, it will not just be
Firestone tires that are shredded _ it may well be Jac Nasser's
mercurial career as well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TURNING POWER LINES INTO DATA LINES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `LOOPY'-TECHNOLOGY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Everybody seems to love the ``local loop'' nowadays.
That is what the firms now battling for control of it call the
wires that connect telecommunications networks with homes and
businesses. Thanks chiefly to the Internet, consumers everywhere
are clamoring for ever-faster ways to download ever-larger
quantities of data, and are willing to fork out tidy sums for the
privilege. The obvious beneficiaries of such windfalls should be
the local telecoms firms that already have customers in the grip of
their copper tenacles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
